<HEADER>
A3079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GIULIANI-STEPS-LIMITS     04-21 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-STEPS-LIMITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR DEFENDS LIMITED ACCESS TO CITY HALL STEPS
</HEADLINE>
 By THOMAS J. LUECK  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Thursday defended his
decision to issue new emergency restrictions limiting access to the
City Hall steps, saying they were modeled on those governing the
steps of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sensitivity of City Hall is roughly equal to the
sensitivity of the United States Congress,'' the mayor said. Under
the emergency order, anyone wanting to hold a news conference or
protest on the City Hall steps or in City Hall Park must obtain a
police permit, applying at least two days in advance for large
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Michael D. Hess, the city's corporation counsel,
also announced that City Hall Plaza, now used as a staging area for
official events and for parking for the mayor and the City Council
at the foot of the City Hall steps, would be opened to pedestrians
during the day.
</P>
<P>
   He said electronic scanning devices, similar to those used for
airport security, would be installed at the two main entrances to
the plaza and used to check pedestrians for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor issued the rules on the City Hall steps two weeks
after a federal court threw out his previous guidelines after
determining that they violated the First Amendment right of
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The old rules gave the police far-reaching authority to decide
what groups or individuals would be granted access.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules were put in place on a day when a rally against
police brutality made its way across the Brooklyn Bridge to City
Hall, where it was contained behind police barricades on a sidewalk
outside City Hall Park.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Connolly, an assistant corporation counsel, said the
timing of the new restrictions was unrelated to protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing had to do with Judge Baer's decision, which last
week left us without any rules at all and meant that any group
could have descended on City Hall,'' he said, referring to Judge
Harold Baer Jr. of U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   First released on Tuesday night, the restrictions were explained
in detail late Thursday. Hess said groups of up to 300 people could
be granted permits to assemble on City Hall steps and the broad
plaza at its base, and groups of more than 300 would be consigned
to City Hall Park, but only with a separate permit from the city's
Parks Department.
</P>
<P>
   Under the previous rules, groups using the City Hall steps and
plaza were limited to 50 people, and those using City Hall park
were limited to 150. Police approval was required for all groups.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, and Peter Vallone, the Council speaker, said the
new rules still denied the public general access.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said he would ``wait to see how the rules are put into
practice,'' but was prepared to file suit if they intruded on free
speech in ways similar to the rules thrown out by Judge Baer.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a spokesman for the U.S. Capital Police, Lt. Dan
Nickels, said the new City Hall restrictions were ``very much in
line'' with rules governing access to the steps of the Capital
Rotunda since the 1970s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
