<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-WIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE VAGINA MONOLOGUES' MAKING A POLITICAL CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Call it a bit of political theater or merely some
inspired casting, but Donna Hanover's latest acting job might raise
some eyebrows at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning May 30, Hanover, the wife of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
will take over a lead role in ``The Vagina Monologues,'' the
off-Broadway hit that features a dozen or so monologues on topics
like orgasm and childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   Joannie Danielides, a spokeswoman for Hanover, confirmed the
casting, which had been rumored in theatrical circles for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was asked by the producers, and she said she'd like to do
it,'' Danielides said. ``Donna makes her own professional
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover, who has appeared in several films and is the host of
the program ``In Food Today'' on the Television Food Network, will
perform for two weeks, sharing the play's monologues with two other
women.
</P>
<P>
   While her decision to do the play was a professional one,
pundits may wonder if there is a political subtext in Hanover's
choice of material.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``The Vagina Monologues,'' after all, is Eve
Ensler, a personal friend and political supporter of Hillary Rodham
Clinton, Giuliani's opponent in the race for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A playwright long concerned with women's issues, Ensler was an
honorary member of Clinton's exploratory committee for her campaign
and visited the White House last year for a personal meeting with
the first lady. Clinton, meanwhile, is writing a foreword to
Ensler's new play, ``Necessary Targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielides had no comment on Ensler's connection to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A call to the mayor's office for comment was not immediately
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vagina Monologues,'' which began at a small theater in
SoHo in 1996, reopened at the Westside Theater in October with
Ensler performing all the monologues. Since February, however,
those duties have been shared by rotating trios of performers,
including Broadway actresses like Audra McDonald and the singer
Alanis Morisette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
