u a BC-OBIT-McMORROW-NYT &LR;      04-21 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-McMORROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.) 
</HEADLINE>
   FRED McMORROW, 74, AUTHOR AND EDITOR  
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fred McMorrow, an author and a retired editor and
Long Island section columnist for The New York Times, died Thursday
in a nursing home in Walhalla, S.C. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Jeanne Baker McMorrow, said he had recently had a
stroke after a long struggle with Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Over his career, McMorrow, a humorist, poet and jazz pianist as
well as a journeyman journalist, worked on copy desks at every
surviving New York daily newspaper, often as chief or deputy chief
of the desk.
</P>
<P>
   His most successful book, ``Midolescence: The Dangerous Years''
(Strawberry Hill, 1974) was a wry look at the problems of the
second adolescence sometimes called middle age. He also wrote
``Jimmy: the Candidacy of Carter'' (Strawberry Hill, 1976),
published at the end of that presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick J. McMorrow was born in New York City on Nov. 29,
1925. He served in World War II before attending Adelphi College on
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, he began as a cub reporter at The Long Island Press. He
worked for four other newspapers, The Journal-American, The New
York Herald Tribune, The New York Post and The Daily News, before
joining The New York Times in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to working as an editor on the foreign and national
desks and for the Style section, he wrote the weekly ``About Long
Island'' column from 1980 to 1992. He also wrote short stories for
magazines, including The Saturday Evening Post and Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to the late Eileen Palmer, ended in divorce;
he remarried in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, he is survived by his brother, Thomas Ever
McMorrow of New York; his children from his first marriage, Thomas,
Robert and Fred, of Long Island, and Mary Smith, of Connecticut;
and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
