<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-SATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS EYE SATHER FOR THE FRONT OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
  By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been a silent spring at Madison Square Garden
regarding the vacancies in the New York Rangers' hierarchy, while
Garden President Dave Checketts methodically undertakes his search
for a new general manager. That scenario could change as soon as
Friday night, if the Dallas Stars wrap up their first-round series
against the Edmonton Oilers in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Oilers are eliminated from the NHL playoffs, their
longtime team president and general manager, Glen Sather, can be
wooed. Even though Sather has two seasons remaining on his
contract, he also has an escape clause. According to several people
in hockey, the Rangers are interested in Sather as a replacement
for Neil Smith, who was fired on March 28 along with John Muckler,
the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Before the playoffs began, Sather said he was not going
anywhere. But in a telephone conversation Wednesday night, Sather
did not rule out the possibility of a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I'm flattered that people mention my name when jobs
open up around the league,'' the 56-year-old Sather said from
Dallas. ``I'm really not in a position to make any comments about
that. I haven't given it one second of thought. As far as what I'm
going to do, I haven't made any public statements about it. When
the time comes, I'll deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the Garden interested in Sather, but also, according
to one person in hockey with knowledge of the situation,
``whoever's second is a distant second.'' Because of Sather's
escape clause, the Rangers will not have to ask for permission to
speak with him. That is something they would have to do with
Pittsburgh if they pursue the Penguins' general manager, Craig
Patrick, who is also believed to be on the Rangers' list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the proper protocol,'' Sather said. ``But I, on the
other hand, have a loophole that I wrote into my contract that says
that I will be able to do this should I decide to leave Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   One longtime league executive said earlier this week that both
Wayne Gretzky, who played for Sather in Edmonton in the 1980s, and
Commissioner Gary Bettman have encouraged the Rangers to pursue
Sather.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rumor is not correct,'' Bettman said Thursday. ``I don't
do that. It's up to the teams to decide. I don't get involved in
personnel decisions.'' But it is no secret that Bettman and others
hold Sather in high regard.
</P>
<P>
   Sather played for 10 NHL seasons as a left wing for six teams,
including the Rangers from 1970 to 1973. He became the Oilers'
coach in 1977, when they were a part of the World Hockey
Association. Three seasons later, Sather became the team's general
manager and was the architect of the Oilers' dynasty in the '80s,
when the franchise won four Stanley Cups in five seasons (plus a
fifth without Gretzky in 1990).
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers have not advanced past the second round of the
playoffs since 1992, but the Rangers have failed to qualify for the
playoffs in the last three seasons. And there are many league
executives who believe that Sather will allow himself to be wooed
by the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   But many are also skeptical about the Rangers' chances of
actually persuading him to leave Edmonton. Sather has been there
for 24 years, the last 21 as general manager. That gives him the
second-longest tenure as a general manager in the NHL behind
Boston's Harry Sinden. Sather has long said he is comfortable in
the West. He owns houses in both Palm Springs, Calif., and Banff,
Alberta, and enjoys outdoor life.
</P>
<P>
   Sather's current contract calls for him to be paid just under $2
million in each of the next two seasons. One thing in the Rangers'
favor is their ability to pay him significantly more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-SERIAL-KILLER-SPI &LR;      04-21 1793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLE-AGED FATHER LINKED BY DNA TO AT LEAST 12 SLAYINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LEWIS KAMB and SAM SKOLNIK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOKANE _ As the man suspected of killing as many as 18 women
sat in a downtown prison cell, investigators fielded calls from
other detectives who are trying to solve similar slayings across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from as far away as Alabama, New York and even
Germany are wondering whether Robert Lee Yates Jr. _ described by
authorites as a ``family man,'' could be the same person who killed
women.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, detectives dug deeper into an investigation they now
say could take two or more years and millions of dollars to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a busy, but good day,'' Spokane COunty Sheriff Mark Sherk
said Thursday. ``Detectives are relieved we've finally made an
arrest, but the immensity of the task ahead of them is starting to
sink in.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives fielded dozens of calls with tips from people who
knew Yates or others passing along information they believed could
be helpful, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratories here and across the state and nation buzzed as
criminologists analyzed crime scene and other evidence generated
since Yates' arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators seized another vehicle _ a van located in Idaho _
they say is one of nine automobiles Yates owned or had been known
to drive.
</P>
<P>
   And detectives here and in Western Washington worked with
federal agents to piece together a timeline of Yates' whereabouts
over the past decade trying to place him in areas when and where
bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty confident once we get a timeline, it will all
correspond,''terk said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say DNA evidence links Yates to the deaths of at
least 12 of 18 victims _ women mostly caught in at-risk lives of
drugs and prostitution Evidence may also tie him to all of the
cases, they say.
</P>
<P>
   All of the women were shot. Investigators said Thursday they
have not recovered a firearm in the case, though Sherk said a bomb
sniffing dog that ATF agents from Miami led through Yates' home on
Tuesday hit at least ``six alerts'' _ areas where guns or bullets
may have been kept in the house at one time.
</P>
<P>
   Blood drawn from Yates links him directly to genetic material
the killer left where eight bodies were dumped _ though
investigators would not say what that crime scene material is. Four
other victims investigators say positively link to Yates were also
linked through DNA and other evidence. But again, they would not
disclose how.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, relatives of all 18 victims had been contacted by
investigators. Detectives have not released the names of the 12
directly linked to their suspect, who has yet to be charged in 11
of those slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Yates, 47, was charged Wednesday with the first-degree murder of
16-year-old Jennifer Johnson, a wayward youth from Spanaway who
sold sex on Spokane streets up until her disappearance in August
1997. Her decomposing remains were found later that month dumped in
off a roadside in rural Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were able to link Johnson's death this week to
Yates, an Army vet and father of five who worked at a Mead aluminum
smelter, through blood and other evidence found in a car he once
owned.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic evidence, a button identical to one missing from a
jacket found on Johnson's corpse, and other evidence obtained from
a 1977 white Corvette Yates owned between 1994 and 1998 tied him to
her killing, leading investigators here to arrest him in north
Spokane early Tuesday while Yates drove to work.
</P>
<P>
   Blood drawn from him shortly after his arrest has since
identified Yates as the serial killer of at least 12 women _ and
possibly up to 18 _ across Washington, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the guy we were looking for,'' Sterk said. ``He's
finally behind bars.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates sat Thursday in a 8 by 9 foot prison cell in the Public
Safety Building in lieu of $1.5 million cash bail. Prison guards
surveyed him under a suicide-type watch _ checking him every 15
minutes _ though investigators say he has not threatened to harm
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He remains isolated from the general prison population, said
Jail Commander Sheriff's Capt. Dick Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Though the murder charge against him has been formally read at a
preliminary hearing, prosecutors have yet to formally file the
charges. They have until Friday morning to do that. After an
arrest, prosecuting attorneys have 72 hours by law to file such
charges or they must release their suspect, court officials said
Thursday. An arraignment will be scheduled once those files are
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Though court officials said Yates has applied for a court
appointed attorney, they would not disclose whether one has yet
been assigned to them.
</P>
<P>
   While detectives worked locally to tie him to all 18 murders in
the state, calls began flowing in from other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Since authorities began investigating the murders, the serial
killer here has been looked at as a person of interest in several
other slayings, including one in Germany, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army helicopter pilot and reservist now in custody moved
with his family across the county over the years. Yates has lived
in New York, Alabama and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Now authorities in some of those areas are looking into whether
Yates alleged killing spree may have started long before he moved
to Washington state
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Joseph Goss of the Watertown, N.Y., Police Department says
his detectives are now actively investigating whether that small
city's one unsolved homicide is tied to Yates.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Hosmer Smith was shot and killed at 4 a.m. august first
1990 on a street just behing Watertown police headquarters. Smith,
an unemployed 20-year-old, was estranged from her husband at the
time. Goss said the husband had a strong alibi and quickly ruled
out as a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was not involved in drugs and prostitution, according to
the police file, Goss said. but it's possible that the perpetrator
might have thought that, walking alone on a downtown street at 4
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Goss says that Watertown police have called spokane
detectives to inquire about a possible connection to Yates.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few fundamental questions outstanding however. it is
unclear whether Yates was stationed at Fort Drum, just outside
Watertown, at the time. Yates first was stationed at Ft. Drum in
late 1990 or early 1991 according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a case we would like to compare notes on,'' said Goss,
``Is there a link? it's to early to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be a much firmer connection between Yates and
Connie LaFontaine the Tacoma woman found dead on Oct. 13, 1998.
Police have connected LaFontaine, a prostitute, to the serial
murders from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Yates, retired from the army and moved to spokane in 1996. Soon
after, he joined the Washington Army National Guard for the last
three years, one weekend a month, he flew to Ft. Lewis 12 miles
outside of Tacoma to teach helicopter flying lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to Dave Hall of the pierce co. sheriff's
department, La Fontaine and Yates seem to be solidly linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to say that from what we know so far, it looks very
promising,'' hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Yates' arrest, Pierce County sheriff investigators have
been coordinating with Spokane police, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Pierce County detectives are concentration on where
Yates might have stayed in the county; what kind of car he may have
been driving at the time; and where he may have flown in her
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Less is known about the connections between Yates and Melinda
Mercer, a Tacoma area woman found dead in december 1997. She was
also thought to be the serial killer's victim.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mathis, a spokesman for the Spokane police Department which
is handling the investigation, could not be reached for comment.
Police investigating another the third western Washington woman
connected to the Spokane serial murderer are not yet ready to make
the tie to Yates.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Barnes, whose body was discovered in 1995, has hereto
for haas only been listed as a possible victim of the murder. She
was from Port Orchard.
</P>
<P>
   Kitsap county sheriff's office chief of detectives Mike Davis
says his office has been communicating with counterparts in Spokane
regularly 'to try to establish a firmer connection between the
Barnes homicide and they're serial murderer.'
</P>
<P>
   But Davis is not as optimistic as his pierce county counterpart
regarding a connection to Yates.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's still premature to advise that we've
reached the conclusion that she is indeed a victim of the
particular man they've arrested over there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Spokane, an investigator revealed Thursday they got an
unlikely break in the Corvette that helped bring Yates to custody.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Jones, the woman who bought the Corvette from Yates in
1998, is the sister of a woman who works in the Spokane city-county
joint property room. Everything from confiscated pot pipes to
recovered stolen articles is kept there, Detective Cal Walker said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After she bought the car, Jones stored it in her sister's garage
for months, leaving crucial evidence that helped link Yates to
Johnson's murder undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no type of cleaning to contaminate the evidence,''
said Walker, who added that the blood, carpet fibers and button
found in the car broke the case.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were able to arrest Yates for Johsnon's murder
largely on that evidence alone. They then were able to draw the
blood that his linked him to 11 other victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Corvette basically has been put to bed,'' Walker said of
the importance of it to the case. ``It probably won't come out
again til court.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators showed media members five other cars they have
confinscated since Yates arrest. Among them, two blue Hondas, two
Ford vans and a Ford pick up that still has a vehicle registration
sticker to Ft. Drum, Ny York from 1993 on its bumper.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also allowed media passed police barricades to
view Yates' South Hill split-level home that hs been shrouded by
tarps since his arrest for the first time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Three tripods sat in the home's front and side yards, holding up
sophisticated equipment provided by the Washington State Patrol
that will create a three-dimension map of the scene. A white flag
could be seen in a wood pile next to at least two sheds visible in
the home's yard marking a place of interest to detectives.
</P>
<P>
   The house was typical of the split levels that line East 49th
Avenue. Well kept and landscaped, it had flowers shrubbery, a
blossoming cherry tree and evergreens surrounding it. A basketball
hoop hung on the side of a garage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
