<SLUG> BC-SOC-MATTHAUS-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTHAEUS LEAVES METROSTARS DAZED AND CONFUSED
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION, N.J. _ After enduring what might be the most trying month
of his illustrious career, Lothar Matthaeus is scheduled to board a
flight to Germany shortly after the MetroStars play D.C. United on
Saturday night, with the renowned sweeper going to his homeland to
play in an exhibition game with the German national team.
</P>
<P>
   Matthaeus is expected to return to the United States before
missing the next MetroStars game. But it is not out of place to ask
three questions, all related: Does he want to come back? Can the
MetroStars make him come back? Does the team really want him to
come back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way, I wouldn't be surprised if he didn't come
back, and I wouldn't blame him for not coming back,'' goalkeeper
Mike Ammann said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Following a tirade during a 2-1 loss to the Kansas City Wizards
on Wednesday night, Matthaeus met with MetroStars coach Octavio
Zambrano and the team's general manager, Nick Sakiewicz, after
Thursday's practice. On Saturday night in a 1-0 loss to Columbus,
Matthaeus criticized his teammates. Then on Wednesday night, he
argued with the assistant referee Chip Reed, tossing his captain's
arm band at the official and then repeatedly trying to hand it to
him while play continued on the other end of the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the meeting Thursday, Matthaeus explained the most recent
outburst as an attempt to provoke a reaction from his teammates.
While the team accepted the explanation and did not impose a
penalty, the MetroStars also expressed little patience for a repeat
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him that there is no room for that, that it is not
going to fly here,'' Zambrano said. ``I don't endorse it.'' ``If he
genuinely believed that he was trying to wake up the guys, then
what can I say? I can't punish him for that. But he has been warned
that that is not to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthaeus said he did not feel better Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a good feeling after losing games, directly after
the games or the day after, I don't like to lose,'' said Matthaeus,
who has a one-year contract with the team. ``I have no problem with
Octavio or Nick. I speak open, and I think they can understand me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have played professional soccer for 20 years, and I have
played on good teams and not-so good-teams,'' Matthaeus said. ``I
know the level is not the same in the Italian League or the Spanish
League as in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I see these guys play good in the practice, and we don't
do that in the game. I don't understand that. I am frustrated
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Wednesday's game, when asked if he would stay, he
said: ``I don't know. After five weeks, it's not a good time for
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope in the next weeks, there will be better results,''
Matthaeus said. ``I have my contract here. I will stay in New York
for this season, and it changes a little bit, I can make the
season. For me, it is no problem.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Zambrano left the door open that the defender might not fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `yes,' right now because I don't think he's a guy that
would walk away from his obligations as a player,'' Zambrano said.
``The only thing that would prevent him from finishing the
situation here would be some outrageous situation that just can't
be tolerated or something of that nature. If he does the same thing
again, I think the nature of our meeting would be of a different
sort.'' &QL; 
NOTES: The MetroStars have been pursuing Romanian midfielder
Gheorghe Hage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
