<SLUG> BC-BIGNAME-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDENTITY THIEVES AIMED HIGH IN THEIR FRAUD, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ark., Miss)  By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most identity thieves raid the accounts of ordinary
citizens. But big shots have bigger credit limits, and James
Rinaldo Jackson and Derek Cunningham went after some of the
biggest, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   According to an indictment returned Thursday by a federal grand
jury in Manhattan, the two men used credit card and bank account
information stolen from the chief operating officer of Coca-Cola
Enterprises, the chief executive of Hilton Hotels and the late
president of Wendy's International, among others, to acquire more
than $730,000 worth of diamonds and Rolex watches.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 39, and Cunningham, 28, were each charged with 29
counts of conspiracy and fraud for crimes committed between late
December and late February, the U.S. attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who live in Memphis, would obtain prospective
victims' financial data, and, impersonating them, change the
billing addresses for their accounts to hotels in Tennessee,
Arkansas and Mississippi, the indictment states.
</P>
<P>
   Then they would contact jewelers and buy expensive items, like a
five-carat diamond or a $10,000 watch, order them to be shipped to
one of the hotel's addresses, reserve hotel rooms in the names of
their victims, and tell the hotel to expect a package, the
indictment states.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was arrested Feb. 25 after FBI agents watched him pick
up a package at a Tennessee hotel. Cunningham is not yet in
custody, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, one of the men posed as Stephen Bollenbach, the
chief executive officer of Hilton Hotels, called the issuer of his
Visa card on Feb. 22 and changed his billing address to a hotel in
Holly Springs, Miss., according to court records. The next day,
someone ordered two diamonds costing a total of $48,000 in
Bollenbach's name from Diamondcutters.com, a New York City
merchant, and had them shipped to the hotel, court documents state.
</P>
<P>
   The men's deceased victims included Nackey Scripps Loeb, the
publisher of The Union Leader, who died in January, and Gordon
Teter, the president of Wendy's International Inc., who died in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office released the names of some of the
other victims but identified others only by their titles. The chief
operating officer of Coca-Cola Enterprises is John R. Alm, and
Lehman's chairman and chief executive is Richard Fuld. If
convicted, Jackson and Cunningham would face the possibility of
more than 40 years in jail and fines of more than $1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
