<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER THE DIFFERENCE IN SERIES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He came here full of promise.
</P>
<P>
   After Seattle watched Shawn Kemp grow moody and distant and
demand his divorce, Vin Baker was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in our collective memory, there's an image from his
inaugural season in 1997-98 of Baker running back down the court
after making a big move against Shaquille O'Neal and the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Baker is pumping his fist.
</P>
<P>
   His intensity and passion and desire were vivid as Kodachrome.
His happiness and sense of hope infused the team with a sort of
refreshed innocence.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. He played. It was all new and unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were bouncy and joyful, too. Instead of being
derailed by losing such a warhorse as Kemp, they kept in step with
their new 6-foot-11 power forward whose talent was ready to be
tapped.
</P>
<P>
   He was at last out of Milwaukee, freed from a team he believed
was holding him back, a team on which Baker had never made a
playoff appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, traded to Seattle, Baker was a main cog in a team that
a contender in '96 and was looking to use Baker and Gary Payton as
the one-two punch toward a new round of NBA title contention.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics won the Pacific Division. They went 61-21. They had a
party in the visitors' locker room in Portland, where they wrapped
up the regular season with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was time for the 1998 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And then Vin Baker found out what it's like to play basketball
in the NBA's real season.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That season was fun,'' Baker said Thursday, a smile actually
stretching across a face that has spent too much time lately in
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great for us but I've said all along it's ironic
because ... within two weeks in the playoffs, that season went down
the drain,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker took responsibility for what happened. He decided his
inconsistent play was the main reason the Sonics did so poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I think I didn't play well in those two playoff
series we had against Minnesota and the Lakers because I did put
too much pressure on myself. I pressed too much,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Vin Baker has never really recovered from that
public exposure of his lack of playoff experience, his
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can observe (the playoffs) but until you're in the middle
of it, you just don't know,'' Sonics' president Wally Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Vin after that first year, when he talked about the
playoffs, he said `I know I've seen it on television but I just
didn't know what it's about.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Sonics, who barred the media from asking Baker or
Payton anything about Baker's recent disclosure that he is battling
depression, we won't delve into the problems Baker has had this
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be said that Baker's inconsistency seems to be a
continuation of what happened during the '98 playoffs and last
season's 50-game nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   This season, as Baker again fell into a prolonged slump, Baker's
most startling admission was that the way he plays is the
difference between the Sonics being a No. 3 seed or a No. 7 seed in
the Western Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He said it again when he admitted his erratic play probably cost
the Sonics 10 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   He understands that if Payton is the Sonics' MVP, then he has
been its MIA.
</P>
<P>
   The seriousness of his downfall has taken him out of the
starting line-up as of last week and, more critical, is the biggest
underlying question about the Sonics and their future:
</P>
<P>
   Can Baker consistently be the force of which he has shown only
hints?
</P>
<P>
   Can he be the difference between winning and losing?
</P>
<P>
   Can he shake the inclination to internalize his problems and
instead, use his anger or frustration to fuel fire towards a better
performance?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to go out and be wild and crazy in this. In my
situation, I don't think things can get any worse,'' he said, again
showing some humor.
</P>
<P>
   If there ever was a perfect time for Baker to shrug off his
demons and dust off his critics, it is now. Saturday is Game 1 of
the Sonics first-round playoff series against the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   A younger, aggressive and hungry Sonics team has a good shot
against the Jazz, if the team isn't mired in a funk and rotation
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday against Sacramento in the Sonics' paydirt game of the
season, Baker showed signs of being on track. He came off the bench
and contributed to the Sonics' spirited win, first with some
rebounds and defense and eventually, with scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last week or so has been better. The other night in
Sacramento was a great game. I don't know how long it's been since
I felt as good as I did after the Sacramento game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to believe he is poised to turn this thing around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a great situation. I realize how important these
playoffs are and what you come out of a playoff looking like. I'm
in an ironic situation. Things didn't go well in the regular
season, but being as optimistic as I am, I think I have a great
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He came here full of promise. He came here to play in the
playoffs. Now is the time for Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
