<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      04-21 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KILL PREVIOUS VERSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 el1l  el1l 
 &HT;     el1l 
 &HT;     el1l 
 &HT;     el1l 
 &HT;     THE YOUNG AND THE RELENTLESS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is often said what does not obliterate you, will
make you stronger.
</P>
<P>
   So Paul Westphal is at it again.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, it looked like a time to stick a fork in the
Sonics. But Westphal opted for a paring knife of sorts. The Sonics
coach carved out of the starting lineup despondent power forward
Vin Baker, along with shooting guard Brent Barry and small forward
Ruben Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal boldly inserted little-used Cuban forward Lazaro
Borrell and spare guard Shammond Williams. He also promoted backup
forward Rashard Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Some might call the changes an act of desperation. More
appropriately, they moves amounted to a calculated gamble that
effectively earned the Sonics a Lucky 7 _ as in the seventh seed of
the Western Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, never in recent history has a team guaranteed a playoff
berth overhauled three-fifths of its starting lineup with five
regular-season games left.
</P>
<P>
   Now begs the question: Will the adjustments hold up in the
life-and-death arena that is the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   The timing of it all initially hurt some like rubbing alcohol on
an open wound. But no one is openly upset. No one is struggling.
The only evidence in four legitimate games is that Westphal's
re-vamped lineup has value.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the Sonics appear more hearty by the moves, but
their metamorphose from a stagnant team to one that is dangerously
unpredictable could create a respectable edge against the Utah Jazz
in a first-round playoff series, which begins Saturday in the Delta
Center.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that is what the Sonics are counting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a different look than we've had, and it gives a
lot of different players to have a good game,'' Westphal said. ``We
can see who is having a good game and make adjustments from
strength with guys that are experienced coming in off the bench. We
can play a lot of different styles, and I think we're a harder team
to prepare for. We certainly have a lot more quickness, and
quickness is hard to counteract.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal has been noncommittal on whether he plans to revert to
the team's original starting five. It is possible that Baker, who
has played with confidence in three of the past four games, could
re-join the starters.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lineup the Sonics field likely won't be known until
they step onto the floor for Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   It is, though, difficult to argue with results.
</P>
<P>
   Before Westphal stirred the pot for an April 12 home game
against Minnesota, the Sonics had lost nine of their previous 11
games. Included in that stretch was a five-game losing streak at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the team's downfall seem to coincide with Baker's
struggles. Barry lost his rhythm along the way, too. However, Baker
had grabbed 10 or more rebounds in just one game from Jan. 26 to
March 29. The Sonics went 12-15 during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   As the team fell further under a lethargic trance, losing
streaks became normal for the once-surprising Sonics. While making
the playoffs was never in doubt, they found themselves trying to
climb out of the eighth seed, and a quick exit scenario against the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' record was 3-2 with the lineup changes, a mark
skewed by a season-finale loss to the L.A. Clippers on Wednesday
when the regulars played sparingly. Aside from a 117-103 loss at
Dallas, the newlook Sonics have been fresh, energetic, quick and
flexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lineup we had wasn't really working so change was
forthcoming,'' center Horace Grant said. ``(Westphal) didn't have
to explain anything to us. He's the coach. But those young guys are
giving us a spark. We're winning so why not keep rolling with it? I
wouldn't change a thing. We have a chance to run the ball up and
down the court more than we have all season.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in essence, is how the Sonics expect to beat an aging and
less athletic Jazz team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well with this lineup,'' said Baker, who is still
hoping to reclaim his starting spot. ``Those guys give us a lot of
great energy, and obviously with me coming off the bench, it will
be a different look for (Utah). ...Those guys are learning fast and
enthusiastic on the floor. Myself, Ruben and Brent have been
starters all season, but the changes gives us a chance to get in
with the flow of the game. That's an advantage for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The advantages for the Sonics with Lewis, Williams, Borrell,
Grant and Gary Payton starting are three-fold.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, at 6-foot-1, is lightning quick and able to handle the
ball. That allows Payton to operate without the responsibility of
creating shots for others. Payton can instead run off screens and
attack the basket. And whenever Payton draws double teams, Williams
is adept enough to sink open jump shots or take his man off the
dribble and get shot attempts in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup modifications has induced Payton to play the last
week with renewed energy, although the all-star guard seemed
indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's been effective,'' Payton said. ``I just
know we're winning basketball games. We started a new lineup, OK.
You think about who has been coming in to play more of the minutes.
It's been Vin Baker and (Patterson and Barry) playing the most
minutes. It doesn't make a difference to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to use Lewis centers mostly on his skill level at
6-foot-10. The 20-year-old can handle the ball and create a
mismatch in the post against most small forwards guarding him.
Lewis' shooting range extends to the three-point arc, and he has
the ability to blow past defenders and explode to the basket for a
dunk or layup in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can outquick them and try to get off to a fast start. Youth
is going to be one thing. But we know we're going to have to rely
on experience because Utah is an experienced team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' leaping ability and enthusiasm makes him a chore for
anyone to contain on the boards. He works hard to grab offensive
and defensive rebounds. The coaching staff is captivated by the
versatility and confidence Lewis displays from game to game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most intriguing addition by subtraction was Borrell.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics originally signed the 6-foot-8 forward with an intent
to use him next season. Conventional wisdom suggested that Borrell
needed this season learn English, adjust to the NBA game and life
without his family following his defection.
</P>
<P>
   But what the Sonics learned from Day One in training camp was
that Borrell appeared undaunted about those life changes. He
performed consistently well in practices, using his instincts and
natural feel for the game to establish himself.
</P>
<P>
   He is a crafty defender who does not get burn easily. Although
Borrell is not a serious outside shooting threat, he can score in
the post and take a defender off the dribble. Borrell's most
impressive attribute is his heart. He plays with confidence all the
time and does not appear awe-struck by the NBA arenas and superstar
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any difference to him. He was living in a
shack a year ago,'' Westphal said of Borrell, who defected from
Cuba last season then joined the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Still wondering where Borrell came from and how can the Sonics
afford to rely on him?
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line on Borrell is that he is a seasoned basketball
player. His experience ranges from playing for Cuba in the Olympic
Qualifying tournament last summer to two stints in the Argentina
Basketball League where he averaged 20 points and 10 rebounds
against international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Sonics keep a plus/minus chart of every player. It is
an evaluation that tells coaches how the score fluctuates when that
player is on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last five games Lazaro's plus/minus is better than anyone
we have,'' Westphal said. ``I like that. (The new lineup) gives us
a little bit of unpredictability.''
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantage of playing essentially two rookies (Borrell and
Williams) and Lewis (a second-year player) is that they have no
playoff experience. How they might react is part of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you can't predict these guys,'' assistant coach Nate
McMillan said. ``But these guys do an excellent job of moving
without the ball. They do an excellent job of defending and
covering for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bold move, but everybody was supportive. We needed a
change. Us being unpredictable is something (Utah) has to be
concerned about. Who do you put your center on? Who do you put
(Karl) Malone on? Are they going to all of a sudden become a
trapping team? Are they going to try and run? They don't kn ow what
we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in itself, brings out another positive aspect of the
lineup shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Sonics' young players not respond well, the team can
quickly go to Baker, Patterson or Barry for an early save. In
effect, Westphal, whose rotations have been capricious until now,
has manufactured a sturdy bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of the season, if you don't have a bench, you
don't win. It's just as simple as that,'' said McMillan, who once
was a Sonic starter before Payton's arrival. ``Your starters are
starters, but your bench players are just as important. Both of
those groups are equal. Whoever plays well in the first half
between those 8 to 10 players will finish the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some new young talent. We've got new life and no one
knows what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the playoffs, even if it appears the Sonics are
well done.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
