<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT &LR;      04-21 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUN BY MORA WARMS COLD SHEA
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Melvin Mora dropped his bat and acted as if he had
just hit a single. He motored to first base while keeping his eyes
focused on center field, watching his booming shot off Curtis
Leskanic sail higher and higher. Could it go? Would it go?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it could. Yes, it did.
</P>
<P>
   Mora's first regular-season homer in the major leagues gave the
New York Mets a 5-4 victory over the Milwaukee Brewers in 10
innings at Shea Stadium Thursday night. He finally started trotting
when he got past first base. A swarm of Mets waited for him at home
plate. The postseason hero was suddenly a hero in April, too.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lifeless feeling at Shea before the game even
started. The upper deck was completely empty, the mezzanine was
mostly empty and the fans were mostly chilly. Al Leiter could have
changed this dull atmosphere with a nifty outing, but he failed to
enhance it because he was constantly in danger and was simply
trying to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets survived in a game in which they trailed by 4-1, and
finally they thrived because Mora, who went into the game in the
top of the 10th, crushed Leskanic's 95 mph fastball. The homer
caromed off the television camera stands beyond the center-field
wall, a 417-foot shot that was not as momentous as his homer
against Atlanta in his first National League Championship Series
at-bat last October. But Mora was smiling as if this one was
momentous, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this is big,'' Mora said. ``I like this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Mora faced Leskanic, Edgardo Alfonzo told him that
Leskanic throws a powerful fastball, a nasty slider and a cut
fastball. As Mora strode to the plate, he said later, ``I wanted to
jump on the fastball,'' which he did.
</P>
<P>
   It helped the Mets sweep a three-game series, beat the Brewers
for the eighth straight time and win for the sixth time in their
last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him hit like that in BP,'' said Derek Bell,
referring to batting practice. ``He got a hold of one and I was
like, `Wow.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Leiter struggled all evening while allowing four earned
runs on eight hits and three walks, this would have been a
difficult game for the Mets to lose. The Brewers are more hapless
than pesky and they look like the junior varsity trying to play the
varsity. When Charlie Hayes, who had a homer among his three hits,
is the cleanup batter, the team is not exactly fearsome.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Woodard, who has not won a game since July 16, 1999,
squelched the Mets, except for Mike Piazza's monstrous
second-inning homer, through the first six innings. Bell homered to
begin the seventh, and a single and a walk ended Woodard's night.
Todd Zeile hit a run-scoring single off David Weathers and the
Mets' fourth run scored on Jeromy Burnitz's throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had trouble navigating through the first inning last
season and searched for remedies to solve this problem. The problem
emerged again Thursday night as the Brewers quickly put him in a
1-0 hole. Marquis Grissom doubled and later scored on Burnitz's
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza helped the Mets tie the score as he blasted a 438-foot
homer over the picnic area in left field off Woodard. It was
Piazza's 17th hit in his last 33 at-bats, and it was the most
majestic one.
</P>
<P>
   But James Mouton hit a broken-bat two-run homer off Leiter in
the third, and Hayes poked a homer in the fifth to push the
Milwaukee lead to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Three Mets relievers helped tame the Brewers after that, as Bell
keyed a three-run rally in the seventh and then Mora played the
hero in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Mora is obviously new at this. After a television interview on
the field, a fan threw a T-shirt that hit him in the face. Mora
stopped, picked the shirt up, signed it and politely returned it to
the fan.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? It had been a good night for the utility player with a
penchant for heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to play every day,'' Mora said. ``I'm the kind of
player who likes to play every day. Now I'm going to continue to do
this because this is how they want me to help.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
