   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-COCAINE (Montclart, Colombia) _ New York Times Special
Report: Nearly half the world's supply of cocaine comes from within
150 miles of this isolated Colombian military outpost on the
Putumayo River. So when Lt. German Arenas and his anti-drug troops
recently set out by boat, they knew finding a target would be the
easy part. Four hours later, his squadron of young marines stopped
and marched into the equatorial wilderness, guns at the ready. By
nightfall, they had found three crude cocaine-processing
laboratories in the open jungle, more than 6,000 seedlings of a
new, more potent variety of coca plant, a half-dozen large fields
brimming with ripening coca bushes and four hapless peasants. But
after they destroyed as much as they could, arrested the peasants
and headed back downriver, the soldiers left behind at least
another 200 labs hidden in the dense, trackless jungle and
thousands more acres of coca plants, visible from the air
everywhere across southern Colombia. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT18 and 19 are being sent to NYT photo
clients and locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-LOBBY (Effingham, Ill.) _ Rep. David Phelps, one of
40 Democrats who are undecided about the China trade bill, is as
conflicted about the key vote as is his diverse constituency.
Farmers and agribusinesses urge him to vote yes to open up Chinese
markets; longtime labor allies are against a deal that could cost
union jobs. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CULT (Beijing) _ China has acknowledged some problems in
dealing with the spiritual movement Falun Gong as new reports of
sect members dying in police custody are made. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   WESTBANK-MARTYR (Al-Jaba, West Bank) _ Peace effort or no, it is
still considered a badge of honor in Palestinian society to be a
martyr for the cause. But no one ever expected Hilmiya al-Tous,
mother of 12, to become one. She was not militant; she was not even
political. In this small, isolated village, she raised goats,
chickens and children. That was her life, modest and circumscribed.
By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-CLASSES (Undated) _ The wedding day was set, guests
invited, and Linda Santarelli and Teddy Roland mused about a beach
ceremony near their home in Loxahatchee, Fla. Then they learned of
a new state law giving couples a marriage license discount if they
take a marital education class. They took it, and by the end they
were convinced they were moving too fast. That is just what Florida
lawmakers wanted when, determined to discourage divorce, they began
pushing marriage 101. And across the country, other states are
creating similar programs. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-CAMPAIGN-REGULATE (Undated) _ As more campaigning goes
online, federal regulators are confronting a set of tricky
questions about how _ and whether _ to regulate the Web when it is
used to promote candidates, raise money or encourage political
discussion. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE (Washington) _ Medicare payments for caring for elderly
people at home have declined dramatically. The result: patients are
being forced to stay instead at nursing homes and hospitals, which
are far more expensive. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ White House officials assess
Republican proposals for Medicare coverage of prescription drugs,
explain why President Clinton views them as totally inadequate. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANKS (Moscow) _ MDM Bank recently offered a service
allowing Russian companies to sidestep requirements to set aside
money for pensions and other costs associated with salaries. As a
substitute for salaries, the employees received interest payments
on company deposits in the bank. This is the Alice-in-Wonderland
world of Russian banking. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIOTT-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ When the Marriott hotel chain
agreed in February to pay over $400 million to settle lawsuits
brought by disgruntled investors in its hotels, lawyers on both
sides were quick to praise the deal. But for many of the limited
partners, who put up hundreds of millions of dollars to finance
Marriott's growth in the late 1980s, the deal will mean a huge tax
bill at a time when their investments have finally begun to perform
as promised. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
