<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     04-21 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BACK when, Ray McCallum was named the best little man in college
basketball his senior year at Ball State. And word is that, at 39,
he can still dunk a basketball, although he's no taller _ 5-10 _
than your average sportswriter.
</P>
<P>
   But, no, he couldn't handle Clyde Drexler one on one. If coaches
got to play, too, the University of Houston would have taken a huge
step backward Thursday. Of course, if coaches got to play, Drexler
wouldn't have lost 39 games over his ill-fated two-season trial at
the Cougars' helm and UH probably wouldn't be bringing in McCallum.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, folks. Clyde's spirit might have been willing early on,
but his flesh was never into it. He didn't need the money, and he
found out he didn't need the long hours. But McCallum was never on
the NBA superstar/Hall of Fame track. His short-guy work ethic,
essentially the same gene that turned Napoleon into an emperor,
would be channeled into X's and O's early on. This crazy racket is
McCallum's life.
</P>
<P>
   And it has been a good life. He posted a better record at Ball
State than Rick Majerus had a number of years before him there,
despite having inherited three years of NCAA probation from his
predecessor, Dick Hunsaker. McCallum went 84-15 at home while
averaging 18 victories per season and posting the best winning
percentage (.624) over the first seven seasons of any coach in
league play in the Mid-American Conference's 53-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Another stat: He was 44-0 when the Cardinals held their
opponents under 60 points. Note: His teams get in your face.
</P>
<P>
   So, by any measure except uber-celebrity status, the change
appears to represent tremendous progress, never mind that Ray is as
much an outsider as Clyde was family and as unknown locally as
Drexler was an icon. McCallum is a real coach who eats, sleeps and
breathes the profession. If he can do at UH what he did at Ball
State _ in a word, win _ he won't be an outsider, or unknown, for
long.
</P>
<P>
   OK, should he succeed, can the Cougars keep him? Good question.
But they'll worry about that when the time comes. As athletic
director Chet Gladchuk noted, after saying all the right, polite
things about the residue of the, ahem, Drexler era: ``Winning would
fit nicely into our equation.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Ray's closet is full of red accessories. He doesn't
have to go shopping. He can start recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always recruiting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no alternative, really, as Drexler found out the hard
way.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum's first priority is to ``recruit'' the kids Drexler
left him, especially super-freshman George Williams, selling them
on how much fun his program _ a run-the-floor-offense combined with
a squeeze-the-blood-out-of-you defense _ is going to be. Second, he
needs to convince the incoming studs, Alton Ford and Patrick
Okafor, that UH is still the place for them to further their
education. And, third, he needs to make every high school coach
within a 50-mile radius of Hofheinz Pavilion his new best friend.
</P>
<P>
   If selling real estate is location, location, location, coaching
college basketball is talent, talent, talent. And local talent is
the best kind. McCallum can well appreciate same, having grown up
in Muncie, Ind., not far from Ball State.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler had a significant natural ``in'' on name recognition
alone, and his assistants, Reid Gettys and George Walker, were
familiar faces around town as well. For that reason, some of you
die-hard Cougars types probably believe Gettys would have been a
smarter hire than McCallum because of his longstanding ties to the
community.
</P>
<P>
   But Reid, a practicing lawyer until Drexler dragged him back to
UH, wasn't any more ready to inherit the head coaching reins than
Clyde had been, and he didn't have Clyde's cachet to boot. In
another year, assuming the Drexler regime finally had enjoyed a
semblance of success on the court, promoting Gettys might have made
sense. It simply didn't under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Walker, on the other hand, seems an option McCallum
needs to consider, although coaches tend to favor assistants they
know. Ray's top aide, John Fitzpatrick, will be a candidate to
replace him at Ball State, though, so perhaps a spot will open up
for George.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick and another Ball assistant, Jerry Francis, were in
town Thursday, and they hit Texas running. While McCallum was
handling the all-important ceremonial duties of his hiring, meeting
the administration and the media and glad-handing the alumni, the
two of them charged out to Baytown's Lee College to attempt to
ingratiate themselves with Okafor, said to be upset that Gettys had
been snubbed.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum's stated mission is to restore the Cougars to their
former Phi Slama Jama glory. He must make sure no would-be Clydes
in Houston are permitted to glide elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
