<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3114 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      04-21 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
April is not the time to start tossing around phrases like
``must-win game,'' but the Astros needed Wednesday's victory over
the Los Angeles Dodgers the way Mark Chmura needs a good attorney.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just 14 games into the season, the jury is out on how good the
Astros are, but the first two weeks of the season have offered some
reasons to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Astros salvaged the road trip to San Diego and
Los Angeles with a 2-3 record is encouraging, considering their
overall play.
</P>
<P>
   But certain trends will have to be reversed if they are to win
the National League Central Division title for a fourth time. For
all the talk about the increased offense throughout baseball over
the past few years, pitching is still the key ingredient to a
winning ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows that better than the Astros, who ranked among the
top three NL teams in ERA in each of their championship seasons.
Their current 5.61 ERA is the highest in the NL and a main reason
they have lost eight of their first 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had so much success over the past two years that we
expect to be over .500 and winning ballgames,'' first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said. ``We were 42 games over .500 in 1998 and 32 games
over .500 last year. We don't expect to be under .500, so we have
to turn this thing around now.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, hitter-friendly Enron Field is somewhat responsible for
the inflated ERA, but the pitching hasn't exactly been airtight on
the road, where the Astros have allowed opponents a .307 batting
average and compiled a 5.43 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents are hitting .274 at Enron Field, where the Astros have
a 5.83 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitching has been very inconsistent, and the bullpen has
been disappointing,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``We
have some young and inexperienced guys in our rotation, and that
creates more uncertainty, but I think the rotation is going to be
OK and I think the bullpen is going to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pitching as well as we can pitch, but we have to get
better overall. It's not just one area of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense, which is supposed to be the strength of the team,
has been equally weak. Through Wednesday's games, the Astros' .236
team batting average was 14th in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   Among the factors contributing to the slow start at the plate
are injuries to Ken Caminiti and Moises Alou and battles with
illnesses by Bagwell and Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Astros know they are a better hitting team
than they have shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no consistency with our lineup,'' Biggio said.
``It's been weird. With guys being sick and hurt, we just really
haven't gotten into a groove. If we continue to play like this,
yeah, I'm going to be worried. But it's still in the early stages,
and if we start panicking now we're going to be in some serious
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, your gauge for everything is the All-Star break. You
play the first half, and you see what kind of position you're in.
If you have a chance, you know that by the All-Star break. It's a
long season; you don't panic now. Sooner or later, we're going to
get into a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can only hope that process began Wednesday in Los
Angeles, when they scored 10 runs and banged out a season-high 14
hits, which moved them out of the NL basement in team hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Wednesday, the Astros ranked last in hitting and
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty bad,'' Bagwell said. ``Offensively, we haven't
been at full strength, and that hurts a little bit. But we're still
not doing the things we're capable of doing. What concerns me is
that we're obviously going to need to pitch better. You can't have
to score six runs to win every single night. If that's the case,
that puts more pressure on the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not doing well, which we're not, the pressure
mounts and everyone is trying to do more. Then there's always the
three-run homer instead of `Let's just get the run across and move
guys over' and things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing at Enron Field, there's pressure to score a lot of
runs because other teams are going to score,'' Bagwell continued.
``It's going to mount up if we don't correct the ship pretty quick.
I don't feel real good about this right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to not look at last in hitting and last in
pitching. That's not a good sign, especially when the division is a
pretty good division. If you start slipping, somebody has the
ability in this division to take off. We're going to have to right
the ship pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, like most of his teammates, is quick to point out that
the Astros' struggles are magnified because they have occurred at
the beginning of the season, rather than in June or July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about us too, until I looked at the schedule and
saw that there were a heck of a lot of games left,'' shortstop Tim
Bogar said. ``The way we've played has been very uncharacteristic
of us, but I wouldn't bail on us yet. We have too many veteran guys
who know how to pitch, who know how to hit and who know how to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stink right now, but we won't stink the whole year. The
expectations are high for us because of the way we played the last
three years. To start off this slow, no one is accustomed to it.
We're too good of a team to be (6-8) right now, but we could run
off 10 or 12 wins and be right back in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first guys to panic are always the first guys to fall off
the boat, and we don't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
