<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3115 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-HOUSTON-McCALLUMN     04-21 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-McCALLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
At first, it was the eyes and Ray McCallum's laser-like intensity
that clinched the decision that he should be the next University of
Houston men's basketball coach.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The first time we met, that was the thing I noticed right
away,'' UH athletic director Chet Gladchuk said Thursday as
McCallum was introduced as the Cougars' new coach.
</P>
<P>
   In seven years at Ball State, McCallum's alma mater, the
Cardinals compiled a 126-76 record and made two trips to the NCAA
Tournament and one to the National Invitation Tournament. During
those seven years, the Cougars were 66-123. And they have not been
to the NCAA Tournament since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to outwork coach McCallum,'' said the
5-foot-10 McCallum, a 1983 graduate of Ball State who once was the
all-time career scoring leader in the Mid-American Conference.
``You can see how big I am, so you know I have to do it with work
ethic. That's the way it's going to be with our team. We're going
to bring back the pride and tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach McCallum will get excited, I'll tell you that. You'll
see a hard-working team, and one that has fun with it. I'll be
working that sideline and working those officials. We're going to
get it back. Every day, we're going to be doing something to
improve the Cougar program.''
</P>
<P>
   McCallum, 39, UH's sixth head coach and the third hired in the
last eight years, agreed to a five-year contract that includes
$200,000 in annual base salary and $150,000 a season in guaranteed
outside income. He also can earn bonuses based on overall team
grade-point average, graduation rates and on-the-court achievements
such as postseason appearances and Conference USA records. There
also is a rollover extension for each NCAA appearance.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum was paid $92,000 a year as Ball State's coach.
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk's hiring mission, as it was with new football coach
Dana Dimel, was to connect with a young, energetic coach ``on the
upper side of the learning curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk referred to similar hirings like Georgia Tech's Paul
Hewitt (from Siena) and Nebraska's Barry Collier (from Butler).
</P>
<P>
   McCallum and his wife, Wendy, grew up in Muncie, Ind., attended
high school there and stayed at home to attend Ball State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to leave,'' McCallum said of the move from Muncie,
a college town of about 70,000, to the Houston area and its sprawl
of 4 million people. ``My parents live there, my in-laws live
there, and I left a great team (with just one senior returning from
a 22-9 team).''
</P>
<P>
   McCallum said he doesn't foresee a big adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll just have to allow more time (for the traffic),''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum, introduced three weeks after Clyde Drexler's sudden
resignation March 30 following two seasons as UH coach, met briefly
with his new players Thursday and will meet today with the
basketball staff of George Walker, Reid Martinka, Michael Young and
Byron Smith, who are under contract until June 1. Assistant Reid
Gettys has said he is not interested in returning.
</P>
<P>
   John Fitzpatrick and Jerry Francis, members of McCallum's staff
at Ball State, paid a visit to UH recruit Patrick Okafor at Lee
College in Baytown on Thursday morning. Okafor, Milby's Alton Ford,
Fort Worth Diamond Hill's Chris Booker and Blinn College's Justin
Lyman make up the Cougars' latest recruiting class. McCallum said
he talked briefly Thursday morning with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``They signed to play with Clyde,'' McCallum said of the
recruits signed by Drexler's staff. ``I'm sure that Clyde will be a
supporter of our program. I think I'll be a great coach to play
for. I just want a chance to present our program to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The November signees could request a release from their UH
letters of intent if they decide to play elsewhere because of the
coaching change.
</P>
<P>
   UH president Arthur Smith and Gladchuk acknowledged the
contribution of Drexler and his staff in rekindling interest in the
basketball program despite a two-year record of 19-39.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about succeeding Drexler, a hero of the early-1980s Phi
Slama Jama era, McCallum said, ``The guy who replaces me at Ball
State will feel the same kind of pressure, following a hometown
hero. He has showed local kids they can stay home and have a great
career and receive a great education.''
</P>
<P>
   McCallum said he can't wait to get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right on the edge,'' McCallum said. ``We're tired of
being kicked around. It's time to make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
