r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-L     04-21 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' ERA GOING SKY-HIGH WITH LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Anaheim Angels had ``one of those games'' Thursday
night when they lost to the Toronto Blue Jays 12-11 before 13,985
at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, though, is they've had two of those games in the
past two nights.
</P>
<P>
   One night after starter Ken Hill gave up 10 runs in 3 innings,
Kent Bottenfield gave up nine runs in 3 innings in the series
finale. The Angels made a game of it, rallying from an 11-1 deficit
with eight runs in the sixth inning. They had the go-ahead run at
the plate several times in the final three innings before Blue Jays
closer Billy Koch struck out Orlando Palmeiro to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, with all the runs (23) and hits (33) in the game,
the difference might have been the defensive play made by Blue Jays
shortstop Alex Gonzalez in the ninth. Troy Glaus was on second base
with one out, representing the tying run. Matt Walbeck, one of five
Angels to get three hits, hit a pop up to shallow center field.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez, who entered the game as a defensive replacement in
the eighth inning, made a running, over-the-shoulder catch that all
but sealed the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   By that time Bottenfield was long gone, failing to make it out
of the fourth inning. After an easy first inning, he lost his
ability to locate pitches. The Blue Jays hitters, though, located
those pitches off the barrels of their bats.
</P>
<P>
   They scored three times in the second inning, twice in the
third, then broke it open with six in the fourth. Bottenfield left
the game down 7-1 with two out and two runners on in the fourth.
Kent Mercker came in, walked Tony Batista to load the bases, then
surrendered a grand slam to Darrin Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those days,'' Bottenfield said. ``I had no idea
where the ball was going. For some reason I was hyped up,
everything was going 100 mph. It's like I lost my whole game plan
in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was moving so fast. My heart was going 200 beats a
minute. That's not normal. The game plan I had going in was good,
and I forgot it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels trailed 11-1 but were not out of it, knowing that the
Seattle Mariners scored 47 runs in three games against the Blue
Jays before the Angels came to town.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the sixth inning, the Angels broke out with nine hits,
including two by Mo Vaughn, to narrow the gap to 11-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not satisfied we lost, but I'm satisfied with how this
team came back,'' Vaughn said. ``It shows the team's mentality. We
didn't want to start like we did, but we keep pushing. Teams that
play hard when it isn't going well - that's a sign. ... It shows
we're a team that's going to be around all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's three hits could be a sign he's ready to snap out of an
early- season slump. Darin Erstad's three hits were, well, typical.
Erstad went into the game leading the majors with a .483 average,
and he raised it to .492. Adam Kennedy continued his hot hitting by
going 3 for 5 and scoring twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's encouraging to see we didn't lay down, and kept
fighting,'' Erstad said. ``We've had some crazy games in this
building.''
</P>
<P>
   The past four games could be included among those Erstad was
referring to, as the two teams combined for 73 runs and 111 hits.
The Blue Jays outscored the Angels in the series 41-32 and won
three of four. It was the first series loss for the Angels since
the season-opening series vs. the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   For a lifelong National Leaguer like Angels manager Mike
Scioscia, the high-scoring games take an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything surprises me, obviously I knew it was a
high-scoring league,'' he said. ``These games got a little out of
hand from what I'm used to. It comes back to the basics - make good
pitches and you get guys out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
