<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHRA STRIP A PRIORITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Irwindale Speedway track president Bob
DeFazio says the second-year facility has the inside edge on
attracting a National Hot Rod Association-sponsored drag strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've told us in no uncertain terms that this is their No. 1
choice,'' DeFazio said.
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio and track chief executive officer Jim Williams were
guests of the NHRA when it held its inaugural Las Vegas event two
weeks ago. The two groups met to discuss the NHRA's desire for a
Southern California site for its street legal, import and Junior
Drag events.
</P>
<P>
   NHRA president Tom Compton said Thursday that little has changed
in negotiating with Irwindale, or other tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still awfully early, but things are going well,'' DeFazio
said. ``You can't make soup without the soup.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton has said he would prefer a quarter-mile strip. DeFazio
said the speedway would build an eighth-mile strip. If built, it
would be along the southeast corner of the current track property.
DeFazio said very little of the current site's configurations would
need to be altered.
</P>
<P>
   The NHRA, Fairplex Park and city of La Verne recently agreed to
end the street legal races at Pomona Raceway and to allow only a
set amount of other events. The Junior Drag program was recently
OK'd for the remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly would not be doing this for a large profit,''
DeFazio said. ``We think adding this would be good for the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither organization has set a time limit on the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Streak on the line: Former Evernham/Hawley chief mechanic Todd
Burns will try to keep his winning streak alive in NASCAR Late
Model Twin 40-lap races Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Burns has won the speedway's first two Late Model races. Burns,
from Riverside, won the pole and eight-lap Trophy Dash his last
time out. In both races, Goleta's James Weston has been second, Oak
Hill's Tony Green third and Cathedral City's Guy Goldstein fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The track's Mini-Stock division and USAC's Three-Quarter Midgets
will be making their season debuts on the oval. Super Stocks and
Figure 8s will also race.
</P>
<P>
   Gates open at 4 p.m., with the first Trophy Dash scheduled for a
7 p.m. start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
