<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3120 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     04-21 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' SEASON DOMINATION GIVES OTHERS LITTLE HOPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ How ridiculous is this? The Los Angeles
Lakers post the second-best winning percentage in franchise
history, and herewith, your morning newspaper presents a breakdown
of their losses. All, ahem, 15 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Journalistic nit-picking? No, just consider this a perspective
builder on the eve of the Lakers' pursuit - a very realistic
pursuit - of their first NBA championship in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Because really, the most ridiculous notion right now is that the
Lakers can be beaten in a playoff series at all. And it's their
rare defeats that offer insight into why they are heavily favored
to bring home the Lawrence O'Brien trophy in June.
</P>
<P>
   And why New York Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy almost conceded the
Lakers the title this week, comparing them to one of coach Phil
Jackson's former teams - the 72-10 Chicago Bulls of 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Van Gundy said, ``there's certainly a form of
intimidation by them. I know when we played them, we didn't have
that same belief that we have against a lot of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   --The Lakers lost consecutive games only three times all season
never more than two in a row - and the last pair came this week,
when they had nothing left to gain.
</P>
<P>
   --Only three teams beat the Lakers more than once this season.
One, the Houston Rockets, missed the playoffs. The second, the
Portland Trail Blazers, have been a mess since the Lakers beat them
Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The third team is the San Antonio Spurs, the only team to win a
season series against the Lakers this season (3-1). But the Spurs'
last two wins come with, well, asterisks: Shaquille O'Neal didn't
play April 8, and he was among a handful of starters who played
limited minutes in a meaningless season finale two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   --From the second round on, all playoff series are seven games.
It takes four victories to win a series. The Lakers lost four out
of seven games just once all season - during a shaky stretch in
late January when they lost six of nine games. After that slide,
the Lakers went 33-4 to finish the season.
</P>
<P>
   --They have home-court advantage throughout the playoffs, and
the Lakers lost just five times at Staples Center this season.
</P>
<P>
   --And when they do have to hit the road, the Lakers have the
confidence earned by a league-best 31-10 road record.
</P>
<P>
   How do you beat the Lakers? Golden State Warriors coach Garry
St. Jean burst into high-pitched laughter at the very question. ``I
don't think anybody's going to beat them consistently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one has this season, as the Lakers have bounced back quickly
from defeat. But as if to pump up opposing coaches' blood pressure
even more, Jackson points to another sign that his team has become
truly dominant: On the occasions when the Lakers played the same
opponent twice in a short span - a week or two - they usually won
the second game (and often the first one, too).
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are adjustment games, or reading games, that really
measure how do you read an opponent from game X to game Y in the
regular season, what adjustments have you been able to make,''
Jackson said. ``And we've done, I thought, very well in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But if that's a harbinger of doom to opponents, Jackson won't
say so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that you're going to convince either Sacramento
or San Antonio or Seattle of that,'' he said. ``Players don't think
in those terms.''
</P>
<P>
   A breakdown of the losses reveals few methods for beating the
Lakers. Double-teaming O'Neal won't always work (unless you have
Tim Duncan and David Robinson), and intentional fouling doesn't
work much either (ask Dallas' Don Nelson).
</P>
<P>
   The majority of losses fall into three categories, none offering
much hope to opponents:
</P>
<P>
   THE NO-SHOWS: Kobe Bryant missed the first month of the season
with a broken hand, and the Lakers collected 27 percent of their
losses (four) before he returned Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was a loss at Portland, in a game in which O'Neal was
ejected, stopping a Lakers rally in the fourth quarter. They lost
at home to the Houston Rockets, while O'Neal was serving a
suspension for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   They also lost at home to the Toronto Raptors, and a road game
to the Denver Nuggets, two athletic teams that required a perimeter
defender like Bryant to slow them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we beat them, they were without Kobe Bryant,'' Denver coach
Dan Issel said. ``So if you get them without Kobe Bryant, you have
a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was missing for the Lakers' recent home loss to San
Antonio and was held out of the fourth quarter in their loss to the
Spurs this week. Only 10 losses came with both O'Neal and Bryant on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   THE MISSTEPS: In Bryant's first start of the season, Dec. 8, the
Lakers lost at Sacramento. In that defeat, the Lakers got sucked
into the Kings' uptempo game, and Bryant coughed up six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Lakers went 2-3 this season when Bryant committed
six turnovers. The other losses: at Washington, March 16, and at
Dallas, April 18. In Bryant's two other six-turnover games, the
Lakers struggled to pull out the wins - against Cleveland on Jan.
19 and Minnesota on April 16.
</P>
<P>
   FOUL PLAY: One other note to would-be spoilers of the Lakers'
championship run. Go at Shaq and Kobe. Go directly at Shaq and
Kobe, and get them in foul trouble early.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers lost at Washington, Bryant got into foul trouble
and eventually fouled out trying to contain Rod Strickland at one
end, hounded by Mitch Richmond at the other.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also fouled out trying to stop the Pacers' Travis Best,
who dealt him three fouls in the decisive fourth quarter when the
Lakers lost at Indiana on Jan. 14, and he fouled out in the Lakers'
home loss to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was also in foul trouble in the Washington loss, the
Denver loss and the back-to-back defeats at Houston and San Antonio
on Jan. 30-Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   So knocking off the Lakers between now and June will be a tall
order for anyone. But they're not all making Van Gundy-like
concession speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're the clear-cut favorites,'' Utah's Karl Malone
said. ``But there's a lot of teams that want what they want. So you
can't convince other teams out there they don't have a chance to
play against them.''
</P>
<P>
   And a cautionary note from Jackson, who has been in this
position many times before: ``We've been able to do it in an
82-game season. That doesn't mean a series is going to go any
easier for us than anybody else,'' he said. ``It's actually nice
and an honor to have the pressure put on us like this. It says
something about the way we've been playing. But we certainly can't
let it go to our heads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
