<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3155 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBO-AVENGERS-COBRAS-R     04-21 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-AVENGERS-COBRAS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVENGERS LOSE HOME OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was their inaugural regular-season home game,
but the Los Angeles Avengers already earned their first on-field
distinction Thursday night: They are the worst expansion franchise
in the Arena Football League.
</P>
<P>
   At least for today anyway, following their 58-50 loss to the
league's other expansion team, the Carolina Cobras, before 10,718
at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, this is the Arena Football League, so the fans were
probably more pleased with the constant barrage of points than who
actually won the game.
</P>
<P>
   And the game was entertaining, with the Avengers scoring a
touchdown with 24 seconds left on a pass from quarterback Scott
Semptimphelter to Chris Jackson to cut the lead to 52-50. But
Carolina's Dexter Dawson intercepted Semptimphelter's pass on the
two-point conversion to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   The Cobras added a consolation touchdown on a 10-yard run by
quarterback Jim Arellanes with eight seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But 108 total points scored with flair and style didn't do much
for the Avengers' morale, especially when Carolina scored 21 points
off three L.A. fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't quite the way the Avengers wanted the official home
opener to unfold against their fellow expansion colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have gotten blown out, really,'' Avengers coach Stan
Brock said. ``The turnovers are what kill you. I don't like losing
anywhere, but this is home. The fans are here, and you're
establishing something. This is our turf.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rough week for the Avengers (0-2), who had only a few
days to prepare for the Cobras (1-1) after losing their season
opener to Grand Rapids last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, they showed less composure than Carolina,
despite having a team composed of mostly veteran players. Carolina,
by contrast, chose to stock its expansion roster with rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (1-1) had no turnovers while the Avengers (0-2)
finished with four.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that shouldn't happen with a veteran team,''
Semptimphelter said. ``We've all got to look at ourselves. Whether
it's a change of players, who knows? When you lose, you get sent
home.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss certainly won't discourage Brock from making promised
roster changes next week, when he has more time to evaluate the
personnel as the team takes a 10-day break before its next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to put a group out there that can win,'' Brock said.
``I don't like to lose. I don't accept losing, no matter who we
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the mistakes, the Avengers were in the game
throughout, and managed to rally to tie the contest 31-31 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But the errors continued in the third quarter when Aaron Frazier
fumbled for the second time, and Carolina quickly jumped out to a
45-31 lead. The Avengers never fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The game featured two excellent performances by the
quarterbacks. Carolina's Arellanes, the former Valley College star,
passed for 231 yards and four touchdowns without an interception.
Semptimphelter completed 25 of 39 passes for 313 yards and six
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Some diehard fans were apparently unaware of those stats,
however, considering they were chanting ``We want Todd'' in the
third quarter, begging for an appearance by Avengers backup
quarterback Todd Marinovich. He did not play.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: In arena football, any ball that goes in the stands is
property of the fans. So after a ballboy took away a football from
a small child in the end-zone seats following a kickoff, Avengers
coach Stan Brock ran over and gave the fan a free ball. Unlike the
Avengers' exhibition game, no fans fell over the retaining wall and
onto the field while chasing loose balls Thursday night. ...
</P>
<P>
   Former Muir High and USC cornerback Ken Haslip, who has been the
property of the Canadian Football League's Edmonton Eskimos, said
he still intends to play for the Avengers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 0306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0035 </DOCNO>
