   &UR; PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This week's droll ``Primary Color'' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RESURGENCE OF LAOS' FORGOTTEN WAR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HMONG-LAOS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southeast Asia's poor relation, Laos, could be facing a
resurgence of a war that many had forgotten. There is evidence of a
renewed campaign by surviving remnants of the Hmong guerrilla army
that America's CIA trained to fight Lao communists during the
Vietnam War. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENTRAL ASIA AND AMERICA: WOOED _ BUT NOT WOWED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YANKS-CENTRALASIA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fresh on the heels of Vladimir Putin's election last month as
Russia's new president, the American government has wasted no time
in asserting its interests in the oil-rich region of the ex-Soviet
Central Asian republics. It dispatched a series of senior
government officials _ including CIA head George Tennet, FBI
Director Louis Freeh and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright _ to
the region immediately following the Russian election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAUDI ARABIA ON THE DOLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAUDI-REALITYCHECK-ECONOMIST-900&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saudis have long accepted their rulers' lavish way of life as
the price for rapid development and relative stability. But Saudi
Arabia's almost limitless reserves of oil are no longer quite
enough to pay for everything _ even with prices at a steep $25 or
so a barrel. With income per person having tumbled from $16,650 in
dear-oil 1981 to $6,526 in cheap-oil 1998, it is becoming painfully
clear that the Saudi regime cannot keep itself and all of its
citizens solvent without a major economic overhaul. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 75-word optional trim; 1,050 words uncut) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUN, SURF, AND DEATH: AIDS DECIMATES CARIBBEAN COUNTRIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIV-CARIBBEAN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Africa apart, nowhere in the world suffers more from AIDS than
the countries of the Caribbean. The impact is broad, growing, and
potentially devastating to what are already some of the most
vulnerable countries in the Americas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DEATH OF A SALESMAN: WEB SITES BURY WILLIE LOMANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEB-KILLS-SALESMEN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In all the upheaval that has been brought about by changing
technology, one constant has remained: the sales force has
maintained its aura of 1960s Organization Man. Driving to customer
calls, white-shirted and neatly coiffed, the salesman seems to have
changed little in decades. Alas, not for much longer. E-business,
transformer of all corporate processes, has arrived in the land of
strong handshakes and special deals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RE-INVENTING THE WHEEL: PIRELLI TIRES TREAD NEW GROUND &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW-SPIN-TIREMAKING-ECONOMIST-700&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every company dreams of changing its industry. Pirelli, an
Italian industrial group spanning tires and cables, may actually
succeed. If a new, flexible and revolutionary tire-production
system fulfils its potential, tire making will never be the same
again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 500 words; 1,475 uncut) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
