<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POLITICS-POLITE-0422-     04-21 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-POLITE-0422-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME CALL FOR A LITTLE CIVILITY ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL, PLEASE
 &HT;    630&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Enough, already! The purveyors of etiquette and
civility have had it up to their arched eyebrows with rude
political candidates and the unruly journalists who pursue them.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns may not be tea parties, but a little politeness in our
politics wouldn't hurt. It would even bring honest differences into
sharper focus, they maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the rules of etiquette that enable people to air
controversy,'' Judith Martin, better known as the columnist ``Miss
Manners,'' declaimed this week at a forum at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger the controversy, the more rules you need,'' she
said, ticking off examples such as Robert's Rules of Order for
legislatures, the formalities of the courtroom and military
protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Few such restraints exist on the campaign trail, where attack
ads smear opponents, candidates misstate each other's positions and
video masters use techno-tricks to ``morph'' a competitor's face
into something akin to Frankenstein. Add to that the rise is
surreptitious phone campaigns in which callers try to plant doubts
about an opposing candidate's character.
</P>
<P>
   These are all among the no-nos in ``The Little Book of Campaign
Etiquette,'' authored with a light touch by Stephen Hess of
Brookings and updated for this election year. The guide lays out
rules for the political road from A (for advertising without
distortion) to W (winning or losing with grace).
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, a collection of about 50 denominations known
as the Interfaith Alliance has drawn up its list of ``thou shalt
nots.'' The group denounces ``deception, half-truths, falsification
or innuendo,'' and calls on politicians to avoid all references
that tend to ``demonize or dehumanize those holding opinions
different from yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts are hardly the first attempts to bring civility to
a field that has long resisted taming.
</P>
<P>
   ``In politics, etiquette has been treated as such a sissy
restraint on virtue that obeying it must be a sign of moral
turpitude and defying it a sign of moral fervor,'' Miss Manners
writes in the introduction of Hess's book.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Hess offers rules of etiquette for the campaigners, the
press and even the public.
</P>
<P>
   For candidates, he says that ``comparison,'' which highlights
legitimate policy differences, is good. But he says its evil twin,
``negative'' campaigning, is debasing American politics. Hess
defines ``negative'' campaigning as ``nasty and mean-spirited
remarks based on rumors, lies, and half-truths.''
</P>
<P>
   The book urges journalists to overcompensate for their biases,
stop using bellicose metaphors such as ``battleground'' and ``war
chests,'' and be willing to admit their own mistakes. ``Being a
professional should mean sometimes saying you're sorry,'' Hess
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign etiquette requires citizens to call ``local TV stations
and newspapers, as well as the headquarters of slandered
candidates, to register disgust'' whenever they receive a call that
appears to be part of a smear campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hess also assigns a rule of etiquette for sex scandals, which
during the Clinton administration have divided the public into
those who are outraged at the politician's misbehavior and those
who are angry at the news media for reporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual misconduct should be part of campaign coverage, he says,
if the candidate lies about it or is currently involved in a
liaison, if the relationship affects the politician's public life,
or if the candidate is guilty of outright hypocrisy. The Wall
Street Journal's Albert R. Hunt, who formulated this scandal test
in 1992, told the Brookings gathering this week that he still
stands behind it.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether anyone will heed these rules of campaign
decorum.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent presidential primaries, all the major participants
signed on to the Interfaith Alliance campaign credo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential candidates affirmed civility as a concept
almost like motherhood and apple pie. It sounded like they were
running for Holy Man of the Year,'' said the Rev. C. Welton Gaddy,
executive director of the interfaith group.
</P>
<P>
   But when the campaign heated up, Gaddy acknowledged, the
promises went up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   His group has not given up, however. They announced this week
that more than two dozen congressional candidates from both parties
have endorsed its standards.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have signed up are Florida's three leading
candidates for U.S. Senate, Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher
and Rep. Bill McCollum, both Republicans, and Bill Nelson, the
Democratic state insurance commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Also endorsing the standards are House candidates, including
Democrat Roger Kahn, who is running in Georgia's 7th Congressional
District, and Rep. Tom Sawyer, running for re-election in the 14th
District of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www:brookings.org, www:interfaithalliance.org
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
