<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-JESSE-COLUMN-N     04-21 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-JESSE-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT RACISM ACROSS THE RAINBOW, REV. JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating for all needing. For use Thursday, April 20, or
thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An open letter to the Rev. Jesse Jackson:
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, it was said the most dangerous place in the
world was the space between you and a TV camera.
</P>
<P>
   Cute. But as I've said before, why shouldn't you be a publicity
hound? How can you not take advantage of your fame to advance the
cause of the week or the boycott of the month? It's your job. It's
what you do. It's who you are.
</P>
<P>
   Saw you were in the news again last week. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   You toured Gladstone Elementary School in Chicago and encouraged
education officials to improve conditions in minority-attended
schools. And you marched with 1,000 supporters to Cook County Jail
to protest racial profiling and to call for better treatment of
incarcerated minorities. Then you protested racial profiling in a
Chicago suburb.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, your activities were well-documented by the media.
Good job, reverend. You keep walking and talking, we'll keep
writing and broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   In that same vein, I don't know what you've got on your calendar
this week, but might I bring something to your attention?
</P>
<P>
   It's an alleged hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, a 25-year-old man man was walking on the
South Side of Chicago about 6 p.m. last Monday, on his way from his
job at Columbia College to an art studio, when he was suddenly and
without provocation attacked by a teen-ager wielding a golf club.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager allegedly bashed the young man in the head with
the club, causing a deep gash that would require multiple stitches.
As he swung the club, the attacker allegedly made a pointed
reference to the young man's race and said something like, ``You
... shouldn't be here. ... you don't belong!''
</P>
<P>
   I suppose we can't be shocked that this sort of thing still goes
on in the year 2000, reverend _ but we can be outraged, appalled
and disgusted. What kind of world do we live in when a young man is
attacked in broad daylight simply because of the color of his skin?
</P>
<P>
   A Chicago police spokesman told me that a 14-year-old suspect
has admitted he attacked the young man and made the racial remarks.
The juvenile _ already on probation for a stickup _ was picked out
of a lineup by the victim. He faces felony charges of aggravated
battery and committing a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   Call a press conference, Rev. Jackson. Take a photo op with the
victim. Demand justice. Lead a march through the neighborhood.
Initiate a healing process within the hateful soul of this young
assailant.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but what am I doing, advising you? You're the master of
protest theater! You don't need any tips from me.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I haven't mentioned, though I can't see why it would
make any difference in the grand scheme of things:
</P>
<P>
   The victim is white. His alleged attacker, who reportedly
shouted, ``You white boys shouldn't be here! Go on, whitey, you
don't belong''?
</P>
<P>
   Black.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an interesting statistic, reverend. According to the
Chicago Commission on Human Relations, in 1999 there were 20
reports of blacks attacking whites because of race, and 22 reports
of whites attacking blacks.
</P>
<P>
   So it's about ``even,'' if we can use such a term to describe
this garbage.
</P>
<P>
   As you've no doubt heard over the years, Rev. Jackson, a lot of
white people wonder why you seem to be concerned exclusively with
injustices, inequality, hatred and prejudice as it affects black
people. Your critics seem to think you should feel everyone's pain
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   That's not fair. On the other hand, why wouldn't you be offended
by this alleged incident of last week? Why wouldn't you take a
public stance against hate crime on any side of the rainbow
coalition?
</P>
<P>
   Even from a cynical standpoint, imagine the public relations
value in making this your cause celebre of the moment. Even your
most virulent and vocal detractors would have to admit you'd thrown
them a curve. Even the whites who can't say your name without
making a sour face would have to give you credit for being an equal
opportunity crusader for justice.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can galvanize the media like you, Rev. Jackson. So here's
the question:
</P>
<P>
   Got anything to say about that alleged racial hate crime that
took place in Chicago last week?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
RICHARD ROEPER column and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
