<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3244 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN22-COX     04-21 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maybe you should let your child wear the Emperor's new uniform
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ If there is something that I understand less
than why we really need uniforms at our local junior high, it is
why some parents seem to be so upset over the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The high percentage of teens wear uniforms daily: blue jeans and
a t-shirt. They all look alike now. With little exception, there
isn't a thread of intentional individuality in clothing from ages
12 to 17. For teens, being an individual is not seen as a good
thing and this conformity is supported, sometimes forcefully, by
the parents themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (This, of course, is also the reason I am baffled about why we
need uniforms, but, that is another column.)
</P>
<P>
   But for a couple of months, anyway, your child will trot off to
school looking ever so nice and neat. Is that a bad thing? Haven't
you been trying to do that forever?
</P>
<P>
   Rejoice and take plenty of pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Because, unfortunately, it will not last. Within just a few
months time, the uniforms will get scruffy or show fraying or
downright holes. Some will lose buttons that will never be
repaired. Some will be put in the wash with red or purple socks and
will forever carry the patina of the laundry-challenged.
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, perhaps they will change the uniforms to tie-die
so that the coming mustard and ketchup stains will be
complimentary, or at least unnoticeable.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems to me that the absolute worst thing you can say
about uniforms is that they will have no effect at all. And however
much you hate the idea, you must agree to the fact that a few
students may actually benefit from the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   So why the uproar from some parents? I haven't heard a single
compelling argument that uniforms will hurt anyone.
</P>
<P>
   If you are really concerned about your child's stunted
individuality, I suggest you let them practice it with abandon
elsewhere. Let them wear their beer T-shirts to church. Take them
out to eat wearing the Emperor's new uniform. Let them be free!
</P>
<P>
   To those who think that we are asking too much of our dear,
sweet children, think just a moment please. Most of us send them to
school expecting them to eat cafeteria food, others willfully send
them off on speeding school buses. Your concern is in the wrong
place.
</P>
<P>
   In more than three years, no public discussion has depressed me
more than those who oppose the necessity of providing uniforms for
those who cannot afford them.
</P>
<P>
   Uniforms may be less expensive than designer clothes, but they
may be much more expensive than some of the clothes needy children
were going to wear.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major selling points of this whole program is
self-esteem for those who cannot afford good clothes, remember?
</P>
<P>
   Some families have a ritual each year of buying new school
clothes and think that is the way it is for all children.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Most of us don't understand what real poverty is all
about.
</P>
<P>
   There are more children than we would like to believe in our
community who simply don't get new store-bought clothes _ ever.
They use hand-me-downs from relatives or they go to resale shops
and get them at much-reduced prices. Some simply fit into the
clothes they wore last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's wonderful that, as the program begins, private donations
have been helping these children, but school district officials
need to understand this is our responsibility, donations or not.
When donations dry up over the months or years, poor kids will
still be needing uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   If we aren't prepared to use tax money to pay for these few
uniforms, then we shouldn't begin the program at all.
</P>
<P>
   These are the students who might actually benefit. We should not
leave them without a safety net.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
