<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3245 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN22-COX     04-21 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Out of Egypt: Tombs, temples, people preserved in memory
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABU SIMBEL, Egypt _ She was sitting atop her suitcase as I
struggled to get it closed. Packing for the trip home is our
biggest challenge when we go abroad. A souvenir here and a souvenir
there, and pretty soon we have a yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can hang on two more days I think you'll survive,'' she
said. Abu Simbel, home of the Temple of Ramses II and our last
stop, lies deep in Africa, near the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure hope so,'' I said. ``I'd hate to die over here and wind
up just another mummy.'' After viewing the mummies in the King Tut
collection in Cairo, I don't think I'd especially enjoy being one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mention it before we left home,'' she said, ``but
when I told our pastor we were planning a trip to Egypt he said an
elderly member of his former church died over here. His wife
thought it too much trouble to bring him home, so she just left him
in one of the mausoleums.'' One thing I appreciate about my wife is
her sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Our excursion to Cairo and up the Nile River has been
enlightening. I learned not to say Sahara Desert. Sahara means
desert in Arabic. Saying Sahara Desert is like saying Desert
Desert, or like saying Liberal Democrat back home in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Our Egyptologist guide cleared up a misunderstanding about the
Pyramids. They were not built by slaves toiling under whips of
cruel overseers as depicted by Hollywood. They were built by local
farmers, who when the growing season was over, were hired out to
wrestle 20-ton blocks of granite to pick up a little extra change
from wages paid by generous kings.
</P>
<P>
   That's their story and they're sticking to it. We had a similar
situation in Fayette County in the '30s and early '40s when farmers
were hired on at the peach packing plant in Woolsey after lay-by
time.
</P>
<P>
   On the voyage up the Nile and down into Africa, our numerous
stops included a visit to King Tut's tomb, the temple at Luxor
where terrorists machine-gun tourists, and the Temple of Karnak,
made famous by Johnny Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has no shortage of antiquities. In fact, if the Russians
hadn't sprung for a loan to finance a dam for the world's largest
man-made lake at Aswan, inundating thousands of acres and hundreds
of tombs and temples, we'd have been lucky to be home for Fourth of
July.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptians are proud of their embalming skills. They were
described in detail at almost every stop. Although this tended to
become redundant and a little boring, it was worth the time. If
Social Security goes into the tank, I'm now qualified for at least
part-time work at one of the H.M. Patterson &AMP; Son funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a bow-splintering collision with another boat on a
sailing trip at Aswan, where sailors are endowed with skills
similar to New York taxi drivers, the highlight of our Nile cruise
was a celebration of Jim and Marjorie Waggoner's 30th wedding
anniversary. The Waggoners have one of the most successful mixed
marriages I know about. She is a devout Florida Gator and he an
unabashed barking Georgia Bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   Since they bake a cake and pass out free champagne, it's prudent
to line up several anniversaries and birthdays whenever you're
aboard ship with a tour group. My colleague Bobby Mobley has become
a much sought-after traveling companion after word got around that
he can always be depended on for one of each on any given trip.
</P>
<P>
   English-language newspapers in Egypt carry a lot of interesting
news that is ignored at home. I was surprised to learn that
transplanting pig parts into humans has become so successful that
only the eyes are not used. Pigs have red eyes and nobody wants red
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Gazette also reported a local trend I wouldn't mind seeing
take hold at home. You can rent a preacher in Cairo. The reverend
will come to your home for a set fee and deliver a sermon as long
or short as you specify, and since you're paying, say pretty much
what you want to hear. You don't have to hold hands with strangers
or try to sing politically correct hymns even the choir doesn't
know.
</P>
<P>
   According to our Egyptologist guide, average per capita income
is a little more than U.S. $1,300. The low figure isn't all that
surprising considering that a man can have up to four wives and has
to pray five times a day. Not much time is left for earning a
living.
</P>
<P>
   Counting all the bad things that could have happened, including
Russian-made airplanes that make funny noises and are flown by
pilots who might take a notion to drop in on Allah, this trip
hasn't been all that bad. There is one good side effect I had not
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have any social engagements in Peachtree City or north
Atlanta right after we get home?'' I asked my wife. ``It would be
an ideal time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one in Peachtree City,'' she replied. ``Why is it an
ideal time?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because with two weeks away from the garden and not having to
grease the bushhog, my fingernails are clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
