<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3247 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GOSPEL-MUSIC22-COX     04-21 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL-MUSIC22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian musicians gather to focus on God
 &HT;    By James Lloyd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ One of the little-publicized parts of Gospel
Music Week is the Sunday-night worship service. It's the one time
of the week when the Christian music artists, retailers, industry
representatives and media who are in town for seminars, networking
and lots of performances forget about careers and appearances and
gather as a body to focus on God.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, it is among the week's highlights, and this year
was no exception. In 1999, the event was moved to the Gaylord
Center and was open to the public for the first time. Sunday's
musical service, however, was only for those attending Gospel Music
Week and returned to the more intimate surroundings of Ryman
Auditorium, an appropriate venue because it was once a church and
still feels like holy ground.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 well-known worship leaders, from Fred Hammond to
Michael W. Smith to Darlene Zchesch, led songs during the 2
1/2-hour service. From the boisterous celebration of Hammond
leading ``We Lift Up Your Name From Praise'' to the humility of
Smith choosing others' praise songs rather than his own, to Pete
Shambrook's quiet, awe-filled plea, ``Give Me Jesus,'' the service
ebbed and flowed in a river of unself-conscious expression.
</P>
<P>
   The only nonmusical moments were a prayer and benediction led by
Gospel Music Association Chaplain Darrell A. Harris, who during one
particularly moving song could be spotted in the wings offstage
with his hands raised, dancing to the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   The modern worship songs led by Shambrook and Rita Springer were
intimate and painfully honest, emphasizing God as
overcomer-redeemer and humanity as broken, yet salvageable. As a
counterpoint, Fernando Ortega offered the traditional hymns ``Come
O' Redeemer Come'' and ``Come Thou Fount,'' whose lyrics showed
that hymn writers' subject matter hasn't changed as much as some
critics of current music might think.
</P>
<P>
   The service seemed a call to surrender all to God, a spirit
summed up by Zchesch in ``Potters Hand'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Take me, mold me/Use me, fill me/I give my life to the
Potter's hand./Call me, guide me/Lead me, walk beside me/I give my
life to the Potter's hand.'' Amid all the ``business'' of Gospel
Music Week, Sunday's service offered a much-needed pause for
spiritual refreshment and renewal _ and a healthy motivation check.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
