<P>
   MUSEUM-SHAPIRO _ ATLANTA _ Profile of Michael Shapiro, the new
director of the High Museum of Art. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SHAPIRO-BIO _ ATLANTA _ Thumbnail bio of Michael Shapiro, the
new director of the High Museum of Art. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTO. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ONCE-AND-AGAIN _ A few weeks ago, I was on the phone with a
publicist for HBO. After we chatted at length about The Sopranos,
we turned our attention to other TV shows we like and don't like.
``Do you watch Once and Again?'' I asked. ``Nah, it's too sappy,''
the publicist said. ``I saw the first two episodes and stopped
watching.'' Of course, I told her that was a mistake. A big one, in
fact. Not only is Once and Again, whose season finale airs Monday,
far from sappy, it remains TV's best new drama. Calm down, West
Wing fans. NBC's political drama comes in a close second.
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post). 14. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   SPRING BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SOUTH-MYSTERIES _ Southern mystery writers have learned a
valuable lesson from such masters of the genre as Raymond Chandler
and Dashiell Hammett: Where a crime takes place is as important as
whodunit. Carl Hiaasen's novels of greedy developers destroying the
environment would not be the same outside of ecologically fragile
south Florida. James W. Hall's bone-fishing loner Thorn would be
lost away from the Florida Keys. And Kathy Hogan Trocheck's
Callahan Garrity would seem out of place cleaning houses anywhere
except in Atlanta. (OBriant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 60.
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-FICTION _ What's new in fiction. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 44. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ROBBINS _ Review of Tom Robbins' new novel, ``Fiece
Invalids Home From Hot Climates.'' (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 16 EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-RAY-REVERSE _ Review of Daniel Wallace's novel ``Ray in
Reverse.'' (Jacobs, Atkanta Jounal-Constitution). 17. EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-BIOGRAPHIES _ What's new in biography, autobiography and
memoir, including Sidney Poitier's ``A Spiritual Autobiography.''
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-LANCE _ Short feature on Lance Armstrong's memoir ``It's
Not About the Bike: My Journey Back to Life.'' (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 6. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-NONFICTION _ What's new in nonfiction. (Harrison, Atkanta
Jounal-Constitution). 38. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-RAISINGBOYS _ Books about raising boys are hot. A quick
look at three of the more intriguing ones coming up: ``Real Boys'
Voices,'' ``The War Against Boys'' and ``Boys Into Men: Raising Our
African American Teenage Sons.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WOMEN _ Between them, they had written 11 books, but never
one together. Best friends for a quarter-century, they had actually
only lived in the same city once. Now they'd be living in the same
house to finish the book. What sounds like the basis for a wacky TV
sitcom is the real-life story behind ``I Know Just What You Mean''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25), a new book that turns the spotlight on
women's friendships. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SHIELDS _ Review of Carol Shields' stories ``Dressing Up
for the Carnival.'' (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ Five years ago, when the Library of America series
inducted Raymond Chandler into what amounts to a hall of fame of
the native tongue, it was acknowledgment that the detective mystery
had achieved a certain respectability. ``As I look back on my own
stories,'' he wrote in ``The Simple Art of Murder,'' ``it would be
absurd if I did not wish they had been better. But if they had been
much better they would not have been published.'' Chandler wrote
pulp fiction, and he neither apologized for it nor thought it
literary. And yet literary it was _ in the creation of a believable
character and a psychological world, in the cadence of his
sentences, in the concrete images. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 23. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SOUTH _ What's new in southern fiction and nonfiction.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WILLIE _ Breakout on ``Remembering Willie,'' a collection
of tributes from author Willie Morris' funeral Aug. 5 in Yazoo
City, Miss., as well as appreciations from newspapers and magazines
around the county. (OBriant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6.
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 22
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET HEALTHY LIVING PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET HEALTHY LIVING 0418: TREATING SHYNESS -- A professor at
the Shyness Research Institute at Indiana University Southeast has
studied very aspect of shyness: shyness on the Internet, shyness in
various cultures, the strategies shy people use to deal with their
fears. He's convinced he can help. (Moss, Dayton Daily News) Art
includes an 4-column color illustration and a 1-column photo of the
book.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHYNESS TIPS BOX -- Tips on parenting shy children.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHYNESS FACTS BOX -- Some basic facts about shyness.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKIN STRESS: Dr. Marta Rendon, a dermatologist, says at
least 10 common skin disorders, including acne, dandruff and hives,
are either triggered or worsened by stress. ``We don't know exactly
how or why stress triggers these diseases. And people don't have to
have any psychological disorder. It's just the way they deal with
stress, how the stress affects their body,'' she said. (Susman,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKIN BOX -- A list of stress-related skin disorders.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BETTER ABS -- With warm weather approaching, many fitness
buffs are placing greater emphasis on well-defined abdominals.
(O'Brian, Waco Tribune-Herald) Art includes 1-column color photo of
a woman with ``six-pack'' abs.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL-MUSIC _ One of the little-publicized parts of Gospel
Music Week is the Sunday-night worship service. It's the one time
of the week when the Christian music artists, retailers, industry
representatives and media who are in town for seminars, networking
and lots of performances forget about careers and appearances and
gather as a body to focus on God. (Lloyd, Dayton Daily News). 11.
MOVED
</P>
