<HEADER>
A3255 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-ADV28-NY     04-21 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-ADV28-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV28 
 TELL YOUR HUSBAND YOU WANT HIM TO BE YOUR LOVE SLAVE  
 FOR USE FRI., APRIL 28, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DRJOY-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call (888)-269-8796. 
 By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: I've been married for 14 years to a wonderful guy,
who has no concept of romance. He thinks romance and sex are the
same, and expects me to be ready whenever he is.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried everything _ hints, suggestions and coming right
out with it, but to no avail. I can't remember the last time I had
a climax. Sex seems so dry and mechanical.
</P>
<P>
   Am I crazy or do women need more time? I would give anything for
a soft touch or a compliment. Most of the time I feel like he
doesn't care as long as he is satisfied, and that is making me
depressed. Should I accept the fact that I will never enjoy sex
again? _ R.D.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: It is time to have a serious conversation with your
husband. Criticizing his technique will only make him mad. Why not
say to him: ``Listen, I want you to be my love slave tonight. I'm
going to tell you exactly what to do and how to do it. Then I'll be
your love slave tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   This should be fun for both of you. Most men haven't really been
taught much about sex. You're absolutely right that women need more
time to become relaxed and lubricated, but don't give up on him or
the relationship. You need to be braver and more assertive. Explain
to him _ in a playful way _ what you'd like him to do.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: My girlfriend of six months told me that she
wanted to break up with me because she goes to college about three
hours from were I live. She also told me that she has mixed
feelings about the decision because she really likes me but wants
to spend time with her friends at school.
</P>
<P>
   She usually comes down to my place every weekend. She said that
she still wants to come visit me and told me not to jump into
another relationship right away because she may change her mind. I
told her it would be too hard for me to spend time with her if we
weren't going out. She said it could help her decision.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to come down and see me on a weekend that I have a
party arranged. I told her I didn't think it would be a good idea,
but she said she really wants to come. What should we do? _ C.S.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: The two of you need to decide to fish or cut bait. If
you really care about her, and want to continue the relationship,
let her come to the party. Don't make silly sounding excuses that
you've made other plans.
</P>
<P>
   If you want her to be in your life, then let her be in your
life. If you want to break it off, be honest with her. Tell her
you're ending the relationship because she lives far away and she
has said that she is less interested in the two of you staying
together.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: I am a happily married man of 61. My lovely wife
is 57. We have been in love for about 19 years and married 16
years. We had enjoyed a wonderful, exciting and satisfying sex life
for most of that time _ until menopause came into the picture. My
wife does not want to use estrogen replacement because it increases
the risk of developing certain types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   I will not offer an opinion, mostly because I don't want her to
think that it matters so much to me whether or not we have a sex
life _ and it doesn't, if that is what the future holds.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think our sex life is essentially over or will my wife
continue to have some interest? How should I conduct myself in this
circumstance? _ R.L.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Don't give up on your sex life so quickly. Sex is a
normal part of a relationship and can be mutually satisfying to
both of you as you grow older. You're asking a perfectly legitimate
question, but you're asking the wrong person. You should be asking
your wife.
</P>
<P>
   While your wife may not want to take estrogen replacement, there
are herbal remedies available. In terms of lubrication, you can
always apply a topical ointment. While the jury is still out on
estrogen replacement, Viagra turns out to be a useful prescription
for women as well.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways the two of you can be physical and sensual with
one another without being sexual, per say.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than making unilateral decisions or being a martyr, have
a serious discussion with your wife. Tell her: ``Look, I'll love
you to my dying day, whether we're sexual or not, but I miss our
sex life. Do you? And what can we do about it?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168, or to
drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot
be answered individually.
 &UR; Copyright 2000 by Dr. Joy Browne. &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   For information on subscribing to Dr. Joy, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell or Connie White, at
(888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
