<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3260 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      04-21 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 NEW &AMP; NOTABLE (a) 
 &HT;    (Editor's note: Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book
reviews. 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Anne Stephenson(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITORS: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS. MOVING
IN THE ``E'' and ``L'' CATEGORIES)
</P>
<P>
   LAS MAMIS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Esmeralda Santiago &QL;
</P>
<P>
   and Joie Davidow(Knopf, $20)
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Goldman ((beginitalic)The Ordinary Seaman(enditalic))
points out that Gabriel Garcia Marquez once was asked to write the
introduction to a book about Che Guevara, and he said, roughly,
``Sure, but I'll need 1,000 pages and 10 years to do it.'' That,
Goldman says, is the way he felt when he sat down to write about
his mother. But he managed (in only 12 pages), and so did the other
contributors to this anthology of poignant essays written by Latin
authors about their mothers. Dagoberto Gilb ((beginitalic)The Last
(enditalic)(beginitalic)Known Residence of Mickey Acuna(enditalic))
writes about his love as a young child for the beautiful woman who
gave birth to him, and the sadness of his estrangement from her as
he grew older. Editor Santiago (beginitalic)(When I Was Puerto
Rican)(enditalic) recalls the difficult life of her mother, a
determined, tenacious, sometimes violent woman who was, her
daughter says, ``an example of what we should avoid and what we
should aspire to.'' Other contributors include Junot Diaz and
Gioconda Belli.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE FALL
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Lent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Atlantic Monthly Press, $25)
</P>
<P>
   This is a terrific first novel that will appeal to readers who
loved Charles Frazier's 1997 book, (beginitalic)Cold Mountain.
(enditalic)You might even think they're the same story for a while,
because Lent's hero, like Frazier's, is a soldier making his way
home at the end of the Civil War. But Lent's Norman Pelham reaches
his family's farm in Vermont quickly and without trauma, and he
brings a woman with him. Her name is Leah, and she is a runaway
slave who helped Norman when she found him wounded in Virginia.
Lent's novel tells three stories: that of Norman and Leah, their
marriage and family and the making of their successful farm; that
of their troubled son, Jamie, a bootlegger during the years of
Prohibition; and that of Jamie's sweet-tempered boy, Foster, who
travels into the South to uncover the secret that eventually
destroyed his grandmother's life with Norman and their children.
There's violence, romance and poetic prose here, from a writer who
shows remarkable talent. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   BURT LANCASTER  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kate Buford
</P>
<P>
   (Knopf, $27.50)
</P>
<P>
   During filming, studio censors suggested, laughably, that
``either Karen or Warden put on a beach robe or some other type of
clothing before they go into the embrace.'' Karen was Deborah Kerr,
Warden was Burt Lancaster, and the beach robe was notably absent
from their surf-jostled kiss in (beginitalic)From Here to
Eternity(enditalic). Lancaster, Buford says, ``blends into our
collective memory like a famous uncle who was once a great
athlete.'' Throughout his life, he was a study in contradiction.
Known for his rages, promiscuity and mood swings, he also was
capable of great kindness and loyalty. In his youth, he was one of
Hollywood's most macho stars, yet the town simmered with rumors of
his bisexuality. And his movies were both provocative
((beginitalic)Atlantic City(enditalic)) and vapid
((beginitalic)Airport(enditalic)). Most of all, he was known for
his physical presence - his strength, his beauty, his sexuality.
That's what readers bring to the table, and what makes this
biography so fascinating: our memories of how splendid he was.
</P>
<P>
   WANDERLUST
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Solnit
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Your mind will wander as you read this, and who's to say that's
not what it's supposed to do? Solnit offers a history of walking,
in which meandering, both mental and physical, is part of the
exercise. As Jean-Jacques Rousseau said, ``I can only meditate when
I am walking. When I stop, I cease to think; my mind only works
with my legs.'' Or, as Solnit writes, ``Walking is a state in which
the mind, the body and the world are aligned, as though they were
three characters finally in conversation together, three notes
suddenly making a chord.'' She discusses how walking touches many
fields - anatomy, gardening, anthropology, architecture, geography,
history, literature, philosophy, sexuality, religious studies.
This, of course, gives her license to talk about everything and
everyone, from the street sense of Charles Dickens to the poetry of
Gary Snyder to the role of walking in courtship, protest and
emancipation. Best of all, this is a book that encourages you to
put it down, and go for a walk of your own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3262 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a SPERLING &LR;      04-21 2135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 SPERLING  
REBEL EDUCATOR BUCKED ESTABLISHMENT TO FOUND UNIVERSITY OF PHOENIX
(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED THIS. MOVING IN
</P>
<P>
   ``A'' AND ``K'' CATEGORIES)
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- John Sperling doesn't dwell on the past.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, he could. In his 79 years, Sperling survived a
harrowing childhood, sailed in the merchant marine, flew in the
Army Air Forces, earned a Cambridge degree and worked as a
firebrand union organizer.
</P>
<P>
   He also parlayed a $26,000 investment into the University of
Phoenix, the nation's largest for-profit university, an empire
worth more than $2billion.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he defied the education establishment, which
tried to label his school a diploma mill and run him out of town.
In recent years, he was demonized by some for attacking the
government's drug war and pushing a medical marijuana initiative.
</P>
<P>
   His many battles are chronicled in his coming autobiography,
(beginitalic)Rebel With a Cause(enditalic), which comes out next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Sperling keeps score but no trophies. His
Venetian-style home in the Arcadia neighborhood of Phoenix is
decorated with sculptures and artwork, including a series of four
Andy Warhol originals that hang in the entryway. In his modest
office out back, he has virtually no keepsakes. The only link to
his past is a single black-and-white photograph of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most influential person in my life,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't explain why. Sperling is moving too fast to be
sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in the present and plan the future,'' Sperling said.
``It's more fun. Optimists live longer.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his enemies, Sperling quotes Cardinal Richelieu, a French
statesman from the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richelieu, who was very old, was being brought up the Rhone
River after visiting the naval base at Toulon,'' Sperling said.
``And his aides said, 'Sire, aren't you afraid that your enemies
will gather in Paris against you?' And he said, 'Peace, my son.
They're all dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling grins. ``My kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   At heart, Sperling is a leftist-turned-entrepreneur, a union
organizer who became the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, the troops would say, 'Sperling, are you in this to
improve education or make money?''' he said. ``And I had a mantra:
If we don't make money, we won't improve education. You understand
that? You have to have money to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, powerful forces have conspired to kill Sperling's
brainchild, only to be vanquished by his unique blend of political
savvy, gutsy risk taking and plain old stubbornness.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Sperling reveled in the battle. In the 1970s,
when he was scrambling to keep his school alive, he worked 80-hour
weeks. Exhausted, he would pull his car to the side of the road,
sleeping as the traffic roared by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fight,'' Sperling said. ``If you like fighting, it
doesn't bother you. For some reason, I didn't think I'd ever
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling asks for and gives no quarter. Over the years, he's
fired friends who grew weary of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As CEO, you're responsible for everyone and their kids,''
Sperling said. ``You've got several thousand employees depending on
the company for their livelihood, and you don't endanger that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling's life is about forgetting the past, moving on. He was
raised poor, and he never wanted to go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to separate myself as far as possible,'' Sperling
said, ``to put as much distance between me and my past (as I
could.)''
</P>
<P>
   A sharecropper's son
</P>
<P>
   John Sperling was born in 1921 in a log cabin in the Missouri
Ozarks, the youngest of six children and the son of a sharecropper.
</P>
<P>
   Things were rough from the beginning. At age 7, Sperling
contracted a lung ailment and needed a dangerous operation to save
his life. Using local anesthetic, a doctor sawed through one of
Sperling's ribs to drain pus from his lung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the incision like a knife in my brain,'' Sperling
recalled in his book. ``I screamed and struggled ... it took all
the strength of the two doctors and two nurses to hold me down ...
when it was over and as I lay moaning, I kept repeating, 'Oh,
please let me die.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling was deeply ashamed of his father, who failed miserably
at farming and was often out of work. He also whipped Sperling with
a belt on a regular basis, until young John threatened to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, one day the miracle happened,'' Sperling wrote. ``He
died in his sleep. In the morning when my mother told me my father
was dead, I could hardly contain my joy. I raced outside, rolled in
the grass squealing with delight.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling had five siblings but was close to only one, his sister
Ruth. Of the others, he wrote, ``I neither asked of them nor gave
of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After his father's death, Sperling's family moved to Portland,
Ore., and he soon signed aboard a freighter, working in the engine
room. There, Sperling's education began. Many of the crew brought
books aboard, and almost all of the crew members were leftists
{ndash} socialists, Trotskyists and Stalinists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any political philosophy, my political awareness
began at that time,'' Sperling said in an interview. ``I was only
vaguely aware of fascism. They were violently anti-fascist. They
awakened me to what was going on in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling's interests shifted from the maritime to the academic.
When World War II broke out, he was attending Reed College, a
prestigious Portland liberal arts school, then joined the Army Air
Forces. He learned to fly, but the war ended before he saw combat.
</P>
<P>
   True to his nature, he never climbed into a cockpit again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last plane I flew in and landed, I got out and kissed the
ground, and that was the last time I would fly a plane,'' Sperling
said in an interview. ``I thought, 'God, I haven't killed
myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   After a short, failed marriage, Sperling enrolled in graduate
school at the University of California-Berkeley, which he
considered to be ``the intellectual capital of the world.'' He
married again and was accepted into the doctoral program at
Cambridge. When he returned to the United States after three years,
Sperling found jobs scarce and accepted an instructorship in the
history department at Ohio State. While in Columbus, Sperling
joined the American Civil Liberties Union, but he otherwise hated
the experience.
</P>
<P>
   He bounced around the Midwest for a few more years, then landed
at San Jose State, where he would become active in the teachers
union.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sperling was ultimately dumped from the union's
leadership, he said the experience proved invaluable later in life,
when he had to defend the University of Phoenix from legal assaults
and attempts to legislate it out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   His union job a memory, Sperling threw himself back into
academia and soon would sow the seeds that would grow into an
education empire.
</P>
<P>
   An innovator
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, while at San Jose, Sperling worked on a federal grant
to lower juvenile-delinquency rates. He developed curricula for
teachers and police officers, and before long they were asking for
more classes.
</P>
<P>
   The small program grew into the Institute for Professional
Development, which became affiliated with the University of San
Francisco. At the time, there was little in the way of college
classes for working adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person could go two or three nights a week for 10 years and
maybe get a degree,'' Sperling recalled, and he told the story of
Bobby Maybee, a police detective who had accumulated 130 credit
hours but still had no degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget when we finally got him into this program,
and he said, ``Now, Sperling, if I go through this, I'm going to
get a degree, right?' And I said, 'Bobby, so help me God, yes.' And
he patted his shoulder holster and said, 'I hope you're right.'''
</P>
<P>
   At age 52, Sperling went from university professor to
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was popular, Sperling's adult-education program came
under attack from heavy hitters among the education establishment
in California. To them, a for-profit institution with part-time
instructors and no tenure was an anathema.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents pressured the University of San Francisco to drop the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling survived there for five years, just enough time to get
his organization moving. After leaving California, he began
searching for another site and settled on Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The move gave Sperling several advantages. The state was covered
by a different accreditation body and the atmosphere was
pro-business. Although the accreditation process was rough,
Sperling made some powerful friends: Gov. Bruce Babbitt, state
House Speaker Burton Barr and Dino DeConcini, brother of former
U.S. Sen. Dennis DeConcini. Babbitt even met with Sperling on the
sly to help advise him, having lunch in a hotel suite and leaving
through the service entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, when I got our message through the Legislature, then
the Legislature became friendly,'' Sperling said. ``If we hadn't
had a friendly Legislature, I think the public university system
would have been able to destroy us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the state Board of Regents attacked Sperling on every
front, and the University of Phoenix was trashed with allegations
that it was a diploma mill.
</P>
<P>
   The late '70s were a rough time for Sperling. He was in the
battle of his life on two fronts, defending his school and fighting
prostate cancer. He eventually was fitted for radioactive implants,
which caused a constant burning sensation. Sperling numbed the pain
with Percodan, alcohol and, eventually, marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Although the University of Phoenix won accreditation in 1978,
the regents went after Sperling again, seeking new legislation and
ultimately refusing to accept University of Phoenix credits. The
last effort was turned back by Barr.
</P>
<P>
   With his university safe and his health back on track, Sperling
turned to other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he began a self-proclaimed stealth campaign against the
government's war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling argued that the drug war was little more than a
publicity stunt, using dramatic busts to mask the huge fiscal and
human costs.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Sperling argued, although it filled up prisons, it did
nothing to stem the tide of drugs. And because enforcement
increased the price of drugs, Sperling said, users were forced to
commit crimes to get the money.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling's plan was to offset the drug war by legalizing certain
drugs for medical use and diverting some drug offenders into
treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his strategy, Sperling wanted to stay under the radar
screen, to keep the opposition from organizing against him. He
conducted a quiet effort to make sure public officials didn't try
to destroy it, lining up a powerful list of backers, capped by
Dennis DeConcini and Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters met privately with members of the congressional
delegation, most of whom agreed to stay neutral. As Election Day
1996 approached, drug czar Barry McCaffrey launched an attack, but
Sperling blunted it with a $1million radio and television assault,
which was funded mostly by Sperling and two partners, New York
financier George Soros and Cleveland businessman Peter B. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``These funds allowed us, in the final two weeks before the
election, to turn our stealth campaign into a blitzkrieg,''
Sperling wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, Proposition 200, passed by a ratio of almost
2-1. The next year, Sperling had to fight a rear-guard action to
keep it mostly intact. This year, supporters are pushing another
initiative, seeking a state distribution network for medical
marijuana and reductions in sentences for possession.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Sperling said, public officials are losing their fear
that the drug war is a so-called third rail of politics.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, Sperling noted that recently in the U.S. House of
Representatives, ``there was a 21/2-hour debate on drug policy. A
handful of representatives, led by Nancy Pelosi of San Francisco,
attacked the drug war directly. That hasn't happened in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Sperling is staying busy with programs such as
Seaphire, a seawater irrigation program, and the Kronos Group,
which is involved in longevity research. His son, Peter, is still
involved with the family business and is active in other ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling is enjoying life. He throws lavish parties at his
Arcadia home and maintains a place in San Francisco. Despite all
that's happened, he says each new day is the best day of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always make sure that whatever I'm doing,'' he said, ``I'm
enjoying it intensely.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Bill.Muller(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8178
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
