<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-U-571 (Undated) _ In a way it's refreshing how
unrefreshing the new submarine thriller, ``U-571,'' is. Taut,
suspenseful, good-looking, it strives to be old-fashioned
entertainment, complete with cardboard characters (who have names
like Chief, Rabbit and Trigger) injected with doses of star power.
Almost belligerently, it refuses to break new ground (or water, for
that matter). By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BASKETBALL (Undated) _ ``Love and Basketball,'' a
romantic comedy about a love triangle between a boy, a girl and a
game, has some nice moves and winning players, but ultimately loses
steam down the stretch. The film plots out a predictable romance
between two young ballplayers who've grown up as next-door
neighbors: Monica Wright, played by the earnest and likable Sanaa
Lathan and Quincy McCall, played with much swagger and sweat by
Omar Epps. By KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STOOGES (Undated) _ Before there was professional wrestling,
``Monday Night Football,'' muscle cars or Playboy, there was ``The
Three Stooges.'' The brothers Howard, Larry Fine and a pair of Joes
pounded, poked and nyuk'ed each other through 190 or so film shorts
for Columbia Pictures from 1934 to 1958. They later became staples
on television _ where they live on today _ as well as a successful
touring act. The ABC biopic ``The Three Stooges'' is a fun and
touching, if sketchy, homage by producer and major Stoogehead Mel
Gibson that airs Monday. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-RESTAURANT (Undated) _ Eric Bross did not set out to
make a film about race. He set out to make a film about
restaurants. He had spent years working in them, his collaborator
had spent years working in them, and the nightly hustle and bustle
just seemed fair bait for a small feature. But along the way to
making ``Restaurant,'' Bross' study of Gen-X Jersey food workers
became something else: a movie about blacks and whites, and the
uneasy space between them. By AMY BIANCOLLI. (For release Sunday,
April 23.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VENUS-GLOW (San Francisco) _ Scientists at SRI International in
Menlo Park, Calif., have received a $250,000 NASA grant to
scrutinize the legendary ``ashen light'' of Venus, the second
planet from the Sun. The ashen light is an elusive luminescence,
sometimes faintly visible on the dark side of Venus. It has
enchanted and mystified generations of stargazers. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-CELLPHONES (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown, joining a disgruntled population that's tired of being
interrupted by cell phones, has weighed in, with increasing
frequency, about the burgeoning use of the noisy technology that
seems attached to nearly every belt, suit jacket, purse and brief
case. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-NIGHT-VISION (San Antonio) _ GM's Cadillac DeVille
2000-model comes equipped with a high-tech innovation born of the
military and the Gulf War: the new night-vision system made famous
during Operation Desert Storm. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Beauty is definitely in the eye of
the beholder, and there are people who don't much care for the
looks of the new 2001 Mitsubishi Eclipse Spyder convertible. Don't
count me among them, though. I think it's stunningly beautiful,
almost too gorgeous to be a Mitsubishi. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS
III.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANDY-MOLDS (Undated) _ Candy molds come in a variety of shapes,
sizes and materials. For years, collectors have prized tin candy
molds. These may still be in use, but candy-making experts say that
the new lightweight, clear plastic molds leave a better shine on
the candy. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release Sunday, April
23.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EASTER-PASSOVER (Undated) _ Celebrations of Passover and Easter
coincide this weekend, as they frequently do. Yet something is
different; for many Catholics and Jews, there is a new awareness of
each other. Last month, when Pope John Paul II asked for
forgiveness of sins committed by Catholics across the last two
millennia, he included Jews and Muslims. That confession, followed
by the papal visit to the Holy Land _ to Israel, the Palestinian
territories and Jordan _ spoke eloquently to a collective hope for
the future. By JOHN P. SCHLEGEL.
</P>
