</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TELECOM (London) _ The British government will likely
end its auction of next-generation mobile phone licenses next week,
and then the next telecommunications battle begins: A furious
bidding war is set for Orange, the British wireless provider that
Vodafone AirTouch must shed. France Telecom, MCI Worldcom and
Telefonica are expected to make offers. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   RENAULT-SAMSUNG (Paris) _ Developing: The French automotive
group Renault S.A. appeared Friday to be on the verge of acquiring
Samsung Motors, part of the Samsung Group of Korea. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-GYPSY-PROFILE (New York) _ Most of Spokane's Gypsies would
just like Jimmy Marks to shut up. He has brought too much exposure
to their secretive world, a tale told in ``American Gypsy,'' a
documentary film by Jasmine Dellal which reveals how Marks came to
be an outcast, ``marime''_ ``unclean'' in Romani, the Gypsy
language. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FUTURE-DESIGN (Undated) _ A new branch of history has
sprouted: the history of film titles, which generally appear before
the movie proper has begun. Because they are physically and
historically ``on the periphery of films,'' said David Peters, a
graphic designer who studies title sequences, they have often been
more experimental, a peek into the future of filmmaking. By Sarah
Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   MODERN-NOVELS (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: Such masters of
the contemporary novel as Don DeLillo, Toni Morrison, Thomas
Pynchon and Salman Rushdie _ along with a new generation of writers
like Dave Eggers, David Foster Wallace and Zadie Smith _ have
discovered a myriad of ways to fuse the cerebral and the visceral,
the high and the low, the world of ideas and the world of raw
experience. By Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
