<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SEIZES JAPANESE BOAT IN INTERNATIONAL WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Russian coast guard fired on and seized a Japanese
fishing boat Friday in waters near Japan's northernmost main
island, according to Japanese and Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The incident threatens to revive tensions between the countries,
which have had disputes about maritime boundaries and possession of
a number of small islands in the area since the end of World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, is scheduled to visit
the Russian president-elect, Vladimir Putin, in Moscow on April 29.
Japan has been pressing Russia to negotiate a formal peace treaty,
which it says should include the return of northern islands seized
by Moscow in the closing days of the war.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russian officials who briefed journalists in
Moscow, the Japanese fishing vessel disobeyed orders from a Russian
patrol boat to stop for inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intruder was shelled by the Russian border guards when it
attempted to escape from the Russian economic zone into neutral
waters,'' the Russian ITAR-Tass news agency said. None of the 20
crew members was injured, Japanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian authorities said the Japanese ship, the No. 7
Daitoku-Maru, was operating with its name and identification
numbers concealed and had tried to escape after being summoned.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese authorities gave an entirely different account, saying
that the fishing vessel was operating in Japanese waters near what
Japan calls its Northern Territories.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese coast guard sent three aircraft and four patrol
boats to the scene, 60 miles south of the cape of Ochiishi off the
island of Hokkaido. But officials said the Japanese coast guard
withdrew after the fishing vessel was brought, under escort, into
Russian waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that two Russian soldiers are standing on the
bridge of the Japanese ship,'' said a Japanese official quoted by
Reuters. ``If this continues, we will consider the ship seized.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3330 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-RESTAURAN     04-21 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-RESTAURANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A TOUCHING FILM ABOUT RACE RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eric Bross did not set out to make a film about race. He set out
to make a film about restaurants. He had spent years working in
them, his collaborator had spent years working in them, and the
nightly hustle and bustle just seemed fair bait for a small
feature.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way to making ``Restaurant,'' Bross' study of
Gen-X New Jersey food workers became something else: a movie about
blacks and whites, and the uneasy space between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The restaurant is kind of a metaphor for our American society,
because we have a kind of a melting pot, as they say here in
America,'' said the director, 31, chatting earlier this week from
his home in Los Angeles. ``We thought it was a perfect kind of
metaphor (or) microcosm of what we see in our world today:
undercurrents of racial tension within a harmonious environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like we said, `Hey, let's set out to do it.' It just
kind of grew.''
</P>
<P>
   And as it grew, it matured into an honest-yet-subtle look at the
intersection of African-Americans and Caucasians in contemporary
urban life. Chris (Adrien Brody of ``The Thin Red Line''), the
young white protagonist, is a Hoboken bartender and aspiring
playwright who's still heartbroken over an ex-girlfriend's long-ago
infidelity. It so happens that the ex-girlfriend (played by hip-hop
Grammy winner Lauryn Hill) is black. It so happens that Chris'
current girlfriend (Elise Neal of TV's ``The Hughleys'') is black.
And it so happens that the idealistic, even-handed Chris, a
peacemaker in the restaurant's racial politics, finds that he can't
quite escape the bigotry he observed _ and loathed _ in his own
father.
</P>
<P>
   The film splits its time between intimate one-on-ones (Chris and
his girlfriends; Chris and his pals) and the noisy crosstalk of
work and parties. Well-acted by a young ensemble that also includes
David Moscow, Malcolm Jamal-Warner and Jesse Martin, the plot
crosses a lot of territory: racial, generational, romantic, human.
</P>
<P>
   Retooled punctuation here: None of it's facile, although some of
it's messy. Much of the mess involves characters facing down a few
nasty ethnic stereotypes. The `N' word gets a work-out.
</P>
<P>
   Bross said he and screenwriter Tom Cudworth ``were striving to
say, `You know, let's just be honest.' In our world today, we're
becoming more and more intolerant of racism. But there's another
thing growing out of it, which is this whole political correctness
_ which is a danger in itself. To be politically correct implies a
sort of stricter kind of rule, where you're asking people to
repress something, to hide something.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Restaurant,'' he said, ``I felt we were more capable of
saying, `I have that, I'm willing to deal with that, I'm willing to
face it.' It's psychology: If you don't address the issue, how can
you deal with it? In the African-American community, one of the
gripes they have is they feel that white people aren't honest
(about racism) ....
</P>
<P>
   ``I still agree there's something correct about political
correctness,'' Bross said. ``It's a good idea, but it's not
perfect. It should be a guideline more than a rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Bross' film is one of several in current or recent release to
address the subject of black-white relations. ``Liberty Heights,''
another Brody film, takes a look at interracial dating. James
Toback's ``Black and White'' also tackles matters of race, albeit
in a much sloppier and less insightful manner. (Bross' previous
collaboration with Cudworth, ``Ten Benny'' _ again with Brody _
followed lifelong buddies in suburban New Jersey and made a minor
splash with critics.)
</P>
<P>
   Why now? Why so many films on a topic so often overlooked by
mainstream movies? Bross isn't sure, but he suspects filmmakers are
tracking the cyclical nature of American racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things build to a certain point, and there's cultural
change,'' Bross said. ``Right now, the hip-hop thing is sort of
scaring a lot of white people _ I mean, really scaring a lot of
white people _ and they don't understand it, and it's spreading
into their own children's lives. It's becoming cultural. And when
that sort of thing starts to happen, it becomes not just a black
thing but a black-and-white thing. And therefore, I think, people
start to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bross, for one, was deeply influenced by an early encounter with
racism. Reared by liberal-minded parents in West Caldwell, N.J., he
was taught not to judge his playmates by the color of their skin.
Then the African-American family next door had their lawn torched
by angry whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 4 or 5 years old, and I just never forgot it. I'll never
forget it _ the family, the Winstons, sitting in our living room,
because our yards were connected and we used to have barbecues
together, and we used to play with their daughters,'' Bross
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid you don't make those (racial) distinctions. You don't
think about it, and I never have. I'm not gonna sit here and say I
don't have the same kind of white fear that (other) white people
do, but what this did for me was I saw firsthand how people were
behaving. And I never fully understood what it meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on, his mother _ Joanna Bross, a lyricist and writer _ got
a job coaching candidates for Miss Black New Jersey. The girls and
their beaus often visited the Bross household for sessions on
public speaking and deportment. Apparently, the sight of beautiful
black couples traversing the white side of town was too much for
the neighbors, and they complained. Often. Loudly. ``It was just
very bizarre, very bizarre,'' Bross said.
</P>
<P>
   Such youthful introductions to bigotry had a profound effect on
Bross, underscoring for him the absurdity of adult prejudices _ and
our equally absurd reluctance to talk about them. When it comes to
race, no one is wiser than a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's fine for children to explore differences,'' he
said. ``I remember sitting with my sister _ my older sister's a
year older than me, so she must have been five and I must have been
four _ with the girls next door, twins named Judy and Becky. It's a
memory I have of sitting there with my sister there in the dirt,
and my sister's putting dirt on her legs and saying, `Now I look
like Judy and Becky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids address differences. They don't address them as an issue
or as a problem, but as something that's interesting,'' he said.
``Something that's different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
