<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3346 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-DANIELS-ART-BOS     04-21 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DANIELS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SOPRANO SHARON DANIELS PASSES HER EXPERTISE TO BU STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sharon Daniels has seen opera from every side. During
the '70s and '80s she was one of America's most captivating
sopranos, successful not only in opera but on Broadway, where she
sang a three-month run of ``The Most Happy Fella'' _ the Frank
Loesser show was also taped for television and shown on ``Great
Performances.'' Now she is one of Boston's most successful voice
teachers and stage directors..
</P>
<P>
   Recently Daniels, still blond, sparkling, and chic as she sails
through her 50s, took a break between rehearsals to talk about ``La
Clemenza di Tito,'' a student production of Mozart's last opera,
and her triple career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this opera is a most unusual choice for a student
production,'' she admits, ``but we have two wonderful full casts,
and an additional cast of covers that is ready to go on. The piece
is a big challenge, but everyone has worked really hard and is
ready for it. I'm also very happy with the design by Tod Shiba, who
made it a point to know the score. I was determined that there
would be no slow and squeaking scene changes. We had the
opportunity to use some elements of the Huntington Theatre's set
for `Mary Stuart,' but Tod incorporated them into a fabulous design
that is all his own.''
</P>
<P>
   The work will be sung in Italian. ``No one wanted to hear those
great arias in English. But this is also a show that is full of
recitative. We began to address the problem of singing convincing
Italian a few years ago by setting up a conversation class, which
really paid off in our productions of `La Boheme' and `Gianni
Schicchi.' In this opera we have singers of American, Armenian,
Portuguese, and Korean origin, and everyone was held accountable
for the Italian text. We began by asking them to paraphrase the
text in their own languages, to identify and physicalize their
objectives for every line. Only then did we move on into the
Italian. I think the audience will not need to look at the
supertitles very often. The costumes are soft and flowing and
emphasize the humanity of the piece, although the period puts the
two women who sing men's roles into skirts, which poses a challenge
they have met. No, it never occurred to me to have the wigmaster
put hair on their legs!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniels was born in Arizona in 1943 and began singing solos in
church as a child; ``I'd Rather Have Jesus'' was her debut number.
At Chapman College in California Daniels developed a special talent
for acting, appearing in straight plays as well as in musicals and
even an opera, ``Amahl and the Night Visitors.'' While her first
husband was studying for a pastorate at the Pacific School of
Religion, Daniels embarked on a career in elementary school
teaching. ``Yes, I was at Berkeley in the '60s,'' Daniels says, her
eyes dancing. ``And I was teaching second grade in Oakland. But I
found a wonderful voice teacher named Amy MacMurray, who was about
90 years old, and that saved my life. I began to sing concerts and
appear with all the local orchestras; I had no idea I could make a
career in opera.''
</P>
<P>
   When Daniels auditioned for the Merola Program for young singers
sponsored by the San Francisco Opera, she knew only five arias. She
sang small roles with the parent company and saw prime-time Beverly
Sills in Massenet's ``Manon.'' ``When I saw that, I said, `I'm
going to do this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels's career, like so many others, began with the touring
Goldovsky Opera Theater; she sang ``The Barber of Seville,'' ``La
Traviata,'' and ``Don Giovanni.'' Soon Daniels was singing
regularly at the New York City Opera (for her debut in the title
role of Offenbach's ``La Belle Helene'' she was paid $150 a
performance) and on the American regional opera circuit. She
developed a particularly close relationship with the Kansas City
Lyric Opera, where she sang ``The Ballad of Baby Doe'' in two
different productions and later returned to direct the opera. Over
the years she sang Micaela in ``Carmen'' and Musetta in ``La
Boheme'' countless times, and says she never tired of singing
Micaela. She was a vivacious and popular Merry Widow, and she
particularly loved singing Marguerite in ``Faust'' and all of those
roles in American operas thatgive great acting opportunities to a
singer, particularly Birdie in ``Regina,'' Baby Doe, the title role
in ``Susannah,'' and Curly's Wife in ``Of Mice and Men.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniels took her first step into directing 14 years ago. For
years, both she and her second husband, baritone Daniel Sullivan,
were busy traveling and performing, and wherever they went, they
took their daughter Megan, now 21, with them. ``But then, suddenly,
Megan was 7, and she didn't know where she lived,'' Daniels recalls
ruefully. ``We wanted to see what we could do to center her life,
and our lives, too, so Dan took a job at the University of Arizona,
and Tucson became our home base. At first this was very difficult
for us; I missed New York and I felt that by going back to Arizona
I was somehow going home and giving up. But I needed to be reminded
that I could do other things besides sing. For five years I ran an
educational program about opera that traveled all over the state
and I did a lot of work with affiliate-artist programs, small
hands-on residencies. When you are performing all the time, you get
into the habit of promoting yourself and the product, and it is all
too easy to forget your roots, and the human reasons why you wanted
to do this in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels came to Boston University in 1991 on a temporary
appointment as artist in residence, and she has been here ever
since; Sullivan came too, and has remained active as a performer
(he's been in several Boston Lyric Opera productions). Daniels has
directed BU productions of ``The Mother of Us All,'' ``The Merry
Wives of Windsor,'' ``The Marriage of Figaro,'' ``Street Scene,''
``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' and ``Albert Herring''' she also
directed ``Baby Doe'' for the Boston Lyric. Along the way, she _
and others _ discovered what a gifted and inspiring voice teacher
she is. ``A voice teacher should be like a launching pad for a
singer,'' Daniels says firmly. ``Not like a mother.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Daniels tried to keep on performing. She gave a
recital here, took the lead in a BU production of ``A Little Night
Music,'' and went to the Opera Theatre of St. Louis to sing the
lead in a revival of Conrad Susa's ``Black River.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she loved doing the Susa opera. ``One of the reasons I
enjoyed it is that I was playing an older woman rather than a
perpetual ingenue or soubrette, and I had a great mad scene. That
was five years ago, and I haven't done any performing since then. I
still want to sing, but my life isn't about finding time to sing
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the next chapter, Daniels says, ``I am totally
committed to everything I'm doing, but it's a struggle to keep
everything in balance; I probably say yes to too many things. I
love teaching voice and I love directing _ not many people do both.
But I have to say that I miss singing. I would love to work up a
new recital program and try it out in some inconspicuous venue,
nothing grand, but something special, for me. My voice is still
fresh, and I think I still have something to share. Singing is like
a very dear friend that I have neglected for too long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
