<HEADER>
A3348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-U571-BOS &LR;      04-21 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-U571-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`U-571' HEAVY ON THE MELODRAMA BUT DOESN'T SINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
U-571 
Directed by: Jonathan Mostow 
Screenplay by: Mostow, Sam Montgomery, David Ayer 
Starring: Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Harvey Keitel, Jon Bon
Jovi, Jake Weber, Matthew Settle, Erik Palladino, David Keith,
Thomas Kretschmann, Jack Noseworthy, Thomas Guiry, T.C. Carson 
Running time: 117 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (war violence) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When submarines stopped being driven by diesels and went
nuclear, the submarine movie genre took a dive. ``Crimson Tide''
and ``The Hunt for Red October'' can't hold a torpedo to ``Das
Boot,'' ``Run Silent, Run Deep,'' or ``The Enemy Below.'' Jonathan
Mostow, who demonstrated an uncommon ability to breathe new life
into an old genre in ``Breakdown,'' gives it a good try in
``U-571.'' Propelled by nonstop action sequences, it's a slickly
crafted throwback to those World War II movies in which character
didn't matter as much as the fact that we, the good guys, won in
the end, even if it meant believing that the Germans couldn't shoot
straight and we couldn't miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``U-571'' not only wants to place itself alongside ``Das Boot''
in its depiction of the perils faced by a submarine crew on a
dangerous mission, but freely admits being heavily influenced by
the German award-winning undersea saga. Several of its designers
and technicians were hired to work on ``U-571.'' The result is a
film that never lets down, even if depth of character always takes
second place to depth charges. There's never a dull moment aboard
the sub. There's also never any serious attempt to establish
characters who are more than emblematic. The young crewmen have
generic American names like Trigger, Rabbit, and Tank. They may
barely be old enough to shave, but they come through with huge
heroics.
</P>
<P>
   They frankly come off better than the leads, although Matthew
McConaughey looks better than he has in his last few so-called
serious roles and is more focused and compelling. It's too bad that
he's stuck with a script that reduces him to little more than his
character's macho need to prove himself under fire to resolve any
doubts his commander (Bill Paxton) may have had about his ability
to lead. For all its aspirations to follow in the wake of ``Das
Boot,'' this film never tries for the tragic dimension enveloping
that film's U-boat commander, Jurgen Prochnow.
</P>
<P>
   As for Harvey Keitel's chief petty officer, who could have
bolstered ``U-571'' with his aura of experience, but isn't
permitted to, one could wish that he didn't have to bark lines like
``I'm a sea dog.'' But if the interpersonal dynamic seems stunted
and stereotyped in ``U-571,'' the ensemble cast throws itself at
its work wholeheartedly. They and the absolutely first-rate
technical experts never give you time to contemplate the film's
shortcomings at length. Mostow's jackhammer pacing keeps throwing
trouble first at the US sub and then, after a firefight, the
commandeered German U-571 with the secret code the Allies badly
need to stop getting clobbered by the U-boats. (There actually was
such a device, called the Enigma, and it was captured by the
British; we later captured a U-boat.)
</P>
<P>
   They get fired upon by destroyers and other subs, and the model
builders do a sensational job of convincing us we're seeing both
subs dodge torpedoes and depth charges by the dozen, while
continually improvising the repairs they need to keep going and
keeping a wary eye on their not-to-be-trusted prisoner, the U-boat
commandant (Thomas Kretschmann). There's no end of suspense, as
depth charges and torpedos come as close as grazing the hull of the
sub with the Americans, while our side can usually take care of
things with one well-aimed shot. It has to be one because we
haven't got the time or ammo for two.
</P>
<P>
   For all its wish to show ordinary guys rising to heroism,
``U-571'' turns out to be one of those old-style World War II
movies that depends for Allied success on the Germans having bad
aim. More than once, the film's biggest struggle is not with the
Germans, who are rather too easily eliminated, but with its own
growing credibility gap. The American commandos operate the
captured German sub proficiently in minutes even though only two of
them can read and comprehend German. Mostow's intermittently
successful game plan is to never let the film sit still long enough
to make its shortcomings _ which is to say its essentially
mechanical, generic nature _ apparent.
</P>
<P>
   He ratchets up the suspense by frequently having the sub dive to
avoid depth charges, with the crew huddling tensely as they listen
to the noises that mean the steel sides are groaning under the
pressure. When in doubt about what to do next, Mostow simply has
the sub spring another leak, complete with crew member grimacing as
he tries to free up a balky valve handle or hatch cover. ``U-571''
works well enough as a straight-ahead adventure thriller as long as
you don't stop and think about it, and instead just let it sweep
you up in its momentum. But not every detail contributes to the
film. Why, for instance, do the crew members whisper when they've
got an enemy ship in their sights? Do they think they'll be
overheard 500 yards away? Adrenaline-filled as the submerged
``U-571'' may be, it spends a lot of time, figuratively speaking,
on the surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
