<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUIRRELS NO MATCH FOR A MAN OF STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There must be some relation between working outdoors and having
fun outdoors. Between:
</P>
<P>
   Shoveling snow and skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Mowing a lawn and walking on a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Raking leaves and hiking in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Even _ if we really narrow the focus _ painting the house trim
and painting the boat bottom.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is a chore, the other a joy.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter S. Thompson inspired me with a fantasy that visits often
in the spring when I am trying to get my lawn mower going, having
neglected to have it serviced _ as suggested in the long-lost
maintenance manual _ in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, you may have read, had a Jeep he disliked. Living in
the ranch country of Woody Creek, Colo., Thompson parked the Jeep
near enough to his house to take shots at it with all manner of
weapons _ shotguns, hunting rifles, pistols, and the like. He even
wired it with dynamite as part of his crusade of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   So my fantasy involves moving into my log house on some woody
shore left in its absolutely wild state. Neither the house nor the
grounds would require the least maintenance. Then I wheel my lawn
mower out to its execution, shoulder my Remington 870 pump, and
blast it to bits.
</P>
<P>
   ``And here's one for the time you wrecked my back. Remember
that?'' I would growl. ``Sixty-seven pulls before you started!
Remember?
</P>
<P>
   ``And you remember the time your wheel fell off right by the
garden and you wrecked those azaleas?''
</P>
<P>
   Blam!
</P>
<P>
   ``And you remember how you'd always be dripping oil on the
garage floor?''
</P>
<P>
   Blam!
</P>
<P>
   ``And how your adjustable wheels were always stuck and never
adjusted? And how in the spring your gas line was caramelized and
required an $80 job at the fix-it shop, and it took three weeks to
get done? And by then the lawn looked like a Wisconsin wheat
field?''
</P>
<P>
   Blam! Blam! Blam!
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's what I call combining outdoor work with recreation
in the best possible way.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose having a bad relationship with an inanimate object may
seem a bit perverse. So let's try creatures, for this season of
renewal almost always rekindles my war with the squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   No, I do not try to kill them or harm them in any way, yet I
would not be reporting this were I not winning the war in rather
dramatic fashion. I am delighted to say that not a single squirrel
has reached my bird feeder for seven years now.
</P>
<P>
   The old ones have long given up, but as the youngsters start
gamboling around my yard in the spring, they pause now and then,
behold the huge feeder chock full of gray stripe and black oil
sunflower seed, and set about trying to get at it. Simply watching
them is worth the price of admission.
</P>
<P>
   But first the device itself: The feeder has three columns of
seed, each about 14 inches tall, covered on top by a plastic dome.
When full, the feeder holds about 10 pounds of seed, so it needs
strong support. Several attempts to fit it atop the aluminum pole
that came with it ended in failure, as the squirrels would reach
the feeder within seconds of my turning my back on it.
</P>
<P>
   Greasing the pole with Crisco made for some fun viewing for a
while (even more fun with Crisco and hot pepper), but soon the
first few sacrificial squirrels would have cleaned the grease off
the pole and they'd be back at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, well,'' said my kindly wife, ``squirrels have to eat,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   No way. I wasn't giving in to that nonsense. Our house is
surrounded by big oak trees teeming with these rodents, and I
needed some kind of victory. So I turned to my fishing gear for
help. (I was still mentally a long way away from aforementioned
shotgun.)
</P>
<P>
   Finding a long, overhanging oak branch about 25 feet high, I
cast a sinker over it and rigged the feeder to a length of strong
twine. The squirrels could not leap up to the feeder, or jump to it
off the tree. But their valedictorian figured out that he (she?)
could merely go up the branch from which it hung and bite through
the twine. I found the ransacked feeder on the ground, seed half
gone.
</P>
<P>
   I tried Stren 30-pound test monofilament, which did not last
much longer, but then I knew exactly what was needed. In my tackle
box was a reel of 40-pound stainless steel wire, which, once rigged
with the bird feeder, solved the problem for good.
</P>
<P>
   The feeder now swings in the breeze about 9 feet off the ground,
20 feet out from the tree in a space absolutely inviolable by the
squirrels. It withstands blizzards and summer blows, and is
patronized by all manner of small birds, from wrens to bright red
cardinals and goldfinches; even an occasional pair of Baltimore
Orioles, with those striking orange breasts, stops along its
migration route.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then a young squirrel will make a new attempt, but it
always ends the same. Starting from the branch above, he will grab
the wire _ unable to chew through it _ and try descending it. But
once his back claws leave the limb, he streaks down the wire out of
control, bonks his head on the feeder and flips onto the lawn,
where he lies until recovering consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   He then _ I fervently hope and almost believe _ goes back into
the woods to warn the others about a bird feeder they should
definitely not attempt mess with. They don't.
</P>
<P>
   Spring is the time to renew the wire and set the feeder once
again in mid-air, attatched to its squirrel-proof skyhook. And I
remain ready to capture on video the attempt by the next young
squirrel to reach it by sliding down the wire. That videotape would
be my retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The whole trick in doing spring chores, you see, is to turn them
into outdoor games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3355 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-21 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL'S DILEMMA: NO ONE'S WATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the same old story with the NHL _ very few people are
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Fox tried everything, including the infamous blue puck, and
couldn't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   And now ABC, ESPN, and ESPN2 have completed the first regular
season of their five-year, $600 million television deal, and the
ratings numbers are the lowest ever.
</P>
<P>
   It's not for lack of trying. ABC, ESPN, and ESPN2, all
subsidiaries of the Disney Co., have cross-promoted the sport like
crazy and still can't grow the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into this knowing that some building had to occur,''
said Artie Bulgrin, ESPN's senior vice president of research,
sales, and development.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgrin is at least telling the truth. ESPN is up 2 percent for
its coverage of six first-round playoff games, from a .64 rating
last year to a .65 this year. ESPN2 has had seven playoff games and
its numbers dropped by 16 percent, from .56 last year to .47.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Point something or other. The NHL is the only
major professional sport for which the bulk of the playoff games
are not only shown on cable but also generate such a chilly
response.
</P>
<P>
   The regular season wasn't much better. The last regular-season
game on ABC, on April 9, averaged a 1.0 rating and a 2 share.
Unlike Fox, which aired 11 days of regional games, ABC opted to
have four days of regional games. ABC averaged a 1.3 rating and a 4
share, the lowest in the history of network sports television.
</P>
<P>
   Fox didn't do much better when it had the rights to the NHL. In
1997, the network aired six games and averaged a 1.9 rating. That
number fell by nearly 30 percent when Fox officials decided to air
five more games the next year. In 1998, with 11 games, the ratings
dropped to a 1.4.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL is an embarrassment on television for all the reasons
that viewers have known for years. The sport doesn't translate well
to the small screen. The sport has a regional appeal, and, for the
most part, the game's biggest stars are not home-grown talent.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Eliot, CNN/SI's NHL analyst, said another reason for the
lack of interest is Americans' unfamiliarity with the sport. ``Most
people have played catch with a football or baseball or played
basketball, but very few have actually played hockey,'' Eliot said.
``The lack of grassroots knowledge has hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is changing. Eliot said that the emergence of the
in-line game has helped younger fans gain knowledge about the game,
and as ESPN officials tell the story, the networks have seen proof
of a growing interest in hockey among Gen Xers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Bulgrin said, the number of male viewers ages
18-34 has grown by as much as 70 percent over the last year. ESPN
aired 27 games last year and delivered about 124,000 men in that
key demographic last year. ESPN delivered about 165,000 this year
during the regular season. The numbers dropped slightly on ESPN2,
but Bulgrin explained that the Deuce showed more games. Last year
ESPN2 aired 75 games and delivered about 76,000 men ages 18-34.
ESPN2 aired 101 games this regular season and delivered 69,000.
ESPN2 did deliver a much younger audience. Men ages 12-24 increased
by 4 percent on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fairly good proof that we are connecting with the
young male viewer,'' Bulgrin said. ``All of this bodes well for the
networks. We recognize the value and growth potential of this
important demographic and are very encouraged by what we have seen
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Apocryphal or not, the NHL still has a long, very long, way to
go. The consistently low numbers belie a deeper question: Can
hockey ever become a popular, nationally televised sport in this
day of a gazillion channels filled with sports programming?
</P>
<P>
   The NHL contract with Disney expires in four years. What happens
if ESPN decides not to air the games and finds other suitable
programming to fill the NHL's place in March, April, and May? ESPN
and ABC officials remain optimistic, but for how long?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1340EDT &QL; 
