<HEADLINE>
FOR RAYTHEON, DIVERSIFICATION WAS THE WRONG MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many moons ago _ 16 years, to be exact _ we were summoned to
Raytheon headquarters for a dressing down by then chief executive
Thomas Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Our sin? We had the temerity to write an article that had
suggested Raytheon would be better off selling its commercial
businesses and concentrating on defense.
</P>
<P>
   A decent but stern man, Phillips let us know we were all wrong.
The defense business, he told us, was a fickle one. Defense
build-ups were inevitably followed by defense build-downs. A
company heavily dependent on the Pentagon could wind up in deep
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was diversification. A Raytheon with one foot in the
commercial world and another in the defense world would produce the
steady results investors would appreciate, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years later, Raytheon is finally reversing course.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Lexington, Mass. company announced the sale of
its troubled engineering and construction unit. Rumors suggest the
commercial aircraft business is on the block, too. The appliance
business was sold off in 1997 and 1998; the publishing and
road-building arms of Raytheon are gone as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the not-too-distant future, Raytheon may be just what Tom
Phillips didn't want it to be: almost a pure-play in defense
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Is that a good idea? Wall Street thinks so and has thought so
for a long time. ``The company should focus on its knitting,'' said
Keith Patriquin, an analyst with Loomis Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   But a look at Raytheon's history doesn't give you that much
confidence the new course will be a better one. If anything, what
Raytheon has proved is that there are risks both inside and outside
defense and that shareholders can be blindsided by either.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon began its diversification efforts in 1964 with the
purchase of Amana, an appliance maker. Over time, the company
became a miniconglomerate. The commercial businesses had their
moments; Amana always had a good reputation. In the mid-1990s, the
construction company was extremely profitable. The Beech Aircraft
line is still considered a bona fide success.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, Wall Street has been underwhelmed by Raytheon's
performance in commercial lines. ``The returns have not been
stellar,'' said John Hayes, an analyst with Independence Investment
Associates in Boston. Others use words like ``spotty'' and
``mixed'' to describe the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awful'' would be a better description for the recent
performance of the construction business. Raytheon practically
handed the division over to Morrison Knudsen this week _ the
purchase price was actually $10 million. Writing off the business
forced Raytheon to post a $181 million loss for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1980s and most of the 1990s, Raytheon excelled on
the defense side. When the Cold War ended, Raytheon gobbled up its
weaker rivals to ensure it would be one of a handful of survivors.
</P>
<P>
   But since last fall, the company has reported heavy casualties
on the defense side, too. Part of the problem is the environment.
As The Wall Street Journal wrote Thursday in a story about
Lockheed, ``Despite a decade of consolidation among US weapons
makers, a global downturn in high-tech arms sales means even the
most competitive contractors are living hand-to-mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the wounds, however, have been self-inflicted. Raytheon
has discovered a series of problems in the units it acquired from
Texas Instruments and Hughes Electronics Corp. that have led to
several quarters of disappointing earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has noticed. Since July, Raytheon's stock has lost
70 percent of its value. Over the long haul, the numbers look
equally dismal.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, Raytheon's stock has provided an annual average
return of 6 percent, compared to 18 percent for the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Index. Put another way, if you had invested $10,000 in
Raytheon in 1984, it would now be worth about $26,000. A comparable
investment in the S&AMP;P would be worth about $148,000. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts and money managers applaud Raytheon's decision to
focus on its core business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty good time to be concentrating on defense
electronics,'' said Paul Nisbet, an analyst with JSA Research.
Nisbet expects defense spending to pick up in the years ahead; that
spending could grow faster still if Republicans win the White House
this fall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Friedman isn't so sure. An analyst with the S&AMP;P Equity
Group, he said that Raytheon is back to square one. The company
moved away from defense in the first place because defense was an
unreliable business. In Friedman's opinion, it still is. He
complains about the government's ``dysfunctional'' procurement
system and the Pentagon's push ``to cut costs to the bone.'' Said
Friedman, ``I have a negative outlook on the whole industry.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the answer? Will Raytheon be better off mostly as a
defense electronics company than it was as a diversified company?
</P>
<P>
   Check back with us in 2016 _ 16 years from now _ and we will
compare the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
