<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3358 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CYBER-TRADING-ART-BOS     04-21 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRADING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BARTER'S BACK, BUT WITH A CYBER-TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the Internet, everything old is new. Even barter, the
practice of buying goods with other goods instead of with money,
has made a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   New Web sites have sprung up to help consumers swap their old
boring books and music recordings for new interesting ones. No cash
changes hands. It's almost like a high-tech return to the Stone
Age, with hunter-gatherers trading meat for vegetables, and waiting
for somebody to invent money.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kevin Wells has done _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Swapit, a Maynard-based music CD exchange launched this month by
Wells and partner Howard Schneider, features bartering with a
difference. His company provides a guaranteed market for people
with unwanted CDs. No need to wait for someone who wants what
you've got; Swapit will take it off your hands, in hopes of trading
it at a profit to somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that there are a lot of friction points for folks in
barter right now,'' says Wells, chairman of the firm's board. One
of these friction points is painfully obvious. How can you be sure
that someone will want to trade their John Coltrane for your Pink
Floyd?
</P>
<P>
   This inability to consistently match buyers and sellers has
always been the crippling defect of barter systems. So people came
up with the idea of money _ an all-purpose medium of exchange that
you could always use to buy something you wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Swapit has come up with its own barter currency, called Swapit
Bucks. Customers get them by sending in disks they no longer
desire. Right now, Swapit only handles music CDs, and only
recordings likely to appeal to a youthful audience, like rock and
rap. The company hopes to add computer games and DVD movies this
June.
</P>
<P>
   People who register at the Swapit Web site (www.swapit.com) can
download and print out postage-paid mailing labels that they can
use to mail the merchandise to Swapit's warehouse in Chicago.
Swapit also plans to set up Federal Express-like drop boxes on
college campuses all over the nation. They're starting out with
drop boxes at the University of Massachusetts at Boston and
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   At the warehouse, all disks are inspected to ensure they're fit
to be swapped. Each disk that passes muster is worth a minimum of
$2 in Swapit Bucks, or more if it's an especially valuable
recording. The company sets disk values with the help of a database
of prices for 300,000 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Once the user has swapped in a few disks, he can start swapping
out others already stored at the warehouse. The Swapit Web site
lists every available disk. If the customer sees something he
likes, he pays the listed price in Swapit Bucks, plus a $2 per disk
transaction fee, which is where Wells figures to make his profit.
There's also a shipping charge of $2.95 per shipment, no matter how
many disks you order.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could literally take five CDs out of the inventory for a
grand total of $12.95,'' said Wells. ``That's the best deal on the
Web, off the Web, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Swapit's competitors might not think so. Such firms as Mr. Swap
and Switchouse use a more conventional approach. Users post
messages about what products they'd be willing to swap and what
products they'd like in exchange. Michael Lin, CEO of San
Francisco-based Switchouse, says that because his site has 200,000
items listed, there are plenty of opportunities to do a deal.
``When you add the tens of thousands of people together, you begin
to find that the matches do exist,'' Lin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells doesn't see why customers should have to wait until
exactly the right swap partner comes along. Besides, Swapit
actually inspects every bartered item, and makes sure they get
shipped. The two parties aren't forced to simply trust each other,
as in a traditional barter system.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists take the barter business seriously; Swapit
is being backed by NetValue Holdings. But Jonathan Gaw, who tracks
e-commerce for International Data Corp. in Mountain View, Calif.,
is dismissive of Internet swap sites. ``Why would I give up the
flexibility of cash for something called Swapit Bucks?'' he
chuckled. ``Money was invented for a very good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Wells claims that 42,000 people have registered at
Swapit since the site went live on April 4, and thousands of swaps
have already taken place. Perhaps barter isn't quite obsolete after
all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
