<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRULY ROBOTIC NEWSREADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is Ananova, the computer-generated character billed as ``the
world's first virtual newsreader,'' just so darn creepy?
</P>
<P>
   It's not the green hair. It's not the jerky facial movements or
the robotic voice that sounds a bit like Max Headroom on estrogen.
It's not the hype that surrounded her debut this week on
ananova.com, a news site launched by the British Press Association.
And it's certainly not the fear that this digital lady will replace
all legitimate journalists and send us begging for PR jobs at _
gasp _ some dot-com startup.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's none of that. The real problem is that she looks
exactly like Mary Poppins.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously. Watch her tilt her head and purse her lips with a
certain smug satisfaction. Give her an umbrella and a perky little
hat, and the next thing you know, she'll be telling you to take
your medicine while she reads the latest headlines. This is too
much to handle: A virtual Mary Poppins look-alike dishing up dirt
in a virtual broadcast shown in streaming video format. It's just
too, well, weird to see the flying nanny tarted up like one of the
Spice Girls (she is said to resemble Posh Spice) and programmed to
express virtual emotions. She winks, she blinks, she grins. When
will she burst into song?
</P>
<P>
   Is this the New New Thing in news delivery or is it a gimmick?
Consider the top stories the synthespian ``covered'' on the Web
site one night recently: An Austrian television station is trying
to attract more female viewers by offering free breast
enlargements; Saddam Hussein's son was voted journalist of the year
by the Iraqi Journalists' Union even though reportedly he can
barely read and write; and a New Zealand cat survived an electric
shock.
</P>
<P>
   These are real stories that were read by the virtual anchor. At
one point in the broadcast, she asked, ``How bizarre is this?''
Good question. It's hard to know which is more disturbing: the
sensation over a crude digital creation or the sensational news she
delivers. Why make such a big deal over a robotic announcer when
instant news read by real anchors is available 24 hours a day on
CNN? And most major news operations are now offering streaming
video coverage of breaking stories on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The folks who gave life to Ananova claim that their creation
isn't just a marketing scheme for the Web site, which is a news
portal. She was designed to deliver information on mobile
telephones, says Mark Hird, publishing director of Ananova Ltd.,
the Press Association's new media division. ``There is a bit of fun
to be had with the concept, but for us, it's deadly serious,'' he
says. ``We are in the real-time information business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site was certainly doing serious business after the
announcement hit all the major news media Wednesday. It took
forever to gain access to the site after traffic skyrocketed. One
television station even conducted a ``live'' interview with the
synthespian. Hird says Ananova has ``an army of fans'' and has
received a few marriage proposals. But despite all the hype, she's
just a computerized glam girl with glassy eyes. It just goes to
show that it doesn't take much to garner headlines these days _ or
to read them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The prim Mary Poppins wouldn't be too popular in a nutty new
online game called Sissy Fight. The game takes you back to the
schoolyard, where catty little girls gang up on each other and
scratch and tease and tattle and cower. Decidedly low-tech, the
game is pretty hilarious. You pick a name, say All That or Marcia
Brady, and compete against as many as five other players. You don't
have to know how to handle a joystick: This is a girl's game, after
all. You chat with the other players as the game proceeds and win
self-esteem points by successfully terrorizing the other players.
The girl with the most self-esteem points wins. The game is at
www.sissyfight.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While some folks were learning to survive in the schoolyard,
others escaped into the supernatural world of the ``Lord of the
Rings'' trilogy. Frankly, some of us never got the whole Tolkien
thing, but it continues to be widely popular. In fact, a film
adaptation that won't even be released until December 2001 is
already creating quite a stir online. The trailer for ``The Lord of
the Rings: The Fellowship of the Rings'' was downloaded 1.7 million
times in the first 24 hours after its release online a few weeks
ago. The film stars Elijah Wood and Liv Tyler. The trailer is at
www.lordoftherings.net/previews.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange day, indeed, when the president-elect of Russia
emulates an American horror writer. But that's exactly what
happened this week when Vladimir Putin's publisher announced that
an English translation of the Russian politician's memoirs will be
available on the Internet at the same time it is released in US
bookstores next week. Stephen King made headlines earlier this year
when he published his newest novella, ``Riding the Bullet,''
exclusively online. The e-book version of Putin's memoirs, titled
``First Person,'' will be distributed at www.peanutpress.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The upheaval in the music industry continues apace, as Dr. Dre
threatened to sue Napster, which developed the popular online
song-swapping program, if Napster doesn't remove his songs from its
system. Earlier this month, Metallica sued Napster for copyright
and also sued Yale University, the University of Southern
California, and Indiana University, where the popular program is
widely used; the heavy metal band has since dropped the suit
against Yale, which has banned Napster on campus. And April 20
Indiana blocked the program on its campus as well. The battle seems
like it's only going to get hotter and more contentious.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, EMI announced that it is putting its entire catalog
online _ in sheet music form, that is. Musicians who want to cover
songs by Sting, Aerosmith, or other EMI artists can download the
sheet music from www.net4music.com for $3.95 a song. It's hardly a
revolution, but like Ananova, it's being billed as another
(dubious) Internet first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Patti Hartigan's e-mail address is hartigan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
