<HEADLINE>
TAUT `CROUPIER' DEALS A WINNING HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CROUPIER 
Directed by: Mike Hodges 
Screenplay by: Paul Mayersberg 
Starring: Clive Owen, Gina McKee, Alex Kingston, Alexander Morton,
Kate Hardie, Nicholas Ball 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Unrated 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three best British crime movies of the last few decades are
``Get Carter,'' ``The Long Good Friday'' and ``The Krays.'' Mike
Hodges's ``Croupier'' isn't quite in their class, but it comes
pretty close. It's brilliantly precise in its detailing, stylishly
jagged and sensual by turns, and utterly unpredictable. Hodges, who
also directed ``Get Carter,'' sets ``Croupier'' in an airless
world, whether in the glassy closed circuit of the casino, or the
cramped basement flat where the croupier of the title lives with an
ex-policewoman girlfriend who romanticizes his own view of himself
as a writer and, without meaning to, increases the tension level
between them by trying to nag him into writing a literary
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Clive Owens's title-role in ``Croupier'' is just as arresting
and compulsively watchable as Michael Caine's avenger gunning for
the man who killed his brother in ``Get Carter.'' But while Caine's
nemesis figure went looking for trouble, Owen's sinister but more
passive protagonist goes to a lot of trouble to insulate himself
from it. A native South African, he has come to England partly
because literary careers are not made in South Africa, and partly
because he wants to get beyond the reach of his con-man father, who
keeps phoning him long-distance and posing as a big shot while
working as a bartender in a resort.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, Jack says, ``I hate cheaters,'' and means it.
But what he's really saying is that he hates his father, played,
during the few times we see him on the phone, with a con man's mix
of bluster and desperation. Of course, Jack is a run-of-the-mill
fugitive from intimacy, too. When he fears he's growing too
dependent on his girlfriend's salary, he reluctantly but resolutely
goes back to the one thing he does know well, which is how to cut
the cards and stay cool. Apart from the fact that he's got the
right skills, the croupier's job suits him temperamentally. Unlike
the players and the plungers, he can hang back and be in the
action, but not of it.
</P>
<P>
   What changes his game plan, and forces him to scramble to find a
new one, is first an involvement with Kate Hardie's sexy little
sparrow of a fellow croupier, then a flirtation with a worldly
woman (Alex Kingston), whose invitation to drinks quickly turns
into a heist scheme. Naturally, none of this sits well with his
girlfriend, the ex-cop. In several ways the walls close in, and
Owen's taciturn pillar of non-involvement exchanges his slightly
sinister look for a hunted expression. Can he negotiate the
labyrinth devised by someone cleverer than he? Or will he become
yet another neo-noir casualty? Hodges and Owen keep us guessing _
and caring _ in this delicious little silken minefield of a movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
