<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FILTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FILTH' DOCUMENTS PISTOLS' FURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE FILTH AND THE FURY 
Directed by: Julien Temple 
Produced by: Anita Camarata and Amanda Temple 
Starring: Johnny Rotten, Sid Vicious, Steve Jones, Paul Cook and
Glen Matlock. 
Running Time: 105 minutes 
(Unrated) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most rockumentaries _ documentaries that look back on the glory
days _ are insufferable. They tend to be stupefyingly dull, smugly
self-aggrandizing, or they follow the cliched arc of
struggle/success/failure, as the ancient (surviving) band members
reminisce about all the drugs taken, groupies plundered, and music
made. Those were the days, my friend . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Sex Pistols' rockumentary, ``The Filth and the Fury,'' made
by director Julien Temple, is a different animal. True, the
pioneering British punk rock band imploded after one album and one
US tour, with singer Johnny Rotten spitting out ``Ever get the
feeling you've been cheated?'' at the audience during the last
show, in San Francisco. And, true, one of its members, Sid Vicious,
is shown nodding off during an interview, being jabbed by his
junkie-nag of a girlfriend Nancy Spungen. And, after being accused
of killing her, Vicious overdoses on heroin and dies shortly after
being released from jail.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sex Pistols really did change the course of pop history
_ their angry, bastard children are still spitting out songs of
discontent. The Sex Pistols came from another time and place _
certainly not a less cynical time, but a time when rock revolution
seemed a possibility. In 1976, the Pistols emerged from the
underbelly of London's working class and, with the aid of manager
Malcolm McLaren, turned 1976 upside down in its native land,
landing a no. 1 single, ``God Save the Queen,'' that the BBC
banned. They got signed by one record label _ then sacked. Signed
again _ sacked. They were, as Rotten sang, ``the poison in the
human machine . . . the flowers in the dustbin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and the Fury,'' which employs previously unused
concert footage and intercuts it with scenes of London street life
at the time, makes its point: The Pistols were very much about the
collision of rock and politics. They came from a time before rage
was codified _ before it became a product and entertainment tool.
It is richly ironic that Temple made an earlier Sex Pistols movie,
``The Great Rock 'n' Roll Swindle,'' as a fantasy concocted by
McLaren; the current movie, as Rotten says as a key narrator (in
silhouette), was done to right the many wrongs. As to the band, he
posits, it was ``a bit like a Harold Pinter play _ it shouldn't
work but it does.'' Fast hard music, quick cutting from scene to
scene, with step-back moments such as Rotten musing about his old,
duped friend Vicious: ``I wish I was smarter. Poor sod.'' This is a
warts 'n' all portrayal _ there's no dodging the feelings of both
disgust and amusement the Pistols take toward Fleet Street and the
muck they kick up. (The movie's title is taken from a tabloid
headline the day after the Pistols appeared on national TV and,
goaded by a drunken host, cussed and cut up on camera.) Rotten is,
as always, entertaining and lacerating _ both to himself and
others. Guitarist Steve Jones also hits with comments that often
counter Rotten's perception.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Temple interrupts the action and the yak to
include scenes from the 1955 film version of ``Richard III,''
suggesting the Pistols saga is a classic three-act tragedy and that
Rotten modeled his hunchbacked persona after the doomed king. The
Sex Pistols proclaimed ``No future!'' and, of course, it was
self-fulfilling. But the hellbent ride they went on was
exhilarating. ``The Filth and the Fury'' captures the essence of
that trip and the surviving, older Pistols put it all in context.
One thing you come away with: This was rebellion, this was anarchy,
but this was fun. Briefly, the world was their oyster and, even if
they hated oysters, they loved spitting them out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
