<SLUG> BC-HKN-PODEIN2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRINDER PODEIN HAS COLORADO RIDING HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ No one is saying that he is going to dominate the
playoffs or turn himself into this spring's surprise sniper, a la
John Druce or Chris Kontos or Stephane Matteau of playoff years
past, but Colorado left wing Shjon Podein already has broken out in
this year's Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   By all definitions, he's an NHL grinder, a guy who skates his
lane, takes the body, and who for the better part of eight seasons
now has chugged along in two-bladed anonymity. However, in the
first three games of Colorado's first-round series against the
Coyotes, the reliable, hard-working Podein scored three of the
Avalanche's 13 goals.
</P>
<P>
   In today's low-scoring, clutch-and-grab, offense-be-damned NHL,
three goals from a guy like Podein is a downright embarrassment for
the third- and fourth-liners of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he's an ambassador for us all,'' kidded teammate Jeff
Odgers, the ex-Bruin who has made a career of filling out third and
fourth lines, mostly for his pugilistic prowess. ``Shjon Podein,
the people's wrist shot.''
</P>
<P>
   On a team far better known for its multitude of offensive
riches, Podein for the most part is just a suit, the navy blue 40
regular kept in the back of the closet for family functions and
annual performance reviews with the boss. Originally a draft pick
of the Oilers, he played two-plus seasons in the AHL (Cape Breton)
before finally getting his chance in Edmonton, and his stay there
was fragmented over two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed up at my first Oiler camp at 225 pounds,'' recalled
Podein, now a well-conditioned 200. ``I went in thinking that I'd
bulk up, that I'd need that extra weight and muscle to play in the
NHL. I was going to be that big defensive winger. It took me about
two shifts to realize that I was skating about half the speed of
everyone else. I figured right there, `Hmm, this ain't gonna work.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, though, he was accustomed to the hockey world
flying by him. Born and raised in Rochester, Minn., Podein wasn't
drafted out of high school as an 18-year-old. He also was left off
everyone's wish list the next year, in the 1987 draft. By the time
the '88 draft rolled around, and the local paper was running
stories of how he probably would get selected this time, after a
respectable freshman season (4-4_8 in 30 games) at the University
of Minnesota-Duluth, Podein had learned not to get too emotionally
invested in the annual amateur jamboree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember driving back from California with a friend of
mine, and I stopped in Omaha to call home,'' said Podein. ``My dad
was telling me, `You know, there's a story in the paper here that
says you'll probably get drafted.' They were saying maybe I'd go in
the fifth or sixth round, somewhere in there, but I'd heard all
that before. I didn't think it would happen, and if it didn't, I
was going to finish my four years at college, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   What he did care about, if someone did want him, was the state
of the NHL at the time. Summed up neatly, that state was Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The high-powered Oilers, who were still a few weeks away from
trading Wayne Gretzky, already had won four Stanley Cups. There was
a bonafide dynasty in northern Alberta, with the likes of Mark
Messier, Glenn Anderson, Jari Kurri, and Paul Coffey filling out
the most powerful offense in league history. They scored at will
and skated like the wind.
</P>
<P>
   No way in the world, thought Podein, would Edmonton want a guy
like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmonton,'' came the voice over the public address system that
late afternoon at the draft, ``your selection, please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmonton, with the 166th selection,'' answered the Oilers'
table, ``drafts Shjon Podein from the University of
Minnesota-Duluth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, just back from the drive from California, Podein
tiptoed into the family home in Rochester in the wee hours of
Sunday morning. There was no note on the kitchen table: ``Shjon,
good goin', you're a proud member of the (fill in the blank).'' He
tapped his mom's shoulder around 3 a.m., and listened incredulously
as she mumbled his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's all groggy and everything, but she says, `Oh, yeah, you
got picked by Edmonton,' '' he recalled. ``Edmonton? No way. The
fastest, best-skating team in the whole league, and they pick me?''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years later, history shows that Podein, though not fleet
afoot, was the best of the 13 picks the Oilers made that June day.
Their top choice, No. 19, was Francois Leroux, the lumbering
6-foot-6-inch defenseman who never has made it beyond journeyman
status in his tours with Edmonton, Ottawa, Pittsburgh, and
Colorado. Of the 11 other picks, the only to enjoy even limited
success has been Len Barrie, playing these days with Florida, his
second stop there after tries with Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, and
even a couple of seasons in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Before Podein got anywhere in the NHL, he had to drop the 25
pounds and pick up his pace. That meant two full seasons in Cape
Breton, playing for the Oilers' farm team, where he worked first
and foremost on his skating. Eventually up to speed, he got two
looks with the Oilers, each lasting about half a season, but 27
points over 68 games would not be enough to convince the Oilers to
keep him in the organization. In the summer of 1994, the Flyers
signed him as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   In his four-plus seasons with the Flyers, cast into the
defensive winger role, Podein's scoring pace picked up slightly.
His best season there, though, was only 32 points (14 goals) in
1996-97. By early last season, the Flyers were looking for someone
with similiar size, but with more of a scoring touch. The answer,
they thought, was Keith Jones, the ex-Washington right wing whose
scoring touch was beginning to wane in Colorado. On Nov. 12, 1998,
Jones headed east and Podein went west.
</P>
<P>
   ``His production had kind of slowed down,'' said Colorado
general manager Pierre Lacroix, referring to Jones. ``He'd been
used on top lines, previous to us, and his production here had
slowed down. We were pleased with what we'd seen in (Chris) Drury
and (Milan) Hejduk, and Podein looked like more of an all-around
player for us. It was a question of adjusting the chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the tinkering looks like a magical touch. Podein
was shut out in Colorado's 3-2 loss to the Coyotes Wednesday night,
dropping the Avalanche's series lead to 3-1, but his offense and
speed have made him an unsavory presence for the Desert Dogs. It
was hard enough for them to cover the likes of Joe Sakic, Peter
Forsberg, Drury, and Hejduk. Now they've got to find a way to
contain the guy with that funny first name.
</P>
<P>
   Shjon. It was a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad wanted to name me Wolfgang,'' said Podein. ``My mom
didn't like that. She wanted Shaun. They put that together with my
grandfather's name, Jon, and went with Shjon. I think Wolfgang
would have been kinda tough, sort of like that song, ``A Boy Named
Sue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue, the sniper with the sizzling wrist shot. It probably
wouldn't have caused many to quake in their skates. But it is the
playoffs, a time when the otherwise unknown often do make a name
for themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
