<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MORNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LIFE AND HARD TIMES OF A JAZZ PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MORNING GLORY: A Biography of Mary Lou Williams 
By Linda Dahl. 
Pantheon Books, 463 pp. illus. $30.00. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Lou Williams was the first great woman instrumentalist in
jazz. Born in 1910, she started playing the piano by ear when she
was 3, and spent much of the remaining 67 years of her life at the
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   She was not just a superb pianist but a first-class musician who
created jazz Masses, attempted a concert suite, and wrote tunes and
arrangements for Benny Goodman, Jimmy Lunceford, and Duke Ellington
himself. Her real genius nevertheless lay not in composing or
arranging, but in improvisation, in letting her soul pour through
her fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Her career was not an uninterrupted series of musical triumphs.
She made everything she did sound easy, but in fact she achieved
every success in the face of intimidating obstacles _ personal,
musical, artistic, financial and social. She was an
African-American women working in an artistic field that was
inventing itself as it went along; her art was produced in the
moment, but there is no way to extricate it from her life and its
times.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's life makes a great story, and Linda Dahl's new
biography narrates it with zest and compassion. Williams was born,
out of wedlock, in Atlanta. Her mother took in laundry and drank.
She never met her father until she was in her mid-20s. When she was
5, the family moved to Pittsburgh, where she became ``the little
piano girl of East Liberty.'' She played for friends and neighbors,
she played in church, roadhouses, saloons, and brothels. The
sporting men looked out for her until her natural beauty came into
bloom, and then she had her hands full.
</P>
<P>
   Abused and unhappy at home, Williams left at age 13 to join a
``talent show'' called Boise De Legg and His Hottentots; she spent
decades in what she called ``the mud and muck'' of life on the
road. Her first great success was with Andy Kirk and his Twelve
Clouds of Joy; as ``The Lady Who Swings the Band,'' she was to a
significant degree responsible for that success. She married a
couple of times, had an abortion, went through a long series of
love affairs, but steered clear of the occupational hazards of
drink and drugs. She had a big heart, and her Harlem apartment was
for decades a kind of informal rehab for family members, friends,
and jazz musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Williams enjoyed great success and was ``taken up'' at various
times in her life from childhood on, but when you are taken up, it
isn't long before you are put down. Williams was never financially
secure until the last three years of her life, when she became
artist-in-residence at Duke University (a plan for her to come to
the University of Massachusetts never came to fruition). By the
mid-1950s, Williams had reached some kind of personal and artistic
crisis. The personal crisis found resolution when she entered the
Catholic Church. That decision may have prolonged the artistic
crisis, because Williams became reluctant to play in nightclubs and
other ``sinful'' environments; she tried to support herself by
opening a thrift shop. Several priests proved helpful to her,
persuading her that she could serve her faith through her music;
one of them, a Jesuit, Peter O'Brien, became her manager, and
brought her back into her musical world _ she trusted him to
protect her. Much of her music from that time on was religious in
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Dahl depended on O'Brien's cooperation to produce Williams's
biography, so she handles him with kid gloves, but it's still
abundantly clear why he became a controversial figure, and how
their friendship brought both deep satisfaction but also unleashed
complex tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Dahl is unsatisfactory only in describing the most important
part of Williams's life, her music. For decades Williams kept up
with changing styles and fashions in jazz, from boogie to bop,
often one step ahead of others, while always remaining true to
herself. Sometimes a somewhat radical figure, Williams became
fundamentally conservative, and mistrustful of developments she
thought inimical to the true spirit of jazz. Because Dahl is wobbly
when writing about music, she turns to a variety of sources of
variable quality when she needs to describe Williams's playing,
improvisation or composition. When an observation comes along that
actually make sense, and lets you hear Mary Lou Williams, it
usually comes from Gunther Schuller.
</P>
<P>
   What Dahl's book does make you want to do is listen to Mary Lou
Williams again. Although Dahl's ``selected discography'' runs to
some 30 pages, not enough of it is readily available, and even the
complete discography is hardly an adequate survey of her art _
Williams made no solo records between 1929 and 1971, for example,
and many of the records she did make were poorly recorded and
undertaken in adverse circumstances. Has anyone ever mentioned, or
even noticed, that she recorded one of her famous creations, the
``Zodiac Suite,'' on an inferior and out-of-tune piano? The
``Zodiac Suite'' is a series of playful, allusive and elusive
portraits of jazz colleagues, but it also tells you a lot about
Williams. What the recording sounds like tells you about what she
had to overcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
