<HEADLINE>
CLAYMATION `MIRACLE' SOMEWHAT WOODEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MIRACLE MAKER 
Starring the voices of: Ralph Fiennes, Miranda Richardson, Julie
Christie, Ian Holm 
Directed by: Stanislav Sokolov and Derek Hayes 
On: ABC, Sunday at 7 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the dog with a conscience on ``Davey and Goliath,'' the
stop-action animation series on Sunday mornings in the '60s and
'70s? A few minutes into ``The Miracle Maker,'' a new clay
animation feature about Jesus Christ, you may begin waiting for
Goliath to wander onto the streets of Galilee, plaintively
muttering something like ``But Day-vee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miracle Maker,'' which airs Sunday at morning, is
old-fashioned Sunday-morning TV, for sure. While ABC has scheduled
it in prime time, in honor of Easter, the movie would stand more
comfortably beside daytime religious-school programming for kids.
From its quaint, retro look to the way it makes its morals and
lessons extremely plain, ``The Miracle Maker'' is traditional,
educational, and a little dull.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Jesus is popular on TV these days, maybe as a
result of network honchos on the prowl for big millennial themes.
Last November, NBC served up ``Mary, Mother of Jesus,'' and next
month CBS will deliver a two-parter called ``Jesus.'' This version,
made in the UK, follows the familiar narrative path, as the adult
Jesus gains the trust of the people while he poses a threat to the
powers that be. He selects his apostles, one of whom will betray
him; he teaches his parables, which are shown to us in 2-D
animation; and he performs miracles, most notably bringing Lazarus
back from the grave. The movie skips quickly through the
Crucifixion, placing more weight on the later resurrection of
Christ and the faith that it engenders.
</P>
<P>
   The voice cast is impressive, with Ralph Fiennes as a gentle
Jesus and Miranda Richardson as the outcast ``Mad Mary'' Magdalene.
But the characters' clay figures appear exceedingly stiff, and many
of the male faces are generic. It takes a while to distinguish the
apostles, as they move about in jittery increments. Maybe I've been
ruined by the slick stop-motion approach that you find in the
music-video era, maybe I like a few humorous moments blended in
with all the earnestness, but I found ``The Miracle Maker''
visually monotonous and thematically oversimplified. It's an
honorable portrayal of Jesus, one that won't offend, but it's not
very dynamic television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
