A3387 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-LOVE-BOS &LR;      04-21 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING HOOPS, WINNING `LOVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
LOVE &AMP; BASKETBALL 
Written and directed by: Gina Prince-Bythewood 
Starring: Omar Epps, Sanaa Lathen, Alfre Woodard, Dennis Haysbert,
Debbi Morgan, Harry J. Lennix 
Running time: 118 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sexuality and language) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Love &AMP; Basketball'' is not only Hollywood's first film built
around a woman basketball player. It's also Hollywood's first good
film built around a woman basketball player. It's a breakthrough
movie with a breakout performance by Sanaa Lathan as a woman who
resents having to choose between love and basketball, and wants
both. You'll care whether she gets both because love counts for as
much as basketball in this film that's much more than a sports
highlight reel as the boy next door and the girl next door fall for
each other, helped by their mutual passion for the game, then spend
years trying to balance both.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a driveway scrimmage in an LA suburb as a bunch
of preteen guys are forced to admit that the girl who tricked them
into letting her play by hiding her long hair under a baseball cap
is demonstrably better than most of them. Then the film skips a few
years and really gets interesting on a couple of fronts. Omar
Epps's high school all-star goes on to USC. It's expected of him,
given that his father (Dennis Haysbert) is a former NBA star.
What's not expected is that Lathan's young woman hoopster will also
go to USC and play varsity basketball there, too.
</P>
<P>
   When they take their identical dreams to the next level, they
aim at the NBA and WNBA, respectively. They also have eyes for each
other, and one of the things that sets this film apart not only
from most sports films, but from most Hollywood films, is that they
are given the chance to let us feel how their relationship deepens
over time. Both performers are warm and personable, and we want to
see them get together. They try to in college, but they can't make
it work, mainly because Epps's Quincy is too self-centered not to
allow for the fact that Lathan's Monica must battle harder than he
has to in order to be a player.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, basketball comes a lot easier than the rest of life
does to each of them. Each has to work at love, or, rather, at
finding room for it alongside the single-mindedness demanded by
their passion for the game. Problems between his parents call forth
a becoming sensitivity from Quincy. Monica's parents (Alfre
Woodard, Harry J. Lennix) are blessed with a more stable life. Most
of her problems stem from a fiery nature she must learn to control.
Each is generous, but at different stages in their respective
lives. The romantic suspense is generated by the question of
whether they'll ever get their believably deep and genuine feelings
for the other in phase.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the basketball-playing component of their respective
lives is a breeze. Commendably, the film plays down glamour to
spotlight the grueling routine of the fast-track professional level
each is chasing. Nothing quite works out as either plans, but
another engaging thing about the film is the way it allows its
characters a few missteps, yet lets them keep their dreams alive.
``Love &AMP; Basketball'' has a bit more sprawl than is good for it; on
the other hand, it breathes and has an emotional amplitude that is
all but unknown in sports movies. In basketball, the best shooters
have soft hands. In filmmaking, too. ``Love &AMP; Basketball'' is the
cinematic equivalent of a high, arching rainbow of a three-pointer
from midcourt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1353EDT &QL; 
