<HEADER>
A3392 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-YOUNG-BOS &LR;      04-21 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-YOUNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GEM FROM NEIL YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Without a doubt, Neil Young was the star of the recent Crosby,
Stills, Nash &AMP; Young tour that passed through town. Ask people who
were there and the answer is the same. They'll tell you that
Young's comrades performed well, but that he stole the show,
whether it was on cosmic hippie ballads or on primitivistic rockers
that he lifted into &UR;  &LR; the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In the year 2000, a keen argument could be made that Young, even
more than Bob Dylan, is the most skilled troubadour of his time _
or at least the most enduring and most reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Young can seem ageless, which is how he appears on his new solo
album, ``Silver &AMP; Gold'' (Reprise Records), due out Tuesday. An
acoustic-based work, it completes a trilogy of sorts that started
with his ``Harvest'' album in 1972 and continued with ``Harvest
Moon'' in 1992.The zenith is reached in ``Silver &AMP; Gold,'' which
has some of the most affecting, and certainly most pure, love songs
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Harvest'' was more damaged _ think back to its
centerpiece song, ``The Needle and the Damage Done'' _ the new
album reveals Young to be a contented man who has recaptured an
almost childlike belief in love. He starts out with ``Good to See
You,'' a jaunty acoustic track (with harmonica and pedal steel
guitar) in which he sings, ``I've been down on the endless highway
. . . Now at last I'm home to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Young has enjoyed a solid marriage to his wife, Pegi, who is
known nationally for organizing the annual Bridge School benefit
concert in San Francisco, which aids disadvantaged children and has
starred everyone from Pearl Jam to David Bowie. The Youngs have a
son with cerebral palsy. They've worked together to support him _
and that loving bond is supremely apparent on the new CD.
</P>
<P>
   The title track, ``Silver &AMP; Gold,'' is a prime example. Amid
ringing guitar chords and silvery harmonica runs, Young sings, ``I
don't care if the sun don't shine and the rain comes pouring down
on me and mine/Because our kind of love never seems to get old/It's
better than silver and gold.''
</P>
<P>
   The dobro-flecked ``Red Sun,'' featuring gleaming harmonies from
Emmylou Harris and Linda Ronstadt, is another example. Young the
innocent poet sings: ``When the red sun sets on the railroad
town/And the bars begin to laugh with a happy sound/I'll still be
here right by your side/There'll not be anyone in my heart but
you.'' Warm and fuzzy, yes, but the music is simply transporting.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when many musicians feel they must shout to be heard,
Young succeeds with an unspeakably tender tone on this year's best
album. Nine of the 10 tracks are superb _ and not all are about his
wife. ``Daddy Went Walkin','' a country-spiced tune with pedal
steel guitar licks from Ben Keith, is about Young's parents: an
``old man crossing that road, he's feeling fine/ Mama's waiting at
the top of the hill/They'll be laughing, oh the stories they'll
tell/When he holds her in his arms again, they'll be sweethearts.''
</P>
<P>
   While Young is mostly blissed out on this album, he looks back
longingly to the '60s when he was in the band Buffalo Springfield
with future CSNY member Stephen Stills. ``I'd like to see those
guys again and give it a shot/Maybe now we can show the world what
we got/But I'd just like to play for the fun we had,'' sings Young.
</P>
<P>
   The sparsely arranged, quietly brilliant album is being released
in conjunction with a ``Silver &AMP; Gold'' home video, which is
another treat. It's a concert special taped in Austin, Texas, with
Young sitting at a stool surrounded by 10 guitars or alone at an
upright piano. Dry-ice smoke wafts up occasionally from behind his
amp, which heightens the mystique. That, and sheer talent, enable
Young to capture the viewer's attention and never let it go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      04-21 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONHAM REDISCOVERS HERSELF `DOWN HERE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about a contrast. Tracy Bonham had her fleeting moment of
Grammy fame four years ago when nominated for two awards for her
debut album (``The Burdens of Being Upright'') and its modern-rock
hit, ``Mother Mother.'' She won neither award _ and the next year
was back in the Boston suburb of Watertown, wearing her pajamas all
day and mired in the dreaded sophomore slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hole myself up and try to write, but my mind would take
over and I'd worry about all the people who might really hate me,''
says Bonham. ``And I'd have (record label) people come in and hear
what I was doing and say, `I don't know if I hear a single. Can you
fix that?' So I was rewriting all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, she overcame her malaise. She took a mind-clearing trip
to Belgium with her new husband, Steve Slingeneyer (a drummer who
now plays in her band), and read the self-help book ``The Artist's
Way,'' by Julie Cameron, which eased her fears with its suggestions
to lighten up and not be so hard on oneself.
</P>
<P>
   After spending 10 years around Boston and attending Berklee
College of Music, Bonham then moved to Brooklyn, and the new
surroundings further unlocked her creativity. The upshot is the
much-anticipated sophomore disc, ``Down Here,'' which is worth the
wait. It features a sturdy rock framework of riffing guitars
enhanced by more of her sensuous violin accents (she had even
played violin with Page &AMP; Plant at their Boston show), topped by
her famously malleable voice and survivor lyrics such as ``Thank
God that I'm not perfect _ I happen to like all my defects.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonham has a new single, ``Behind Every Good Woman,'' which is
another likely hit. It's a satirical, role-reversal story that
turns the cliche of ``behind every man lies a good woman'' to
``behind every good woman lies a trail of men.'' She admits that
she's poking fun at the machismo of the record business, but also
at the culture in general, exemplified by the song's video in which
a motorcycle-driving Bonham visits a strip club and high-fives
other patrons just as men might do.
</P>
<P>
   The new album also has empowering tracks ``Jumping Bean'' (``I
can't be your jumping bean anymore'') and ``You Don't Know Me''
(``You think you own me, but you don't know me and your thickness
is hard to believe''). Bonham may be happily married these days,
but she still hasn't forgotten past relationship hurts. It's a
personal album and a highly musical one thanks to the ingenious
experimental production team of Mitchell Froom and Tchad Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're complete opposites,'' Bonham says. ``Tchad looks like
he should be in a pickup truck driving through the desert. He
brought in a loose element of `who (cares)?' But Mitchell is more
uptight and brainy _ very Woody Allen-like.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though she's now in New York, Bonham hasn't lost touch with
Boston. She has two Boston musicians in her band _ Peter Adams and
Joe Klompus, who was in Jack Drag and Orangutang. And though she
doesn't miss some of the jealous, local ``backstabbing'' that
occurred after her ``Mother Mother'' success, she admits, ``I miss
a lot of things about Boston. I miss all the good bands.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bloodhound Gang spoof: The song has been all over rock radio
with its refrain of ``You and me, baby, we ain't nothing but
mammals, so let's do it like they do on the Discovery Channel.''
Entitled ``The Bad Touch,'' it's a hit for the Bloodhound Gang, a
former frat-party band whose frontman, Jimmy Pop, wrote it after
``watching monkeys mate'' on the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not write a song about it?'' asks Pop, has rib-tickled the
mainstream with previous ditties such as ``Why's Everybody Always
Pickin' on Me?'' and ``Kiss Me Where It Smells Funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Pop readily admits that his group's music revels in junk culture
(``People can relate to junk culture everywhere in the world,'' he
says), which is obvious on the band's new album, ``Hooray for
Boobies.'' Some of the songs, however, are a lot less clever, and a
lot raunchier, than the Discovery Channel anthem. As Pop writes in
the bio that accompanied copies of the record sent to the press: ``
`Hooray for Boobies' is stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with him on such songs as ``The Ballad of
Chasey Lain'' (a paean to a porn queen) and ``The Inevitable Return
of the Great White Dope,'' of which he says, ``I tried to write a
song about how cool I am, but I ended up sounding like a 7-year-old
in a crash helmet having a temper tantrum through a Mister
Microphone.'' But other songs are hilarious in a kind of Kid
Rock-meets-Kinky Friedman way, including ``Hell Yeah'' (with its
line, ``If I were god, I would not worship false Billy Idols'') and
``Take the Long Way Home'' (``Life is an aimless drive that you
take alone/ You might as well enjoy the ride'').
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, the Bloodhoung Gang is heavily influenced
by shock jock Howard Stern, who has often played their music on his
syndicated morning show. ``I grew up listening to Howard Stern,''
says Pop. ``He's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Korn backlash: This writer is still digging out from some
hostile e-mails concerning the positive review I gave Korn at the
Worcester Centrum Center recently. Korn sold out two nights and
gave its best show in memory, but detractors were quick to mail in
their dissension. Wrote one: ``Next time you are searching for
adjectives for lame, flavor-of-the-month groups such as Korn, think
twice before you use words such as `heavy.' . . . Rap-rock groups
like Korn are riding the coattails of far more deserving, true
metal bands.'' Another wrote: ``Here's a list of bands to check out
(instead): Opeth, Emperor, Satyricon, Mayhem, Immortal, Absu
Abigor, Cryptopsy . . Incantation, Morbid Angel, etc.'' Hey,
whatever gets you through the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
