<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-STOOGES-HNS &LR;      04-21 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STOOGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE THREE STOOGES STORY: BIO-PIC DOES HONOR TO AMERICAN ICONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years back, a buddy of mine was getting married. Killing
time before the ceremony, we clicked on the television in the B&AMP;B
where we were staying: On popped ``The Three Stooges.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't get it, don't worry: It's a guy thing. The marriage
didn't stick, but the Stooges are forever.
</P>
<P>
   Before there was professional wrestling, ``Monday Night
Football,'' muscle cars or Playboy, there was ``The Three
Stooges.'' The brothers Howard, Larry Fine and a pair of Joes
pounded, poked and nyuk'ed each other through 190 or so film shorts
for Columbia Pictures from 1934 to 1958. They later became staples
on television _ where they live on today _ as well as a successful
touring act.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was and remains strictly male. Why do most women hate
the Stooges?
</P>
<P>
   Probably because of all the wanton violence, base behavior,
meanness, pure idiocy and absence of plot. In others words, for all
the reasons guys love 'em.
</P>
<P>
   But even women should like the ABC biopic ``The Three Stooges,''
a fun and touching, if sketchy, homage by producer and major
Stoogehead Mel Gibson that airs Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While they were the kings of irreverence, the Stooges are looked
upon reverentially by fans. Portraying the act known for more than
65 years on film and four decades of television is a risky
proposition. (Go try to find a satisfying dramatic rendition of
Babe Ruth.)
</P>
<P>
   We know Moe, Larry and Curly, and lesser Stooges Shemp, Joe and
Curly-Joe. Screw up a re-creation of the boys and it will leave us
with a bitter taste _ and you with an eye poke, face slap and shin
kick.
</P>
<P>
   No worry: ``The Three Stooges'' does honor to the Three Stooges.
</P>
<P>
   As Moe Howard and his lifelong friend Larry Fine, Paul
Ben-Victor (``Crazy in Alabama'') and Evan Handler (``It's like,
you know ...'') bear a strong resemblance to their counterparts,
while John Kassir is a more than adequate Shemp.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Chiklis (``Daddio,'' ``The Commish'') has the
toughest role, playing the often imitated but never duplicated
Curly, with his finger snapping, face rubbing and nyuk-nyuking. The
whole movie hinges on Chiklis being able to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   He does. In fact, the makers of the film _ based on Michael
Fleming's biography ``From Amalgamated Morons to American Icons:
The Three Stooges'' _ felt comfortable enough to let the actors
re-create scenes from some of the classic shorts. Chiklis nails it,
especially the famous shellfish-spitting scene.
</P>
<P>
   Told from Moe's perspective, ``The Three Stooges'' follows the
trio from their stage beginnings through the untimely deaths of
little brother Curly and Shemp and their post-film careers.
</P>
<P>
   While two hours doesn't offer much of a chance for depth, it
would have been nice to get more than thumbnail sketches of each
performer: Moe got bamboozled by the studio execs; Larry was a
gambler who felt Hollywood was ripping off the troupe; Curly just
went along with his big brother when not out partying; and Shemp
was a nervous wreck.
</P>
<P>
   That said, even Stooge fans (although not the die-hards) will
learn things from this film:
</P>
<P>
   Shemp, not Curly, was in fact an original Stooge, although he
left the act before the boys hit it big in Hollywood. ``I haven't
run out of brothers yet,'' Moe says when Shemp left in 1933. Shemp
only returned after his brother Curly's 1946 stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Moe, Larry and Shemp started out in vaudeville working as backup
players to a jealous egomaniac named Ted Healy (Marton Csokas), who
grossly underpaid them. ``I know it's rough, but we are stooges,''
the movie Moe tells his brother Shemp in 1925. ``We're a dime a
dozen.''
</P>
<P>
   Curly was known as Jerry (his given name was Jerome) to his
friends, and Babe (for baby brother) to his sibling Moe.
</P>
<P>
   For a short time after his film career waned, Moe delivered
sandwiches to Hollywood lots. The act was chronically underpaid,
although that practice was pretty common under the studio system.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of ``The Three Stooges'' could have given us a little
more on the women in their lives to provide context, but Gibson and
company did not attempt to make a definitive history here. A hammer
to the head, a double-gut punch and a good nose wrench is good
enough. Must be a guy thing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
