<P>
   COURT-ABORTION (Washington) _ The cultural and legal war over
abortion turns to the U.S. Supreme Court this week, as the justices
hear arguments on the constitutionality of a state's ban on
late-term abortions. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   IDENTITY-THEFT (Washington) _ Thieves have swiped personal data
such as Social Security numbers, birth dates and addresses for more
than a decade primarily to get bank and checking accounts and
credit cards. But now identity theft is becoming more widespread as
crooks use other people's personal data to open utility accounts,
rent apartments, apply for loans, start businesses, buy cars and
even declare bankruptcy. Some lawmakers, led by Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., are pushing legislation to curb the problem.
By JUDY HOLLAND. (1STLD-WRITETHRU filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE (Washington) _ Child advocacy groups say the 1996 law
requiring welfare recipients to go to work is not providing enough
money for most of them to put their kids in day care. Only about 15
percent of the youngsters eligible for the federally funded care
actually get the subsidy. So many parents can't work or can't get
better paying jobs. But the push for additional funds is iffy since
most Republican lawmakers don't want to spend more for ``a national
nanny,'' as one puts it. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
