<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-U-571-HNS     04-21 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-U-571-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ``U-571'': A SOLID MOVIE BUT NOT MUCH DEPTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a way, it's refreshing how unrefreshing the new submarine
thriller, ``U-571,'' is.
</P>
<P>
   Taut, suspenseful, good-looking, it strives to be old-fashioned
entertainment, complete with cardboard characters (who have names
like Chief, Rabbit and Trigger) injected with doses of star power.
Almost belligerently, it refuses to break new ground (or water, for
that matter) _ certainly it isn't about to give ``Das Boot'' a run
for its money _ but nevertheless it is irresistible entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Based loosely (very loosely) on actual World War II missions to
recover the Enigma coding devices, which contributed largely to
Allied victory, ``U-571'' opens with the German crew of the title
boat in a thrilling battle with a U.S. destroyer. The U-boat
escapes, but is severely crippled and radios for help.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Capt. Dahlgren (Bill Paxton) and his rag-tag crew, who
have just been granted 48 hours' leave. Now it is revoked. The
mission: get to the U-boat, disguised as Germans, capture the
Enigma decoding device and sink the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, each character has flaws _ cliched and almost proud
of it _ to overcome. But the most important plot line _ and really
what the film is about if you are to dilute it to its
pop-psychology moral _ is second-in-command Tyler (Matthew
McConaughey), who has just been passed over for command of a boat
of his own, and Dahlgren had something to do with it. Keeping the
peace is Chief (Harvey Keitel), who has such memorable lines as
``What the hell are those yardbirds doing on my boat?''
</P>
<P>
   Simple stuff, but the action is well thought out, logical and
wastes no time getting down to it. Director Jonathan Mostow keeps a
brisk pace and always seems to come up with the perfect shot,
exploiting the U-boats like some elaborate Rube Goldberg device,
except with the stakes raised high.
</P>
<P>
   This shouldn't be surprising for anyone who saw ``Breakdown,''
Mostow's kinetic and gripping thriller starring Kurt Russell as a
yuppie whose wife is kidnapped by an evil trucker. His direct,
no-nonsense style makes him different from the hyper-productions of
John McTiernan (``Die Hard,'' ``The Thomas Crown Affair'') or the
super-cool flash of John Woo (``Face/Off,'' ``Mission Impossible
II''), but he is with them in that pantheon of Hollywood action
directors.
</P>
<P>
   What's odd here is how muted all these personalities are. Tense
submarine movies have big stars _ Cary Grant in ``Destination
Tokyo,'' Burt Lancaster in ``Run Silent Run Deep,'' Sean Connery
and Alec Baldwin in McTiernan's ``Hunt for Red October,'' Denzel
Washington and Gene Hackman in ``Crimson Tide.'' They rely on those
stars for those over-the-top performances that push the tension
forward in the super-cramped spaces.
</P>
<P>
   But the players in ``U-571'' all come in under the radar, a
method that worked for Mostow in ``Breakdown'' but seems out of
place here. When you've made Jon Bon Jovi, as a jar-head
lieutenant, and Keitel into standard characters, you know you've
done something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Keitel, he's taken a scary turn in his career. The
otherwise dangerous, iconoclastic independent actor has in the last
month played a pilot in the live TV production of ``Fail Safe'' (in
which the biggest suspense was not so much will Moscow be
destroyed, but if Keitel would swear on national TV) and now he's a
Navy underling.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? An Air Force colonel, to complete his military
trilogy, who's ``getting too old for this crap?'' A disaster movie
with Harvey Keitel as the president? Someone phone Martin Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of this heap is McConaughey, who was once touted
as the next Paul Newman in the years of ``A Time to Kill'' and
``Amistad.'' He's serviceable here, which is about all you can
really expect of him.
</P>
<P>
   He's as much Newman as ``U-571'' is ``Das Boot'': Good-looking,
solid, but not nearly as much depth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
