<HEADER>
A3494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BASKETBAL     04-21 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BASKETBALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ``LOVE AND BASKETBALL'' IS SWEET BUT GOOEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Love and Basketball,'' a romantic comedy about a love triangle
between a boy, a girl and a game, has some nice moves and winning
players, but ultimately loses steam down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The film plots out a predictable romance between two young
ballplayers who've grown up as next-door neighbors: Monica Wright,
played by the earnest and likable Sanaa Lathan (who also appeared
in ``The Best Man'' and ``The Wood'') and Quincy McCall, played
with much swagger and sweat by Omar Epps.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's basic game plan goes something like this: Boy meets
girl. Girl and boy play basketball. Girl loses boy. Girl gets boy.
Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by rookie Gina Prince-Bythewood, ``Love and
Basketball'' is produced by Spike Lee and his 40 Acres and A Mule
Filmworks. But those looking for another Spike Lee Joint like ``He
Got Game'' _ or even a modern ``Hoosiers'' _ won't find it here.
The title is ``Love and Basketball,'' after all.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there aren't plenty of suspenseful game
sequences, filmed in the familiar fast-break music video style or
hear-your-heartbeat slow motion. But basketball is really just the
arena in which the bigger and more important games of the heart are
played out.
</P>
<P>
   Epps, who made his screen debut with Tupuc Shakur in ``Juice''
and also appeared in ``The Wood,'' delivers the film's most
engaging performance. With his bedroom eyes and basketball jones,
Epps is as believable sinking jump shots as he is delivering the
film's frequently flat dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Lathan, whose character is the focus of the film, gives up a
pleasant if less compelling performance as Monica, the tomboy next
door who worships Magic Johnson and hopes to be the first woman in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But the supporting characters are stereotypes: As Quincy's
father, Dennis Haysbert (``Waiting to Exhale'') plays the standard
macho ex-athlete; Monica's mother (Alfre Woodard of ``Passion
Fish'') remains the prissy stay-at-home mom who never watches her
daughter's games. They mostly serve as backboards off which the two
lead characters bounce their emotions.
</P>
<P>
   For a movie about such a fast-paced sport, the film has some
surprisingly slow passages _ perhaps because the characters are not
deeply developed, or because the plot is stretched a little thin.
Director Prince-Bythewood slows things down even more with loving
and lingering shots of a character's profile or objects in a
bedroom, set to Quiet Storm-style R&AMP;B music.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the film takes on the feel of a music video with
characters shooting around to New Edition's ``Candy Girl,'' or
bumping and writhing through a high school dance to the sounds of
'80s hip hop.
</P>
<P>
   There are some star cameos _ by Magic Johnson, supermodel Tyra
Banks and the ubiquitous Dick Vitale _ and genuine laughs,
especially early in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after meeting his new neighbor, 11-year-old Quincy
bluntly asks Monica if she'll be his girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I have to do?'' she asks. He informs her that they'll
play basketball and ride to school together and ``when you get mad
at me, I got to give you flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica frowns. She doesn't like flowers. ``How about Twinkies?''
she suggests.
</P>
<P>
   And that really sums up ``Love and Basketball'': sweet, light, a
little on the gooey side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3511 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-STACEY-EARLE22-COX     04-21 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STACEY-EARLE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    Old-timey, comfy songs grounded in real-world experience
 &HT;    By Ron Rollins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The first sound you hear when you put Stacey
Earle's debut CD into the player is probably the most important
sound _ a distinctive, immediately identifiable noise that most of
us don't hear very often anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It's the soft pop, crackle and hiss of a needle dropping onto a
record. It's there on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took an old Radio Shack record player and got a really old,
scratched-up copy of `Rubber Soul,''' Earle said. ``We wanted it
just right.'' But this was more than just a sound effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost so much when we lost vinyl,'' she said. ``I actually
like that hiss. When albums went away we lost some great things,
like sequencing _ when you made album, you got an extra chance to
sequence your songs on the B side. It gave the listener a chance to
pause and think about what they'd heard when they stopped to turn
the record over. It gives the ear a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do a CD and you put 13 songs on there, they'd better
all be strong songs. Lots of people don't have time to listen to
the whole CD all the way through, and you may lose them. I wanted a
side A and a side B.''
</P>
<P>
   Album sides, needle drops _ ``Simple Gearle'' is proudly
old-fashioned. It's a lovely, summertime waltz of a record, 13
gentle country-folk songs about the joys and hardships of
day-to-day life _ wedding nights, next-door friendships, teenage
rebellion, lost and found lovers, getting ready to face another day
and finding strength in doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Earle put the record out on her own tiny Gearle Records label,
using E-Squared as a distributor. But getting to that point took a
long, long time _ and a relatively late career start.
</P>
<P>
   She watched as her famous brother, Steve Earle, forged a career
as a roughhousing country-rocker of considerable acclaim, and also
helped him through his equally famous substance-abuse problems.
</P>
<P>
   Family is important to her. She raised her own sons _ Kyle Mims,
now 18, and Christopher Mims, 21 _ as a single mom in Louisiana and
moved to the Nashville suburb of Ashland City in 1990 to be near
her brother. He asked her to sing backup and play guitar on a
record and some dates. She enjoyed it enough that she started
writing a lot of songs _ getting a job as a staff songwriter at Ten
Ten Publishing, and eventually hosting the weekly songwriter's
night at a place called Jack's Guitar Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids were always so supportive,'' the 38-year-old said.
``They'd always say, `Come on, Mom, go play tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   So play she did. She learned writing basics and tricks at Ten
Ten, but Earle noted that the more commercial, country-radio type
songs she was being paid to write at the office didn't go over as
well as the songs she wrote for herself at the kitchen table in the
mornings before work. ``Those were the ones where I'd see people's
heads pop up,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Her confidence grew, and things started to click. She met and
married Mark Stuart, one of the musicians she met at Jack's, in
1994. They've written, sung and played together ever since. (His
album, ``Songs From A Corner Stage,'' also on Gearle, also starts
with a needle drop). Her son Kyle stopped playing ska and punk long
enough to become her drummer. Her brother helped out with
encouragement. ``Simple Gearle'' was born.
</P>
<P>
   The followup, ``Dancin' With Them That Brung Me,'' in stores May
9, has a little more polish but still the same old-timey, comfy
feel. It includes a song by her brother and a guest turn by Sheryl
Crow, who turned out to be a fan of the first record.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty exciting,'' Earle said. ``It was nice to have
the nod and the OK from my peers and the veterans in the music
world.''
</P>
<P>
   She's touring extensively _ 274 shows last year _ moving through
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Family operation, family show, she says. She's happy to have had
years of motherhood, neighborhood and real life happen to her
before she started a career in music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no regrets at all,'' she said of her late start. ``All
that gave me lots to say. Some people keep journal or diaries. I
write songs, and I write them about the regular things in life that
go on around me. You can hear the happy times, the tough times, how
I turned it around for me and the kids and what I learned from it.
But they aren't depressing records; I don't live on a negative
note.'
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
