A3517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-CO     04-21 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Burning issues and a torrent of
mail
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ From Elian to flag burning, from capital
punishment to Microsoft, from guns to chili, such are the burning
issues of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The readers write ...
</P>
<P>
   From Crawford Parker Jr., a lawyer in Carthage, Texas:
</P>
<P>
   ``We who served in the military did so to protect the rights of
all Americans, not some rights, but all rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person is unbalanced or warped enough to burn the
American flag, that person surely has the right to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, that is what we served our country for, to protect the
rights of all Americans regardless of their beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   From Susan Dart, North Carolina:
</P>
<P>
   Concerning Microsoft: ``It's like AT&AMP;T's stranglehold on the
telephone business. For years we had to use AT&AMP;T's phones and their
long distance service, with unbelievable rates, and poor people
simply could not afford to talk long distance. This is called a
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   From Pat Cunningham, Pineland, Texas:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am of the opinion that if the state or government can kill
(execute) our sons and daughters for murdering someone, then we as
parents should be able to apply some corporal punishment
(spankings) when they are young to teach them that there are
consequences to hurting others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe that if parents were encouraged to discipline
their little darlings, there would be fewer people in the prisons
and on death row.''
</P>
<P>
   From E.J. Karcher, North Carolina:
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose I, an American, had a wife who was an Iranian citizen.
Suppose she took our son to Iran to visit and then refused to
return my son to me. Where does Elian belong?''
</P>
<P>
   From Joyce Barnes, Springfield, Ohio:
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself in the father's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to various reports, his ex-wife kidnapped his son to
embark on an impossibly risky escape from Cuba by boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only through a miracle did his son survive the ordeal, then
was whisked away to a family of relatives he probably had never
met, and used as a political tool for their purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of his uncles had served jail sentences for drunk driving.
How would you feel to have your son taken from you in this
fashion?''
</P>
<P>
   From Mary Lou Siau, ``a 74-year-old lady,'' no address:
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know how to safely shoot a gun, but I do know they do
not hurt anyone or anything until a human is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, saving the most important issue for last, that of suet
as an ingredient in chili:
</P>
<P>
   From Lorraine Luca, Lufkin:
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe you were misinformed about the definition of suet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to my trusty old Webster's dictionary, and he agreed
with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suet is the hard fat deposited around the kidneys and loins of
cattle and sheep, and is used in cooking and as a source of tallow,
which is the nearly colorless and tasteless solid fat rendered from
the suet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is also used in making candles, soap and lubricants. It is
good as food for wild birds in the winter. I guess it gives them
energy, and they don't have to worry about the cholesterol or their
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. One reader also wrote to ask how are my dogs. My dogs are
fine, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
