<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS22-COX     04-21 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lakers sitting pretty as playoffs begin
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From where the Los Angeles Lakers sit, the fall would be
startling. And loud.
</P>
<P>
   The team with the championship coach, MVP candidate and
brilliant young star is unfazed about its position atop the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why settle for the apartment?'' center Shaquille O'Neal asked.
``We want the whole house.''
</P>
<P>
   The best record in the league during the regular season is a
nice start toward the final goal. Only a championship will satisfy
the cast in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It is set up perfectly for the Lakers. They have the home-court
advantage through the playoffs. They have coach Phil Jackson, who,
with Michael Jordan's help, led the Chicago Bulls to six titles in
the 1990s. They have the best player in the league in O'Neal and
one of the most complete players in Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, the most dominant team in the regular season, have
the respect _ and in some cases, fear _ of every team in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle and Sacramento put a lot of effort into trying to finish
above the eighth playoff spot in the Western Conference, to avoid
facing Los Angeles. The SuperSonics ended up seventh and will face
the Utah Jazz; the Kings landed in La La Land, a.k.a. trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no bargain playing Utah, but I think even Utah would have
to admit that it's more wise putting off playing the Lakers as long
as possible,'' Seattle coach Paul Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck for Sacramento, which became a national darling
last year when it put up an admirable first-round fight in losing
to Utah. The Kings won just one of four meetings against the Lakers
this year, but because of their offensive potency, L.A. is not
taking the first round for granted. Even so, O'Neal expects
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're the best team, everybody wants to come at you and
beat you, and the Kings are very confident,'' O'Neal said. ``With
that comes a lot of adrenaline, a lot of luck. But our A game
against their A game, we'll win eight times out of 10. So, we just
have to be prepared and bring our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Their best depends on O'Neal. The 330-pound all-star has played
brilliantly all season. He has shown more determination on defense
and some nimble low-post moves on offense, but his strength remains
the foundation of his production.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a word to describe his strength,'' Seattle forward
Horace Grant said. ``There's really not. To try to describe his
strength would be to disrespect him in a way. You can't explain
it.''
</P>
<P>
   No disrespect to the defending-champion San Antonio Spurs, but
this championship appears to be the Lakers' to lose. The Spurs have
had a tumultuous season, with Sean Elliott's kidney transplant and
remarkable return, the erratic play of Mario Elie and, now, Tim
Duncan's knee troubles that threaten his availability or
effectiveness. San Antonio's first-round date with the Phoenix Suns
is not a cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland TrailBlazers, who opened the season as a title
contender, became ordinary after the Lakers went to the Rose Garden
and won about six weeks ago. The Blazers have the depth to beat
Minnesota in the first round, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``In the West,'' Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders said,
``outside of the way the Lakers are playing, I don't think there's
any series that would be an upset. Any team (ranked) two through
eight right now can win a five-game series.''
</P>
<P>
   The East might not be as strong, but it's just as competitive.
Indiana has the best record, but the Pacers were 20-21 on the road,
where they probably will have to win to finally get past the
conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning Eastern Conference champs, the New York Knicks,
have the team built to return to the NBA Finals again. With Patrick
Ewing strengthening the inside game and Allan Houston and Latrell
Sprewell on the perimeter and on the fast break, the Knicks are
tough.
</P>
<P>
   But their first-round opponent is Toronto, which has beaten them
three of four times this season. Vince Carter, who averaged 33
points against New York, ``scares'' the Knicks, according to coach
Jeff Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors are confident. ``We play good in the Garden; that
might be our second home,'' Toronto forward Charles Oakley said.
``Like the song said: `Papa was a rolling stone, wherever he laid
his hat was his home.' We've got two hats, one in Canada and one in
the States.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every team in the East has such confidence, because no
one has been dominant. The Philadelphia 76ers, with the addition of
Toni Kukoc and their forceful defense, believes it has a legitimate
shot. So does their opening-round opponent, the remarkable
Charlotte Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   Through Bobby Phils' death, Anthony Mason's arrest and constant
griping, the car accident involving Derrick Coleman and Eldridge
Recasner, and the release of veteran three-point artist Dale Ellis,
coach Paul Silas has held together a team that enters the playoffs
hotter than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets have won seven in a row, and they have the weapons
to make some serious noise. Charlotte, after handling the 76ers,
very well could defeat the No. 1-ranked Pacers in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the scene is established for the Knicks to face
nemesis Miami in the second round. New York and the Heat form the
most fierce rivalry in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   However, neither team has a pass to the next round. In Miami's
case, its trouble is more about not having point guard Tim Hardaway
(sprained foot) than about its underwhelming opponent, Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway is not allowed even to walk, so his availability is
questionable. Alonzo Mourning ``is by far and away the most
dominating player we have, our best and most impactful player,''
coach Pat Riley said, ``but there's something about Tim Hardaway
that creates a confidence and a spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Such confidence abounds throughout the league.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
