<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3568 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-QUINN-ART-SFCHRON &LR;      04-21 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUINN-ART-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PASSION FOR THE ARTS: Actor Anthony Quinn turns his
legendary  energy to painting, sculpture  
 By JESSE HAMLIN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Anthony Quinn won an Oscar for his portrayal of
the passionate French painter Paul Gauguin in the 1956 film ``Lust
for Life.'' The movie was about Van Gogh, but the title was
tailor-made for Quinn, whose zest for living and making art has
hardly diminished as he turned 85 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to work,'' says Quinn, who's in San Francisco for the
opening of an exhibition of his artwork at the Richard Thomas
Galleries. It features about 100 paintings, sculptures and prints
by the legendary actor, a lifelong visual artist who planned to
pursue painting and architecture until Hollywood came calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can't go on acting all my life,'' Quinn says in that
famously rough, resonant voice. ``I'd love to make a couple more
pictures. But if I can paint the way I'm painting now, I'd just as
soon settle for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn has made close to 250 movies, bringing to life such
unforgettable characters as Zorba the Greek, the brute Zampano in
Fellini's ``La Strada'' and the Bedouin chief Auda abu Tayi in
``Lawrence of Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   But most people don't know that he's been equally active as an
artist, turning out thousands of works in a modern Expressionist
mode that draws inspiration from a wide range of sources, from
Picasso and Matisse to African sculpture and Mexican art.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been productive in another area, fathering 13
children, the oldest of whom, Christina, is 56. He and his third
wife, Kathy, who's 37, are raising their two children, Ryan, 3, and
Antonia, 6. They travel with him everywhere, he says, and they're
the focus of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, every moment is wonderful with them,'' says Quinn, who
lives on a seaside estate in Bristol, R.I., where he paints and
sculpts daily after taking his daughter to school.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when Quinn carved big chunks of marble brought
from the hills of Carrera to the villa he once shared with ex-wife
Iolanda and their three kids. ``It's become a big physical job, and
I don't do it as much,'' says Quinn, who these days tends to work
with materials close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son and my daughter and wife and I walk around our
property, and we find wonderful stones along the ocean, wonderful
pieces of wood in the forest. I pick them up, take them home, carve
on them, and they turn out to be sculptures.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who's of Irish and Mexican ancestry, was born in
Chihuahua, Mexico, in the midst of the Mexican Revolution. His
parents joined Pancho Villa. After moving from Texas to
migrant-worker shacks in California, the family settled in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who began painting at 5, made money drawing pictures of
movie stars (Douglas Fairbanks gave him $10 for a portrait the
young artist mailed him).
</P>
<P>
   After winning an architectural competition in high school, he
was given a scholarship to study with Frank Lloyd Wright. The great
architect, Quinn says, thought he had a speech impediment;
believing that architects needed to speak clearly, Wright sent him
to a doctor to be examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor sent me to an acting class to learn how to speak,''
Quinn recalls. ``I did a play by Noel Coward, and somebody at
Universal saw me and offered me a contract. I called Mr. Wright and
told him they offered me $300 a week to become an actor. He said,
`By God, take it. You'll never make that from me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike acting, Quinn says, he can take his time making creative
decisions when he's painting or sculpting.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor, you have to come up with truth at 8 o'clock, when
the curtain goes up or it's `Action!' There's no time to be
self-critical or analyze, like you can with a canvas or a piece of
marble. I've been working on paintings for 40 years, and I still
haven't found out what I want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   He has yet to finish a painting in which he holds his friend,
actor Vittorio Gassman, in his arms. ``I want get the truth of that
moment, and it's quite difficult,'' Quinn says.
</P>
<P>
   He cites Picasso, Matisse and Miro as primary influences, and he
greatly admires Rembrandt. African and Mesoamerican art have
inspired him as well. The masklike face of his painting ``Pride''
suggests the African-influenced Cubist forms of Picasso's
``Demoiselles d'Avignon'' period.
</P>
<P>
   He quotes Picasso and laughs: ``A poor man borrows, a rich
artist steals. I steal, of course. With the wealth of art that
Africa has produced, the wealth of art from the Aztec and Incas? My
God, you steal from them and hope you make it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn tries not to repeat himself in his art. ``You find you do
that more as an actor because something sells and you want to do it
again. I'm much more honest in my painting than I am as an actor.
You can't do 240 films and do your best in each one. You go on the
set, hoping it's going to be great, and the director gives you the
wrong direction, and you say (to yourself), `We're heading the
wrong way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He's quick to add that he's worked with some great directors _
Fellini, George Cukor, David Lean. He's made his share of ``awful
pictures,'' he says, but some good ones, too. Among his favorites
are ``Zorba,'' ``La Strada,'' ``Lawrence of Arabia'' and ``Requiem
for a Heavyweight.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn's most recent film is Ricardo Bravo's ``Oriundu
(Foreigner),'' filmed last year in Brazil. He plays a 93-year-old
man who thinks he sees his late wife _ who died at 23 _ at his
birthday party. He turns down almost all the scripts he's offered
because the roles are usually ``the routine old man,'' Quinn says,
``and I don't like to play the routine old man.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd rather spend his days with his family, carving a chunk of
wood or exploring his ``fantasy world'' in paint.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how one stays vital at 85, he replies, ``Keep walking.''
Then he talks about an old oak tree near his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm part Druid, and we love trees. I have this tree that I'm
absolutely insane about. It says, `This is the way to ride it out.'
Just stand there and listen to the wind blow through your arms and
legs. It's thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
