<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A WORLD PERSPECTIVE, CLINTON HASN'T BEEN SO BAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 23)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Blessed are the peacemakers,'' quoth the Book of Matthew,
``for they shall be called the Children of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the peacemakers can also get called a lot of other
things, as the up-and-down career of one of the all-time busiest
peacemakers, Mr. Bill Clinton, demonstrates.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the planet's best-known and most powerful individual,
America's president of seven years has traveled far and wide in the
peacekeeping role he attends to virtually every day on the job. But
his reputation, image, and influence shrink the closer he gets to
home. The farther he goes from the Beltway, the better he does with
the masses.
</P>
<P>
   He is the world's most influential character, by virtue of his
office, mostly, but also thanks to his remarkable personality. But
it is his character, or the news media's perception of same, that
drags his personal popularity level down well below his
surprisingly durable job approval rating, the best on average of
any recent president.
</P>
<P>
   Today's $64 question: How many countries has Bill Clinton
visited in the seven years of his presidency? And the $64 answer?
Sixty-four. Bill's Victory Lap year in the Oval Office took him
most recently to India (his 62d foreign visit), Pakistan (63d) and
Bangladesh (64th).
</P>
<P>
   Even when he's home, he's thinking distantly; he spent a good
part of Holy Thursday massaging Yasir Arafat to coax the
Palestinians into a term-ending Middle East peace treaty. The week
before, Bill schmoozed with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has more foreign visitors than Kennedy International
Airport. And he apparently never turns down a chance to fly. He's
on the road almost as much as Whitey Bulger. The White House Press
Office said Friday it no longer logs how many miles the president
has flown.``We don't get frequent-flier miles,'' said a press aide
somewhat ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   Can you name a country where Clinton hasn't either gone, phoned,
sent money or planes or medics, had the ambassador in, or tossed a
dinner for the local potentate (and a few dozen interested parties
who might also make campaign contributions from time to time)?
</P>
<P>
   I think Clinton has so far missed going to either pole; until
now he's not hosted a fund-raiser at McMurdoo Sound, to my
knowledge. And I'm sure there are some African backwaters, remote
Pacific islands, and old Soviet Union body parts with names
consisting of a handful of consonants ending in ``-stan,'' whose
air space has yet to be penetrated by Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   But not many. Big Bill has logged umpteen thousands of air miles
and swallowed a forklift-load of Air Force One peanuts in his urge
to splurge on the free plane tickets to anywhere that come with the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a foreign minister with whom he has not palavered? A
king or emperor he hasn't had in for the inevitable
sitting-either-side-of-the-fireplace photo? They love Clinton in
Northern Ireland, in Britain, on the Continent. In most countries
of the world, he is as or more popular than the local chieftan,
nabob, or emperor.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton had left India for arch-enemy Pakistan, an Indian
commentator told the BBC that the visit had mesmerized Indians of
every class and stripe.
</P>
<P>
   At home, alas, it is a much different story. Clinton's problems
with old and newer girlfriends, old and newer special prosecutors,
and the old-new-we-never-really-change-our-stripes news media have
left his public image hide lacerated with reopened wounds and
running sores.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment battle found his enemies coming up short. But
the snarling continues. Kenneth Starr's successor has vowed to
continue the war to destroy Clinton's reputation at government
expense. Like the Japanese soldiers who went to ground in the
jungles of the South Pacific archipelago, Starr's worn-out veterans
mumble bravely about fighting the fight forever.
</P>
<P>
   The public may be sick of it, but the Republicans trying to hold
onto control of the House and Senate keep telling one another
there's something buried that will somehow come to light and enable
the Great Right Wing Conspiracy to finally topple Bonnie Prince
William.
</P>
<P>
   On a rare moment, Clinton indulges in a bit of sport with his
enemies in the media conglomerates. After ABC News mangled a
trivial Earth Day photo-op interview with the prez by sending in
teen heartthrob Leonardo DiCaprio to interview the Leader of the
Free World, Clinton gouged the red-faced network bosses for trying
to weasel their way out of the resulting PR debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you news people ever learn?'' deadpanned Clinton at the
Radio and TV Correspondents dinner, one of those dreadful DC
wingdings presidents are blackmailed into attending. ``It isn't the
mistake that kills you, it's the cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   But rare are the opportunities for the target to one-up the
shooters. Dragged before the American Society of Newspaper Editors'
annual clambake in Washington for yet another go-round with the
flower of American journalism, Clinton was asked two insulting
questions by editors who inquired if he'd line himself up a
presidential pardon, as Nixon got from Gerald Ford, and did he
contemplate adding an impeachment wing to his presidential library.
</P>
<P>
   His ill-fated dalliance with Lady Monica cost him dearly. He
confessed to the editors that he ``struggled very hard to save my
relationship with my wife and daughter _ I have paid quite a lot''
for what he called ``the wreckage'' he brought on himself.
</P>
<P>
   There are millions of Americans who hate Clinton, or scorn him,
or wish him to fry in the deepest vat of whatever it is they cook
those french fries in. Some of that is just politics. But a lot of
it is pure hatred. Perhaps because of his looks, his easy manner,
his mysterious knack for connecting with the masses on TV and in
person, those opposed to his policies gnash their teeth in envy.
</P>
<P>
   Deep inside Bill's well-thumbed Bible is a passage from the
Sermon on the Mount with which our battle-weary president may take
some solace this Easter Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   ``Blessed are ye, when men shall revile you, and persecute you,
and shall say all manner of evil against you falsely, for my sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rejoice, and be exceeding glad: for great is your reward in
heaven: for so persecuted they the prophets which were before
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew 5:3-12 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
