<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3585 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MAYOR-CELLPHONES-HNS &LR;      04-21 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-CELLPHONES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO'S MAYOR TAKES AIM AT CELL PHONE USERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ILLENE LELCHUK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You are trying the mayor's patience.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you. You with your cell phone ringing. The one playing a
teeth-grating, tinny rendition of Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown, joining a disgruntled population that's
tired of being interrupted by beeps, pings and ditties, said he's
had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, three times this one guy's goddamn cell phone
went off,'' Brown said after a Thursday morning press conference
about affordable housing That was frequently interrupted by
electronic hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has weighed in, with increasing frequency, about the
burgeoning use of the noisy technology that seems attached to
nearly every belt, suit jacket, purse and brief case.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has snapped at department heads, reporters, even at
audience members when cell phones have gone off during formal
swearing-in ceremonies for commissioners. And his staff will soon
post a sign on the door to the mayor's press conference room that
will remind visitors to put their pagers and cell phones on
vibrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your situation is such that you are expecting such a great
emergency, then we should change the meeting so you can deal with
the emergency,'' Brown, a democrat, chided a group.
</P>
<P>
   And don't get him started on drivers and their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the state of California has got to do something,''
said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is not alone. San Francisco restaurateur Ed Moose, for
example, recently banned cell phone use inside his popular Moose's.
And the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art in May will put up signs
telling visitors not to use cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   As for drivers using hand-held phones, San Francisco Supervisor
Amos Brown has called for a hearing on the matter. A proposed
statewide ban failed in the legislature three years ago but the
discussion is continuing here and in 15 other states and dozens of
cities across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash is growing as the number of cell phones _ about 91
million in the United States _ increases. Almost one in three
people owns a cell phone, said Jeffrey Nelson, a spokesman for the
Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule of thumb is, mind your manners,'' Nelson said.
``Think if your parents were right there with you, what would they
say? And if they didn't raise you well, then borrow someone
else's.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently there's a learning curve.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Carlson, vice president of the Pacific Exchange, said a
colleague answered her phone during a business lunch and he was so
insulted he grabbed it and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was mortified,'' Carlson said. ``But I was pretty
mortified. I would hope over time ... there are some standards of
behavior and etiquette that become widely accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he was recently shocked when a cell phone rang
while he was watching the movie ``Rules of Engagement'' at an area
cinema. He was thrilled to see a manager escort the offender out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so damn rude,'' agreed Marc Pascucci, spokesman for Loews
Cineplex Entertainment, which owns the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Loews doesn't, as a policy, kick out every cell phone user, but
the noise is becoming a problem, Pascucci said. Loews is
considering filming a preview that would lay down the rules of
etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   At San Francisco city hall, Board of Supervisors President Tom
Ammiano also is cracking down on noisy electronics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rude. It's self-centered and somewhat pretentious, I'd
say,'' Ammiano said. ``Particularly annoying are the little musical
numbers. I really don't want to hear `Row row row your boat' when
we're taking testimony about someone being evicted. It trivializes
the whole democratic process of a committee or board meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano turns his phone off. And the mayor says he doesn't carry
a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know how to use one,'' he said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Then what's that in his chauffeured black Lincoln Towncar?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Brown shrugged. ``Whatever the cops put in the
car.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3586 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-OSCAR-KNOCKOFFS-ART-2     04-21 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-KNOCKOFFS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT DRESS, DEAR. DID YOU MAKE IT YOURSELF? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 23)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stepping out recently in a certain strapless taffeta
gown, I felt a mixture of embarrassment and anticipation. Not that
the shirred olive-colored dress wasn't flattering. But I was
wearing a knockoff of the endlessly photographed gown Hilary Swank
had so stunningly preened in three and a half weeks earlier at the
Academy Awards _ a copy ginned up by an ever nimbler arm of the
fashion industry specializing in reproductions from runways and
awards ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed ridiculous trying to trade on a movie star's cachet.
But I also hoped that for one split second I might be mistaken for
this year's best actress. Or at the very least, as someone wearing
a dress with major snob appeal.
</P>
<P>
   To my dismay, my entrance at the Waldorf-Astoria _ at a gala
celebrating the 55th Anniversary of the Boy's Town of Italy _ went
unnoticed. No flashes erupted, no shutters snapped, no one
requested autographs. I wasn't expecting a high-fashion crowd, but
the guests included luminaries like Gina Lollobrigida, Franco
Zeferelli and Ivana Trump. When I spotted someone I knew, Dr.
Lucinda Harris, my internist of eight years, not only did she fail
to recognize my dress, she didn't even recognize me.
</P>
<P>
   As I passed the statuesque model Noemie, one of the hot new
faces gracing runways and magazine covers, she touched the fabric
of my gown and asked, ``Is this the new season of DKNY?''
</P>
<P>
   No, it was the new season of ABS, a moderately priced clothing
line designed by Allen B. Schwartz, the king of phony couture.
Within 12 hours of the Oscars on March 26, he came up with an
approximation of Swank's dress and four others that had stolen the
show: the ``Charlize Theron,'' ``Cameron Diaz,'' ``Cate Blanchett''
and ``Ashley Judd.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before buyers from Bloomingdale's, Saks, Macy's and Lord &AMP;
Taylor had seen the dresses, thousands were on order, and in little
more than a week after the awards, the gowns were featured on seven
television shows. Although they won't be in stores until late July,
I was able to borrow samples of two of them.
</P>
<P>
   I made my way across the Grand Ballroom at the Waldorf to chat
with the designer Mary McFadden, assuming that she would
immediately recognize my famous gown. ``That looks like the dress
Hilary Swank wore,'' she said, pronouncing the star's name
``schwank.'' ``How pretty you look.''
</P>
<P>
   The bodice's unraveling lining caught McFadden's eye. ``You just
have to sew that down, and then it could look like the real
thing,'' she said, blowing my cover. ``But don't worry, at
nighttime it looks great.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Duke, the designer who created Swank's dress, had
warned me that his original, inspired by the master couturier
Charles James, would be a tough act to imitate. A few years back,
after Schwartz had whipped up an impressive replica of a slinky red
dress that Duke had designed for Minnie Driver, he wised up and
began concocting designs defying easy duplication. For Swank, he
used 20 yards of bronze-colored douppioni silk from the 1950s. Each
fold of the dress was sewn by hand, and a petticoat, with 30 layers
of silk tulle, gave the skirt its soft volume. To recreate the
one-of-a-kind dress in the vintage fabric, Duke estimated, would
cost $24,000.
</P>
<P>
   When I put on Schwartz's copy, it was so cumbersome I felt as if
I were wearing the drapes ripped off a window a la Scarlet O'Hara.
The skirt had stiff tulle netting, giving it substantial pouf. In
place of antique copper silk, Schwartz had used olive green
polyester. The tight, strapless bodice was asymmetrical and
ill-fitting, the shirring pretty shoddy.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the price was $320.
</P>
<P>
   I was about to make my exit from the Waldorf party when a
thirtysomething blonde, wearing a skintight white sheath, stopped
me. ``Love your dress!'' she fawned. ``It looks like the one from
the Oscars _ that woman who won and had the big teeth wore it,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Before I could answer, she stepped in closer, eyeing the fabric.
``Hey, is that an Allen Schwartz?'' she asked. ``I almost bought
one of his dresses, the pink one, last year. Didn't I see your
dress on the `Today' show?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but Randolph Duke did the original,'' I stammered, as if
that conferred prestige on the facsimile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I never knew who did it,'' she shrugged and disappeared
into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness, I realized, the copy had eclipsed the original. After
all the refracting media images of Oscar dresses and their
mass-marketed knockoffs, Duke's prototype was almost beside the
point. To some, the surrogate had acquired more allure than the
original.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Schwartz insisted, ``My dresses are better than the
originals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more forgiving, less risky,'' he told me. ``They're a
good fit at a good price. Movie stars and suburban housewives buy
our clothes. Nobody in the real world wears the real dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are few legal limits to what a knockoff house can do as
long as it does not use a designer's label or logo. Clothing has
little protection under copyright law, and designers, of course,
borrow from one another all the time, in ways subtle and not so
subtle. Schwartz is in the latter category. He said that he had
sold 80,000 copies of Carolyn Bessette Kennedy's wedding dress.
``Last year,'' he boasted, ``I sold 20,000 pink Gwyneth Paltrow
dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the cult of the celebrity rules, but why would anyone
want to wear a dress identified with the personification of
uniqueness, namely a movie star?
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, I had to admit that my weakness had a history. In
1986, when I married, the bridal gown du jour was the one worn by
Diana, Princess of Wales _ a silk and taffeta confection with bows
trimming the neckline and a 25-foot train. Diana, who had married
five years earlier and was my age, seemed to live a real-life
fantasy. I bought a copy of her dress, sans train, for $1,500 at
Kleinfeld, the Brooklyn bridal shop. While I took my vows under a
chuppa at the Garden City Hotel on Long Island, no St. Paul's
Cathedral, I half hoped the royal lineage of my gown might make my
dreams come true.
</P>
<P>
   I had something similar in mind last week when I slipped into
ABS's version of the halter-style dress Charlize Theron had worn on
Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   The original Vera Wang creation was cut on the bias and made of
gossamer layers of irisdescent tangerine silk chiffon. The straps
of the dress were adorned with a $95,000 pair of diamond butterfly
clips by Fred Leighton. Were the dress to sell at retail, without
the clips, it would cost $4,000, Wang said. By contrast, the orange
ABS version, with red and coral acetate underlayers _ and
rhinestone clips included _ was $360.
</P>
<P>
   Copying Theron's 1930s hairstyle for the Oscars and wearing the
imitation of her dress, I ascended the steps of the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, the 4-foot train of the knock-off slithering behind
me. I was attending the Acquisitions Fund Benefit, a lavish affair
where a swell crowd, including Annette de la Renta and Mercedes
Bass, gathered in the Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That dress is really terrific,'' said Edwin Weisl, the former
Parks commissioner, greeting me as I tripped over the hem, ``but it
looks hazardous.''
</P>
<P>
   To put it mildly. When Myra Walker, the acting curator of the
Costume Institute, accidentally stepped on my train, I jerked
backwards, splashing my glass of Perrier down the front of my gown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great dress,'' Walker said, after apologizing for the
faux pas. ``It looks vintage. But is that ABS? I saw it on
`Oprah.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the copy had more name recognition than the
original. And even the cognoscenti seemed to like it. Stephanie
Krieger, an antiques dealer, wearing a flesh-toned, sequined column
dress by Oscar de la Renta and a chinchilla-trimmed cardigan,
offered compliments, as did de la Renta himself.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, I felt a dainty hand on my bare back, adjusting a
hook that had come undone on my halter. ``I had to fix your
dress,'' purred Jill Swid, a style editor at Mirabella, in a
stunning black Christian Dior gown.$``I know it's not Vera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you tell?'' I asked glumly, as she looked me up and
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fit, the fabric and those clips,'' she sniffed. ``They are
definitely not Fred Leighton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those clips are very crackerjack,'' added her date, Jim
Brodsky, president of Sharp Communications. ``We figured your dress
was from Strawberry.''
</P>
<P>
   That did it. In certain circles where status and style are
closely scrutinized, copies still don't cut it. And as my stardust
fantasy faded, I vowed never again to wear a dress that has all but
a starlet's name tag on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
