<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3588 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INTERNET-ENTREPRENEUR     04-21 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ENTREPRENEUR-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNER ALWAYS GETS OUT IN TIME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SERGE WILSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember musical chairs? Think of it as a paradigm for the new
economy, where it has morphed into ``musical shares,'' a game that
anyone can play.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how: First, buy equity in a company incorporated in the
state of NL _ Negativemargin Land _ where the motto is ``Loss is
lovely.'' You can get in before the company goes public, by playing
as an employee, angel investor, venture capitalist, private bank or
corporate player, or you can get in later.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have your stake, it's time to play evangelist. Get in
those chat rooms. Tell your friends. And remember that all news is
good news: ``Losses widening? Great! We're aggressively acquiring
customers!''
</P>
<P>
   Once the market at large starts believing _ and these days it
doesn't take long _ you quietly get out with a tidy profit. Don't
worry about leaving money on the table; you can always play again
with a new company. What you don't want to be is the sucker holding
a lot of NL stock when the market wakes up and realizes some
things:
</P>
<P>
   _ Your company's market (books, pet supplies, whatever) is very
competitive, with low margins.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet players will drive margins even lower, down to
commodity levels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Profits for commodity retailers are made through efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   _ NL companies are not very efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The last point is the crux. It's already conventional wisdom
that the Internet is a giant steamroller, crushing inefficient
infrastructure as it rumbles through market segments. You might
infer that the companies that will be left standing are the lean,
mean, efficient ones that can survive on the slim margins of the
newly disintermediated world.
</P>
<P>
   But here is the paradox: Most of the Internet companies that are
supposedly driving the steamroller will instead be steamrolled
themselves, because they have no incentive to operate efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   The way these companies begin is horrifying. A start-up can get
a venture capital firm to throw $10 million at it by persuading
1,000 people to buy something online at 50 percent off. The company
is encouraged to burn through that $10 million and go for an
additional $100 million _ fast.
</P>
<P>
   All the focus on being the ``first mover'' and ``grabbing market
share'' sucks all the cash into marketing. A company burns $3
million for one Super Bowl ad or pays insane bounties to drive
``customers'' to a Web site. But if you walk, look, and quack like
a duck.com, you get to your initial public offering faster.
</P>
<P>
   What does this cash-fueled orgy produce? A bloated, inefficient,
self-indulgent company that doesn't know how to control costs, or
even want to _ just the kind of business that the Internet
steamroller will crush to smithereens on the next lap.
</P>
<P>
   As a dot-com chief executive, I've seen companies that hand out
cell phones and Palm V's to employees as if they were after-dinner
mints.
</P>
<P>
   I have a barometer for such waste: I ask partners and potential
partners at well-financed Internet start-ups how much they pay for
chairs. So far I've heard $800, $900 _ even $1,500 apiece. I'm
waiting for the $2,000 chair _ it's inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are adding employees as wastefully as chairs, often
without having a job for them or anyone to train them. (But they do
get a nice place to sit.) When most of us landed our first jobs,
our transcripts were scrutinized and references checked. Today you
can get in at some dot-coms on nothing more than an odd haircut and
a mini-backpack.
</P>
<P>
   (Contrast this approach with that of, say, Cisco Systems, which
does not let any department grow faster than 10 percent a year, so
it can maintain the quality of training and level of experience of
the group.)
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day you have a company that is full of:
</P>
<P>
   _ Human resources people that never had to make a good hire.
</P>
<P>
   _ Salespeople that never have to sell at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marketing people with unlimited ad budgets and no
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buzzword-slinging executives to manage all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a steamroller, perhaps we should picture the Internet
as a scythe, with razor-thin margins serving as its business end.
It is only a matter of time before masses of venture capital- and
Nasdaq-fattened Baby Hueys are mown down by the digital economy
they helped create.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, of course, their nimbler backers will have dined
very well indeed, and moved on to even greener pastures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
