<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEMONSTRATORS-JAILED (Washington) _ Defense lawyers and
prosecutors were negotiating Friday for the release of some 150
demonstrators still being held in the D.C. jail after being
arrested during protests against the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund earlier this week. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-RELIGION (Miami) _ The sea rescue of Elian Gonzalez and
his place in the hearts of Cuban-Americans in Miami have taken on a
distinctly religious aura. Among those ringing the house where
Elian is living, many of them devout Catholics, there is much
evidence that he is viewed as a genuine miracle. By ED HEGSTROM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ As much as I hate to write this, I
have come to believe it's true: Microsoft has kicked the legs out
from under the business of designing and selling computer mice. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A readers asks, ``In a couple of
reviews of video cards and computers you've written, you mention
running something called timedemo in Quake III Arena to test the
speed of the card and the computer. How do you do this? I don't see
it in the manual.'' A look at assorted computer-related Q&AMP;As. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ The federal government doesn't want
employers to discriminate against a prospective employee because of
her age, and it will sue you if you do. But when the government is
doing the hiring, it seems to cut itself some slack. Federal law
enforcement agencies have a rule that new hires cannot be 37
years-old or older by the time they join. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-ABORTION (Washington) _ The cultural and legal war over
abortion turns to the U.S. Supreme Court this week, as the justices
hear arguments on the constitutionality of a state's ban on
late-term abortions. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   IDENTITY-THEFT (Washington) _ Thieves have swiped personal data
such as Social Security numbers, birth dates and addresses for more
than a decade primarily to get bank and checking accounts and
credit cards. But now identity theft is becoming more widespread as
crooks use other people's personal data to open utility accounts,
rent apartments, apply for loans, start businesses, buy cars and
even declare bankruptcy. Some lawmakers, led by Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., are pushing legislation to curb the problem.
By JUDY HOLLAND. (1STLD-WRITETHRU filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE (Washington) _ Child advocacy groups say the 1996 law
requiring welfare recipients to go to work is not providing enough
money for most of them to put their kids in day care. Only about 15
percent of the youngsters eligible for the federally funded care
actually get the subsidy. So many parents can't work or can't get
better paying jobs. But the push for additional funds is iffy since
most Republican lawmakers don't want to spend more for ``a national
nanny,'' as one puts it. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (''i`` category)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-REFORMS (Tehran, Iran) _ Social strictures imposed after
the 1979 Islamic Revolution are beginning to ease across Iran. Yet
many remain skeptical of the ability of the reformers, led by
President Mohammed Khatami, to bring significant political change
to the Islamic Republic of Iran. Since Khatami was elected in 1997,
the reformers have been locked in a political dance with the
conservatives to determine the direction of the country, moving in
a pattern of two steps forward, one step back. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-WOMEN (Tehran, Iran) _ Many Iranian women are testing the
limits of their country's strict Islamic controls over their lives
and are finding ways to loosen the restraints. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-INTERNET (Qom, Iran) _ Perhaps more than anything else, the
Internet, which the ruling mullahs praise as an Islamic research
tool, has helped Iranians break out of the profound sense of
isolation they have felt for the last two decades. The free flow of
information makes any effort to keep outside influences from
seeping into the country more difficult and allows the world to
more easily find out what's happening inside Iran. By DEBORAH
HORAN.
</P>
