<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-NEMETZ-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO'S STUDS TERKEL, FOCUSING ON THE UNSUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 23)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By LINDA LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Brent Sterling Nemetz has perfected the art of
hanging from cables on the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge and climbing
backward up the ladder in the Statue of Liberty's arm, all the
while asking questions and shooting from a Sony video camera.
Wednesday night found him going the wrong way down the stairs from
the 110th floor of the World Trade Center, Tower No. 2, looking for
the night's interview subject, Samantha Hue, a tour guide at the
observation deck.
</P>
<P>
   Nemetz has a day job shooting footage for slick television
fashion shows _ ``You know, all the ones that are on Saturday
morning,'' he said _ and editing film and video at his Manhattan
production company, Sterling Films. But in his spare time, he
exercises the curiosity that has made him a video Studs Terkel, a
man obsessed with New York's unsung laborers _ the people who
fillet fish, makeup artists on ``Cats,'' Zamboni operators on
Madison Square Garden ice and people who sell toy mice on sidewalks
or carve gargoyles on the Cathedral Church of St. John the Divine.
</P>
<P>
   He compiles his interviews into a half-hour series on PBS called
``Souls of New York,'' which appears locally at 8:30 on Thursday
nights. Last Sunday, he was awarded a New York Emmy for Outstanding
Director of a Documentary Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is documentary lite,'' he said of his brief lives, the
two-and-a-half-minute segments outlining what it's like to be a
grave digger at Potter's Field, an auctioneer at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Nemetz, 26, operates as a one-man band. He does his own
lighting, finds his own subjects _ Hue appeared on the 110th floor
at 8:30 after taking a late ``lunch break'' _ writes his own
questions, runs the camera, shoots ``A'' roll and ``B'' roll
(primary interview and background footage) and edits. ``I can shoot
anywhere from 10 minutes to one and a half hours to get enough for
a two-and-a-half-minute segment,'' he said. ``The editing can be
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   He quickly stationed Hue near the rail on the north side of the
building, with an awesome view of the Empire State Building, while
the full moon rose like a klieg-lighted egg yolk. Then he asked her
his usual softball questions: how she got her job, why she likes
it, if she's ever met any celebrities. (Two: Danny DeVito _ ``He
was nice,'' she said, with a dazzling smile _ and Ricky Martin.)
</P>
<P>
   He dragged his camera and tripod down to the south railing and
filmed her pointing out the Statue of Liberty. ``Everyone wants to
see her,'' she said. Then he hit the east side of the building,
``the windy side,'' she noted with another dazzling smile, and
asked her to interact with tourists. She asked a young woman if she
would like to be in the photo she was taking, then advised the
whole family to scrunch down a little, so the moon could get into
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after the guards shooed the last tourists off the 110th
floor and closed the observation deck for the night, Nemetz said
goodbye to Hue and went downstairs to shoot the building from
street level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done 180 of these things,'' he said. ``It's such an
education for me. Doormen, dog walkers, squeegee guys. I like the
nickel-and-dime people best.'' And the ones with truly odd jobs,
like poisoning rats in the subway. ``I said, `This job is not for
everyone,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Which could be the mantra for many of the people he films,
including one of the city's last scissors sharpeners, the last
milkman, the last civilian lighthouse tender. ``I'd stop doing
this,'' he said, as he walked down a Wall Street canyon looking for
a bottle of water to top off the night, ``but I don't see anyone
else doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
