<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-WALLACE-BOS &LR;      04-21 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WALLACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 3 LIVES OF GEORGE WALLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GEORGE WALLACE: SETTIN' THE WOODS ON FIRE 
Produced and directed by: Daniel McCabe and Paul Stekler 
Written by: Steve Fayer, McCabe and Stekler 
Based in part on: ``The Politics of Rage'' by Dan Carter 
On: PBS, Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rise and fall and rise of George Corley Wallace is an
astonishing story that would also be deeply tragic if his appetite
for power hadn't swallowed up most of his own humanity.
</P>
<P>
   He was once a liberal Alabama judge, and many believe his early
racial egalitarianism was the real thing. But when he perceived
that it cost him his first run at the governorship, Wallace called
for ``segregation forever.'' That propelled him to the State House
in Montgomery and onto the national stage. He spewed race hate at
home, then coded it in softer language when running for president,
which he did four times, once nearly throwing the election into the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, he fostered ghastly violence against black civil
rights activists. And his national messages left destruction in
their wake, perhaps including the 1972 assassination attempt that
left Wallace himself paralyzed. Then came an extraordinary
transformation. From the wreck of his political and personal life,
Wallace rose again and, through public repentance, won black as
well as white support to become Alabama's governor for a fourth
time.
</P>
<P>
   The mere outlines of his life are the stuff of great drama.
PBS's ``American Experience'' captures it in all its dark and
dazzling complexity in ``George Wallace: Settin' the Woods on
Fire,'' airing Sunday and Monday nights at 9 on Channel 2. This is
a mesmerizing chronicle of a fascinating political opportunist and,
lest we forget, once an influential and dangerous national voice.
The three-hour documentary brilliantly balances the epic and the
intimate _ sweeping almost 80 years from Wallace's roots in the
poor rural South to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, TNT broadcast an arresting docudrama starring a
galvanic Gary Sinese as ``George Wallace'' and covering some of the
same material. As excellent as it was, ``Settin' the Woods on
Fire'' is better still. To its roaring plot line, the nonfiction
version adds enlightening commentators including Wallace family
members and colorful cronies as well as crackerjack journalists and
historians. None is wiser than J.L. Chestnut, a deep-voiced black
civil rights attorney whose penetrating remarks rise to the level
of a Greek chorus. After Wallace is shot in Maryland campaigning
for the presidency, he says: ``You just can't go around preaching
hatred, however you dress it up . . . and not have it come back and
bite you.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers masterfully braid revealing political and personal
subplots into the main story line, almost any of which could have
been spun into a self-contained historical drama. One is a
suspensful account of Wallace's assailant, Arthur Bremer,
methodically stalking the candidate through the '72 primaries _ the
archival footage of Bremer is copious and chilling. Another
involves President Nixon and his machinations to undo Wallace, whom
he saw as a formidable threat to his own power.
</P>
<P>
   And threaded through ``Settin' the Woods on Fire'' are the vital
parts played by the strong, devoted women in Wallace's life,
notably Lurleen, his first wife, and Cornelia, whom he married
after Lurleen died of cancer. Because Alabama's governors couldn't
succeed themselves at the time, Lurleen ran for the office in 1966
to hold on to her husband's national power base. Later, Cornelia
gave him a makeover to enhance his national appeal, inspiring a wag
of the day to note that the couple was ``a kind of Dogpatch version
of Camelot.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, and many Wallace adversaries, were deceived by
his rustic rhetoric and redneck persona. He loved power, as he told
his daughter Peggy, and he not only knew how to pander to southern
whites to get it, but also cleverly exploited the national media.
Campaigning in the North, he wanted scruffy-looking Vietnam War
protesters to give him the Nazi salute in front of TV cameras. The
nightly news footage would solidify his angry, conservative
blue-collar constituency.
</P>
<P>
   What we have in the end is more than a detailed, full-length
portrait of the pugnacious Wallace: an amateur boxing champion and,
later, shrewd and often cynical political combatant. It is more,
too, than a useful, alternative lens through which to examine the
turbulent '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Through close attention to biographical and historical nuance,
``Settin' the Woods on Fire'' raises enduring questions about the
very nature of political ambition and, of course, about the core
nature of George Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Was he really contrite when he phoned his old enemies before the
1982 gubernatorial election and recanted his racist dogma? Veteran
civil rights leader John Lewis thinks so, contending that Wallace
reverted to his liberal roots, ``his true self.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, in any event, a tribute to the film that it depicts this
evildoer in all his clenched ambiguity and even allows the story of
his life to move us. Wallace possesses a kind of animal tenacity
and courage that's impossible to ignore and hard, at moments, not
to admire.
</P>
<P>
   The eloquent Mr. Chestnut should have the last word. ``How is
it,'' he says, ``that a demagogue, insulting 20 million black
people daily on the television, can rise to the heights that
Wallace did? . . . Forgive? Yes. Forget? Never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
