<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV23-     04-21 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING: A WALK IN THE WOODS, WITH EYES NEWLY OPENED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mass.)   (For release Sunday, April 23)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I wander the woods in Maryland these days, I find myself
bending down to admire tiny little flowers I never noticed before,
counting petals, noting the shapes of leaves.
</P>
<P>
   I've been inspired by a book with the catchy title ``The New
England Wild Flower Society Guide to Growing and Propagating
Wildflowers of the United States and Canada'' (Houghton Mifflin,
$40). Just out, it's written by William Cullina, the propagator and
manager of the nursery at the society's Garden in the Woods in
Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Cullina, 35, who has run the nursery for five years, has a flair
for description. The open seedpods of claytonia, for example,
remind him of ducks opening their bills wide and sticking out their
tongues, an image I'll remember when collecting seeds.
</P>
<P>
   I think Claytonia virginiana, or spring beauty, is growing in my
woods. The tiny little white flower, with its faint pink striping
on five rounded petals and narrow, grasslike leaves, matches
Cullina's description and the accompanying photograph. And Maryland
is within its range.
</P>
<P>
   But the propagation notes _ ``moderately easy from seed; easy
from division'' _ raise a question that is hotly debated.
</P>
<P>
   With even common wildflowers disappearing under housing
developments and roads, every gardener can bolster biodiversity by
growing the native plants most suited to local conditions, insects
and animals.
</P>
<P>
   But when, if ever, is it beneficial to collect seeds or make
divisions of wild plants?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have as much of a problem with collecting seed, as
long as you're taking a small amount and it's not a rare plant,''
Cullina said in a telephone interview. Digging corms or making
divisions is trickier. ``I used to think that taking a few spring
beauties from a big patch wouldn't hurt, but look at what happened
to the fishing industry,'' he said. ``People keep harvesting and
harvesting, and then they're all gone.''
</P>
<P>
   He encourages gardeners to join local native plant societies or
botanical gardens, which often sell or swap local plants, divisions
and seeds. The book has a good list.
</P>
<P>
   I want to increase the population of the spring beauties in my
woods, but Cullina warns that growing them from seed is difficult
(which is like holding a red flag up to a bull: here goes). The
ducklike pods shed their seeds quickly, within a month of
flowering, so you have to keep an eye on them.
</P>
<P>
   Cullina picks the pods, lets them dry several days and then sows
the shiny little black seeds outdoors, where they lie dormant
through the summer and winter and germinate in the spring. The
plants take years to reach blooming size, however, ``so I usually
let them self-sow and dig up sections when I need to,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Cullina suggests planting claytonia in drifts with dicentra,
asarum, creeping phlox, sanguinaria and tiarella. His 300-page book
explains the divisions and families of the plant kingdom, the
definitions of shade (less than two hours of sun) and wet soil
(when you dig with a shovel, standing water is visible one foot
down). He discusses the ``floristic provinces'' of the country,
from tundra to Great Plains to Eastern deciduous woods, explaining
how basic conditions like sea level, weather and soil have shaped
them. Rocky Mountain plants, for instance, have thick,
semitranslucent leaves and a covering of down, to protect them in
thinner air from the sun's radiation.
</P>
<P>
   If you understand these traits, you will be less likely to try
to propagate alpine plants, say, around the muggy Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, our marshy woods is a mass of emerald green skunk
cabbages and May apples (Podopyllum peltatum) unfurling their
umbrellas. I could spread the wealth to neighbors who have the
right conditions, but no plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``May apple is extremely tough and, once established, can grow
in poor, droughty conditions where most woodland wildflowers
fail,'' Cullina writes. But in rich, moist soil, the deeply
indented leaves, aloft over delicate flowers, can reach a foot in
diameter and make a wonderful ground cover. Judging by its picture
in the book, I think Trientalis borealis, the starflower, is also
in our woods. This common spring ephemeral's creeping rhizomes send
up stems with a whorl of leaves and little white starflowers on
threadlike stalks. It is equally at home, Cullina says, in dry
sandy soil or swampy hummocks.
</P>
<P>
   See what a lot of work this book could be? The waxy gray seed
clusters should be collected as soon as the leaves wither, but they
are difficult to spot, so Cullina suggests marking the plants while
in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   The book is also full of easy-to-increase common wildflowers.
``Anything in the aster family is easy,'' Cullina said. ``Butterfly
weed is easy to grow from seed. And jack-in-the-pulpit is good for
a woodland.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget solidago, or goldenrod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Convincing gardeners to grow goldenrods is a bit like trying
to sell Toyotas in Detroit,'' Cullina writes. But goldenrods are
insect-pollinated, he explains, so their pollen is heavy and
sticky, to hang onto a transporter's body. So don't blame goldenrod
if you can't breathe: wind-pollinated ragweed, grasses and trees
are the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   The plants can be divided in spring or early summer, but don't
wait until midsummer, because they are weaker from flowering and
may not root well before winter, Cullina advises. Seeds germinate
easily after a cold period and should be collected when heads are
brown and fluffy. Softwood cuttings taken in spring also root
easily.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why I'm so happy about this book. It just means a
lot more work in the garden. And this one has no walls.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIS WEEK: PUSHING TULIPS AND PULLING ROOTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By PATRICIA JONAS &LR;  &QC;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tulips require at least six hours of sun a day and good
drainage. Small flowers are a sign of inadequate light or
nutrition. Mulch with compost or well-rotted manure in fall, or
apply high-nitrogen fertilizer in spring just as shoots emerge.
Foliage provides nutrition for next year's flowers and must be
left, unbraided and untied, to die back naturally.
</P>
<P>
   When planting container-grown perennials, don't coddle the root
balls: work roots apart with your hands, or cut upward with a knife
about a third from the bottom in three places. Encourage roots to
grow out, not around, to keep the plant from strangling.
</P>
</TEXT>
