<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-CHARLIE'S-ANGELS-2TAK     04-21 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLIE'S-ANGELS-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGEL HAIR, ANGEL LIPS: CHARLIE'S GIRLS RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 23)  
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hard to say exactly when I cleaned a small
fortune's worth of clothes out of my closet and began to stockpile
my new look. First came the tubs of berry-colored lip gloss that
could smother a fly. Then I bought a pair of denim flares with
braided detailing at the waist, a flowing chiffon blouse and tinted
aviator sunglasses. And finally I went to the drugstore and spent
$6.99 on that instrument of torture I hadn't braved since I was 12,
a curling iron.
</P>
<P>
   I had become obsessed all over again with ``Charlie's Angels,''
the hit television series from 1976 to 1981, my pre-preteen years,
about three beautiful she-detectives who peeled around in cool
sports cars and used kung fu on bad guys even as they changed
outfits a dozen times an episode, putting on a fashion parade.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, I desperately wanted to be Jaclyn Smith, who played
the classy brunette Kelly Garrett with luscious, hot-rolled curls.
In my quest to re-embrace the show, I even asked for a ``Charlie's
Angels'' haircut, but unfortunately I forgot to specify which
Angel, and instead of Kelly's feathered wings, I walked out into
the Manhattan night with the signature athletic crop of Kate
Jackson's character, the masculine Sabrina Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to me that I had gone too far. I was considering
therapy until I realized I was not alone. On a couch at Moomba, I
met Allison Sarofim, a co-owner of the Tribeca restaurant Vandam.
She was wearing the same 1970s-style jeans by Katayone Adeli that I
had on, and she had a gold name chain that read ``Candy'' in
cursive lettering, exactly like the one Jackson used to wear over
ribbed turtlenecks.
</P>
<P>
   Sarofim, 28, had also been hit by the ``Charlie's Angels''
lightning. ``I just started losing interest in all my black clothes
by Helmut Lang and Calvin Klein and started gobbing on the frosty
blue eye shadow,'' she said. Hours earlier she had sat with big
can-size rollers in her hair under a dryer at a Lower East Side
salon to achieve those perfect angel curls.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Kelly Lamb, a New York artist who sported
salmon-colored Gucci hip-huggers, strappy heels and a glittery
Chloe blouse at her opening at the Spencer Brownstone Gallery in
March. Underneath her photographs of fleshy Playboy bunnies, which
were juxtaposed with a video of a disrobing geisha, she told me how
she had recently started scouring dusty dime stores for Bonnie Bell
kissing sticks and oversize aviator sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Charlie's Angels' look is the female equivalent of a guy
trying to look ghetto fabulous,'' Lamb said as she shellacked her
lips with Chanel's new sparkle gloss. ``It's a parody of being sexy
and bad, but at the same time you actually get to look sexy and
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Angels'' craze is being fueled primarily by a Columbia
Pictures film adaptation of the television series that will star
Cameron Diaz, Lucy Liu and Drew Barrymore. The three sashayed onto
the stage in skin-baring synchronicity at the Oscars last month to
present the award for best costume design. But in an example of the
blistering pace of fashion cycles, trend-setters are being
influenced not by the movie, but by anticipation of the movie,
which will not be released until November.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, Elle, Mademoiselle and Jane magazines have
had fashion layouts inspired by ``Charlie's Angels,'' each with its
own take on the same silk chiffon halter tops and slinky wrap
dresses by Louis Vuitton, Emanuel Ungaro, Celine and Versace. Jon
Moore, Elle's style director, used a 14-page ``Angel'' spread in
February to present the spring collections to working women. Three
Angel look-alikes appeared primarily in office settings, sitting on
desks and strutting down corridors with long flipped tresses,
tight, elegant slacks and Lucite heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seeing the spring collections, there was no way to avoid
the over-the-top glamour,'' Moore explained. ``Vogue addressed it
in terms of rich suburban housewives whose primary concern was
cocktail parties, but Charlie's Angels were very modern in the
sense that they were glamour girls who also had jobs. The timing
for that idea is perfect right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Versace ads with the model Amber Valletta in
a low-cut, palm-tree-print wrap dress, her hair feathered and her
lips glossed to kill, in what seems a strong set of ``Angels''
references.
</P>
<P>
   Donatella Versace, who briefly had discussions about designing
the ``Charlie's Angels'' movie costumes, said in a faxed reply to a
question about her influences: `` `Charlie's Angels' is about
maximal fashion _ glossy lips, layered hairdos and highly
accessorized, body-conscious looks. Minimalism seems over and
clearly never was in at Versace. Often when a trend dies, people
look to the opposite, so that's why the Angels are back.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a nonstop procession of 1970s revivalism has occurred
in the last 10 years. The movie ``Boogie Nights'' unearthed
roller-disco styles, which have been echoed by Stella McCartney at
Chloe, and scruffy young artists in the Williamsburg section of
Brooklyn and Silverlake in Los Angeles are in perennial thrall to
the geek chic of the Brady Bunch.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to ``Charlie's Angels'' style, the interest is
in the swank, almost conservative elegance of classic Yves Saint
Laurent, Evan-Picone and private labels of long-forgotten Beverly
Hills boutiques. The Angels wore career-woman classics like pleated
pantsuits or knee-length A-line skirts in neutral browns or ivory,
paired with big-collar shirts or turtlenecks. They lounged on
leather couches or behind the bar at the Townsend Detective Agency,
where their boss, Charlie, would brief them by speakerphone. (``The
water runs deep in this case, Angels, and I'm up to my hips in it
right now,'' he'd say as a bikinied girl massaged him in a hot
tub.)
</P>
<P>
   The three Angels had distinct personalities, and even their
haircuts and clothes matched their images. Jackson played the
razor-tongued smart Angel with the butch gait and severe straight
hair. (Neighborhood bullies liked her the best.) Smith was the
fashion plate with playful curls, and Farrah Fawcett, with her
trashy blue eyeliner, fluoride smile and flirty feathered tresses,
was the dream babe that a generation of women fried their hair
trying to duplicate. (Guys thought she looked California natural.)
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett left after the first season, and Cheryl Ladd came in as
her character's cute kid sister. Jackson was later replaced by the
bookwormish Shelly Hack and then the streetwise Tanya Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of course, being professionals, if the job called for it, the
Angels would strip down to more revealing attire like lacy
nightgowns and string bikinis. That was inevitable with story lines
like ``Lady Killer,'' where Fawcett went under cover as a porn
centerfold, and ``Consenting Adults,'' with Smith posing as a call
girl.
</P>
<P>
   The series, produced by Aaron Spelling and Leonard Goldberg for
ABC at the height of the women's liberation movement, was in the
top 10 in the Nielsen ratings for three of its five years. It
stirred a huge debate among feminists, who said it represented a
retreat for women's images. In a 1976 issue of Time, ABC's head of
programming was quoted as saying, ``Typically, each `Angels'
episode makes sure at least one co-star strips down to a bikini in
the first 10 minutes, the better to keep males in a state of
gape-jawed passivity and expectation thereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, many remember the series as liberating, because it
was one of the first to have female leads who were not playing the
roles of secretaries or nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Angels were total knockouts, but they were constantly
strategizing about catching the criminal and being the most
efficient at their jobs,'' said Marcelle Karp, a co-founder of the
postfeminist 'zine Bust, who as a teen-ager feathered her hair and
rode a skateboard in homage to Fawcett. Karp said the series had
more in common with the girl-power genre that includes ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' and ``Xena: Warrior Princess'' than with the
modern-day jigglefest ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Each episode of ``Angels'' had an unprecedented $20,000 budget
for wardrobes and styling. The show's costume designer, Nolan
Miller, said Spelling let the actresses pick out and then keep a
majority of their costumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare,'' Miller recalled. ``Every Monday they'd
come in with huge lists of boutiques in Beverly Hills where they
had thousands of dollars' worth of merchandise on hold. But it was
smart on Aaron's part, because the girls really started to develop
their own style.'' Fawcett was into the daring trends shown on the
runways in Paris, including the braless look.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Farrah stopped wearing bras, the other girls followed,''
Miller said. ``The networks relaxed a little bit and let the
outline of a nipple show through a slightly see-through silk
blouse. Before that we used to have to tape the nipples.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith liked Italian-made classic gabardine pantsuits with
matching blouses and vests from the Alan Austin boutique, which was
in Beverly Hills. And Jackson had a penchant for denim and
turtlenecks. ``We must have bought about 300 black cashmere
turtlenecks for Kate,'' Miller said with a fond sigh.
</P>
<P>
   As the decades wear on, this kitsch classic is remembered more
through the filter of nostalgia than reruns on TNT, leaving
personal attempts at duplicating the ``Charlie's Angels'' style
open to interpretation. At a party in the West Village on a recent
Saturday night, Anita Vasmani, 26, was wearing a MaxMara purple
halter top that tied around the neck like a scarf while grooving to
'70s disco songs remixed by Dimitri From Paris, a French DJ. ``It
was so `Charlie's Angels' I couldn't resist,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett herself, speaking by phone from the fitting room of a
Gucci boutique in Beverly Hills, where she was looking for
something to wear to a New York film premiere, said that she, too,
had noticed an ``Angels'' revival. She had just tried on a gray
pinstriped pantsuit with a narrowly cut blazer and slacks that
flared at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it I smiled, because it reminded me of something I
might have worn on `Charlie's Angels,''' she said. ``I guess even
I'm dressing like myself again.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith told me from her California home that she has started
slipping ``Charlie's Angels'' references into the sportswear line
that she designs for Kmart, like scarves that tie around the neck
and retro colors like browns and taupes. (You can imagine my
elation at getting to talk to my idol Smith, although she did seem
a little unsettled when I told her about the impact she was having
on my life.)
</P>
<P>
   I decided I had to have a new Louis Vuitton wrap dress with a
halter top plunging down the middle of the chest and a retro block
pattern. It reminded me of the one Smith wore in the episode where
she went under cover as a fashion model. Too bad it costs $1,020.
</P>
<P>
   I'm only going to look at it, I promised myself as I pushed
through the mausoleum-heavy doors of the SoHo Vuitton boutique for
the first time. I had once thought the brand was too old-fashioned
for me and had never ventured inside. Downstairs in the women's
section, one glance at the meticulous racks of clothing told me the
dress wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   I turned to a saleswoman, who seemed to be sizing up my freshly
feathered hair. ``The halter dress, right?'' she said. She'd seen
my type before.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try back in a few more weeks,'' she said gently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
