<HEADLINE>
LOVE STORY BETWEEN MARIA AND CESAR  
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maria Rifo has a portrait of Cesar Chavez on her bookshelf and a
plaque from the United Farmworker's Union on her dining room wall.
She's all for a holiday celebrating the union leader's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Maria worked with in the 1970s when she was already in her 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Now 93, Maria continues to do what she can for farm workers and
other newcomers to the Latino community in Sonoma County, Calif.,
teaching catechism to children, helping families find housing. She
hopes a holiday named for Chavez, now being considered by the
California legislature, would focus on more than the man and honor
``the pain and effort of the people who put the food on our
table.''
</P>
<P>
   The holiday would grant time off for only a few people _ state
workers and a half day for school children. Ironically, Maria's
farm worker friends would go to work as usual, ``starting at 6 a.m.
and working until sunset, in sun, rain, dust and with pesticides.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria serves tea in her small apartment in Santa Rosa, squeezed
next to a fax machine and surrounded by papers and books. She is
one of those people who shows that life, if you dare, never stops
being a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the most important moment,'' she says, sounding just
like the gurus. She once thought her life would go on pretty much
as it had for her first 56 years in her native Chile where she
taught school and lived close to her parents. ``They told me they
didn't know what they'd do if I ever left.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't leave until after they died and then began to see the
world. First Europe, then New York, then at age 57 a career change
to work for Vista in New Mexico. There is where she first heard the
charismatic leader some call the Mexican-American Martin Luther
King speak about fairness and compassion for the workers _ ``people
who belong to the ground,'' she says. Back then they worked without
bathrooms or drinking water, hunched over short hoes, too afraid to
complain.
</P>
<P>
   Maria had seen similar conditions among peasants in her own
country and wanted to know more. She approached Chavez after his
talk and said, ``I want to work for you.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that she shared a house with four others, lived on donated
food, earned $5 a week pay and slowly learned ``you can make a
difference to people.''
</P>
<P>
   She quit after 12 years when she was 72.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways working with Chavez was a transforming experience
which she recounted in a book on women's spiritual discoveries
called ``The Feminine Face of God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in my work that I actually began to develop
spiritually. Cesar opened my eyes to what I could do. I was
blooming like a plant. Everybody has a lot of gifts they don't know
about.''
</P>
<P>
   She was smitten first by his voice. ``He spoke so soft and from
the heart. Another's way would be to yell and demand but his was to
speak slowly so that every word sunk in.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining was more important to him than directing, she says,
and she tries to pass on that skill. ``When you are working with
people you must encourage them to find their own way. You don't say
`do it my way. Yours is wrong.' You never say `don't be silly' or
`that's stupid.'`
</P>
<P>
   She was Chavez' secretary and sometimes they would sit in the
office and talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like a sponge, always learning.'' They'd argue
semantics. Part of her job was to translate the growers' contracts
into Spanish for the workers. Back then she was a stickler for the
proper grammar and rich vocabulary she was raised with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said why use a plain English word like field when we have
such a beautiful Spanish word as campo. He would say `Maria, are
you working for the farm workers or the Academy of Language?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Cesar helped me to begin to live at 60. He gave me another
life. I changed my total way of seeing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria still does not buy table grapes or head lettuce, boycotted
during contract struggles, and has been known at social events to
gather bottles of wine bearing certain worker unfriendly labels and
pour them down the drain. She sees a Cesar Chavez Day as a kind of
second Thanksgiving, when we celebrate real food _ which is not
genetically altered _ and tended by real people, not machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't replace a real strawberry with one that is big and
has no sweetness or a tomato that is so changed it feels like a
stone. Nor can you replace a human being with a machine.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3645 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-CAR-NIGHT-VISION-HNS &LR;      04-21 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NIGHT-VISION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW CADILLAC HELPS DRIVERS SEE IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN Antonio _ As the Cadillac DeVille cruised down a dark and
quiet stretch of two-lane road, its headlights didn't pick up the
man just starting to cross the road, right in the vehicle's path.
</P>
<P>
   But the driver knew he was there at least 10 seconds before the
man's face showed in the glare of the low-beam headlights. There
was plenty of time to react.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't an ordinary Cadillac; it was a 2000-model DeVille
with a high-tech innovation born of the military and the Gulf War:
the new night-vision system that General Motors and its partner,
Raytheon Corp., developed for the automotive market.
</P>
<P>
   Taken from its military heritage, made famous during Operation
Desert Storm, night-vision technology now goes consumer in the
world's first application in a production passenger car. Only the
DeVille has it, at least for now, and GM reports that the system
has been so popular with buyers that they can't fill all the orders
they receive.
</P>
<P>
   The device has a special camera that mounts in the vehicle's
grill, connected to a computer that processes what it sees and
projects the picture across the bottom of the windshield in front
of the driver.
</P>
<P>
   It can see up to five times farther than the range of the
vehicle's low-beam headlights, giving the driver plenty of time to
react to obstacles in the car's path _ such as a deer crossing a
highway.
</P>
<P>
   The device allows the driver to see stalled vehicles whose
lights are off, people and animals in the road or along the
roadside, and other dangers that lie ahead. It also allows the
driver to see past the glare of oncoming headlights, in itself a
significant safety feature, said Dave Whittaker, vehicle line
executive for Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   On the windshield, the display is about a foot wide and five
inches high, and it is projected low enough to keep it out of the
driver's main line of sight. But the driver can look at the
night-vision projection without taking his eyes off the road.
</P>
<P>
   Offered as an option on the DeVille, the unit costs $2,000,
about the same as a premium stereo system, Cadillac officials
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Developing a usable and affordable night-vision system for
passenger cars will be a great enhancement to automotive safety, GM
and Raytheon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us remember Gen. Schwarzkopf's statement during Desert
Storm that `We own the night,''' said Pat Kemp, Cadillac brand
manager for the DeVille, who demonstrated the night-vision system
to reporters in a touring road show that crossed the country.
``Now, we'll give that option to drivers on America's highways.''
</P>
<P>
   Night driving is the most dangerous kind, highway safety
officials say. Statistics from the National Highway Transportation
Safety Administration show that although only 28 percent of driving
occurs at night, 55 percent of traffic fatalities occur during the
night hours, and 62 percent of pedestrian fatalities occur at
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's often related to the lack of adequate vision to avoid
accidents at night,'' Whittaker said.
</P>
<P>
   With a vehicle traveling at 60 mph, a driver has about 3.5
seconds to react when a hazard comes within the range of the
average low-beam headlights, he said. ``With night vision, that
reaction time is increased to 17 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Night vision systems should help reduce the number of vehicle
collisions with deer, too, he said. More than 300,000 car-deer
collisions are recorded each year, and in many of those vehicles
are heavily damaged and the occupants seriously injured, Whittaker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just how effective night vision systems will be in reducing
accidents remains to be seen, officials of the highway safety
administration say.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all of us agree it looks good,'' said Kenneth Copeland of
the agency's office in Fort Worth, Texas. ``I have seen it
demonstrated on television, but I really don't know much about it
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of night vision on other cars won't be prevalent for
some time, however, because Cadillac has exclusive rights to use
the Raytheon system on the DeVille for at least the entire 2000
model year, and maybe even a year or two beyond that, Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, GM probably will begin offering the system on some
of its other vehicles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other automakers are working to develop their own night-vision
systems, but they are two to three years away from bringing the
technology to market, according to industry reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
