<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) 
 
 SOUTHERN PARTY STRUGGLES TO ASSERT ITSELF   
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
NYT Regional Newspapers   WASHINGTON _ Almost one year after
proudly introducing itself to voters, the Southern Party is
struggling for relevance and respect in American politics.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Striving to attract more followers and money, the party, which
advocates an independent Southern nation, is planning a late June
convention in Charleston, S.C., following last summer's kickoff in
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Baxley, national chairman of the Southern Party, conceded
his party has not been particularly visible this past year and that
internal divisions have stymied growth at times. In fact, the Texas
businessman who served as the original chairman of the party is
already out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   But Baxley, a Virginia resident, said the party has been busy
organizing itself and drafting a constitution. He insisted the
group would ``be there for the duration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been in the news much,'' Baxley said. ``But we're
starting up again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Party captured some headlines last August with a
colorful rally in Flat Rock, N.C., attended by approximately 140
white Southern nationalists. Most political analysts quickly
dismissed it as a fringe group. Party leaders have done little
since last summer to dispel that notion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the group has yet to pick up the interest or apparent
respect of any established political leaders. None of the
presidential candidates, for example, made even a token effort to
appeal to Southern Party members during their primary swings
through the South this past winter and spring.
</P>
<P>
   Baxley said his party is not interested in appealing to
candidates for national office, but will focus on state and local
races. So far, the party is registered in just two states _ Florida
and Louisiana _ but has formed political action committees in other
Southern states. Baxley said the party has roughly 2,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ALIENS, NOT ELIAN
</P>
<P>
   Typically, it's politicians from border states who worry most
about the problem of illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP Sen. Jeff Sessions of Alabama believes his state has an
illegal immigration problem too, and he wants the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to crack down on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the case of one illegal alien who in March was charged
with the rape of a woman in Gulf Shores, Sessions wrote
Commissioner Doris Meissner that illegal immigrants ``have
committed a number of crimes'' in his state. He did not say how
many, but said local law enforcement agencies have contacted him
about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions called on Meissner to address the ``crime problem
caused by illegal aliens'' by assigning more special agents to
Alabama. There are 2,088 special agents for the INS nationwide, but
only one in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS INDIFFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   Southern states brought up the rear when the 2000 Census roll
was called, with South Carolina, Louisiana and Alabama failing to
crack the 60 percent return rate. At 56 percent response, South
Carolina beat only Alaska in participating in the decennial count.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia, at 69 percent was the only Southern state to top or
reach the national response rate of 65 percent. Many even fell
short of their 1990 response though the country as a whole equaled
the previous count. Census officials anticipated a mail return of
61 percent before the door-to-door counters were dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   The South has stood out like a sore thumb for its lackadaisical
approach to the census, with officials speculating that its
minority population and historic antipathy to the federal
government played a role. The chickens may come home to roost
later, however. Federal dollars are parceled out on the basis of
the census and Southern states may find that the relatively poor
response will leave them, well, poorer.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNDING FATHER
</P>
<P>
   Comedians joke that Sen. Strom Thurmond, the oldest lawmaker to
serve in Congress, was around to sign the Declaration of
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, he wasn't. But Thurmond, 97, was in the Senate
in 1966 when the U.S. Supreme Court issued its legendary Miranda
ruling, mandating that police must tell suspects of their right to
remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Thurmond helped write a federal law to allow
the use of voluntary confessions as evidence even when suspects
have not been read their rights. That federal law, which has long
been ignored, is now part of a case recently argued before the
Supreme Court that re-examines the Miranda ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond sat in on the proceedings. Afterwards, he chided the
Clinton administration for not enforcing the 1968 law. He called
his dealings with the Justice Department ``one extensive exercise
in frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
