<SLUG> BC-BIZ-EBAY-SURPLUS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE CASTOFFS GOING, GOING, GONE ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 23) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a year and a half, Massachusetts officials tried and failed
to dispose of a 128-foot lightship, the Nantucket I, most recently
used as a floating museum. ``This was something we couldn't give
away,'' said Paul Guerino, coordinator of the state's surplus
property.
</P>
<P>
   So the state tried one more tack. It posted the lightship on
eBay, the online auction site more commonly used by consumers
emptying their attics of unwanted wedding gifts or Beanie Baby
collections.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the auction was over a few weeks ago, bidding on the
Nantucket I had reached $126,100, and the winning buyers, a former
state senator and his wife, were making plans to have the historic
boat refitted and moved to Boston Harbor, to be used as office
space.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen other state governments have discovered what
Massachusetts did with its lightship: that surplus property fetches
a whole lot more online, where a world of enthusiastic amateurs are
ready to bid, than it does through traditional channels, which
rarely attract buyers beyond a small core of gimlet-eyed
professional bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Governments often have a lot of stuff to get rid of _ old office
equipment, overstocked supplies, abandoned property, items seized
from criminals or tax delinquents _ and are generally required by
law to offer it publicly to the highest bidder. Traditional
auctions tend to be lightly publicized, inconvenient and a bit
intimidating for ordinary people, so pennies-on-the-dollar prices
have long been the rule.
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of online auctions is changing all that,
commonly doubling and tripling the amounts that states receive for
auctioned property. ``I actually thought it was a brilliant
strategy,'' said the new co-owner of the Nantucket I, William
Golden.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure which state thought of it first, but Oregon is
considered a leader in online sales. The state, whose eBay identity
is oregontrail2000, started a year ago with one item, an engraved
commemorative Snap-On Tools socket set from the Portland Police
Department. Late last week, it had 70 single items or lots posted
for sale on eBay, including a seized 12.41-carat black opal, an
Everett &AMP; Jennings wheelchair, a ``bucket of miscellaneous tools''
and two pairs of women's Easy Spirit tennis shoes, size 7{.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do an auction, you've got 400 people in a room for
five hours in a single day,'' said Skip Morton, property
distribution center manager for Oregon's Department of
Administrative Services. ``With eBay, you're dealing with people 24
hours a day, seven days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon officials have been so pleased with the online results
that they have installed public computer terminals in a state
warehouse to allow any resident to bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see electronic commerce, electronic marketing as the way
things are going to be in five years, 10 years most certainly,''
Morton said. ``We'd rather be in the forefront than eating dust in
the back.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 12 states are now active on eBay, according to Don Coy,
the eBay business manager _ and the federal government is working
on its own auction site for public property, which will eventually
be invited to join.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, states are climbing up the learning curve on
commercial sites like eBay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign that the lines between the government and private
sector are blurring,'' said Pete Williams, surplus property program
manager in the California Department of General Services, which
sells on eBay under the ID californiagold2000.
</P>
<P>
   The states are selective about what they post online; they find
that smaller, more valuable goods that can be shipped easily tend
to do best. An Olympus 35-millimeter camera that might have sold
for $25 in a warehouse auction fetched $91 online two weeks ago,
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a state official will post something more
unwieldy, like a 1994 Chevrolet Camaro Z28, equipped for police
use, offered by Oregon last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to one this afternoon; he had a Lear jet he was
possibly going to put on the site,'' said Coy of eBay. ``It didn't
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerino of Massachusetts said that for some items, it was
difficult to find the appropriate product category. For the
lightship, he had to settle for sporting goods, because that was
where boats were listed.
</P>
<P>
   States like the prices they get from online buyers, but some
buyers also see an advantage in Internet auctions of government
property: officials don't always know what they have.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Heath of Las Vegas won the bidding for an old wooden
file cabinet from Oregon, paying $210 plus $127 for shipping. Only
after it arrived did she discover that it was actually a
sought-after Globe Wernicke cabinet from 1938. ``They could have
gotten probably five times what I paid for it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
