<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CULTURE-CLASH22-COX     04-21 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-CLASH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultural differences create legal problems
 &HT;    By Milo Ippolito
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Young Lee was arrested for beating her
stepdaughter black and blue with a cane, she said that's how Korean
families discipline their children.
</P>
<P>
   But a Gwinnett County jury decided last week that Lee was the
one who needed to be punished.
</P>
<P>
   The caning case was the latest clash of cultures to reach a
metro Atlanta courtroom. As tens of thousands of immigrants have
moved into metro Atlanta in the past decade, sometimes traditional
child-rearing methods, health remedies and marital roles have run
afoul of American law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an acute lack of awareness about cultural practices
that gets people in trouble,'' Julia Perilla, an advocate with the
Latino Families at Risk Project, which works to prevent domestic
violence among Hispanics. That lack of awareness applies to both
sides _ immigrants and the American legal system, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the caning case, Lee testified that she beat her teenage
stepdaughter, who has cerebral palsy, for wearing loose blouses and
torn jeans to school. Tried for child cruelty, part of Lee's
defense was that caning is a traditional discipline practiced by
conservative Koreans. Three Korean church pastors testified that
they saw nothing wrong with the beating. However, after viewing
photos of the dark bruises and red stripes covering the teen's
body, a jury convicted Lee. She faces five to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The stepmother took the traditional punishment to an extreme,
said Korean-born Gwinnett police officer Christopher In, who
assisted in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in Korean culture, it is beyond reasonable,'' In said.
Still, In recalled being smacked on the hands and legs with a stick
by schoolteachers when he grew up in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   While Georgia law gives parents the right to use reasonable
corporal punishment to discipline a child, many immigrants have
difficulty understanding the legal limits, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Gwinnett Magistrate Judge Chung Lee said tensions can run high
in homes where parents insist on holding onto traditions while
their kids just want to be American teenagers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korean parents have to come to the United States and learn
American culture,'' he said. ``At the same time, Korean kids have
to learn about Korean culture and understand why the parents think
that way, and find a neutral ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes cultural practices with no violent intent can be
perceived as child abuse. Such is the case with a Vietnamese home
remedy for chills and body aches. A coin or spoon is used to scrape
the skin to bring the bad blood to the surface, explained Binh Le,
an interpreter in Gwinnett County courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tradition handed down from generations,'' Le said. ``A
lot of the doctors who have never seen that, they freak out,
because it does look like whip marks.''
</P>
<P>
   A problem that several immigrant groups are trying to control is
domestic violence. Advocates from Asian, Hispanic, Middle Eastern,
African and Eastern European backgrounds have formed Atlanta
organizations to counsel and shelter battered women. Many of their
home countries have domestic violence laws, which are sometimes
ignored because of traditional gender roles, said Julia Perilla of
Latino Families at Risk Project.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural differences have the potential to end in an immigrant's
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 federal law requires the deportation of legal immigrants
sentenced to at least one year in jail or on probation. The goal
was to kick out immigrants convicted of crimes of drugs and
violence, but in metro Atlanta the law has led to deportation
proceedings against an Ethiopian who stole a sandwich and a
Nigerian who swiped two boxes of doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the problem is a simple neighborly dispute _ with a
cultural twist. In several metro Atlanta communities, immigrants
have been accused of animal cruelty by neighbors who saw them
slaughter livestock in their yards.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a Hispanic family tied a goat to a neighbor's fence
in Smyrna. The neighbor called the police. Officers told the
Hispanic family that they were not allowed to have livestock in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They resolved the problem by killing the goat,'' said Smyrna
police officer Tony Leonard. ``They invited me to have a piece.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar dispute erupted in Suwanee in 1998 when a couple tried
to barbecue a goat in a subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That usually tends to end up registering complaints from
neighbors,'' Gwinnett Planning and Zoning Director Mike Williams
said. ``They just don't know. Once they're informed they're usually
pretty cooperative about correcting the problems. Most of the
immigrant population wants to follow the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution writers Mark Bixler, Christopher
Quinn, Bill Montgomery and Ralph Ellis contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
