<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILM-TITLES-HISTORY-2     04-21 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TITLES-HISTORY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PEEK AT THE FUTURE IN FILM TITLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (with sidebar, GREAT-FILM-TITLES)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new branch of history _ or is it merely a twig? _ has
sprouted: the history of film titles. In case you are someone who
talks through movie previews and credits, film titles generally
appear after the film quiz, after the dancing hot dogs and popcorn,
after the on-screen hushing and before the movie proper has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Film titles have certain responsibilities. They must display the
movie's title and the name of the director, establish the hierarchy
of actors and ease the audience into the movie. Some title
sequences, however, have outgrown their workaday functions. Because
they are physically and historically ``on the periphery of films,''
said David Peters, a graphic designer who studies title sequences,
they have often been more experimental, a peek into the future of
filmmaking. The best of them are movies within movies, with a
rhythm and mood of their own.
</P>
<P>
   If you compare a movie to a dream, said Ken Coupland, a design
writer, then ``the first few minutes of a film can be compared to
the curious stage of consciousness that marks the transition
between wakefulness and sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Now designers and design historians are looking back on the
history of film titles and even creating a canon of film title
classics. A new book, ``Type in Motion'' (Rizzoli, 1999), suggests
that film-title design is the mother of all moving typography _ now
the stuff of music and art videos. This month the Film Society of
Lincoln Center in New York even presented a weekend-long program of
film titles, organized by Wendy Keys of the Film Society with
Coupland and Peters.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is champing at the bit for a history of titles.
``In cinema studies,'' said Annette Michelson, a film scholar at
New York University, ``people are always casting about for
previously unexplored areas of film. Someday, somebody will write a
dissertation on the popcorn stand in the movie lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless the history of title design, a branch of graphic
design studies, is taking shape. Title designers can tell you who
among them introduced multiple screens, quick cuts, atonality,
jazz, government stock photographs and grunge design to the title
sequences of movies. And they have their own private pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   Their uncontested Zeus is Saul Bass, who designed the title
sequences for ``The Man With the Golden Arm,'' ``Vertigo,''
``Psycho,'' ``Walk on the Wild Side,'' and the end title for
``Around the World in 80 Days,'' which is a reprise of the whole
movie in eight minutes. Then there are the other gods: Pablo Ferro
(``Dr. Strangelove''), Wayne Fitzgerald (``Bonnie and Clyde''),
Friz Freleng (``The Pink Panther''), Stephen Frankfurt (``To Kill a
Mockingbird''), Maurice Binder (``Dr. No''), Richard Greenberg
(``The World According to Garp''), Juan Gatti (``Women on the Verge
of a Nervous Breakdown'') and Kyle Cooper (``Seven'').
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, there were no film title sequences. The
earliest titles, for silent films, were presented on title cards _
cards with printed material on them that were photographed and
incorporated into the film. The cards gave the dialogue and set the
time, place and action of the scenes. They also issued polite
commands to the audience, like ``Would the ladies please remove
their hats?''
</P>
<P>
   As decades passed, titles got frillier. They were displayed on
silk, satin or wallpaper or on boxes that opened and on calendars
whose pages blew away one by one. There were some exceptions to the
rule _ notably, Peters said, the title for ``Double Indemnity,''
which featured the silhouette of a man on crutches, and the neon
credits that flashed on the skyscrapers in the opening of ``My Man
Godfrey.'' But fundamentally titles didn't change.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Saul Bass. Bass' title for Otto Preminger's 1955 movie
about drug addiction, ``The Man With the Golden Arm,'' broke the
mold. It was the first to use a jazz score, and it was graphically
gripping. Slim white bars on a black background jostle the actors'
names before twisting into a jagged arm. The arm, which Martin
Scorsese called ``a malignant force reaching down into the world
and the lives of the characters,'' became the center of the movie's
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958 Bass teamed up with Hitchcock for ``Vertigo'' and again
broke new ground. To atonal music he foreshadowed the movie with
graphic puns and symbols. As Peters and Coupland observed, Bass'
close-up of a woman's face was a prelude to the movie's voyeurism;
his splashing the letters of James Stewart's name above her lips
formed a symbolic mustache (suggesting that he was an accessory to
the woman's crime); and a spinning spiral in the iris of her eye
was a preamble to the vertigo to come.
</P>
<P>
   Title designs took off in the late 1950s, but the second ``title
wave'' did not begin, Hall notes, until Stephen Frankfurt created
the opener for ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' in 1962. Frankfurt's
haunting sequence, accompanied by a flute, a piano and a child
humming, was the first ``opener in which a camera lovingly pans
across details,'' like scissors, crayons, dolls and pens _ small,
precious objects that, Hall writes, ``grow in significance later in
the film.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The high renaissance of film titles was in the 1960s. As legend
has it, in 1962 Maurice Binder thought up the famous title for
``Dr. No'' in the 15 minutes before he met with the producers. In
the sequence, the audience looks down the barrel of a gun and then
sees Bond cross the screen, point his gun and shoot at them,
leaving a trickle of blood behind. This became the logo for years
of 007 movies. But it was Robert Brownjohn who carried the Bond
allure one step further in ``Goldfinger'' by projecting film from
the movie onto a nude woman's body.
</P>
<P>
   One other 1960s title became a logo for a series. In 1963 Blake
Edwards asked Friz Freleng of Bugs Bunny fame to make the titles
for ``The Pink Panther.'' The result is forever bonded to the
movie: a cartoon panther, prowling to Henry Mancini's score,
constantly inserts himself into the credits.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most subversive development in film title sequences
was the opening for Stanley Kubrick's 1964 film ``Dr.
Strangelove.'' According to Pablo Ferro, the designer, the U.S. Air
Force was so proud of its B-52s' in-flight refueling capabilities
that it had plenty of stock photographs of them. Little did the
military know that in Ferro's hands, the B-52s tethered to their
refueling ships, bouncing lightly up and down and paired with the
song ``Try a Little Tenderness,'' would come out as a comic sex
scene.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s the tiny design revolution was over. The recession
meant shrinking opportunities and a shrinking screen. As movies
were put on television, titles were squeezed and simplified so they
could fit on the screen and be used as labels for tie-in toys.
</P>
<P>
   Title collectors reverted to old tricks. When Dan Perri did the
titles for ``Star Wars,'' he created ``the Star Wars crawl'': a
typed message to the universe that rolls backward toward a
vanishing point. But that high-tech classic came from an old
western in which the credits rolled into the distance like railroad
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Computer technology revived the art of title design in the
1980s. As Steve Heller notes in ``Design Literacy (Continued)''
(Allworth, 1999), in 1982 ``Richard Greenberg landed in the annals
of design history'' by creating an airborne infant for the opening
of ``The World According to Garp'' with the aid of a programmable
camera.
</P>
<P>
   The latest trend, Hall writes, is grunge title design, the
descendant of the distressed typography of print graphics. And the
king of grunge is Greenberg's former associate, Kyle Cooper, whose
best known title is for ``Seven.'' Cooper used the tabletop shoot
pioneered in ``To Kill a Mockingbird.'' But emotionally the two
sequences are worlds apart. Cooper said that his fetishistic survey
was a view of a serial killer assembling a diary ``documenting the
murders he'll execute during the film.''
</P>
<P>
   The degraded typography, jittery jump cutting and ``twitching,
hand-hewn type'' ushered in a new era in film titles, Hall writes.
And it had a democratizing effect. Everyone with a computer began
thinking, hey, maybe I can do that.
</P>
<P>
   That could explain why title designers are now writing their
history. With desktop filmmaking on the horizon, the very notion of
auteur title designers seems quaint. The writing of history begins
when an era is ending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-6     04-21 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-650&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW HINTS AT PEACE TALKS WITH CHECHEN PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a sign that Russia is looking for a political
solution to its war in Chechnya, President-elect Vladimir Putin
acknowledged Friday for the first time that Moscow had exchanged
peace plans with the Chechen president, Aslan Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, speaking to reporters, said he still regards Maskhadov as
a ``criminal'' but one who could be pardoned. And he indicated that
his government is ready to talk with a man who seven months ago, at
the start of the second Chechen war, it considered politically
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   A glimmer of a political opening also came from the other side
Friday, as Maskhadov, in an interview published in the newspaper
Kommersant, said he had ordered Chechen guerrillas ``to suspend
combat operations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was part of the plan on a peaceful settlement I suggested
to Moscow,'' said Maskhadov, who said he maintains full control
over Chechnya's field commanders _ the rival war lords who are the
real rulers of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The war, which had initially been very popular with the Russian
public and gave Putin his first political boost, has begun to prove
costly to the Kremlin financially, diplomatically and also
politically, as the number of Russian casualties this month topped
2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, 20 Russian regional leaders spoke out in favor
of talks with Maskhadov, whom they referred to as the ``legitimate
president of Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Elected in 1997 after Russia's first devastating war in
Chechnya, Maskhadov was a moderate secessionist who continued to
negotiate with Moscow over the terms of future independence. But
his control over the region, never very firm, slipped as warlords,
criminal gangs and Muslim militants took charge, turning Chechnya
into a virtual no-man's land avoided by Russians and foreigners,
journalists and aid workers who feared being robbed and kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By last fall, with Putin already leading the war effort, Moscow
effectively cut its last links to Maskhadov when he refused to
condemn Shamil Basayev and Khattab, two guerrilla leaders who
brandish a radical form of Islam, for raids last August into the
neighboring Russian region of Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview published Friday, Maskhadov said he had
criticized the actions in Dagestan as ``a provocation against the
Chechen people.'' He also said he had ordered the release of all
hostages held by kidnappers on Chechen territory, which has long
been one of Moscow's conditions for the opening of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There have been hints in the past that Moscow has secretly
stayed in contact with Maskhadov through Ruslan Aushev, the
president of Ingushetia, who has acted as an intermediary. But
Putin has never spoken directly about such contacts until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In their respective comments, Putin and Maskhadov revealed the
gulf that still separates them, with Putin contemptuously
dismissing the Chechen leader as a figurehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decides nothing and will never decide anything,'' Putin
said. ``He is being used to carry out tactical tasks, but those who
are using him will soon realize that he cannot do this, and their
attitude toward him will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov complained that his overtures to Moscow had gone
unanswered. But Putin said Maskhadov had let the exchange lapse
into silence. Putin stressed that Russia has other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every reason to believe that we do have others we can
deal with apart from Maskhadov and the bandits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov applauded harsh criticisms by the Council of Europe of
Russia's conduct of the war, and called for observers from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe to take part in
a peace settlement. Russia has consistently refused offers to
mediate the conflict, although this week it again opened the way
for European observers to travel to Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whether or not the dialogue between Moscow and Maskhadov
resumes, there seems to be new willingness on both sides to look
ahead to a peace settlement, even as military operations continue.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian authorities this week began to allow residents back
into Grozny, the Chechen capital, which was reduced to dust and
rubble last winter as Russian troops fought to seize it. Now that
the Russian presidential campaign is over, pressure for military
success has eased even as the prospects for a long, drawn-out
partisan war increase.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the war has also begun to weigh on Russian
diplomacy. With a new president at the helm, the government is now
looking to deal with other issues, from arms control to foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential election was held on the crest of domestic
support for the Chechen campaign,'' the newspaper Izvestia wrote on
Thursday. ``Now is the time to think about the future of relations
with the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   But given the intransigence on both sides, it is difficult to
predict how peace talks might begin and where they might lead.
Hard-liners in Moscow object to any negotiations with Maskhadov.
They fear such talks would reproduce the false peace that lasted
between the two Chechen wars and also undercut the Russian
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the army's point of view, talks with Maskhadov would be
seen only negatively _ but very negatively,'' said Vladimir
Grigoryev, the leader of a St. Petersburg veterans group.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Russian-held areas of Chechnya are being run
both by the Russian military and by Nikolai Koshman, a deputy prime
minister who is Moscow's chief administrator in the region. With
fighting continuing in scattered districts, not even the division
between Russian military and civilian authority, let alone the role
of Chechen politicians and administrators, has been determined.
</P>
<P>
   As some analysts point out, the main question is about the
future of a region administered by the same forces _ military and
political _ that organized its destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not who should hold talks, and the problem is
not about legitimacy,'' said Boris Kagarlitsky, a Russian
historian, in a recent interview published on Vesti.ru, a Russian
Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is what the talks should be about _ the subject
and goals of the talks,'' he said. ``Not with whom, but about what
_ that is the question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
