<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilot training crunch clips ASA's wings
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fast-growing Atlantic Southeast Airlines has had to
trim flight schedules slightly because pilot hiring and training
isn't keeping pace.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based ASA, a subsidiary of Delta Air Lines, this month
cut one frequency per day to 14 of its 69 destinations, spokesman
Sam Watts said. Though the schedule effect is minor, the move
reflects the feverish pace of pilot hiring in recent years as air
travel grows and Vietnam-era pilots retire.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines hired 15,747 pilots last year, the fifth straight
annual record, according to Air Inc., an Atlanta career counseling
firm. Demand is most acute at regional airlines such as ASA. They
not only need new pilots to fuel their own growth but also to
replace experienced ones being hired by major airlines losing
veteran pilots to retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Watts said the problem for ASA hasn't been a shortage of
qualified applicants. ``I wouldn't characterize it as a hiring
problem, but more of a training issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ASA is adding new Canadair Regional Jets at a rapid rate, which
means many turboprop pilots are being retrained on jets. That, in
turn, adds to demand for new turboprop pilots, who also must get
initial airline training. The training pipeline hasn't kept pace,
Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Kit Darby of Air Inc. said the problem isn't unique to ASA. Some
smaller carriers have reduced hiring standards to widen the
applicant pool, although the average experience level of newly
hired airline pilots remains far above government minimums, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Watts said ASA's schedule cuts are a minor, temporary step. He
cited as examples the Atlanta-Gulfport and Atlanta-Roanoke routes,
where daily flights have been cut from nine to eight. The flights
cut were flown by turboprops.
</P>
<P>
   Watts said so far the problem hasn't slowed the carrier's
deployment of jets.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which hired 225 pilots last year and projects
hiring 400 this year, is expanding its training capacity under a
contract with FlightSafety Inc., Watts added.
</P>
<P>
   ASA, which feeds Delta's hubs in Atlanta and Dallas-Fort Worth,
employs about 1,000 pilots, up from 825 a year or so ago.
</P>
<P>
   The tight labor market is forcing airlines to work harder to
fill other jobs as well. AirTran Airways is in talks with several
Atlanta-area school systems and colleges about programs to hire
students as ticket, reservations and ramp agents, hoping they'll
make it a career.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, meanwhile, has a program with high schools and technical
institutes in Atlanta and three other cities to encourage students
to become aircraft mechanics, who also are in increasingly high
demand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
