<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3662 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-CAR-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW SYPDER IS VERY IMPRESSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Beauty is definitely in the eye of the beholder,
and there are people who don't much care for the looks of the new
2001 Mitsubishi Eclipse Spyder convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count me among them, though. I think it's stunningly
beautiful, almost too gorgeous to be a Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   It looks more like a European luxury sports car to me, and if
that's a bad thing, I can't figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   As near as I can tell, the people who dislike the Eclipse's new
look are mostly owners of the previous generation, and to me that's
normal when a car or anything else, for that matter, is
significantly changed. People are resistant to change.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the new Spyder looks more expensive than it is, and
there is a good reason for that. Mitsubishi has discontinued its
flagship 3000GT sports car, which sold for well over $30,000, but
has redesigned the Spyder to look something like the 3000GT. That
means consumers can buy an exciting, great-looking,
high-performance sports car for about $25,000-$28,000, and find
that it is comparable with other cars on the market selling for
$15,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda should take a cue from this and come out with a new RX 7
that is as affordable as the Eclipse Spyder. Mazda made a mistake
in taking the RX 7 upscale a few years ago, nearly doubling the
price and leaving a large body of loyal owners behind.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Eclipse Spyder doesn't come with a rotary engine,
one of the big draws of the RX 7, the GT model offers a 3.0-liter
V-6 with 200 horsepower and 200 foot-pounds of torque. It might not
be as smooth an a rotary engine, and it might not offer the quick
rush that came from the previous Eclipse's turbocharged
four-cylinder engine (which has been discontinued), but it's mighty
fast and fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the styling, I was most impressed by the Spyder's
handling. This is a car that puts performance on par with styling,
something that you don't often see in an affordable sports car. The
previous-generation Spyder handled well enough, but not like this.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new Spyder's greatest attributes is its structural
rigidity, which enhances its road handling and driveability.
Somehow, Mitsubishi's engineers and their high-tech design
computers have eliminated the body flex that was noticeable in the
previous model. For those who care, the engineers say ``bending
rigidity'' has been improved by 65 percent over the prior model,
helped in part by a network of lower-body reinforcements that form
a boxed, rolled and corrugated steel perimeter around the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the body of a convertible rigid is quite a challenge.
Just think about it: The only part of the car that continues
uninterrupted from bumper to bumper is the floor. The top comes off
and the two doors open, so there is no continuity of the structure
there. My compliments go to the engineers for such a great job.
</P>
<P>
   The convertible top operates seamlessly. Just pop the two
catches on the top of the windshield and push a button and two
electric motors lower the top quickly.
</P>
<P>
   There are two models of the Spyder convertible. The base GS
version (starting at $23,347 plus $495 transportation) comes with a
2.4-liter, single-overhead-cam four-cylinder engine rated at 147
horsepower and 158 foot-pounds of torque. Standard is a five-speed
manual transmission; a four-speed automatic that allows for
clutchless manual shifting adds $1,000 to the sticker.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car was the uplevel GT model, listing for $25,237 (plus
transportation) for the manual-gearbox version. Again, the
automatic costs $1,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   The one we got came with the manual transmission, which is more
fun in a car of this type. The manual lets the driver get a real
feel for the road and the engine. Unfortunately, no all-wheel-drive
version of the GT is available this year. The car comes with
front-wheel drive, which is not quite as much fun in a sports car
as rear-wheel or all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   The list of standard equipment for our test car was long and
impressive. It included dual air bags, 5 mph front and rear
bumpers, variable-assist power rack-and-pinion steering,
sport-tuned four-wheel independent suspension, stainless-steel
exhaust, air-conditioning, power windows/mirrors/door locks,
210-watt premium AM/FM/compact-disc stereo with seven speakers,
10-way adjustable driver's seat, tilt steering wheel, remote
keyless entry, cruise control, leather-wrapped steering wheel,
17-inch aluminum-alloy wheels, halogen headlights and fog lights,
rear spoiler and power front-disc/rear-drum brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Our vehicle came with the GT premium package ($2,370), the only
option, which added antilock brakes, four-disc in-dash CD player,
leather front seats, power driver's seat, and side air bags for the
front seat occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker was $28,102, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Seating up front was comfortable, but there isn't much leg room
in the rear even though that has been increased an inch over last
year's model, and the back seat really isn't intended to hold
adults. Fuel economy isn't bad for a car with this much zip. EPA
ratings are 20 miles per gallon in the city and 27 mpg on the
highway. The tank holds 16.4 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
