<P>
   ALAMIN-HEARING _ MONTGOMERY, Ala, _ Al-Amin changed his mind and
waived extradition after the lunch break today. He is now on his
way back to Atlanta, probably to the ATlanta city jail's federal
wing. The cops won't say for sure. ``THere is a plan but it is
cloaked in a veil of secrecy,'' said Capt. Chadd of the Fulton
Sheriff's Department. Attorney J.L. Chestnut said this afternoon
that he doesn't think Al-Amin's life is in danger in Atlanta any
longer. But he wouldn't say what had changed. Before the lunch
break, Al-Amin read statement praising Allah. (Whitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-CLASH _ Immigrants are landing in court as they learn
they can't do things the way they did at home. In Gwinnett this
week, a woman was in court on a child abuse charge because she
caned her step-daughter for ``dressing too provocatively.'' The
girl was made to kneel on the ground while the woman beat her for
almost two and a half hours with a cane. (Ippolito, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WATER-WAR _ ATLANTA _ Negotiators for Georgia, Alabama and
Florida meet in Atlanta Friday to try to salvage stalled
negotiations in their rancorous tri-state water water. We cover the
talks and fold in results from Thursday's separate meetings between
Georgia and Alabama. Negotiators in both sessions are facing a May
1 deadline, which they have virtually no chance of meeting. The
states must agree to an extension of the talks by next week, or
throw the issue into the Supreme Court. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE _ NEW ORLEANS _ ``Shadow evacuees'' _ people who
didn't have to leave but did anyway _ caused the biggest problem in
the unprecedented and chaotic evacuation of the East Coast during
Hurricane Floyd last year, according to a Florida State University
study. (Kleingberg, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
