<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK AUTO SHOW OFFERS A DIFFERENT MODEL FOR EVERY MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 23) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just as Fashion Week provides a New York stage for
many top clothing designers, the city's international auto show has
become a runway for the styles that will start appearing in
showrooms and on city streets in the fall and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   And when the doors to the New York International Auto Show
opened to the public April 22, those in attendance could be excused
for thinking that both the couture (concept vehicles that flaunt
designers' skills) and the pret-a-porter (new models that can be
bought, now or soon) have a decidedly outdoorsy look. The sport
utility wave that has been building for a decade seems to be
cresting: Of the 20-some vehicles making debuts, about two-thirds
are utilities, pickups or cars with all-wheel-drive systems aimed
at SUV shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   There are also autos at the auto show, of course, along with a
number of crossover vehicles that combine characteristics of autos,
trucks, sport utilities and almost anything else with wheels. But
manufacturers seem to have decided that one or two or even three
SUV's are not enough. Instead of serving as the equivalent of a
little black dress fit for any occasion, sport utilities can be
marketed like shoes, with a different model for every mood.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the significant sport utilities (and a few
cars) making their debuts at the New York show, which is
celebrating its 100th anniversary this year:
</P>
<P>
   ACURA MDX _ Honda's luxury division will go head-to-head against
the phenomenally successful Lexus RX 300 with this car-based
2001-model sport utility, which goes on sale this fall. The MDX is
Honda's first attempt to design a midsize or large SUV; it had
previously sold vehicles built by Isuzu. Unlike the Lexus, Acra's
entry has a third-row seat, though it is too small for adults.
</P>
<P>
   BMW 330i, 330xi and M3 _ BMW took the wraps off three new
compact models for 2001. The 330i and 330xi have a new 3-liter
six-cylinder engine rate at 225 horsepower, up from 193 for the
2.8-liter engine in current models. The 330xi will be the first
all-wheel-drive BMW car sold in the United States since 1991,
employing the drive system used in the X5 sport utility. The
company also introduced the next-generation M3 performance car,
which now has the body design of the latest 3-Series models and 300
horsepower, up from 240.
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER SEBRING _ DaimlerChrysler's Sebring line expands to
include a sedan, replacing the Cirrus, as well as a next-generation
coupe and convertible with somewhat more sleek styling. The
convertible's 2.7-liter V-6 now delivers 200 horsepower, up 32 from
the previous version.
</P>
<P>
   GMC YUKON DENALI and DENALI XL _ General Motors' GMC division
introduced two premium versions of its full-size sport utilities,
the Yukon Denali and the longer Yukon Denali XL (which used to be
called the GMC Suburban). Outfitted with GM's 6-liter,
325-horsepower V-8 engine and full-time all-wheel drive, both come
with a long list of amenities, including a Bose Acoustimass stereo,
a Homelink system to open garage doors and security gates and the
OnStar communications system.
</P>
<P>
   2001 GM MINIVANS _ The mildly restyled 2001 Chevrolet Venture,
Oldsmobile Silhouette and Pontiac Montana minivans, which go on
sale in the fall, have second- and third-row seats that fold flat
for a more usable cargo area. And an area behind the third row
provides compartments for groceries and hidden storage. An
entertainment system allows passengers to play movie videos and
video games; it has a larger screen and wireless, two-channel
headphones for rear passengers. GM further announced that its
minivans would be available with all-wheel drive in the 2002 model
year. Ford's 2001 Windstar van will also get wireless headphones.
</P>
<P>
   INFINITI Q45 _ This new flagship for Nissan's luxury division is
due next spring as a 2002 model. Larger and more imposing than the
current model, it has a 4.5-liter V-8 engine that promises a
whopping 340 horsepower. Nissan also made news at the show with a
vehicle that wasn't on display, announcing that it would build a
V-8-powered full-size pickup to challenge Detroit on its strongest
turf; Toyota's latest effort at a similar big truck, the Tundra,
has been selling briskly.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   LEXUS SC 430 _ This sporty but luxurious convertible _ Lexus'
first _ will arrive in showrooms in about a year. Details were not
released, but the production car will draw heavily on the Lexus
Sport Coupe Concept. This show car has a retracting hardtop and a
new 4.3-liter V-8 engine, which it will share with Lexus' biggest
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI MONTERO _ The 2001 version will still haul seven
people, but it will get a unit body like a car instead of its
current trucklike body-on-frame structure. Other upscale features
include four-wheel independent suspension and a five-speed
automatic transmission that can be manually shifted. A third-row
seat folds into a well in the floor.
</P>
<P>
   OLDSMOBILE BRAVADA _ This 2002 model will be the first of a line
of GM sport utilities that include replacements for the Chevrolet
Blazer and GMC Jimmy. Its new architecture will also serve as the
platform for a new line of midsize pickups and crossover vehicles.
A larger, roomier body pushes the Bravada into the midsize class;
it has a new 4.2-liter in-line six-cylinder engine.
</P>
<P>
   PANOZ ESPERANTE _ Panoz Auto Development, a Georgia-based maker
of limited-production, high-performance automobiles, showed its
Esperante luxury sport convertible. Priced about $80,000, the
305-horsepower Esperante aims at the BMW Z8, Aston Martin DB7 and
Mercedes-Benz SL500.
</P>
<P>
   SUBARU LEGACY OUTBACK _ The 2001 model will offer a six-cylinder
engine, Subaru's first since the SVX coupe went out of production
at the end of 1996. Horsepower will increase by 28 percent, to 212.
The vehicle will also get an antiskid stability system. Subaru
further announced a marketing agreement that will result in a
limited L.L. Bean Edition of the Outback.
</P>
<P>
   2001 TOYOTA HIGHLANDER _ There was a time when foreign-based
automakers were content to offer one or two sport utilities,
leaving Detroit with the bulk of he market by selling models in
small, medium and large. But Toyota is making it clear that it will
fight General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler in every market
segment. The 2001 Highlander will be the fifth sport utility in
Toyota's lineup, plus two Lexus luxury models. The Highlander,
which goes on sale in about a year, shares its underlying structure
with the Camry sedan _ the same design used for the Lexus RX 300.
The Highlander will be available with either front-drive or
full-time four-wheel drive and with either a four-cylinder or V-6.
In size and price, it fits between the compact RAV4 and the
truck-based 4Runner. (A slightly larger, second-generation RAV4 is
also on display.) Later this year, Toyota will market the full-size
Sequoia utility, which will be priced below the top-of-the-line
Land Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from vehicles that are in the production pipeline, the New
York show offers a glimpse of several design studies that first
appeared elsewhere, including a number of concepts from GM, which
has a particularly prolific and interesting crop of dream cars this
year. These include the Chevrolet SSR, a retro-style hot-rod pickup
that was a sensation at the Detroit auto show in January; the
Chevrolet Avalanche, a combination of SUV and short-bed pickup; the
Hummer H2, a bright-yellow design for a smaller, pickup-based
version of the military vehicle; and the Cadillac Imaj, a
sharp-edged ultra-luxury sedan with electronic gadgets including
Internet access.Two concept cars making their worldwide debuts in
New York come from both ends of the price spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   The BMW Z9 is an ice-blue sports car with gull-winged doors and
carbon-fiber body panels attached to a skeletal aluminum frame,
making the car very light but rigid. While the driver may get
inside through a traditional, hinged door, both that door and a
small rear panel open skyward in one piece to allow access to the
back seat. Inside, the Z9 is uncluttered. Only a starter button and
a control knob on the center console operate hundreds of functions.
</P>
<P>
   And Kia, of South Korea, is showcasing a concept version of its
next-generation Rio, which is destined to be one of the
least-expensive cars in America. That is an unusual move, since the
first-generation Rio has not yet reached the market, and will not
until August. The Rio SV concept has an on-board personal computer
that would, in theory, give passengers Internet access and
navigation help.
</P>
<P>
   The 100th New York International Auto Show runs through April 30
at the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center, 11th Avenue between 34th
and 39th Streets. Hours are 11 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. Monday through
Saturday, 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. on Sunday. Admission is $9 for adults
and $3 for children under 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
