<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, April 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rain will fall for most of Saturday across much of New England
as a very sluggish low-pressure system, which will be virtually cut
off from steering winds aloft, persistently draws Atlantic moisture
inland. Rainfalls of 1 to 2 inches are possible, particularly over
high ground, where the sloping terrain augments the lifting of
Atlantic air. A skiff of light snow will dust the very highest
elevations of the White Mountains in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, farther to the west, a plume of Atlantic moisture
coiling around the lethargic low will fuel steady,
light-to-moderate rains across eastern New York and eastern
Pennsylvania, where ridge tops in the Catskill and Pocono mountains
will be shrouded by low cloud ceilings. Drizzle and patches of
light rain will circulate southward along the Appalachian chain as
far as North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE DRY LINE
</P>
<P>
   The dry line that sets up across the western Plains during the
warm season is anything but linear. This long but narrow boundary
between humid air from the Gulf of Mexico and dry air from the
Rockies can waver back and forth across western Texas, Oklahoma,
Kansas and Nebraska, occasionally causing a local switch from
stifling to refreshingly dry humidity a few times a day. Because
contrasting air masses converge at the dry line, isolated
thunderstorms can form. When a potent jet stream disturbance
arrives overhead, a formidable outbreak of severe storms often
erupts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
