<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3680 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$     04-21 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISTIC PRICING CAN BE REALISTIC, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 23) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVE LOHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what are technology stocks worth? The short answer _ more
today than a week ago, in the wake of their alarming slide _ is
unsatisfying. And if investors are reassured by the rebound last
week, the question of how to value technology companies is likely
to remain important for some time. These are the companies, after
all, that led the stock market's long climb and are responsible for
so much economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Since October 1998, the Nasdaq composite, dominated by
technology stocks, has more than doubled, driven by what is called
momentum investing _ the belief, simply put, that what went up
yesterday is likely to go higher today. That approach causes
conniptions among the intellectual heirs of Benjamin Graham, the
Columbia finance professor considered the founder of modern
securities analysis. Grahamite value investors like Warren E.
Buffett weigh share prices against fundamentals like assets, cash
flows and earnings, and seek bargains.
</P>
<P>
   No one really argues today that technology stocks are
undervalued, or ``special situations'' in Graham's phrase. On
average, the 72 technology companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index are trading at nearly 46 times their estimated
earnings this year; the price-to-earnings ratio for the index as a
whole is 25. Both figures are sky-high by historical standards. Yet
the yawning gap between them opened only in the last year and a
half: in October 1998, the P/E for the technology stocks was 26,
for the whole index a nearby 21.
</P>
<P>
   What created the chasm? A mindless stampede into technology
stocks? Perhaps. But the investment strategists and economists who
labor lucratively on Wall Street cringe at the notion that their
industry is governed merely by fads and frenzies.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Edward Yardeni, chief economist of Deutsche Bank
Securities, has developed a rigorous analysis of the
technology-stock run-up. The conclusion at the end of his trail of
equations: ``The price-earnings ratios of technology stocks are
optimistic, but they may be realistic as well.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Yardeni is known as one of the ``new paradigm''
advocates, who believe that information technology is having
far-reaching effects on the economy. Still, he is not totally
starry-eyed about technology. He was also Wall Street's leading Y2K
hawk, warning _ mistakenly as it turned out _ that the difficulties
of dealing with Year 2000 computer problems might bring on a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   In the technology-stock analysis, Yardeni and a research
associate, Joseph Abbott, started with two sets of numbers for the
72 technology companies in the S&AMP;P. The first was corporate
earnings estimates for the next 12 months by securities analysts,
as compiled by IBES International, going back to the 1980s. The
second was the five-year earnings estimates made by analysts over
the same span.
</P>
<P>
   They found that from 1985 through the early 1990s, the long-term
(five-year) growth estimates tended to range from 10 percent to 15
percent a year, but as the 1990s wore on the projections started
rising, and are now at about 25 percent annually. Around 1998,
Yardeni, believes, investors apparently started taking those
long-term growth estimates more seriously as a basis for valuing
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In Yardeni's thinking, the higher growth estimates, plus a
slight increase in the multiplier attached to the long-term growth,
and assuming low inflation, translate to justifiable P/E ratios of
33 to 50. (The precise methodology is discussed in two papers,
``How to Value Earnings Growth'' and ``Reversal of Fortune,''
posted on the Web at www.yardeni.com.)
</P>
<P>
   The assumptions by analysts and investors make sense, Yardeni
said, ``if you believe we are in a quasi-new economy'' of fairly
robust growth with low inflation. ``Analysts have come to view
technology stocks as less cyclical than before,'' he said. It is
also worth noting that Yardeni's analysis focused on technology
blue chips _ Cisco Systems, Intel, Microsoft, Sun Microsystems _
and not small dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Yardeni observed that ``valuation, like beauty, is in the
eye of the beholder.'' There is a place for sober calculation, but
also for art, instinct and luck.
</P>
<P>
   That investment truism, of course, has been around for
centuries. A classic example: In 1915, a young man named Benny
Grossbaum told his bosses at a Wall Street investment firm that he
thought a fledgling enterprise called the
Calculating-Tabulating-Recording Co. had bright prospects in an
emerging field of technology. No, came the reply, it looked dubious
compared with solid-asset industries like oil, railroads or even
automobiles, the hot industry of the future in Wall Street's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He heeded the advice of his elders. But before long he left the
firm, and later changed his name _ to Benjamin Graham. And the
technology start-up that had caught his young eye later changed its
name as well _ to International Business Machines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
