<SLUG> BC-CANDY-MOLDS-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CANDY MOLDS ARE GREAT PRESENT IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 23.)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candy molds come in a variety of shapes, sizes and materials.
For years, collectors have prized tin candy molds.
</P>
<P>
   These may still be in use, but candy-making experts say that the
new lightweight, clear plastic molds leave a better shine on the
candy. Rubber molds and heavy-duty white plastic molds are used
mainly for making hard candy.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Fellows is a sales associate at Studio 6 in Clifton Park,
N.Y., a candy supply house featuring tools and molds to make candy,
and offers how-to demonstrations twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that plastic is the best material, and you can't beat
the price at $1.75 to $1.99 a sheet, which is the size of a piece
of paper,'' Fellows said. Plastic sheets have indentations to make
one large piece of candy or several smaller pieces. Sheets with
multiple indentations might be all the same design or themed for a
certain event.
</P>
<P>
   For example, for Easter it might be a series of small bunnies or
bunnies in various poses, a basket, an egg and a lily plant.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning to make something like a large solid
chocolate rabbit, plan on spending about $20 for a mold. There are
literally thousands of candy molds to choose from, and if you can't
find what you want, it can usually be ordered.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Frances Ingraham Heins writes about items in, on and around the
home. Write to her c/o Details, Features Department, Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.
</P>
</TEXT>
