<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., April 23)  
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEN HOME IS NO SHELTER
</P>
<P>
   What constitutes a ``New York day''? For workers who live
outside New York State, but work for New York companies, sometimes
from home, the question has income tax consequences. And now that
returns have been filed, the state may be challenging some
taxpayers' version of the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers get a credit in their home states for taxes paid to
New York, explained Jeffrey Kelson, New York tax partner at BDO
Seidman, but because of New York's higher rates, ``the individual
still pays extra taxes.'' For Connecticut, the difference is 2.75
percentage points, but ``New York and New Jersey might as well be
Estonia and Italy _ they're that different,'' he said, making
general comparisons impossible.
</P>
<P>
   People who live in one state and work in another are supposed to
keep track of the days they work in the employer's state and
generally pay taxes there only for those days. Say an employee who
lives in Connecticut and works in New York is temporarily assigned
to the company's Stamford office. She gets a small tax break as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   But New York contends that people must work in the other state
at the employer's request, not the employee's convenience, to avoid
New York tax. ``The only safe thing to do is never come into New
York at all,'' said Nicholas Nesi, multistate tax partner for BDO
Seidman, because if a telecommuter comes to the home office even a
day or two a year, New York is likely to argue he owes New York
taxes for the year. ``But that is almost impossible. You need
face-to-face contact.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JAN M. ROSEN &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
