<HEADER>
A3687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PARKER-JAZZ-REVIEW-NY     04-21 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKER-JAZZ-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVAN PARKER'S MUSICAL LANGUAGE: ACCESSIBLE AND MYSTERIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In describing Evan Parker's music, sooner or later
you're going to use a circle metaphor _ a wheel, a mandala, a
spiral. For 35 years he has been rigorously attached to a
particular kind of soprano saxophone language, one more or less of
his own devising.
</P>
<P>
   In it the normal jazz-improviser's code of conversational broken
phrases is discarded in favor of long, continuous statements;
Parker uses the technique of circular breathing and can blow
without pausing for 20 minutes or more. But rather than droning, he
gives you bunches of notes that come stippled with ornament, making
low tones and high overtones collide, trilling them and rolling
them together so closely into line that he sounds as if he is
playing two instruments at once.
</P>
<P>
   He lights upon distinct patterns, generates a fairly small range
of harmony and uses a handful of favorite polyrhythms that he taps
out on the keys. It's a system and instantly easy to follow, but it
is mysterious, too. His performances are such a complex barrage on
the ears, such an original use of wind and stamina, that they seem
polymorphous: they start as coldly as math and then turn into sex.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker is also a generous player who listens to his
collaborators. Beginning a four-night stand at the Knitting Factory
on Thursday night, he played two duet sets that proceeded
differently by virtue of his partners.
</P>
<P>
   The first was with Ned Rothenberg, and it came close to an ideal
partnership. Rothenberg spent much of the set as accompanist,
interjecting notes and chords on the bass clarinet that guided the
listener harmonically through the gnarled rush of Parker's playing.
You could see the melody and the logic in it, and it was an
illumination, like reading Joyce with clear explanatory footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   But then he came out of his secondary role and took the
spotlight himself for a short while; instead of Parker's leonine
serenity, he played with a thicker, more athletic sound.
Rothenberg's rhythms were different, too, shorter and more
aggressive, and when he used overtones he made little tunes out of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum played live electronics against Parker in the
second set, and it was a more speculative venture. Parker is
working a lot with electronics these days, but it is mostly of a
sort in which his own saxophone sounds are digitally processed, fed
back to him in scrambled form, which initiates (naturally) a
circular process.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum operated differently, using his own samples and
sounds, many of them referring to real things in the physical
world: monkey cries, violins, drums, saxophone choirs, African
singing. There was a philosophical disjunction going on here, since
Parker's work is completely unmoored from references to the world
outside his own playing; also, Teitelbaum's sounds were funny,
whereas Parker's were anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Teitelbaum gave a performance that was more or less
complete in itself, rather than looking for the gaps to be filled;
it forced Parker into a secondary role for most of the set, playing
broken phrases and long tones. (He further acquiesced by playing
the tenor saxophone, which makes him sound mellow and phlegmatic.)
</P>
<P>
   But the set ended with a territorial gesture: changing back to
soprano, Parker ripped off a powerful, 10-minute solo _ reasserting
that his was a music of almost religious conviction, not tinkering
humor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER22-COX     04-21 1798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Like Gingrich said: time for some new faces
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush is looking outside his Texas circle for advice
from supporters of his ex-president father and John McCain in
response to talk that his White House bid is directed by aides
untested by national politics. But the Bush campaign apparently
will remain Austin-based, steered by top aides Karl Rove, Karen
Hughes and Joe Allbaugh. Among new faces expected to be brought in
are three key members of McCain's unsuccessful run: Rick Davis,
Kenneth Duberstein and Vin Weber. The group also includes Mary
Matalin, deputy manager of Bush's father's 1992 campaign;
strategists Charles Black and Ed Gillespie; former GOP Chairman
Haley Barbour and former Rep. Bill Paxon of New York. Former
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney reportedly will head the search for a
running mate. Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich went public with
the criticism this week, saying Bush's team ``still has a little
bit of Austin in their style'' and is ``not quite up to speed yet''
in running a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   SOME CHANGES FOR GORE, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Like his Republican rival, Al Gore is adding new faces to his
presidential campaign and stocking the Democratic National
Committee with loyal aides. Some reported changes: Mark Fabiani,
who helped the president handle his high-profile controversies will
be deputy campaign manager for communications, the most visible
aide in the campaign. Other top-level changes: Lisa Berg,
scheduling and advance; Chip Smith, chief of staff; Heather
Marabeti, deputy chief of staff; Janet Murguia, public liaison;
Elaine Kamarck, policy consultant; Sarah Bianchi, policy and
communications; Michael Whouley and Donnie Fowler Jr., political
strategists.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN COMING UNDER THE BIG TENT
</P>
<P>
   John McCain will be the keynote speaker at the annual Prescott
Bush dinner May 22 in Stamford, Conn. The Republican fund-raising
event is named for George W. Bush's grandfather, who was a U.S.
senator from Connecticut. State GOP Chairman Chris DePino said that
he was ``extremely pleased that Senator McCain has agreed to play a
major role for Connecticut Republicans,'' and that ``McCain will
appear under the banner of Governor Bush.'' McCain's candidacy was
Bush's only serious threat during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   EMPHASIS ON `GREEN' OTHER THAN MONEY
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Earth Day, Al Gore used a half-government,
half-campaign trip to the Detroit area Friday to promote new
government fuel-efficiency research and buff the ``green''
credentials he is counting on to give him an edge over George W.
Bush. Gore surrounded himself with environmental, labor and
trucking industry leaders at the Alvan Motor Freight yard in
Romulus, Mich., to underscore his argument for projects like the
government's new agreement with truck manufacturers to develop
``super fuel-efficient'' pickups, buses, and 18-wheelers within the
next decade to cut greenhouse gas pollutants beyond current
emission standards. Because he was there on behalf of the
administration, he did not mention Bush. But he did criticize
unnamed people who ``always argue that pollution is the inevitable
price we pay for our prosperity.'' According to The Associated
Press, Gore mixed one hour of vice presidential duty in with six
hours of political business.
</P>
<P>
   EMPHASIS ON `GREEN' INCLUDES MONEY
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people like to take on big guys,'' consumer advocate
Ralph Nader said as he spoke to several hundred people at the
University of Kentucky's Singletary Center for the Arts. ``I like
to take on big guys. Big guys invigorate me. And they should
invigorate you.'' His message was simple: Corporations and their
lobbyists have taken over the political system and it is up to
citizens to return the process to its grass-roots origin. Nader's
goal is to get the Green Party on the ballot in every state and
pull more than 5 percent of the vote, which would qualify him for
millions of dollars in federal campaign funds. He currently polls
in single digits, about even with the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   STANCE FIRM AS THE FLAGPOLE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain notwithstanding, George W. Bush is sticking to his
stance on South Carolinians making up their own minds on the
Confederate battle flag. McCain, who took a similar position during
his campaign, reversed field and said the flag should come down
from atop the South Carolina Statehouse. Questioned a day later,
Bush said anew: ``It's the right of the state of South Carolina to
make the decision on the flag.'' McCain said he took that similar
position in February because ``I feared that if I answered honestly
I could not win the South Carolina primary.'' Bush, of course, won
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   3-WAY DEBATES? GORE DOESN'T COMMIT HIMSELF
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said on the Larry King TV show that he's open to
including the Reform Party presidential nominee in the fall
debates. Reform Pat Buchanan has filed a complaint with the Federal
Election Commission arguing for a spot in the nationally televised
forums. The Commission on Presidential Debates has set a 15 percent
threshhold in five national polls to get into the debates.
Buchanan's in single digits. ``I have a mixed feeling about that,''
Gore said. ``It depends on the level of support that they have,
whether it would enhance or impede the debate. I have an open mind
about it. But I think that we need to know more before a decision
like that is made.''
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY MONEY STILL COMING IN ...
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush accelerated his already formidable fund-raising
effort in March. Cox News Service's Ken Foskett reported that Bush
raised $6.4 million in March, up from the $3.1 million he raised in
February, for a total topping $80 million. But Bush also continued
to spend money at record paces _ another $10.1 million in March. In
all, Bush has spent $73.4 million, a presidential primary campaign
record. Al Gore, meanwhile, raised $1.9 million in March and spent
$4.7 million. Gore has raised a total of just under $38 million and
spent $36.4 million. In the crucial category of cash on hand, Bush
listed $6.8 million to Gore's $3.8 million. The Gore campaign said
it anticipates an additional $6 million in federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   ... WITH GORE $9 MILLION FROM LIMIT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is wrapping up his fund-raising with about $9 million
remaining to carry his Democratic presidential campaign through the
convention this summer. Gore faces a spending limit because he
accepted federal matching funds. George W. Bush, who didn't take
the taxpayer money, can spend whatever he can raise through the
national convention this summer. Gore is limited to spending $40.5
million. Because some of Gore's spending was exempt from the legal
limit, he can spend $9 million more before bumping the ceiling,
said Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway.
</P>
<P>
   QUICKIE INTERVIEWS, NOT NEWS CONFERENCES
</P>
<P>
   At last count, Al Gore has not held a news conference in
slightly more than two months, but he ``will have a lot of news
conferences; don't worry about it,'' Gore said in Fort Lee, N.J.
The question was raised by Jay DeDapper of WNBC, as a line of New
York City TV journalists shuttled in and out for a few minutes with
the vice president. Gore has shown a preference for quick,
back-to-back television interviews, with two questions squeezed
into 60 seconds. He did seven of them. A hint about the reason for
Gore's reticence came when a Washington Post reporter pressed him
on Elian Gonzalez. Gore gave a halting answer before his press
secretary, Chris Lehane, cut in to announce that this was not a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   BUT ISN'T A LOT OF POLITICS THEATER, ANYWAY?
</P>
<P>
   Call it a bit of political theater or merely some inspired
casting, but Donna Hanover's latest New York part might raise some
eyebrows at City Hall. Beginning May 30, Hanover, Rudy Giuliani's
wife, takes over a lead role in ``The Vagina Monologues,'' the
off-Broadway hit featuring a dozen or so monologues on topics like
orgasm and childbirth. Hanover, who has appeared in several movies
and hosts ``In Food Today'' on the Television Food Network, will
perform for two weeks, sharing the monologues with two other women.
Interestingly, the playwright is Eve Ensler, a personal friend and
political supporter of Hillary Rodham Clinton, Giuliani's Senate
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   TAINTED MONEY? PERHAPS NOT TAINTED ENOUGH
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald reports that Massachusetts Sens. Ted Kennedy
and John Kerry will keep checks from Vivian Mannerud, a Democratic
donor linked to cocaine trafficker Jorge Cabrera. The
Mannerud-Cabrera connection prompted Hillary Rodham Clinton to
return Mannerud's $22,000 contribution to her Senate campaign
recently. Though Kennedy accepted $1,000 from Mannerud, Kerry had
closer ties: Mannerud hosted an $18,000 Kerry fund-raiser, gave
$1,000 in donations and arranged foreign travel for Kerry's staff
as recently as this month. Though Kerry's advisers warned him that
Mannerud's drug connection could prove troublesome, Kerry wasn't
swayed. ``We accept her word she had no knowledge of Mr. Cabrera's
illicit activities,'' the Herald quoted Kerry spokesman David Wade
as saying.
</P>
<P>
   TAKE THAT! I'LL SHOW YOU
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Matthew Martinez, D-Calif., has abandoned the Democrats on
virtually every party vote since losing the primary last month to
an opponent supported by a number of fellow California Democrats.
Democrats are aware of what's been happening and attribute it to
bitterness about the defeat, Roll Call said, and if the situation
has left some Democrats frustrated, ``they are nevertheless
resigned to fate.'' The publication quoted an anonymous ``top
leadership aide'' as saying: ``That's the problem with an early
primary. You have to live with the dead body for six months.''
</P>
<P>
   HEY, PEOPLE, THERE'S AN ELECTION HERE
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks before North Carolina's gubernatorial
primary, the five major candidates hoping to succeed Democratic
Gov. James Hunt are having trouble garnering attention, The
Associated Press reports. Even Attorney General Mike Easley, vying
with Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker on the Democratic side, admits as much:
``Nobody is paying any attention.'' Battling on the GOP side in the
May 2 primary are former Charlotte Mayor Richard Vinroot, state
Rep. Leo Daughtry and former state Rep. Chuck Neely. Recent polls
show Easley and Vinroot leading.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
