<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-PHIL-JACKSON-NBA-CENT     04-21 3233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHIL-JACKSON-NBA-CENTERPIECE-ART-ADV23-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV23 
 PHIL JACKSON: THE GOOD FATHER OF THE NBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use April 23 or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: Photo is available in JPEG format by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By DAVID SHIELDS  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Halfway through the first quarter of the Feb. 29 game between
the Portland Trail Blazers and the Los Angeles Lakers, with
Portland having just gone up, 8-6, Phil Jackson, the coach of the
Lakers, called timeout. Before the teams met, Jackson said he had
never seen ``a bigger game in my 33 years'' in the NBA, which,
coming from such an exponent of understatement and indirection,
seemed improbable hyperbole.
 &HT;    True, the game did involve two teams with identical records _
45-11, the best in the National Basketball Association _ and
identical 11-game winning streaks. And Los Angeles had lost the
last seven games in Portland. But it still seemed a rather abrupt
and alarming timeout.
 &HT;    Lakers guard Brian Shaw, who had inbounded the ball, said: ``We
were just bringing the ball in and he called a timeout. Everybody
looked at him and was surprised. I thought, 'Uh-oh, he must have
called something in the huddle and we didn't run it the right way.'
So I said, 'Did we do something?' And he said: 'No. I'm just
messing around.' We just went over and had some water and sat down.
And then he said: 'OK. Get ready to go.''' The Rose Garden was
absolutely collegiate in its cacophonous Blazermania, and Jackson's
brinkmanship reminded his players that it's finally just a game
they're playing and that they, too, are supposed to be messing
around having fun.
 &HT;    But it also communicated unmistakably that he was in control _
not only of the team, of course, but of the building. We're running
the show, not them. When the Lakers returned to the court, Shaw
scored on a driving layup. Watch the NBA sometime on NBC or TNT or
TBS; watch how the camera cuts back and forth between the two head
coaches pacing the sidelines and the 10 players running up and down
the court, as if to imply that the coaches are omnipotent
puppeteers and the players their particularly lithe marionettes.
 &HT;    Watch college basketball sometime on ESPN; listen to Dick Vitale
refer constantly to the coach as ``the orchestrator.'' Thus does
race myth get reified: maybe black men can walk on the moon, but
white men still man Mission Control.
 &HT;    One principal reason that Phil Jackson has been such a
successful coach is that he has the ability to function as a subtly
paternal rather than sadistically paternalistic leader of a group
of young black men (many of whom grew up without fathers) who might
have use for a mentor but have none for a tyrant. In Chicago,
Jackson coached the Bulls to six championships.
 &HT;    In Los Angeles, he has transformed the Lakers _ who the previous
three years had failed to fuse the talents of Shaquille O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant into anything resembling a cohesive force _ into a
genuine team, one that, with guaranteed home-court advantage
throughout the playoffs, is now the strong favorite to win this
year's NBA championship. In the words of Lakers forward-center John
Salley, who rarely plays in games but who appears to function as a
sort of ex-cathedra assistant coach and team spokesman: ``With
Phil, it's: 'You're a man. I'm a man. I'm going to help you be a
better man.''' Players seem stunned and grateful that Jackson
neither panders to their wishes nor preys on their insecurities.
 &HT;    Most NBA coaches are naggers; players call them ``little
bitches,'' according to Charley Rosen, a novelist who is writing a
book with Jackson about their basketball-based friendship. Black
players, especially, get tired of, especially, white coaches
yipping at them. Most coaches can't fathom how their tirades can
carry racial connotations to players; the P.J. Carlesimo-Latrell
Sprewell incident of a few years ago is the benchmark example of
this dynamic.
 &HT;    There were also the recent and continuing flareups between
Boston Coach Rick Pitino and the Celtics star Antoine Walker;
between Philadelphia's Larry Brown and Sixers guard Allen Iverson;
between New York's Jeff Van Gundy and Sprewell. Jackson seems to
grasp that in the white-managed, black-content-provided NBA, the
dialectic between coaches and players shouldn't replicate the
punitive patriarchy of the 400-year-old American racewar; the
conversation has to find a new groove.
 &HT;    Pretending to praise Coach Pat Riley before the Lakers faced the
Miami Heat on March 5, Jackson said: ``I have great admiration for
his attention to detail, his driving kind of authoritarian kind of
dictatorship that he runs his teams with. And his motivational work
that he does, it keeps people very busy and very driven.'' Jackson
uses instead what he calls the I Know That You Know That I Know
method of coaching. ``Why are you looking at me? You already know
you made a mistake,'' he'll say when a player looks to the sideline
after a miscue. ``I'm no savior,'' he said when he arrived in Los
Angeles this summer. ``They have to be the savior of themselves.''
 &HT;    Off the court, though, Jackson appears to want to be their
savior and doesn't seem to hear how condescending his
high-handedness can sound. At the beginning of the season, he said
that the Lakers ``are all autistic in some form or fashion. I don't
mean to say that as a snide remark toward a certain population in
our society. But they'' _ the Lakers _ ``have a limitation of their
attention span. A lot of it is probably due to too much rap music
going in their ears or coming out of their being.''
 &HT;    Kobe Bryant, who spent part of his childhood in Italy, said he
found Jackson's giving him ``White Boy Shuffle,'' a novel about a
black child raised in a privileged white community, a bit
presumptuous. Jackson gave Shaquille O'Neal a copy of Nietzsche's
``Ecce Homo'' _ doesn't that smack of noblesse oblige? On the
court, on the other hand, Jackson almost never calls plays; he
thinks play-calling makes players feel as if they're on a string _
his.
 &HT;    This abnegating impulse comes from his practice of Zen Buddhism,
with its strong emphasis on egolessness, but also from his innate
temperament, which he once described as ``low-key _ not comatose
but close to it.'' His wife, June Jackson, has said: ``It's
comfortable to be with him. He's quiet inside.'' And it's so loud
over there in all those other huddles.
 &HT;    When I bumped into Jackson in the elevator at the Benson Hotel
in Portland, he had the least hegemonic presence of any coach of
any sport at any level I have ever encountered. Asked what
distinguished him from other coaches they'd played for, more than
one Laker said, ``During the game, he sits down.'' Players thrill
to this non-Bobby Knight-ness.
 &HT;    Son of two Pentecostal ministers, role player on the
championship New York Knicks teams of the 1970s coached by Red
Holzman, who preached team basketball, idealist whose social values
were formed in the '60s, longtime student of Zen and admirer of the
Lakota Sioux, Jackson was destined to be the anticoach coach. When
he was 4, his mother hung a sign over his bed with a quotation from
John 3:16: ``For God so loved the world that he gave his only
begotten Son, that whosoever believeth in him should not perish,
but have eternal life.''
 &HT;    Jackson has contrived a way to rebel against and yet not
entirely reject his pastor parents by becoming a Wizard of Oz who
insists on stepping out from behind the curtain to let the whole
group play with the control switches. He is an authority figure
whose authority derives from his strategic willingness to
deconstruct that authority.
 &HT;    The night after the Portland game, the Lakers played the lowly
Vancouver Grizzlies in Los Angeles, and ``lethargy'' doesn't begin
to describe the absence of energy in the Staples Center that
evening. ``We were somnambulant out there,'' Jackson said
afterward. ``We were the walking wounded in their sleep.'' Most
coaches would have been calling timeouts, hollering at players,
madly making substitutions.
 &HT;    Perversely, hilariously, Jackson did very nearly nothing for the
entire game. He just sat on the bench, a kind of mirror, reflecting
back to the players their own quiescence, daring them to find a way
out of their torpor. He even let Shaquille O'Neal stay on the floor
after picking up his fourth foul midway through the third quarter;
O'Neal picked up his fifth shortly after, and Jackson removed him
with the game tied. Immediately after O'Neal went to the bench, the
Lakers hit three consecutive 3-pointers, and the Grizzlies never
truly threatened the rest of the way.
 &HT;    ``That's natural, a letdown after last night,'' Jackson said
afterward. ``You have to measure it out and find a way to win. It's
good for them to adjust to that. I think they're really learning
and growing.''
 &HT;    June Jackson once said: ``Sometimes he keeps things moving by
not doing anything. With Phil, there's a flowing rather than a
forcing.'' Jackson's most famous flowing occurred when Chicago's
Scottie Pippen refused to enter a 1994 playoff game with 1.8
seconds left against New York. After the game, Jackson walked into
the Bulls' locker room and said: ``What happened has hurt us. Now
you have to work this out. You've got two minutes to get together,
to talk softly among yourselves.''
 &HT;    Nearly every other NBA coach would have used the occasion as an
opportunity to solidify his own power base; instead Jackson, in his
own words, stepped back and ``let the team come up with its own
solution.'' In the locker room, Bill Cartwright made an unusually
emotional appeal to his teammates; the incident brought the team
closer together. Jackson's goal is to yield control at a
superficial level in order to regain it at a more profound level by
creating an environment in which, he says, the players ``become
policemen of themselves, and that's really more fun for a coach to
watch happen than anything else.''
 &HT;    Of course, in the end, he's still watching them. Jackson is
chief of police. He maintains a chilly margin of mystery around
himself (he agreed to be interviewed for this article only via
e-mail) partly, I think, as a quite consciously crafted technique
to get his players to stay tuned through the grind of an 82-game
season and, perhaps, weeks of playoffs. By being interestingly
paradoxical (gentle but not warm, relaxed yet in charge), he
doesn't bore the team to death; he keeps people alertly off guard.
He's a freaky control freak who sees and seizes the benefits of
granting to his charges a kind of semi-demi-freedom. Jackson's
friend Charley Rosen describes Coach Jackson as a ``benevolent
dictator.''
 &HT;    When I asked Jackson if he saw any relationship between his
apparently emancipated coaching style and the racial demographics
of the NBA, he characteristically slipped the noose of any
too-tight definition by saying: ``I don't think black or white
makes a difference to coaches. I think control is the issue: if I'm
responsible for this team, I'll be damned if I let some kids take
me down. It's my job attitude.''
 &HT;    Jackson's blessing and his curse _ what makes him both an
effective coach and a rather enigmatic person (the qualities are
related) _ is his extraordinary detachment. His wife, who hasn't
moved with him from Woodstock to Los Angeles, gets frustrated by
how little emotion he displays after big victories. She once
suggested that he wave to her in the stands after games to let her
know how happy he is about winning.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I wish we could play in a gym without any people in
the stands,'' he once said, ``and try to play the perfect game
where you don't make any mistakes, and maybe if there's a mistake
it's of omission, not commission, and everything is done at the
right moment, at the right time, and each decision is the right one
and everyone can ride that decision-making wave.'' In an e-mail
message, I asked him, ``Many players seem to view their role as
being not only to compete but to entertain; is there anything you
like about the performance aspects of being a coach?'' His response
was, ``The performance aspect of basketball enhances some players'
ability and hinders others.'' If Buddhism and a fundamentalist
childhood and political idealism are the building blocks of his
remarkably effective leadership style, they're also the ingredients
of a spooky sort of hyperrational perfectionism.
 &HT;    ``The greatness of Michael Jordan is his competitive drive,''
Jackson once said. ``The weakness of Michael Jordan is his
competitive drive.'' When I asked Jackson what his equivalent
tragic flaw might be, he replied, ``My weakness is also
competitiveness to excess.'' June, for instance, refuses to play
board games with him anymore.
 &HT;    The day before the April 8 game in Los Angeles between the
Lakers and the defending champion San Antonio Spurs _ a possible
preview of this year's Western Conference finals _ Jackson said:
``This is a team we not only want to beat, we want to beat soundly.
They showed their moxie last year in an abbreviated season,'' he
added, referring to last year's NBA lockout.
 &HT;    ``But you don't know what a team has until it has played an
82-game season and you come out in the end.'' After the
anticlimactic game _ which the Spurs won by 18 when Shaquille
O'Neal sat out with a sprained ankle, rendering the game
meaningless as a gauge of how the teams match up against each other
_ San Antonio Coach Gregg Popovich said about Jackson's disparaging
remarks: ``He's a great coach who has won a lot of championships.
It's just hard to figure what his motivation would be for the
comments he's made. I'm chalking it up to being childish.''
 &HT;    Luckily for Jackson and for the Lakers, whatever tendency he
might have toward petulance is balanced by his whimsicality. At the
Lakers' first meeting this year, they reportedly practiced without
a ball. Other practices have been conducted in complete silence.
What other NBA coach would have been unable to keep a smile off his
face when in 1996 his player, the Bulls' Dennis Rodman, head-butted
a referee? ``Don't you think it's interesting having Dennis
around?'' Jackson later asked. On the way to a Bulls practice
during the 1994 playoff series against the Knicks, Jackson
redirected the team bus to the Statue of Liberty for an impromptu
group tour. During a midseason slump, he advised the Bulls to order
some pizzas and beer up to their hotel rooms and just relax.
 &HT;    With 24 seconds remaining in the February game in Portland and
the Lakers leading by 3, the Trail Blazers called timeout. Jackson
spent much of the break talking to guard Brian Shaw. ``Questions
were coming up on how we were going to defend certain plays,'' Shaw
said. ``I was just giving him our perspective: 'This is what
they're doing. We feel more comfortable doing it like this.' I play
that role all the time. He said to us from the beginning of the
year: 'You guys are out on the floor. You have a feel for what's
going on. Don't be afraid to come to me and tell me what you
see.''' By contrast, Mike Donleavy, the Portland coach, ran onto
the court at the end of the timeout, yelling last-second
instructions to Greg Anthony, who turned his back on him and walked
away.
 &HT;    The Lakers prevented the Blazers from executing the play they
wanted to run. With eight seconds left, Portland's Scottie Pippen
was forced to toss up a jumper from 25 feet away; the ball bounced
off the rim into the corner. The Blazers' Steve Smith caught the
ball and, panicking a bit, threw up a desperation shot with five
seconds still left on the clock. The Lakers rebounded, and the game
was over. According to Jackson, the Lakers read the play perfectly,
``made the switches correctly and chased them into the spaces they
couldn't operate from.'' He credited his players, in particular
guard Ron Harper, ``who saw and read what was coming up.'' It was a
duel between two very good bands. The Lakers were the tighter band.
 &HT;    They won.
 &HT;    When Jackson says, ``The most effective way to forge a winning
team is to call on the players' need to connect with something
larger than themselves,'' you want to retain your skepticism; you
know how bottomless the selfishness of human nature is, how fragile
the bonds of any (especially artificially constructed) community
are; how calculated and in some ways contradictory Jackson's
persona is. There's a certain ``Stepford Wives'' quality to the
unanimity of players' encomiums about Jackson, a certain aspect of
black athletes returning to white reporters, in an endless feedback
loop, the same media cliches the newspapers printed last week:
``Phil's at peace with himself; that's what he's trying to bring to
us, that peace and that harmony and that resolve that he has within
himself,'' and so on.
 &HT;    And yet when I asked Ron Harper, who played for Jackson in
Chicago for several years before joining him this season in Los
Angeles, whether I could talk to him for a few minutes about
Jackson, he responded with an expletive that referred to his coach.
If a player had uttered this expletive about nearly any other coach
in the NBA, it would have been difficult to take it as anything
besides straightforward venom.
 &HT;    However, in this locker room (in which Shaquille O'Neal was
leading the Los Angeles Times beat reporter in a dance), with this
team (which in a certain sense was still only mimicking secondhand
notions about coming together, but in so doing was taking the first
steps toward actually coming together, in the same way that saying
``I love you'' is the first step toward falling in love), from this
player (whose reputation had always been that of a one-dimensional
shooter until joining up with Jackson in Chicago, where he became a
defensive specialist and floor leader), about this coach (who on
media day in Los Angeles made certain that the first people the
press met were the rookies, followed by role players, then the
starters, then the stars, then lastly himself _ yielding the stage
to his players or underlining that he's in charge, or both; that's
the question he's so good at lodging in players' minds; that's the
ace of his magical coaching trick), it was, I think, a joke, and as
such, pure praise.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;     c.2000 David Shields  
