<HEADLINE>
$ADV23 
 DEPRAVATION, SEASICKNESS AND THEN A NEW LIFE IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use April 9 or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: A family photo of Mirta Ojito and her sister Mabel, taken
after their move to Miami, is available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (PART II OF A 2-PART SERIES.)  
 By MIRTA OJITO  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As night fell my mother and sister found a thin mattress and
went to sleep on the floor. My father and I sat in plastic beach
chairs in front of them. All night names of vessels were called
over the loudspeakers _ a sign that the boat was ready and the
group needed to assemble fast. We did not speak much that night, my
father and I, but we observed. And what we saw was pitiful.
 &HT;    A chemistry professor from Santiago de Cuba, on his knees,
begging an officer to let him join his wife and children, who were
already on the bus to Mariel. His wife's name had been called,
while his, inexplicably, had been omitted. An old woman who cried
inconsolably because her only son was forbidden to leave with her
because his name had been misspelled in some document. She wanted
to stay, but her son pushed her into the arms of an officer, who
took her away as she kicked and screamed for her son. The son left
quickly, while the chemistry teacher lingered, still sobbing on his
knees.
 &HT;    Dawn found us in the same chairs. About 8 a.m., our boat was
called. We went through the process without any problems and soon
were sitting in a bus without glass in the windows, leaving us
exposed to the fury of the mob outside. We were pelted with
tomatoes and eggs. Some people in the bus cried. Others cursed
under their breath. An old lady prayed.
 &HT;    After a short ride, we arrived in El Mosquito, a barren, dusty
field that served as a holding area for people waiting to board
boats at the port of Mariel. We formed a long line outside, in the
midst of a woodsy, rocky area, and waited our turn. What we were
waiting for, we did not know. But because Cubans were trained to
wait in line everywhere, we obeyed.
 &HT;    Sometime in the afternoon our turn came. We were asked to walk
into what looked like a small house with a green roof. An officer
asked my name and wanted to know what I was carrying. He took my
two pens and sent me to a curtained booth for a search. A woman
asked me to lift my blouse, unhook my bra and take off my pants and
panties. Midway through she took pity on me and let me go. My
father turned in the last of his possessions, 200 pesos, about a
month's salary. He protested but was told that where he was going
he would not need Cuban pesos.
 &HT;    We emerged from the house, without money or identity, into what
looked like a sun-scorched military camp. We were assigned to one
of the dozens of olive green tents that dotted a barren field
looking out on a pretty stretch of beach that was fenced off and
patrolled by security guards. The word was that this was the last
stop before Mariel. We were shocked to meet people who had been
waiting 10 days. We could not fathom spending a day there, let
alone a week. We had not taken a shower or brushed our teeth since
leaving the house the day before. We had no towels, sheets, clean
underwear or even an extra set of clothes. We had not slept on a
bed or taken off our shoes or had a minute alone. We also had not
gone to the bathroom.
 &HT;    Someone pointed us to the showers and toilets, a cluster of
tents in the distance. The stench was unbearable. Flies swarmed. My
mother felt ill. We decided, instead, to take a bath in the ocean.
Salt water, we thought, would be better than no water at all. But
when we tried to get to the beach, a guard told us that swimming
was not allowed. We went back to the tent.
 &HT;    The camp was divided into three sections. One large area was
reserved for people like us who had been claimed by relatives who
had come from Miami. Another area, fenced by barbed wire, was for
people who had been in the Peruvian Embassy. They had no tents or
cots. Yet another section, closer to the water, was reserved for
people who had walked into police stations across the country and
applied for permits to leave, declaring themselves escoria. This
term covered anyone from a homosexual to an independent thinker to
a thief. They were also fenced in and guarded by dogs.
 &HT;    Dusk was fast approaching. We had been told that the
loudspeakers would blare through the night. If you missed your
name, you had to wait for space on another boat, if and when space
became available. I don't think anybody in our group slept that
night. An ocean breeze cooled the tent, the loudspeakers droned on
and a spotlight canvassed the entire camp.
 &HT;    In the morning, about 10 a.m., our boat was called. ``Valley
Chief, Valley Chief, Valley Chief.'' Three times. We rushed to an
area where again we were ordered to form a line and board a bus.
After a short ride, we arrived at Mariel. From the bus we could see
the masts of the vessels. There were recreational yachts, shrimp
boats and little two-person speedboats with people who, seemingly,
had buzzed over from Florida just to see what was going on. Good
Samaritans were throwing apples and shiny little bags. I later
learned that the bags contained potato chips. I remember thinking
that it was the first time I had seen apples, but, somehow, I knew
what they were.
 &HT;    There was an atmosphere of energy and optimism around the boats:
people coming and going; men in uniform carrying bottles of water;
reporters interviewing refugees and boat owners. From the window, I
suddenly caught a glimpse of Uncle Oswaldo standing on the dock,
tanned and dirty, and with a beard from 17 days out in the sea. He
was wearing jeans and a white T-shirt that contrasted sharply with
his sunburned skin. Smiling through his tears, he waved at us.
Behind him, white and motionless, lay the Valley Chief, the boat
that we thought would take us to the United States.
 &HT;    Not too long after our group boarded the boat, a bus stopped a
few feet from the dock and people began pouring out. Some were
shoeless; others wore orange uniforms that retained the creases of
clothes that had been folded for too long; most had their heads
shaved. A few were crying. They boarded the Valley Chief, and the
captain was instructed by Cuban immigration officers to take them
to the United States. We did not know it then, but they were people
that the Cuban government wanted to get rid of.
 &HT;    Some were prisoners, doing time for crimes that ranged from
theft to manslaughter. Others were simply nuisances, troubled
people who took up space and resources and did not contribute
anything to Castro's grand plans for a Socialist utopia. By sending
them abroad, the government was not only ridding itself of problems
but also turning the Mariel crisis into Washington's problem.
 &HT;    ``Sector by sector, the police identified the problem types and
told them, plain and simple, 'If you don't leave now, you go to
jail for four years,''' says Carlos Cajaraville, a former
counterintelligence captain who spent six months working at the
harbor. ``Most people, given the choice, would opt to leave.''
 &HT;    Filiberto Casti$eira, who was a colonel in the Ministry of the
Interior, the internal security apparatus in Cuba, and now sells
food from a lunch cart in Miami, worked at the command post that
managed the Mariel operation. He says that Castro would call every
night on a special line to ask how many boats had arrived, what
capacity they had, how many boats had left and with how many
people. He then gave the order concerning which groups of people
should leave the next day.
 &HT;    If too many homosexuals left, then their percentage was lowered
and the percentage of families increased. If too many criminals
left, which could provoke a response from American authorities in
Key West, then that figure was lowered and the percentage of, say,
political prisoners was increased. There were seven categories in
all. Washington was not blind to what was happening, but Carter had
his hands tied. In a meeting at the White House, the high command
of the Coast Guard informed the administration that there was no
way to stop the boat lift without using force, which would lead to
a significant loss of life.
 &HT;    ``Can you imagine Mr. Human Rights killing innocent refugees
seeking freedom from a repressive regimes in Cuba?'' says Robert
Pastor, who was the Carter administration's point man on Latin
America and the Caribbean. ``We were caught in a dilemma for which
we had no answer.''
 &HT;    To make matters worse, in early May, Carter urged Americans to
open their arms and hearts to arriving refugees. His statement was
interpreted as a sign that all Cuban refugees were welcome, but the
administration insisted that the president had been misunderstood.
 &HT;    Five days after the president's remarks the captain of the
Valley Chief received the order to leave Mariel. By then the boat's
blue waterline was no longer visible. There were 210 people on
board, only 17 of whom were related to the Cuban-Americans who had
made the trip from Miami. One of the strange men who came on board
without shoes asked my father for his nail clipper. When my father
asked him what he wanted it for, he said he wanted to cut his veins
open. We stayed away from him as much as we could.
 &HT;    The Valley Chief, creaking under the extraordinary weight,
refused to move. The captain said that the motor was damaged and
that we weren't going anywhere. My uncle went looking for help. He
returned with a tanned and muscled American sailor who spoke with
what I now think was a Texas drawl. I can hear his voice, but not
the words, because at the time I did not understand any English.
 &HT;    He had sailed his yacht, Ma$ana, to the port of Mariel as a Red
Cross volunteer. As my uncle explained the situation to the man, I
sat on the hard cement floor of the docks, trying in vain to
understand. From below, I noticed that the man's right arm was
fake, but so real-looking that it was almost impossible to detect.
The nails were perfectly shaped, and the curves of the forearm
imitated the muscles on his left arm. The man agreed to take the
women and children on his yacht and to tow the Valley Chief to
international waters. When he tried to throw a rope from the docks
to keep the Valley Chief from drifting, his fake arm got tangled up
in the ropes and fell into the water.
 &HT;    Everybody gasped. My mother fainted and hit the cement floor
with a thud. A man dove into the murky waters of the port and,
after a few seconds, came out triumphantly holding up the arm. The
American, who turned out to be a Vietnam vet, simply took the arm,
put it on and continued working. My mother came about. An explosion
of applause followed.
 &HT;    The event is etched in my memory because I remember thinking how
courageous the man was to lead a full life with only one arm and
how great technology must be in the United States to produce such a
fake arm. It was a sign, I thought then, of good things to come.
 &HT;    My father and uncle stayed behind on the damaged Valley Chief
while my mother, my sister and I boarded the Ma$ana. I tried to
help in the kitchen making sandwiches, but someone called me up to
the deck so I would not miss the last views of Cuba _ the faint
edge of a low green hill and the masts of the boats swaying in the
breeze. It was a little after 6 p.m., four days after we had left
home.
 &HT;    Before Cuba had completely disappeared from my view, I began to
throw up. There is little I remember after that. I was sick the
entire night, curled up on the wet floor next to my sister, who was
also sick. While everyone slept, strewn about the boat, my mother
kept a vigil over my sister and me. She was 40 years old and, for
the first time in her life, alone with her daughters. She had never
been on a boat before, feared the water and didn't know how to
swim. Both her daughters were seasick practically to the point of
unconsciousness and she was silenced by her lack of English.
 &HT;    At about 3 a.m., I awoke with a violent stomach spasm. I was
totally disoriented. I did not know where my head was or in what
direction my feet were pointing. I wondered if someone had moved my
bed. Then I realized I was not in my bed.
 &HT;    ``What's wrong?'' my mother asked. I thought for a minute what
to say. I was cold and hungry. I had an intense pain in my bladder
from not going to the bathroom for so long. I could not feel my
legs. My head hurt, as did my throat and stomach, from retching all
night long. My clothes were dirty; my hair was matted. I had not
changed or washed in five days. I felt like crying, but I was so
dizzy that I could not even cry. And of course, pain of all pains,
I had left Cuba.
 &HT;    ``Nothing,'' I told my mother. ``I'm OK.''
 &HT;    It was already Sunday, May 11, Mother's Day. I remember thinking
that my mother was not going to get a card. I had mailed her one
the day before we left our house. It was probably already under the
door. I reminded my mother that it was her day and went back to my
stupor. In a few hours we reached the United States.
 &HT;    So thick was the fog of seasickness that I don't remember seeing
land until I actually stepped on the docks at Key West. I don't
remember feeling anxious, hopeful or expectant. I only remember the
nausea that tortured my empty, pained stomach. The moment I stepped
on land, though, the queasiness disappeared and I started to think
of ways to find my father and uncle.
 &HT;    In the day and one night we had spent on the Valley Chief, my
uncle had taught me his phone number in Florida and I had memorized
it. I still remember it, although he moved from that house years
ago. I gave a volunteer the number and asked her to call my aunt
Tere. We formed yet another line and from there boarded buses to
what looked like a giant warehouse, outfitted for thousands of
people. The floor was lined with cots, row after row of them. There
was a lot of food, soda and gum. And there were clean bathrooms.
 &HT;    On my way to one of the yellow portables, someone called my
name. It was my high school literature professor, a blond woman
with blue eyes and delicate features who had always been highly
critical of people who did not support the regime. I turned my head
the other way. I think I was embarrassed that I had left Cuba and
someone had caught me in the act. Never mind that she, too, had
left. At that point my departure still seemed like an act of
treason. Against what? I didn't know.
 &HT;    We huddled in one cot and waited. At about 8 p.m. we heard our
names called through a bullhorn. As we moved toward the voice, we
saw Tere and her children, jumping for joy. ``There they are!! They
are here!'' Tere kept yelling as she hugged the three of us.
 &HT;    Sometime that night my father and my uncle found us. The Coast
Guard had rescued them from the foundering Valley Chief, and my
father had arrived in the United States in style, after all. A
helicopter had picked them up from the deck of a huge Navy ship and
taken them to a landing strip in Key West. The Valley Chief had
been towed back to the Keys. Together, at last, we arrived the next
morning at my uncle's house in Hialeah.
 &HT;    To me, accustomed to seeing photographs of my relatives in New
York, Hialeah was a major disappointment. There were no tall
buildings, no interesting architecture, no sense of a city, really.
And of course, there was no snow. I remember the summer of 1980 as
the longest and the hottest I have ever lived through, despite the
constant humming of air-conditioning in every house.
 &HT;    A couple of days after we arrived we had to go to an office to
register our presence in the United States. Our lungs were X-rayed
and we went through a series of interviews. At the first table, a
bald man who spoke Spanish asked our names individually. Before I
could tell him, though, he said I could choose any name I wanted. I
did not have to give him my real name. ``You are in America now,''
he said. ``You can forget the past and begin anew.'' I took his
advice and began a new life. But I kept my name and I have never
forgotten.
 &HT;    On Sept. 25, 1980, Cuba ended the boat lift. Even Castro became
embarrassed by the spectacle of so many people clamoring to leave
the island. In all, 125,266 Cubans came to America on 2,011 vessels
and one aircraft. I went on to graduate from Florida Atlantic
University and started a career in journalism that took me from The
Miami Herald to The New York Times.
 &HT;    Today Mariel is just a town lying perpetually under a cloud of
dust spewed by a cement factory nearby. At the port itself, there
is a geothermal power plant, situated inside a military compound,
off limits to civilians. The former Peruvian Embassy is now the
parking lot of a nondescript five-story hotel for businesspeople
and tourists. No Cubans are allowed. Twenty years later most Mariel
refugees are successful men and women who blend in with other
Cuban-Americans in Miami and elsewhere. Among them are writers,
television anchormen, entrepreneurs, public relations experts,
Disney World executives, restaurant owners, engineers, retirees,
homemakers.
 &HT;    But 1,750 ``Marielitos'' remain under the custody of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service for crimes committed in the
United States; 1,425 have been sent back to Cuba. When, in 1994,
the Cuban government seemed on the verge of playing its Mariel card
once again, President Bill Clinton, in his first term, did what
Carter had been unable or unwilling to do 14 years before. He
ordered the Navy to intercept all refugees and take them to
Guant namo Bay, the American military base in Cuba, and announced
that they would never come to America.
 &HT;    Eventually, most of the 30,000 rafters held at the base did make
it here. But by denying them immediate entry, Clinton reversed
decades of immigration policy toward Cuba. Since then, Cubans
intercepted in the water are routinely returned to the island. This
remarkable policy shift went practically unnoticed. No protests in
the streets of Miami. No outcry from the pro-immigration lobby. No
matter how much the boat lift has done for thousands of people like
me, it was clear that no one else _ not Washington, not Havana, not
even the Cuban exiles _ wanted another Mariel.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.2000 Mirta Ojito  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mirta Ojito is a reporter for The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
