<SLUG> BC-TV-BLUES-CLUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S SHOW INCORPORATES LESSONS IN SIGN LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday ``Blue's Clues,'' the Nickelodeon TV series for
preschoolers, will focus the adventures of its puzzle-solving puppy
on a young girl who is deaf and in the process will teach its young
viewers how to say a handful of words in American Sign Language.
The episode will be the first of many episodes to use sign language
in a way that allows young viewers to learn some signing basics.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's episode, ``Signs,'' the host, Steve Burns, and the
bubbly girl puppy, Blue, discover clues around the house to
determine where Blue wants to have a snack. They visit a school for
deaf children and become part of a storybook where they meet a
young girl who is deaf. Burns and Blue are told a story in sign
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to teach kids sign language and show how relevant it
is to their world,'' said Angela Santomero, the show's chief writer
and one of its creators. ``We introduce an animated character who
is deaf, Carly. She'll do something like make the sign for
elephant, and we show an elephant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a one-time diversity issue,'' Santomero said. ``Our
approach to education is mostly through repetition.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Blue's Clues'' is structured as an interactive search
for clues in each episode, with pauses for the young audience to
figure out what Blue is doing, it differs from other educational
shows for preschoolers like ``Sesame Street,'' which for more than
20 years has featured a deaf character who uses sign language with
the muppets.
</P>
<P>
   Burns learned American Sign Language at the Lexington Center
School for the Deaf in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The actress Marlee Matlin, who is deaf, recorded a series of
public service announcements with Burns to promote the show's use
of sign language.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ASL is incorporated naturally into the show, with all the
signs and gestures that Steve uses,'' said Adele Agin, the
executive director of vocational and mental health centers at
Lexington. ``It's a natural language for children because children
are so visually stimulated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous message out there,'' Agin added. ``The
message to deaf children is `you're valuable; you are part of this
society.' The message to hearing children is to be open-minded, to
be accepting, to be respectful to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other population it impacts is deaf children of hearing
parents and the hearing children of deaf parents. There is a
tremendous validation of the language, the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   In each new episode of ``Blue Clues,'' five to 10 new signs will
be incorporated, said Stacey Levin, a spokeswoman for the show.
About seven signs will appear consistently in each episode, like
the signs for ``Blue'' and ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing use of sign language and the interactive quality of
``Blues Clues'' _ Burns talks directly to the audience _ make it
different from other children's programs that have featured people
with physical challenges, Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Bravin, the associate director of development at
Lexington, watched ``Signs'' with his son, who is 2 and a half.
Bravin is deaf. His son can hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see his eyes pop out of his head,'' Bravin said in
American Sign Language as Agin translated. ``He said, `Daddy, I
must watch it again.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
