r a BC-HUMMINGBIRD-SPACE-PRO     04-21 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMMINGBIRD-SPACE-PROBE-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBING A COMET'S CORE  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF APRIL 24, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By MARK SCHROPE  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A hummingbird could soon be visiting the heavens _ in a manner
of speaking.
</P>
<P>
   NASA engineers want to build a space probe that behaves like a
hummingbird approaching a flower. It will use a touch-and-go
landing technique to capture and analyze samples from a comet's
central core for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The team, led by Glenn Carle of the NASA Ames Research Center in
Moffett Field, Calif., is hoping to persuade NASA chiefs to press
ahead with its Hummingbird Comet Nucleus Analysis Mission. The Ames
team hopes to launch the probe sometime around 2005, to complement
three other NASA comet missions.
</P>
<P>
   Comets are at approximately 100 degress Kelvin, and scientists
believe they contain deep-frozen material from shortly after the
big bang.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think is the most interesting question to answer is the
relationships of comets to material that ended up on the early
Earth and took part in the origin of life,'' Carle said. ``We just
don't know what we started with.''
</P>
<P>
   The space probe would be powered by an ion engine. Once it
reached the comet, it would orbit for up to a year taking samples
of the dust, ice and gases in the comet's atmosphere and analyzing
their composition and isotope ratios. During that period, the craft
would take detailed images to help the ground team choose a safe
touchdown spot.
</P>
<P>
   In the next phase of the mission, the craft would advance slowly
toward the comet's solid core, or nucleus, stopping frequently for
safety checks. But the craft would not land in the conventional
sense. Only two dangling tethers would make contact with the comet.
One tether, equipped with temperature, hardness and contact
sensors, would use electronics to sense certain conditions and
trigger a new type of sampling mechanism attached to the second
tether.
</P>
<P>
   The sampler has two counter-rotating carbide wheels with
sharpened blades that would grind up the surface of the comets and
kick chunks of the material into collection funnels on the
spacecraft. A prototype sampler is being built at Honeybee Robotics
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The hummingbird sampling cycle would take less than two seconds.
Then gas thrusters would fire and send the craft back to analyze
its samples as it orbits the comet. Ideally, the craft would repeat
this hummingbird maneuver as many as six times.
</P>
<P>
   As well as taking samples at many points on a comet nucleus, the
concept has several advantages. Comets have a tiny gravitational
field because their nuclei are only tens of kilometers across, so a
normal probe would have to latch onto the comet.
</P>
<P>
   The hummingbird probe's bump sampling would circumvent this
problem. Cutting down the time at the surface would also be safer,
since it means the probe would spend less time without sunlight and
channels of communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the questions we have from 20 years ago still
exist,'' said William Boynton, an astronomer at the University of
Arizona in Tucson. ``We've flown by comets and taken a peek at
them, but we really have not even scratched the surface. It sounds
like this mission would scratch the surface, literally as well as
figuratively.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
