<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3709 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DEMONSTRATORS-JAILED-     04-21 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMONSTRATORS-JAILED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWYERS NEGOTIATING FOR RELEASE OF LAST WORLD BANK PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense lawyers on Friday reached a plea-bargain
agreement with authorities to release most of the remaining
protesters arrested earlier this week in demonstrations outside the
World Bank and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``An agreement has been reached and we expect (the jailed
demonstrators) should be released early this evening,'' said Elena
Temple, spokeswoman for Mayor Anthony Williams. The deal covers
approximately 125 protesters still in jail here.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those in jail have declined on principle to tell
authorities their real names, identifying themselves only by
monikers such as ``defender'' or ``chalice.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement worked out between the protesters'
lawyers _ the Midnight Special Law Collective _ the protesters
themselves and lawyers for the District of Columbia, demonstrators
would plead guilty to minor violations. Natalie Sperry, a paralegal
with the Midnight Special legal team, said the charges were
comparable to ``jaywalking.''
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators would pay a $5 flat fee and would be free to go,
Sperry said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, however, would not cover about 25 other demonstrators
facing more serious charges. Among these are individuals arrested
last week for possession of ``implements of crime`` such as PVC
pipes, heavy chains, bolt cutters, gas masks, and rolls of chicken
wire and duct tape. Individuals in this category would still face
federal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in jail is Joan Norman, 66, of Sunnyvale, Calif., a
long-time activist who marched for civil rights in Selma, Ala. in
1965 along with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people with lacerated heads, (and people who were
exposed to) lots of pepper spray, lots of teargas,'' she told her
companion, Bob Youden, 73, of Sunnyvale, who taped the telephone
conversation and played it back for a reporter. ``There are people
with broken ribs and this is not getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the recording, Norman blamed the mistreatment on the U.S.
Marshals Service, which transports prisoners here and guards them
in court.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dillard, the U.S. Marshal for the District of Columbia, did
not return a phone call seeking comment. ``Thus far we've had no
formal complaints lodged here,'' said Mavis Dezulovich, a
spokeswoman at the Marshals' national office in the Northern
Virginia suburbs of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators converged on Washington with the aim of disrupting
the spring meetings of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund. Protesters rallied for a laundry list of aims
involving world trade and the environment, but the crux was a
demand that the institutions freeze debt collection from
underdeveloped nations.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,300 were arrested, mostly for acts of civil disobedience
in front the World Bank and IMF headquarters buildings where the
meetings were taking place. The vast majority of these were
released on bond or their own recognizance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
