<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-EASTER-PASSOVER-HNS &LR;      04-21 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-PASSOVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RECONCILIATION IN THE PASSOVER-EASTER SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN P. SCHLEGEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Celebrations of Passover and Easter coincide
this weekend, as they frequently do. Yet something is different;
for many Catholics and Jews, there is a new awareness of each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when Pope John Paul II asked for forgiveness of sins
committed by Catholics across the last two millennia, he included
Jews and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   That confession, followed by the papal visit to the Holy Land _
to Israel, the Palestinian territories and Jordan _ spoke
eloquently to a collective hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   And as John Paul prayed at Yad Vashem, the Holocaust memorial in
Jerusalem, he illustrated a major theme of his long years as pope:
building healthy relations between Catholics and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   This is a hopeful start to a much-desired journey.
</P>
<P>
   In the high holidays of both religions, we find symbols and
themes that motivate people of faith to look towards the future
with hope.
</P>
<P>
   And these messages come at a time when many are bored with the
national political scene, tired of the victim culture, concerned
about the new intolerance among us and weary of unsolved social
problems from education to homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   It is in such an age as ours that the timeless and hope-filled
messages of Passover and Easter should resonate.
</P>
<P>
   On Passover, Jews commemorate the exodus from Egypt; on Good
Friday and Easter Sunday, Christians commemorate the death and
celebrate the resurrection of Jesus. These are central moments in
each of our histories. They speak of the hope for continuing
redemption and the coming of the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Passover is a celebration of freedom and new opportunities. It
commemorates the deliverance of the Israelites from Egypt. It is
the charter event of Jewish history, the striking proof of God's
intervention on behalf of his people, and the foundation of their
hope that he would one day do so again.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, the mystery of redemption is a mosaic of saving
events. While all pieces are important, Easter, not Good Friday,
holds the center. A healthy Christian faith affirms and celebrates
life. While recognizing the place of suffering and death,
Christians should be animated by joy and hope.
</P>
<P>
   When understood this way, these celebrations compel us to
confront life in the face of the great commandment of love, to look
into the faces of the victims of prejudice, abuse and harassment.
</P>
<P>
   They compel us to adopt the spirit of the prophet Isaiah to
bring good news to the homeless, the alienated and the marginalized
(and those on death row); to release the captives of poverty,
discrimination and drug dependency; to restore sight to the blind
and give comfort to those living with HIV, AIDS, or breast cancer,
and to lead to freedom those oppressed by racism, ignorance and
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the celebrations in the Jewish and Christian calendars,
Easter and Passover hold the power to make a difference. Faith
empowers the believer to make a difference just as hope motivates
such actions.
</P>
<P>
   As the Jews of old fled the Egyptian armies, they hoped for help
from their God of the covenant, and the Red Sea divided. As the
followers of Jesus wept at his death, they hoped it was not the end
of the story, and the resurrection occurred.
</P>
<P>
   So today, to women and men of hope, God can do great things, can
empower the faithful to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   When this hope is energized, one's personal celebrations take on
a public significance. These holiday rituals unite individuals with
their respective faith community and urge them to go beyond the
security of our front door, synagogue or church to the communities
and neighborhoods in need of Easter hope and Passover renewal.
</P>
<P>
   These were my thoughts as I shared the Seder meal with Jewish
friends and they'll be with me as I celebrate Easter Sunday Mass.
These are sentiments rooted in John Paul's efforts of
reconciliation between Catholics and Jews and so many other groups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   John P. Schlegel is a Jesuit priest. For nine years the
president of the University of San Francisco, Rev. Schlegel will
leave this summer to become president of Creighton University in
Omaha, Neb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
