<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, April 22. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Hank Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-ARMS (Moscow) _ In a display of unity that seeks to
put the United States on the diplomatic defensive, the Russian
Parliament on Friday handed President-elect Vladimir Putin his
third overwhelming vote in a week endorsing a major arms control
accord. At the same time, Russia's military and civilian leaders
warned of a serious confrontation and a resumption of the nuclear
arms race should Washington go ahead with plans to build a national
antimissile defense shield in violation of the 1972 treaty that
prohibits the development or deployment of such defenses. By
Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Fast running out of options, Attorney
General Janet Reno awaited word Friday from her law enforcement
agents in Miami on the best time for them to remove Elian Gonzalez
from his Florida relatives. But she could not give even his father
a timetable for their reunion. While Reno clung to hope for a
last-minute negotiated turnover, she held a surprisingly short,
15-minute meeting at the Justice Department with Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, father of the 6-year-old Cuban boy whom Miami relatives
have refused to relinquish. ``I assured him that I would continue
working toward the goal of reuniting him with his child, but I also
told him that I could not commit to a particular course of action
or timetable,'' Reno said. Justice Department officials said that
key federal marshals and immigration agents were being positioned
in Miami outside the home of Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
(Summary from wires). By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-THERAPY (Undated) _ Now people are even turning to the
Internet for counseling: They plug in a credit card number and
begin engaging in e-mail counseling with a psychologist or other
therapist. To the excitement, and alarm, of experts in the field,
new mental-health sites are beginning to pop up on the Web almost
daily, and many are offering the type of counseling once offered
only in the intimacy of a psychiatrist's office. By Ellen Almer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CASINO (Undated) _ Recent developments in the move toward
casino gambling in New York state. By Charles V. Bagli.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CONSERVATIVES (Washington) _ In an extraordinary retreat
from traditional Republican tenets, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
has in recent weeks advocated an expansion of the federal role on
programs ranging from education to low-income housing to health
care. And he has made overtures to constituencies, like gays and
gun-control proponents, that have never been mainstays of his own
party. Yet what is most striking about Bush's repositioning in the
nine weeks since the South Carolina primary, when he presented
himself as an unflinching conservative, is that prominent fiscal
and social conservatives _ many of whom have been outspoken about
past nominees _ have been silent. Not one leading conservative
organization has aggressively spoken out against Bush. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
