<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WATER-WAR22-COX     04-21 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-WAR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Negotiators in the rancorous water war between
Georgia, Alabama and Florida should seek a mediator to help them
iron out differences that have stalled the talks for more than two
years, a federal representative said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Thomas, President Clinton's appointee to the group
negotiating the water dispute, said gaping differences still
remaining indicate that the states are unlikely to come to an
understanding without mediation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion, based on what I heard from this committee today,
is that I don't think you will ever get an agreement,'' Thomas told
negotiators meeting in Atlanta Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly urge you to consider a mediator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The states have little more than a week remaining to meet a
self-imposed May 1 deadline for a settlement. Negotiators indicated
Friday they were receptive to extending the talks beyond the
deadline and bringing in a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   But final decisions on both those points, they said, will have
to come from the governors of the three states at two other
meetings scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's session produced heated exchanges among the
arbitrators, but made no progress in developing a formula to share
the waters of the Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint river basin. A
similar session in Montgomery on Thursday also failed to make
headway in allocating the waters of the Alabama-Coosa-Tallapoosa
river basin.
</P>
<P>
   If the states fail to extend the deadline for reaching a
settlement in their 10-year squabble, the two interstate water
compacts under which they are conducting the talks will dissolve,
and the bitter feud likely will be tossed into the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who represents the interest of more than 10 federal
agencies at the negotiating table, said there is still hope for a
settlement if an outside mediator can help negotiators resolve
remaining issues.
</P>
<P>
   One such issue, he noted, is insufficient information about
agricultural irrigation practices in southwest Georgia, which could
affect the flow of the Flint River and the entire ACF basin.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said environmentalists, city and county governments and
citizens who rely on the rivers for drinking water and recreation
need resolution of the long-running conflict.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's session, Alabama negotiator Richard Hanan said a
proposal his state placed on the table Feb. 23 for an ACF agreement
was his state's final offer. Georgia's chief negotiator Bob Kerr,
saying that proposal would take too much water from Georgia,
rejected the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Hanan, however, asked Kerr and his staff to look at the numbers
in the proposal and explain why Georgia would not accept them. Kerr
agreed, but also asked Hanan and his staff to explain how Alabama
would be harmed if Georgia rejects their offer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, negotiators for all three states say that instead of
the originally proposed 50-year agreements, they might lean toward
short-term agreements of 10 or 15 years in the ACF and the ACT.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and Alabama want enough water to fuel projected growth
through the next 30 to 50 years. Florida wants adequate water to
protect its thriving oyster industry in Apalachicola Bay, where the
Chattahoochee's waters flow into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Several observers of Friday's meeting pleaded with the
negotiators to keep the water squabble out of the courts. Fred
Aiken, representative of U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., said a court
battle would be expensive and drag the issue out for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes to court, whatever decision is rendered will be
unsatisfactory for all concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1841EDT &QL; 
