<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3728 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-FICTION23-COX     04-21 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FICTION23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's new in fiction
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anil's Ghost. By Michael Ondaatje. Knopf. $25. Ondaatje's first
novel since ``The English Patient'' is set in modern-day Sri Lanka,
where a ferocious ethnic war between Buddhists and Hindus has torn
the island apart. Poet-writer Ondaatje, who lives in Toronto, was
born in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   MotherKind. By Jayne Anne Phillips. Knopf. $24. Phillips, the
highly regarded author of ``Shelter'' (1994) and ``Machine Dreams''
(1984), returns with the story of Kate, whose care for her
terminally ill mother coincides with the birth of her first child
and the early months of a young marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Deus Lo Volt! By Evan S. Connell. Basic Books. $30. The crusades
of the late 11th through early 13th centuries are the subjects of
this semidocumentary novel, Connell's first since ``The Alchemist's
Journal'' in 1991. Beginning with ``Son of the Morning Star''
(1984), a ``nonfictional history'' of Custer's Last Stand, Connell
has claimed the high ground in historical fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The Binding Chair, Or a Visit From the Foot Emancipation
Society. By Kathryn Harrison. Random House. $24.95. Unfortunately
best known for 1997's ``The Kiss,'' her memoir of incest, Harrison
tells the story of beautiful May, who escapes an arranged marriage
in rural 19th-century China for life in Shanghai with a
soft-hearted Jewish idealist.
</P>
<P>
   M A Y
</P>
<P>
   The Toughest Indian in the World. By Sherman Alexie.
Grove/Atlantic. $24. In his first short story collection since
``The Lone Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven'' (the basis for
the film ``Smoke Signals''), Alexie flexes his writing muscle with
his trademark wry wit and wild plots.
</P>
<P>
   Gone for Soldiers: A Novel of the Mexican War. By Jeff Shaara.
Ballantine. $26.95. After two successful novels of the Civil War,
``Gods and Generals'' (1996) and ``The Last Full Measure'' (1998),
Shaara marches onto an earlier battleground, the Mexican-American
War, where then-Capt. Robert E. Lee learns the mysteries of
command.
</P>
<P>
   Pastoralia. By George Saunders. Putnam. $22.95. Saunders' debut
short story collection, ``CivilWarLand in Bad Decline,'' was a
finalist for the 1996 PEN/Hemingway Award and a New York Times
Notable Book. The stories in ``Pastoralia'' are equally inventive
and offbeat, beginning with a Gothic morality tale in which a male
exotic dancer is haunted by his dead maiden aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Half a Heart. By Rosellen Brown. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24. A
former civil rights activist, Miriam Vener feels trapped in her
upper-middle-class life in 1980s Houston. That life shatters with
the appearance of Miriam's 18-year-old daughter, born of a
passionate affair with a brilliant black professor at a Mississippi
college.
</P>
<P>
   Eating Naked: Stories. By Stephen Dobyns. Holt. $23. Dobyns, a
prolific poet and writer of mysteries and thrillers (``The Church
of Dead Girls,'' ``Boy in the Water''), tries his hand at short
stories. Expect the unexpected: A driver hits and kills a deer, a
gas meter reader falls down basement stairs, a panhandler is
mistaken for a robber and a 700-pound pig falls on a poet crossing
the street against the light.
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Range. By Mary McGarry Morris. Viking. $24.95. The author
of ``Songs in Ordinary Time'' and ``A Dangerous Woman'' tells the
story of 30-year-old Fiona Range, a smart, beautiful woman haunted
by the poor choices of her past.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-Sister Radio. By Chris Bohjalian. Crown. $24. Allison, an
elementary school teacher in Vermont, takes a film class and falls
in love with Dana, her professor. Dana feels the same way about
Allison, but when he reveals his plans to undergo a sex change
operation, Allison is tormented with questions. It's a gender
bender from one of Oprah Winfrey's twice-anointed authors
(``Midwives,'' ``The Law of Similars'').
</P>
<P>
   J U N E
</P>
<P>
   Portrait of an Artist, as an Old Man. By Joseph Heller. Simon &AMP;
Schuster. $23. Heller, whose best seller ``Catch-22'' made him a
literary icon, finished this novel just before his death last
December. Ironically enough, it is the last novel by a great author
about a great author writing his last novel.
</P>
<P>
   The Angel on the Roof: Stories. By Russell Banks. HarperCollins.
$27.50. ``To write well, you need an angel on the roof of the house
where you live and work _ a muse that allows you to be smarter,
more truthful and inspired,'' Banks writes. This collection
includes 22 of the 60-year-old author's favorite stories, written
when he was 30 to 40, and nine new ones.
</P>
<P>
   The River King. By Alice Hoffman. Putnam. $23.95. For more than
a century, the small town of Haddan, Mass., has been divided _
between those born and bred in the village and those who attend the
prestigious Haddan School. But one October night the two worlds are
thrust together because of an inexplicable death.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming Madame Mao. By Anchee Min. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25.
Madame Mao, a major instigator of the Cultural Revolution in China,
is the central, complex character in Min's second novel.
</P>
<P>
   In the Name of Salome. By Julia Alvarez. Algonquin. $23.95. The
author of ``How the Garcia Girls Lost Their Accents'' (1991) and
``In the Time of the Butterflies'' (1994) celebrates one of the
heroes of her native Dominican Republic in her new novel. Born in
1850, Salome Urena de Henriquez was a renowned poet and political
activist.
</P>
<P>
   Asleep. By Banana Yoshimoto. Grover/Atlantic. $21. The popular
Japanese author spins the stories of three women: One, mourning a
lost lover, sleepwalks at night. Another, who is having a
relationship with a man whose wife is in a coma, is suddenly unable
to stay awake. A third finds her sleep haunted by a woman whom she
was once pitted against in a love triangle.
</P>
<P>
   The Married Man. By Edmund White. Knopf. $25. Austin, an
American furniture scholar living in Paris, is lonely and pushing
50. One day at the gym he meets Julien, a French architect, who is
much younger _ and married.
</P>
<P>
   Liar's Game. By Eric Jerome Dickey. Dutton. $23.95. Running from
a bad relationship, New Yorker Dana Ann Smith moves to Los Angeles
to start over. When she meets strong, silent Vincent Calvary Browne
Jr., he seems like a dream come true, but he has some secrets.
</P>
<P>
   J U L Y
</P>
<P>
   Not a Day Goes By. By E. Lynn Harris. Doubleday. $23.95. A hunky
former football player and a rising Broadway star meet, fall in
love and plan a lavish wedding. But fate intervenes.
</P>
<P>
   Shock. By Robin Cook. Putnam. $24.95. Two graduate students
become egg donors to help infertile couples _ and to earn a little
money _ but soon stumble across some frightening realities at the
crossroads of technology and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Omerta. By Mario Puzo. Random House. $25.95. The third of the
mafia trilogy begun with ``The Godfather'' and ``The Last Don,''
this crime fairy tale was Puzo's last work; he died last summer.
</P>
<P>
   P A G E T U R N E R S
</P>
<P>
   At End of Day by George V. Higgins (Harcourt Brace, May).
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion of Malice by Barbara Parker (Dutton, May).
</P>
<P>
   Cradle and All by James Patterson (Little, Brown &AMP; Co., May).
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich by Howard Fast (Harcourt Brace, May).
</P>
<P>
   The Empty Chair by Jeffery Deaver (Simon &AMP; Schuster, May).
</P>
<P>
   On Ice by David Ramus, set in the rarefied world of super-rich
Southern horse breeders (Pocket Books, June).
</P>
<P>
   The Search by Iris Johansen (Bantam, June).
</P>
<P>
   Middle of Nowhere by Ridley Pearson (Hyperion, June).
</P>
<P>
   The House on Hope Street by Danielle Steel (Delacorte, June).
</P>
<P>
   Lethal Seduction by Jackie Collins (Simon &AMP; Schuster, June).
</P>
<P>
   The Last Precinct, a Kay Scarpetta mystery, by Patricia Cornwell
(Putnam, July).
</P>
<P>
   Spytime by William F. Buckley Jr. (Harcourt Brace, July).
</P>
<P>
   Sacred Sins by Nora Roberts (Bantam, July).
</P>
<P>
   Hot Six by Janet Evanovich (St. Martin's, July).
</P>
<P>
   Magic Terror: 7 Tales by Peter Straub (Random House, July).
</P>
<P>
   Murder at Foggy Bottom by Margaret Truman (Random House, July).
</P>
<P>
   Riptide by Catherine Coulter (Putnam, August).
</P>
<P>
   The Bear and the Dragon by Tom Clancy, featuring President Jack
Ryan (Putnam, August).
</P>
<P>
   _ Teresa K. Weaver
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
