<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3730 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-LANCE23-COX     04-21 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LANCE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong's amazing ride
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could have forgiven Lance Armstrong if he had chosen a
different, more dramatic title for his book _ something like
``Miracle on the Champs Elysees.''
</P>
<P>
   But that might have put undue emphasis on Armstrong's 1999 Tour
de France win, an accomplishment that put an exclamation point on
an already thrilling and highly improbable tale of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all about the bike, as Armstrong first began to
understand in October 1996, when he was diagnosed with testicular
cancer, which soon spread to his lungs and brain. Only three months
earlier, the 25-year-old had entered the 1996 Summer Olympics (his
second) as one of the world's top-ranked cyclists. Many even
considered him the logical successor to Greg LeMond, the only
American ever to win the incredibly grueling and prestigious Tour
de France.
</P>
<P>
   Quicker than a cyclist takes a spill, however, Armstrong's focus
changed _ to staying alive, and ultimately, discovering new joy in
life.
</P>
<P>
   This book is about the bike and the perfect, storybook ending of
Armstrong's tour victory. It's also an Everyman's tale of beating
back cancer while finding inner strength and reveling in the love
of family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It's Not About the Bike: My Journey Back to Life. By Lance
Armstrong with Sally Jenkins. Putnam. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3731 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-NONFICTION23-CO     04-21 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NONFICTION23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's new in nonfiction
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Search of Moby Dick: The Quest for the White Whale. By Tim
Severin. Basic. $24. Adventurer and writer Severin (``In Search of
Genghis Khan'') has made a career out of replicating the journeys
of earlier travelers, both fictional and real. Here, he journeys to
the Marquesas Archipelago, where Herman Melville began assembling
the stories that inspired ``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   M A Y
</P>
<P>
   One Day in September. By Simon Reeve. Arcade. $25.95. At the
1972 Munich Olympics, terrorists invaded the Olympic village and
took 11 Israeli athletes hostage. This is a companion volume to the
Academy Award-winning documentary of the same name about that
shattering event, told by those who were there.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Phenomenon: The Seven Secrets to the Enduring Wealth
of a People. By Steven Silbiger. Longstreet. $24. With a nod to the
best-selling ``The Millionaire Next Door,'' Silbiger reveals why
Jews have achieved success in the business and professional world
in such great numbers _ and how anyone can do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Astonishing Elephant. By Shana Alexander. Random House.
$25.95. As a staff writer at Life magazine in the early 1960s,
Alexander chronicled a zoo elephant's pregnancy. Her fascination
with the majestic pachyderm has remained, inspiring this cultural
and historical tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Bobos in Paradise: The New Upper Class and How They Got There.
By David Brooks. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25. The bourgeoisie and
bohemians might seem strange bedfellows, but they've been sleeping
together for years, crossbreeding the counterculture of the '60s
with the capitalistic zeal of the '80s. Don Henley may have summed
it up best in his 1984 hit ``The Boys of Summer'': ``Out on the
road today, I saw a Deadhead sticker on a Cadillac.''
</P>
<P>
   Dark Midnight When I Rise: The Story of the Jubilee Singers Who
Introduced the World to the Music of Black America. By Andrew Ward.
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $27. Ward tells the tale of a group of
former slaves who introduced their music to U.S. and European
audiences in a bid to raise money for Fisk University. Known as the
Jubilee Singers, they performed for Queen Victoria and other
European royals and endured abuse and segregation in America _ but
they saved their school.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney: The Story of a City. By Geoffrey Moorhouse. Harcourt
Brace. $25. From the arrival of the first load of convicts in 1788,
to the 2000 Summer Olympics, Australia's coastal jewel makes a
fascinating subject. Conde Nast Traveler says, ``Moorhouse knows
Sydney well, and his sharp and intelligent observations are a
pleasure to read in this affectionate portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   The Unwanted Gaze: The Destruction of Privacy in America. By
Jeffrey Rosen. Random House. $24.95. These days just about everyone
knows too much about everyone else's business _ and the government
knows it all. Rosen looks at how and why we lost our privacy.
</P>
<P>
   A Viking Voyage: In Which an Unlikely Crew of Adventurers
Attempts an Epic Journey to the New World. By W. Hodding Carter.
Ballantine. $25. Carter and his cohorts take on the challenge of
re-creating explorer Leif Ericson's 11th-century voyage from
Greenland to North America in an open-decked wooden ship.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual War: Kosovo and Beyond. By Michael Ignatieff. Holt. $23.
Today's warfare is high-tech, low-risk and seems somehow divorced
from bloody reality. Ignatieff writes that the 1999 bombings in the
former Yugoslavia ``aroused emotions in the intense but shallow way
that sports do.'' His book examines what that means for the future
of warfare.
</P>
<P>
   What I Think I Did: A Season of Survival in Two Acts. By Larry
Woiwode. Basic. $25. A memoir from the author of ``Beyond the
Bedroom Wall'' that Thomas McGuane calls a ``stylish, brilliant
self-examination.''
</P>
<P>
   J U N E
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing Voices: The Extinction of the World's Languages. By
Daniel Nettle and Suzanne Romaine. Oxford. $27.50. Many human
languages die every year, taking cultures with them. Nettle and
Romaine tie this to environmental issues as part of a worldwide
trend toward ecological destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Circus Fire: A True Story. By Stewart O'Nan. Doubleday.
$24.95. In July 1944, the big top of Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP;
Bailey Circus caught fire in Hartford, Conn., killing 167 people.
O'Nan (``A Prayer for the Dying'') shows us the heroes and villains
of a tragic and terrifying event that still haunts the city. Rick
Bass calls the book ``journalism in the service of literature,
literature in the service of history.''
</P>
<P>
   The Water in Between. By Kevin Patterson. Doubleday. $23.95. A
broken heart sends Patterson into the arms of the sea, sailing for
Tahiti. What begins as a comedic adventure turns serious as the
romance of the sea fades and a four-day gale tests Patterson's
will.
</P>
<P>
   How to Read and Why. By Harold Bloom. Scribner. $25. Bloom
shares his passion for literature and its power to enlighten,
entertain and improve the reader.
</P>
<P>
   Life's Matrix: A Biography of Water. By Philip Ball. Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux. $25. We often take it for granted, but water is
the stuff of life. Ball explores the pervasive substance that is
necessary for our existence _ where it came from, where it exists
and the dangers of a dwindling supply.
</P>
<P>
   J U L Y
</P>
<P>
   In a Sunburned Country. By Bill Bryson. Broadway. $25.
Best-selling author Bryson (``A Walk in the Woods'') travels
through Australia. If his previous humor-filled escapades are any
indication, it was probably not always a g'day for Bryson Down
Under.
</P>
<P>
   The English: A Portrait of a People. By Jeremy Paxman. Overlook.
$29.95. No longer the great empire builders, the English are left
to define themselves in new ways. Paxman probes a people at a
crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Papal Sin: Structures of Deceit. By Garry Wills. Doubleday. $25.
Hot on the heels of John Paul II's sweeping apologies, Wills
ponders the Catholic Church's reticence about admitting past wrongs
and keeping up with social change. Controversy seems sure to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   A U G U S T
</P>
<P>
   The Girl in the Picture: The Story of Kim Phuc, the Photograph,
and the Vietnam War. By Denise Chong. Viking. $24.95. The arresting
image of a young girl fleeing a napalm attack in the waning days of
the Vietnam War won a Pulitzer Prize in 1972. Chong relates that
9-year-old girl's story and describes what Vietnam was like after
American troops departed.
</P>
<P>
   Homophobia: A History. By Byrne Fone. Metropolitan. $35. Fone, a
professor at City University of New York, examines the origins and
history of anti-homosexual prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The Math Gene: Why Everyone Has It, But Most People Don't Use
It. By Keith Devlin. Basic. $27. The always-engaging Devlin
believes that our ability to do math arises from the same
instinctual ability that allowed the development of language. We
should be able to do math as easily as we speak, he insists.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
