<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-RAISINGBOYS23-C     04-21 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RAISINGBOYS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spotlight: Raising boys
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raising young males, with all the special rewards and challenges
that entails, is a hot topic in publishing. These are a few of the
more intriguing titles coming up:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boys Into Men: Raising Our African American Teenage Sons. By
Nancy Boyd-Franklin and A.J. Franklin (Dutton, $23.95). The
husband-and-wife psychologists, parents themselves, offer tips on
how to discipline a child, monitor education and recognize
substance-abuse problems or gang involvement, as well as find a
support group and the emotional strength to be a good parent. (May)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Real Boys' Voices. By William S. Pollack (Random House,
$22.95). The clinical psychologist's follow-up to last year's
best-selling ``Real Boys'' lets youngsters speak for themselves
about life's pressures and expectations. It's enlightening,
sometimes frightening, reading. (June)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The War Against Boys. By Christina Hoff Sommers (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $25). The former philosophy professor and author of ``Who
Stole Feminism'' counters the popular idea that girls are society's
greatest victims, arguing that young males' weaknesses are being
aggravated by a widespread ``anti-boy'' prejudice. Boys need love,
guidance and discipline, she writes, but they do not need to be
``rescued'' from their masculinity. (July)
</P>
<P>
   _ Teresa K. Weaver writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
