<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-ROBBINS23-COX     04-21 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ROBBINS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robbins, in fine form
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the thin wedge of an era between George McGovern's fall
and disco's rise, when the '70s were still clinging to what we now
call the '60s, no college student's two-by-fours-on-cinder-blocks
bookshelf was complete without dogeared paperbacks by Carlos
Castaneda, Hunter S. Thompson and Tom Robbins, authors who put the
cult in counterculture with their druggy, wiggy fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 years later, Castaneda is dead, Thompson just recycles
his oldies and might as well be, and Tom Robbins is 63 going on 17.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the author of ``Even Cowgirls Get the Blues'' is
13 years past the threshold for membership in AARP, and in the
autumn of his years has written a new novel that pops like a
dogwood in springtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fierce Invalids Home From Hot Climates'' is, like Robbins'
previous six novels, a cassoulet of wacky folks, rococo plot,
outrageous puns and metaphors (a lie is ``harder to swallow than a
cat fur omelet'') and now-and-Zen philosophizing, all spread with a
tangy glaze of lubriciousness. It will do nothing to dissuade
nose-in-the-air literati who think Robbins is the perfect author
for readers who plan their futures with tarot cards, and it will do
everything to delight those who realize they need a jolt from his
cosmic jumper cables every so often.
</P>
<P>
   Our hero-slash-Robbins-stand-in is Switters, a renegade CIA
agent who's sent to the jungles of Peru to return his grandmother's
dying parrot to the wild. There he encounters a shaman who puts a
curse on Switters so that if his feet ever touch the ground, he
will die, thus confining him to a wheelchair for the remainder of
the novel, with occasional forays on stilts.
</P>
<P>
   While slowing him down somewhat, the curse doesn't dampen
Switters' ardor for the two women in his life: Suzy, his
16-year-old stepsister, whom he aches to seduce, and Sister Domino
Thirry (get it? huh? get it?), a nun in her 40s. Both are slightly
impure virgins, and wildly inappropriate for him, and yet both
relationships have a certain cockeyed sweetness, once you view the
world through Robbins' kaleidoscope eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Notions of virginity (physical and meta-) tie in to Our Lady of
Fatima's last prophecy, which plays a crucial role in ``Fierce
Invalids,'' as does the importance of laughter in quantum
mechanics, a yacht named the Banality of Evil, the Internet and a
convent of excommunicated nuns in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Among the random bumper-thoughts that Robbins flips his pinball
against is the idea that six attributes separate humans from other
animals: humor, imagination, eroticism, spirituality,
rebelliousness and aesthetics. Robbins has most of them nailed.
Switters, he writes, joined the CIA because it offered ``an
unparalleled world-class opportunity for corrective mischief:
subverting subversion.'' He could be, and probably is, describing
his own career as a novelist.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Fierce Invalids Home From Hot Climates. By Tom Robbins. Bantam.
$27.50. 415 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: All grown up, with plenty of places to go.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer is a television critic for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SHIELDS23-COX     04-21 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SHIELDS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digging for treasure
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would Carol Shields be if not an acclaimed writer? An
archaeologist, perhaps? It's easy to picture her painstakingly
tilling the earth for bits of ancient buildings or crockery and
then lovingly turning these treasures over and over, imagining what
they might have meant to others across time.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Shields the writer works. In her best novels, such as
``Small Ceremonies'' and the 1995 Pulitzer Prize-winning ``The
Stone Diaries'' (where _ excavation alert! _ the female
protagonist's father is a stonecutter), seemingly ordinary objects
take on ever-deepening levels of meaning that continually reveal
themselves through characters or, more often, through Shields'
skillful manipulation of time elements and language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dressing Up for the Carnival'' is a dazzling collection of
small gems with such wholly unremarkable titles as ``Keys,'' ``A
Scarf'' or ``Reportage.'' Each story has a richness of theme and
structure that may not hit the reader until the last sentence has
been read and reread.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in ``Windows,'' what starts out as the seemingly
unemotional tale of a communist era-esque tax on windows gradually
expands into the sensory story of two artists who romantically
reconnect and recharge by painting a glorious fake window atop the
real one they had long ago boarded-up. ``Edith-Esther'' concerns a
comically cranky octogenarian writer whose biographer consistently
misreads big themes in her life, when at the end the only things
that ever really mattered were smaller and obvious mostly to her.
</P>
<P>
   Like most archaeologists, Shields often goes back over the same
ground. Sometimes it's a matter of plot: Four stories in ``Dressing
Up for the Carnival'' are about writers or the tools of writing,
while two feature meteorologists on strike or dismissed from their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   More often the repetition is thematic: the never-ending struggle
to connect with and understand other people, not to mention one's
own self.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Scarf'' tells of a woman who can't quite picture the perfect
scarf until she finds it, and then, almost without realizing it,
gives it away to a friend she's no longer close to. ``We are too
kind, too willing, too unwilling too, reaching out blindly with a
grasping hand but not knowing how to ask for what we don't even
know we want,'' the story concludes.
</P>
<P>
   It's wearying at times trying to keep up with Shields as she
does all this digging. Much better, then, to sample ``Dressing Up
for the Carnival'' two or three stories at a time, and then sit
back and savor _ over and over _ the treasures unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Dressing Up for the Carnival. By Carol Shields. Viking Press.
$23.95. 208 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes about books, politics and pop culture for
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
