<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3735 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SKUBE23-COX     04-21 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Literary respectability, all thanks to Chandler
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was about 11 o'clock in the morning, mid-October, with the
sun not shining and a look of hard wet rain in the clearness of the
foothills. I was wearing my powder blue suit, with dark blue shirt,
tie and display handkerchief, black brogues, black wool socks with
dark blue clocks on them. I was neat, clean, shaved and sober, and
I didn't care who knew it. I was everything the well-dressed
private detective ought to be. I was calling on four million
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   If writers can be identified by their distinctive voice, it
would be hard to mistake the ownership of those words. They are
pure Raymond Chandler. ``The Big Sleep,'' published in 1939, did
more than introduce Chandler and his hero, Philip Marlowe. It
created a tone and a style that have been imitated, emulated and
parodied ever since, but never copied with exact fidelity.
Chandler's style was his own, and he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, when the Library of America series inducted
Chandler into what amounts to a hall of fame of the native tongue,
it was acknowledgment that the detective novel had achieved a
certain respectability. ``A certain,'' Chandler would have sneered.
He was the first mystery writer anointed by the Library of America,
and he would have been suspicious of airs unbecoming to a writer
like himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look back on my own stories,'' he wrote in ``The Simple
Art of Murder,'' ``it would be absurd if I did not wish they had
been better. But if they had been much better they would not have
been published.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler wrote pulp fiction, and he neither apologized for it
nor thought it literary. And yet literary it was _ in the creation
of a believable character and a psychological world, in the cadence
of his sentences, in the concrete images (surely some editor must
have tried to excise that ``wet'' in ``hard wet rain,'' but the
writer in Chandler knew why it should stay).
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Spillane would unashamedly boast, ``I don't have readers;
I got customers.'' But the distinction _ crude in the hands of a
Mickey Spillane _ bothered Chandler more than he cared to admit. He
had been classically educated in England, but in middle age, living
in California, fired from his job as a manager for an oil company,
he knew he was better than a genre that respectable magazines
thought too seedy for their tasteful pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``In view of the fact that I was raised on Latin and Greek and
once wrote essays and book reviews for a very highbrow English
weekly,'' he wrote once to Erle Stanley Gardner, ``the story of how
I became a multiple murderer may have a certain piquancy, but
there's not time to go into it now.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Raymond Chandler had all the time in the world in 1946.
In the same year he called himself ``an out-of-work pulp writer,''
but it was his manner to hint at a question and then wave it away,
as if he couldn't be bothered with it. It was part of his mask of
sardonic indifference. To the contrary, he cared passionately, even
as he discounted the worth of what he was doing:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no `classics' of crime and detection,'' he wrote in
1950. ``Not one. Within its frame of reference, which is the only
way it should be judged, a classic is a piece of writing that
exhausts the possibilities of its form and can hardly be surpassed.
No story or novel of mystery has done that yet. Few have come
close. Which is one of the principal reasons why otherwise
reasonable people continue to assault the citadel.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there have not been many. But Chandler wrote two _
``The Big Sleep'' and ``The Long Goodbye'' _ and perhaps a third,
``Farewell, My Lovely.'' More than that, though, he had broken the
hold of the English mystery _ amateur detectives taking time from
tending their begonias to solve crimes Scotland Yard somehow can't
_ and planted the sturdy roots of a native form.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's mysteries were not puzzles in deduction and logic,
but realistic stories of murder, betrayal, greed and the corruption
of honor. They have been going on forever, which is why Chandler
thought the detective mystery too familiar to claim too much for
itself. But neither was he one to genuflect before the altar of
Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know what the loftiest level of literary achievement
is,'' he wrote. ``Other things being equal, which they never are, a
more powerful theme will provoke a more powerful performance. Yet
some very dull books have been written about God, and some very
fine ones about how to make a living and stay fairly honest. It is
always a matter of who writes the stuff, and what he has in him to
write it with.''
</P>
<P>
   This is another way of saying that whatever else art might be,
it is a powerful feeling for a particular subject and a
recognizable style. Many can have the feeling. It's the style
that's remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
