<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-WOMEN23-COX     04-21 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WOMEN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In praise of friendships
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Between them, they had written 11 books, but never one together.
Best friends for a quarter-century, they had actually only lived in
the same city once. Now they'd be living in the same house to
finish the book.
</P>
<P>
   What sounds like the basis for a wacky TV sitcom is the
real-life story behind ``I Know Just What You Mean'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $25), a new book that turns the spotlight on women's
friendships.
</P>
<P>
   If each is as unique and sustaining in its own way as theirs,
authors Ellen Goodman and Patricia O'Brien contend, that's because
women's friendship in general is special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we women lead lives that go through so many phases,
that friendship may be the one thing you maintain all the way
through,'' Goodman explained recently by telephone from Boston,
where she is an associate editor and Pulitzer Prize-winning
columnist for the Boston Globe. ``You will have times in your life
where you will be single, maybe married and maybe single again. Not
every friendship is going to make it for the long run. But the
really strong ones that go right down to the bone, you can retain
and it will make a tremendous difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting it it off right away as Neiman Fellows at Harvard
University in 1973, Goodman and O'Brien saw each other through
numerous life changes. But even they didn't know how strong their
friendship was until a long walk several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started talking about how much our friendship meant to us,
and then we really started talking about friendship itself,''
recalled O'Brien from Washington, where she is a journalist and
novelist. ``I guess one of us at some point said, `Maybe we ought
to write about that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, neither expected the amount of openness they got from
duos famous (Oprah Winfrey and former TV talk-show host Gayle King)
and less so (Atlanta legal headhunters Melba Hughes and Linda
Sloan-Young).
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say those interviews, in all the time I've been a
journalist, were the most revealing and free of any that I've ever
done,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   To O'Brien, many were taking the same ``walk'' they had.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be asked about your friendship is to be asked about
something absolutely central to women's lives,'' O'Brien said. ``I
think a lot of times women have taken that for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   All those stories are woven into chapters with titles like ``We
Talk, Therefore We Are ... Friends'' and ``Are We Traveling in
Different Directions.'' So, too, is the saga of the Goodman-O'Brien
friendship, something the duo initially resisted doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really easy to talk about (writing) the nice little
Hallmark card type of book,'' Goodman said.``We felt that in order
to talk honestly about friendship, we had to talk honestly about
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant covering the good and the bad, the funny and the
painful. But not dispensing advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't writing a how-to book,'' Goodman said firmly. ``We
were exploring something important we thought hadn't been explored
before.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: www.iknowjustwhatyoumean.com
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
