<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SOUTH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern focus
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   F I C T I O N
</P>
<P>
   One Day in the Life of a Born Again Loser. By Helen Norris.
University of Alabama Press. $24.95. Theron Estes returns home from
a 90-day jail stint to find his two young daughters alone and a
note from his wife: ``I had enuff now it's your turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Total View of Taftly. By Scott Morris. Hill Street Press.
$19.95. In Morris' first novel, Taftly Harper longs for a Total
View of his place in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   The Year of Jubilo. By Howard Bahr. Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $25. From
the author of 1994's ``The Black Flower,'' this is the tragic love
story of Gawain Harper, an infantryman who returns home to
war-ravaged Cumberland, Miss., to find that life will never be the
same. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Jim the Boy. By Tony Earley. Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown. $23.95. Short-story writer Earley's first novel depicts a
rather ordinary year in the life of a 10-year-old boy growing up in
North Carolina during the Depression. (June)
</P>
<P>
   N O N F I C T I O N
</P>
<P>
   No Such Thing as a Bad Day. By Hamilton Jordan. Longstreet
Press. $22. The chief of staff for President Jimmy Carter reflects
on life in politics and beyond, including his successful battles
with three types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody Told Me: The Newspaper Stories of Rick Bragg.
University of Alabama Press. $24.95. This collection showcases what
Bragg does best, turning ordinary situations into extraordinary
stories. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Special Kay: The Wisdom of Terry Kay. Hill Street Press. $18.95.
Essays and commentary on topics ranging from advertising and the
lottery to self-help books and insurance. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Serpent Handlers: Three Families and Their Faith. By Fred
Brown and Jeanne McDonald. John F. Blair Publishers. $19.95. The
husband-and-wife writers use extensive interviews with the
participants to tell the stories of three of the most prominent
snake-handling families in Appalachia. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Hearing a Different Drummer: A Holocaust Survivor's Search for
Identity. By Benjamin Hirsch. Mercer University Press. $24.95.
Hirsch, born in Germany in 1932, survived the Holocaust and served
as a soldier in the Korean War before coming to Atlanta, where he
became a prominent architect. (May)
</P>
<P>
   From Southern Wrongs to Civil Rights: The Memoir of a White
Civil Rights Activist. By Sara Mitchell Parsons. University of
Alabama Press. $24.95. A privileged white girl grows up in
segregated Atlanta. (May)
</P>
<P>
   The Ballad of Little River. By Paul Hemphill. Free Press. $25.
The author of ``Leaving Birmingham'' (1993) investigates the
torching of a black church in a small Alabama town by five white
youths. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Get a Shot of Rhythm and Blues: The Arthur Alexander Story. By
Richard Younger. University of Alabama Press. $18.95 paperback. The
first book-length biography of the soul/country singer whose songs
have been recorded by the Beatles, the Rolling Stones and Bob
Dylan. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Not War but Murder: Cold Harbor 1864. By Ernest B. Furgurson.
Alfred A. Knopf. $27.50. A journalist and descendant of Confederate
soldiers recounts the bloody battle outside Richmond. (May)
</P>
<P>
   Southern Belly: The Ultimate Food Lover's Companion to the
South. By John T. Edge. Hill Street Press. $29.95. The tireless
foodie steers readers to prize eateries throughout the South _ from
Maurice Bessinger's Piggie Park in Columbia, S.C., to the Loveless
Cafe in Nashville. (July)
</P>
<P>
   _ Teresa K. Weaver writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
