r e BC-BOOKS-WILLIE23-COX     04-21 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WILLIE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In memory of Willie Morris
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many elegant eulogies to Willie Morris in
``Remembering Willie'' (University Press of Mississippi, $12), a
collection of tributes from the author's funeral Aug. 5 in Yazoo
City, Miss., as well as appreciations from newspapers and magazines
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   All paint a portrait of a gifted, generous writer who retained a
boyish love of practical jokes. Former Washington Post columnist
Edwin Yoder recalls the author of ``North Toward Home'' telling him
that the man who imported kudzu to the South was living in Oxford,
Miss. When Yoder asked to interview the man, Morris insisted the
poor soul felt so guilty about what he had done that he had become
a recluse. The story, of course, was apocryphal.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' practical jokes belied the serious side of one who loved
the South with all its faults. There are many moving passages in
this book, but none as touching as the essay Morris wrote for
Parade about cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been lonely in a cemetery,'' he wrote. ``They are
perfect places to observe the slow changing of the seasons, and to
absorb human history _ the tragedies and anguishes, the violences
and treacheries, and always the guilts and sorrows of vanished
people.''
</P>
<P>
   _Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MUSEUM-SHAPIRO23-COX     04-21 2733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-SHAPIRO23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The High's big-game hunter
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Shapiro is an optimist. But to him life isn't
a bowl of cherries, it's a bottomless pit of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The new director of the High Museum of Art is sitting in his
spacious corner office taking phone calls before the press of
back-to-back meetings begins. A half-full cup of coffee, one of the
many that fuels his energetic pace, is at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   American landscapes and an intimate interior by French artist
Jean-Edouard Vuillard replace the modern canvases that hung there
during Ned Rifkin's tenure. A cluster of small vessels by Atlanta
wood-turner Ed Moulthrop sits atop the desk. A dogeared red address
book containing a careerful of contacts and the red upholstery of
the chairs are exclamation points punctuating the muted modern
decor.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro's cheery demeanor enlivens the room as well, even on the
phone. Good humor notwithstanding, this is business: Each phone
call is a potential exhibition, acquisition, contact.
</P>
<P>
   The acting director of the Wadsworth Atheneum Museum of Art in
Hartford, Conn., is looking for exhibitions to fill a gap. During
their conversation, Shapiro, 50, learns about shows on the museum's
roster that interest him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trade of information that might lead to something,''
explains the director, whose Brooks Brothers dignity balances an
impish face.
</P>
<P>
   Executive assistant Amanda Kingery pops her head in the door.
Robin Vousden, director of London's prestigious Anthony d'Offay
Gallery, is on the line. He and Shapiro make plans to fly to the
south of France to visit the studio of renowned German artist
Anselm Kiefer to scout for paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Later, curator David Brenneman sits down at the table. A dealer
has offered a complete collection of portrait medallions by the
19th-century French sculptor Pierre-Jean David d'Angers. Does the
museum want that many? At what price?
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro barely pauses. What about buying the lot and auctioning
off the ones they don't want? What about getting together a
syndicate of American museums to buy the lot and divide them?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got me thinking,'' Shapiro says.
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't content just to field what comes his way. He likes
to create opportunities. Like the rare loan of Vincent van Gogh's
signature ``The Starry Night'' from the Museum of Modern Art. While
working with MOMA on a series of exhibitions at the High, Shapiro,
then deputy director and chief curator, would bring up his idea for
a small van Gogh show at every opportunity. Persistence pays: It is
coming, along with two others by the Dutch master, in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started laughing when I heard Michael got `Starry Night,'''
says his
</P>
<P>
   older sister Nancy Kosowski, a teacher in Pennsylvania. ``He
used to have a poster of that painting on his wall in his
bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Art was always part of their Manhattan childhood. Their parents
took them to museums regularly, and an uncle, James Shapiro, was a
serious art collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took art classes at the Met,'' Kosowski recalls. ``When you
walked through the entrance, there was a carousel playing a Sousa
march on one side and a Demuth painting on the other. All of us
would go to the merry-go-round. He'd look at the Demuth.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosowski remembers always waiting for her brother when the
family went to museums. ``We went to the Accademia in Venice, and
my mother and I finished in a normal person's amount of time. We
watched the gondolas, got a cup of cappuccino. Michael came out 1
1/2 hours later.''
</P>
<P>
   The young connoisseur's interests deepened over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, I was curious about how works of art stimulated my
mind to make associations,'' he says. ``In a painting, say of a
portrait, I thought, `Who was the subject? Why did the artist
choose to paint that person? What was their relationship?' Later my
academic training in art history allowed me to explore those types
of questions in depth and prompted me to formulate my own responses
in articles, books and exhibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   After college, he began to buy inexpensive works of art that
bespoke catholic interests. A print by pop artist Tom Wesselmann.
An Imogen Cunningham photograph. A 19th-century French drawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has what great museum directors have: a real passion
about art,'' says Emily Rauch Pulitzer, a trustee of the Saint
Louis Art Museum, where Shapiro was curator from 1984 to 1992.
``Everything pulls directors away from it _ the budget, education,
the PR, the social. But the ones who are really great don't lose
their focus on the art.''
</P>
<P>
   A young sleuth
</P>
<P>
   As a budding scholar during undergraduate years at Hamilton
College in upstate New York, Shapiro researched two family
paintings inherited from his grandparents. On a hunch that the
painting of a lute player attributed to 17th-century Dutch artist
Gerrit van Honthorst was really by Hendrick Terbrugghen, a peer, he
had his mother X-ray and clean it, which uncovered a figure that
had been painted over. He wrote to the author of Terbrugghen's
catalogue raisonne _ the document of his complete works _ in
England, inviting him to examine the painting.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro describes the painting, mimicking the musician's pose,
replete with mouth open in an ``O'' to sing. He plays the eccentric
scholar, standing in front of the painting hung over the sofa,
exclaiming, ``It's the hand of the master!''
</P>
<P>
   He had less luck with a painting his grandparents had thought
was a Whistler. The Terbrugghen was sold. The non-Whistler hangs in
his home.
</P>
<P>
   While a college student, Shapiro also tried to advise his mother
on art purchases, encouraging her, to no avail, to buy a Jackson
Pollock. He had more success with acquisitions at the Saint Louis
Art Museum. Although he has a reputation as a scholar and is
remembered for exhibitions of 19th-century American artists George
Caleb Bingham and Frederic Remington, building the museum's
collection is, according to Pulitzer, Shapiro's greatest legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was willing to take risks,'' Pulitzer says, ``and he
acquired extraordinary works of art. The museum has great holdings
of Max Beckmann and the German expressionists. He extended German
art into the second half of the 20th century and made the
collection of national and international significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro bought works by Gerhard Richter, an internationally
known artist who works in both abstraction and photo-realism, and
neo-expressionist Anselm Kiefer, including a sculpture of lead and
glass shards weighing 15,000 pounds that required reinforcing the
floor and raising the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro also raised the funds. When no single donor came forth,
he formed a syndicate to pool smaller donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good fund-raiser,'' Pulitzer says. ``That takes
commitment, no fear of rejection and an ability to communicate your
passion effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro is generally enthusiastic. ``Fantastic'' is a favorite
word. But he gets a special glint in his eye when he talks about
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to go to galleries to test my radar for important
paintings,'' he says. ``I used to do that at the Whitney
Biennial.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1974 biennial inspired him to buy a figurative Pat Steir
painting and a watercolor that he gave to the High last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acquiring art is like big-game hunting,'' he explains. ``Fun,
challenging and stimulating but also serious. It requires judgment,
intuition and a leap of faith. There's risk, drama, excitement.
Lisa (his wife of 22 years) tells me acquisitions get me going.''
</P>
<P>
   He recently visited the Robert Motherwell Foundation in New
York, which sells paintings by the late abstract expressionist to
museums at a discount, to talk about the type of paintings that
would ``make a difference'' at the High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw two `A' pictures, and that's what we want,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``An `A' painting should stop you in your tracks. It should
elicit a response like, `Wow! I didn't know that was here!' We want
to amaze our public with our ability to acquire great works of art
for their collection.''
</P>
<P>
   `The staff adores him'
</P>
<P>
   The curators love his reach-for-the-sky boldness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes anything is possible,'' says Brenneman. ``He
encourages us to set our sights very high. That results in great
things. We are organizing a Degas show,'' he says with a bit of
wonderment about the bluest-chip artist for which the High has ever
organized a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff adores him,'' says Rhonda Matheison, director of
finance and operations. ``They'll do anything because they know
he'll work just as hard to get it done. He makes you think out of
the box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a fan. He challenges everybody. When Ned
left, we didn't miss a beat. In fact, we've picked up a few beats.
Every time you think you're going to slow down, he's got you going,
and we all love it. If he's not coming up with a new idea, we're
saying, `What's happening?'''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro shows no signs of abandoning the personal, informal
approach he established while deputy director.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll go off for a cup a coffee and come back an hour and half
later from visiting everyone,'' executive assistant Kingery says.
``And Michael is a funny guy. You hear bursts of laughter coming
from his office.''
</P>
<P>
   After the blockbuster ``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by
European Museums'' exhibition closed in May, he organized an
Oscar-type ceremony that honored the museum team, from security
guards to curators. The recipients still have their trophies and
refrigerator magnets on their desks.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro may have to apply his charm toward mending fences with
local artists, galleries and academics who think relations soured
during Rifkin's eight-year tenure, and by extension, Shapiro's
watch. Some galleries have felt a lack of respect. Some artists
feel ignored. And the early members of the Twentieth Century Art
Society (now known as the Contemporary Art Society) are galled that
the museum reduced the group's programming and intellectual level
to make it more of a fund-raising arm of the museum. These members
of the art community, who did not want to be quoted, would like the
museum, and Shapiro, to be more responsive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to heal some wounds,'' Shapiro says. ``To that
end, I would like to try to get around to more openings and events
and be a good listener. I'd like to come up with effective ways of
working together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any family, there are inevitable pushes and pulls. But we
have so much more in common than what separates us that we should
get together and talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro certainly did well with a personal approach when he and
Renaissance specialist Gary Radke began exploring exhibition
possibilities in Italy last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ignored the conventional wisdom about shopping for
exhibitions there,'' says the Syracuse University professor. ``This
is the land of introductions, but he wanted to knock on doors. When
I protested, he said, `If they want to see us, they will.' Much to
my delight, they wanted to see us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that the Casa Buonarroti (which is lending an
exhibition of Michelangelo drawings in 2001) was waiting to be
asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Radke and Shapiro, who have been friends since they were
research fellows at the National Gallery in Washington in 1979,
mixed business and pleasure during the weeklong trip. They dined at
Radke's favorite Florence trattorias and pondered such questions as
which Renaissance artists would make good dinner partners. Not
Michelangelo, according to Radke: too crabby.
</P>
<P>
   Learning from L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro collects friends like he collects art. Hence, the many
entries in the well-thumbed address book.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was inundated with calls when he was appointed,'' says
former assistant Julia Gomez. ``He knows everyone everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   MOMA director Glenn Lowry is a big admirer. The two met at a
Cezanne seminar at Williams College in Massachusetts in the '70s
and have been friends ever since. Lowry attributes his decision to
attend Harvard, where both received doctorates, to the fact that
Shapiro went there after earning his master of arts at Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an extraordinarily funny, intelligent, warm person,''
Lowry says.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the van Gogh loan, Lowry says, ``We would consider
anything the High asked, but the fact that it was Michael made it
easier to accommodate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowry was among a chorus of museum directors to applaud
Shapiro's appointment. The sentiment was particularly heartfelt,
perhaps, because of the rough time Shapiro had during his 10 months
as director of the Los Angeles County Museum of Art in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Shapiro says he feels he walked into a difficult
situation unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't research the history and status of the museum,'' he
says. ``I thought I was going to a place with a solid economic
base. When I arrived, there had been an economic earthquake, caused
by the riots. The county cut funding. There were layoffs and
program cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper accounts of his resignation, trustees praised his
performance but suggested that he did not have sufficient
administrative experience to deal with the museum's complex fiscal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael was hired to connect with the community and
reinvigorate the curatorial (area), but virtually as soon as he
arrived, we got a bad financial report,'' says trustee Stanley
Grinstein. ``Administration was not his strength. It was his first
director's job. He was the wrong person at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll do a great job in Atlanta. He's in the right
place at the right time. He's truly ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro's memory of the experience sounds like something out of
a Coen brothers' movie. On his first day there, he had to keep away
from the windows because there was a gunman on the plaza, and the
sprinklers went off in the Japanese pavilion during a visit of the
pavilion's patron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `You're not in Kansas anymore.' It was not like
anything I had experienced before or since,'' he recalls,
describing the experience as ``deeply maturing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot about myself, about human dynamics, the
dynamics of change, healthy and unhealthy,'' Shapiro says. ``I
realized the importance of building a solid foundation of trust
with the staff and the board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has seen every awful thing, and he's wiser,'' says Nancy
Nichols of his Los Angeles difficulties. The practice managing
partner at Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, the executive search firm that ran
the High's hunt for director, Nichols is also an old friend. ``I
don't think any crisis would be a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   After resigning from the L.A. museum, Shapiro returned to St.
Louis. He spent two years teaching and writing until Rifkin chose
him as deputy director and chief curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost embarrassed to call,'' the former High director
says from his new job at Houston's Menil Foundation. ``I could as
easily have been his deputy director as the other way around, but I
thought it was such an opportunity for
</P>
<P>
   the High.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here, the contrast was so amazing,'' Shapiro recalls.
``Where nothing could happen in L.A., here everything seemed
possible. People were aspiring to something.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro and his family _ Lisa, who teaches American history at
the Galloway School, Kate, 16, and Nick, 14 _ have embraced
Atlanta. A longtime runner and veteran of the New York Marathon,
Shapiro jogs regularly in Ansley Park, where he lives in a
comfortable home filled with art and art books.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys a good meal as much as a good run. The museum
director, who used to whip up dinner in the wok in graduate school,
takes advantage of ethnic cuisine on Buford Highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoy the sense of being a visitor among different
cultures,'' he says. ``Mostly we go to the Panda Inn, but we want
to try them all.''
</P>
<P>
   He celebrated his appointment with his family at Midtown's Pasta
da Pulcinella. The excitement of that moment has not abated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have high hopes for this place,'' he says of the High.
``With Atlanta's energy, ambition and openness, we will do great
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny _ he could as easily be talking about himself.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
