A3749 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-NEW-AMERICA-ANTIGAY-M     04-21 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-ANTIGAY-MILITARY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO END MILITARY'S ``DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL'' POLICY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By CHUCK COLBERT  
 &HT;    Last December, Defense Secretary William Cohen directed the
Office of the Inspector General to survey military personnel
regarding the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy concerning
homosexuals. The policy requires that gay men, lesbians and
bisexuals in the Armed Forces keep silent about their sexual
orientation. They are also not permitted to engage in homosexual
acts.
 &HT;    Cohen requested an ``assessment in order to evaluate the climate
at representative military installations in each service with
regard to our policy on homosexual conduct.''
 &HT;    Cohen's directive came in the wake of the last July's murder of
21-year-old Pvt. Barry Winchell, who was bludgeoned to death at
Fort Campbell, Ky. by fellow service members.
 &HT;    Recently, Cohen released the results of that survey, conducted
at 38 bases and on 11 ships and submarines, from Jan. 24 through
Feb. 11, 2000. The results indicate serious problems in a
pervasively hostile, antigay climate in all four branches of the
Armed Forces.
 &HT;    A whopping 80 percent of the 71,500 service members questioned
reported hearing antigay remarks during 1999. Moreover, 33 percent
said they heard such remarks often or very often. The types of
antigay behavior reported by service members included the
following.
 &HT;    _ Offensive speech: 89 percent
 &HT;    _ Hostile gestures: 35 percent
 &HT;    _ Threats of intimidation: 20 percent
 &HT;    _ Graffiti: 15 percent
 &HT;    _ Physical assault: 9 percent
 &HT;    _ Vandalism of personal property: 8 percent.
 &HT;    The survey also found that junior personnel most frequently
perpetuated the harassment against other junior enlisted service
members. Regardless, 73 percent said that even when senior
personnel witnessed such harassment, they did nothing to stop it.
 &HT;    What is even more alarming is the fact that 37 percent of those
who participated in the survey said they had either witnessed or
seen harassment based on sexual orientation.
 &HT;    Cohen said he was ``surprised at the numbers'' of service
members who had witnessed some form of antigay harassment. ``The
incidents and use of abusive language are more widespread than I
had anticipated,'' he reported to the Houston Chronicle.
 &HT;    The only positive outcome of these disturbing findings is that
after years of denial, Pentagon officials are finally acknowledging
that they have a serious, long-standing problem on their hands.
 &HT;    Why has it taken the military top brass so long to believe that
antigay remarks and harassment abound in the Armed Forces?
 &HT;    For more than six years, the Servicemembers Legal Defense
Network, or SLDN, has been documenting violations in connection
with the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy. Earlier this month, the
network published its sixth annual report, citing 968 incidents of
antigay harassment during the past year, including assaults, death
threats and verbal gay-bashing. They report an increase in
harassment of nearly 150 percent from the previous year's 400
reported incidents.
 &HT;    The Pentagon survey ``simply corroborates what we've been
telling them for the last six years,'' said SLDN co-executive
director Dixon Osborn to the New York Times.
 &HT;    SLDN co-executive director Michelle Benecke told the Houston
Chronicle why harassment has become such a serious problem.
 &HT;    ``Ultimately, the key to stopping harassment and other
violations of 'don't ask, don't tell' violence against gays in the
military is leadership and accountability.'' Benecke said. ``Unless
they take immediate steps, someone else is going to get hurt.''
 &HT;    The policy, which was intended to help gays serve in the Armed
Forces, has proven to be detrimental and demeaning. Thousands of
gay service members have been discharged in recent years.
 &HT;    Prior to and during the implementation of ``don't ask, don't
tell,'' military officials have asserted that the presence of
openly gay service members would undermine morale and unit
cohesion.
 &HT;    Now, with the undeniable results of this survey, Cohen is in the
embarrassing position of having to admit that antigay harassment
itself is what undermines the good order and discipline that is
critical to an effective fighting force.
 &HT;    ``When you have a policy that treats an entire class of people
as second-class citizens, it suggests that you can treat them that
way,'' Osborn told The New York Times.
 &HT;    It is time for the policy to change. The country needs the kind
of policy shift that President Harry Truman initiated when he fully
integrated the military after World War II.
 &HT;    Cohen must advocate for the abolishment of the ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy. He must act now, before another private loses
his or her life to violence at the hands of fellow country men.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert was as a naval officer from 1981-85. He serves on
the board member of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists
Association.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Chuck Colbert 
