<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHYLOCK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHYLOCK': A FRESH LOOK AT A COMPLEX CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does the modern world have a place in it for Shakespeare's
``Merchant of Venice''? The question is raised but not resolved by
a film being shown on TV on Saturday in New York, which inquires
into the life and times of the character whom Shakespeare called
Shylock.
</P>
<P>
   With the memory of millions of murdered Jews burned into the
West's consciousness by the Holocaust, how are audiences supposed
to react to the reappearance on stages of literature's most famous
murderous Jew?
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Lasry's documentary, ``Shylock,'' recalls 2,000 years of
European hatred of the Jew, as Christ-killer, ritual murderer,
usurer, perpetual outsider and all-around object of Christian
detestation.
</P>
<P>
   It is against this background that Shakespeare created a more
complicated image of the malignant Jew (``If you prick us, do we
not bleed?'') that has long unsettled audiences.
</P>
<P>
   In the few scenes in which he appears, the character of Shylock
casts a large, dark shadow on what is otherwise a romantic comedy.
Only when the moneylender demands his pound of flesh does the play
justify its reputation as a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   (If you are looking for Oedipal significance, historians report
that John Shakespeare, William's father, was himself a moneylender;
on the other hand, there weren't enough Jews in Elizabethan England
to account for the practice of usury, and it seems unlikely that
the playwright ever met one.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, Shakespeare's Shylock has been portrayed as
a model of cruelty and as a comic caricature of greed, an avatar of
Old Testament justice set against New Testament mercy and a victim
of a vindictive society.
</P>
<P>
   The program offers scenes from a few of this century's
performances, beginning with a powerful few moments from Orson
Welles' unfinished film version, along with various actors' and
directors' explanations of how they tried to make the character
something more than the monster displayed in the scores of
productions of ``Merchant'' staged during the Nazis' ascendancy.
</P>
<P>
   John Gross, the British critic and author of the illuminating
1992 history, ``Shylock,'' who serves as the film's main guide,
describes 20th-century efforts to humanize Shylock by emphasizing
his better side, like his love for his daughter, and belittling the
behavior of the society that ostracizes him and provokes his lethal
inclinations.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, Gross is not impressed; in the effort to clean up
Shylock's reputation, he finds, postwar versions have strayed from
the text of what, however disquieting, is a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   A lineup of theatrical luminaries has given the role a try in
recent decades, among them Peter O'Toole, George C. Scott, Emlyn
Williams, Michael Redgrave, Dustin Hoffman, and perhaps most
notably Laurence Olivier in a 1970 production, directed by Jonathan
Miller, that gave us a Shylock dressed up as a late Victorian
banker.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's point was that except for his Jewishness Shylock was
like all the other upper-class Venetians, perhaps better, since
they are portrayed as corrupt and coldhearted when they are not
merely ridiculous. (Miller tells his television interviewer that he
now regrets cutting Shylock's opening speech about Antonio _ ``I
hate him for he is a Christian'' _ in an effort to soften the
Shakespearean portrait.)
</P>
<P>
   But in his book Gross dismisses the combination of assimilation
and rejection in the Miller-Olivier version and other efforts to
contrast Shylock's dignity with Venetian foppishness as yielding a
``high degree of incoherence.''
</P>
<P>
   He finds such works typical of a tendency over the past 30 or 40
years to present the play as an exercise in irony, ``which cannot
possibly mean what it appears to say, a play that constantly
subverts its own surface values and throws doubt on the purported
motives of its characters.'' He adds: ``Where the key words were
once `justice' and `mercy', `gold' and `love,' they are now
`skeptical,' `tension,' `discrepancy' `distancing,' and
`demystify.'''
</P>
<P>
   While crediting Shakespeare for equipping Shylock with ``senses,
affections, passions'' that make him a big character ``who bursts
the bounds of the play in which he appears,'' Gross does not smooth
over the fact that Shakespeare himself was bound by centuries-old
vicious Jewish stereotypes with which today's directors continue to
grapple.
</P>
<P>
   Granting Shakespeare's effort ``to imagine, within the confines
of his plot and within the limits that his culture set him, what it
would be like to be a Jew,'' Gross takes a poke at efforts to
invest Shakespeare with Brotherhood Week sentiments. He writes:
``One thing we can be sure of: he was not a secret 20th-century
liberal, animated by programmatic opposition to racial prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   His conclusion, one that theater lovers and Shakespeare lovers
have to live with, is that Shylock ``belongs, inescapably, to the
history of anti-Semitism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
