<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE CORRUPTION OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Twenty years ago this week the country that had been
Rhodesia, ruled by a tiny white minority, became Zimbabwe. After a
brutal civil war, the handover of power was remarkably calm. Units
of the white army and of the black guerrillas marched together in a
stadium. A few hours earlier Robert Mugabe had reassured whites in
a radio address.
</P>
<P>
   ``If yesterday I fought you as an enemy,'' Mugabe said, ``today
you have become a friend and ally with the same national interests,
loyalty, rights and duties as myself. ... Our majority rule could
easily turn into inhuman rule if we oppressed, persecuted or
harassed those of us who do not look or think like the majority of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   How strange, how sad it is to read those words today. For Mugabe
has become what he said he must not be: an oppressor. He has sent
black mobs to occupy white farms and terrorize their owners and
workers. He has called white farmers ``enemies of Zimbabwe.'' He
contemptuously ignores the law.
</P>
<P>
   What has gone wrong? One thing is sure: Mugabe has been in power
too long. After 20 years he is a living exemplar of Lord Acton's
warning, a cliche by now but still so often true: ``Power tends to
corrupt, and absolute power corrupts absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   I first met Robert Mugabe in 1979, during the Rhodesian war, at
his headquarters in Maputo, Mozambique. I was impressed by what
seemed to be his cool, practical rationality. Others saw him as the
best hope for a successful Zimbabwe _ among them Lord Carrington,
the tough-minded British foreign secretary who presided over the
negotiations for a transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
   How wrong we were, at least over time. At first Mugabe's
leadership was impressive. He dramatically improved schools for the
majority. He left a productive economy largely alone, forgetting
his socialist rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   But soon things began to go wrong. A brigade of his army,
trained by North Korean soldiers, abused and murdered thousands of
people in the western part of the country. The population there was
Ndebele-speaking; Mugabe and his followers were mostly Shona.
</P>
<P>
   Then it became clear that the best jobs were going to friends
and relatives of those in power. Mugabe, who had seemed so ascetic,
presided over an increasingly corrupt system.
</P>
<P>
   There were two dangerous consequences. Young people finished
school and could not get work for which they were qualified unless
they knew someone. And the economy ran into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Today Zimbabwe, a country blessed with superb farmland and
mineral resources, is an economic disaster. Unemployment is
estimated at 50 percent. The inflation rate last year was 60
percent. Gasoline and diesel oil are scarce because there is no
foreign exchange to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   The economic distress underlies the occupation of white-owned
farms. They constitute most of the best land in the country, and
there is obviously a good argument that that is unjust. But the way
the issue has been brought to a boil reflects not the moral claim
so much as cynical politics: an effort by President Mugabe to
distract people from his government's appalling record.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and other countries agreed years ago to help buy out
white farmers if the Mugabe government produced a plan to turn the
land over to blacks who could work it effectively. But most of the
land that has been bought has gone not to needy peasant farmers but
to government cronies, unable to use it productively.
</P>
<P>
   With a serious opposition movement mobilizing for the first
time, and elections due next month, Mugabe sent thugs on a rampage
against white farmers and their black workers. He called them ``war
veterans.'' Actually, they are a paid rent-a-mob used otherwise to
break up opposition political meetings.
</P>
<P>
   For most poor Zimbabweans, the real issue is not farmland but
jobs. As in the rest of the world, young people who have gone
through school want urban lives. Their outlook is bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Does Robert Mugabe care? I doubt it. He cares about holding onto
power. The inevitable comparison, one he bitterly resents, is with
Nelson Mandela. President Mandela meant it when he said that South
Africa was for all its people, of whatever race; and he gave up
power. He cared for his country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
