<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RENAULT-SAMSUNG-430&AMP;A     04-21 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENAULT-SAMSUNG-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAULT AGREES TO ACQUIRE SAMSUNG MOTORS OF SOUTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PARIS _ Renault SA, the French automaker, reached an agreement
Friday to acquire the ailing Samsung Motors of South Korea,
concluding its second major acquisition in Asia in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Renault, which last year acquired 37 percent of the troubled
Japanese car maker, Nissan, said last month it hoped the takeover
of Samsung would enable it to challenge the market leader, Hyundai,
by securing 10 percent to 15 percent of the South Korean automobile
market.
</P>
<P>
   Financial details of the Samsung acquisition were not announced,
but Renault is believed to have agreed to pay $340 million to $350
million. Of that price, Renault is expected to pay about $100
million in cash, with the remainder to be paid over a 10-year
period. Renault will also assume about $200 million in Samsung
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition was reached after four months of negotiations
when Samsung's South Korean creditors, led by Hanvit Bank Group,
agreed to settle $262 million in debt that the French car maker had
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest entry by a Western automaker into the
Asian market, which was shaken badly by the economic crisis there
in 1998. Last month, DaimlerChrysler AG agreed to pay $2.1 billion
for a 33 percent stake in Mitsubishi Motors Corp. Over the last two
years, seven of Japan's 11 car makers have linked up in various
degrees with foreign partners. Another South Korean car maker,
Daewoo, is up for sale, and Western car makers, including General
Motors, Ford, DaimlerChrysler and Fiat of Italy, are bidding for
control.
</P>
<P>
   Samsung's principal creditors, who effectively took over the
company last July after it foundered under a debt burden of $3.9
billion, are expected to meet Monday to confirm the acquisition,
which would be sealed in a signing ceremony later next week. A
Renault spokesman said further details of the deal would be
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal had been expected for weeks, after negotiators
gradually narrowed the differences between what Samsung's creditors
wanted and what Renault was willing to pay. But it hit a snag
recently after Renault discovered $262 million in debt that Samsung
Motors owed its parent company, Samsung Corp. By Friday, the price
of Samsung shares had fallen to almost one-quarter of their value
last year, before the debt crisis engulfed the company.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition means Samsung will survive as a company, which
was started with the help of Nissan in 1998 but was essentially
taken over by the banks last year after its debt overtook its
assets by about $1 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Samsung basically consists of the company's factory in Pusan,
which can make 240,000 cars annually, largely using Nissan
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In the final ownership breakdown, Renault will have 70 percent
of Samsung, Samsung Corp. will hold 20 percent and the creditor
banks will hold 10 percent through a debt-for-equity swap.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest entry by a Western automaker into the
Asian market, which was shaken badly by the economic crisis there
in 1998. Last month, DaimlerChrysler AG agreed to pay $2.1 billion
for a 33 percent stake in Mitsubishi Motors Corp. Over the last two
years, seven of Japan's 11 car makers have linked up in various
degrees with foreign partners. Another South Korean automaker,
Daewoo, is up for sale, and Western car makers, including General
Motors, Ford, DaimlerChrysler and Fiat of Italy, are bidding for
control.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the economy in Japan, South Korea's economy has been
mending rapidly. In 1999, about 910,000 new cars were sold there,
and the number is expected to rise to about 1.5 million this year.
But Hyundai and its partners control about 70 percent of the
market, which remains tightly closed to foreign car makers, who
last year sold only about 2,400 cars in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   For Renault, the stake in Nissan should be an asset in resolving
Samsung's problems, given the traditional links between the
Japanese and South Korean companies.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Ghosn, a senior executive of Renault who was named
Nissan's chief operating officer, said last week he expected Nissan
to return to profitability in fiscal 2000, which ends March 31 of
next year. Ghosn, a former executive of Michelin, the French tire
maker, has been subjecting Nissan to a rigorous regime of slashing
purchasing costs, shutting factories and reducing the number of
employees. Renault is expected to apply similar rigorous
cost-cutting methods at Samsung.
</P>
<P>
   Renault, which is 44 percent owned by the French government, has
been using its purchases in Asia to extend the market for its cars,
about 85 percent of which are sold in Europe. It has little
presence in the United States, and until the Nissan acquisition,
virtually none in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Samsung has been wrought with political sensitivity.
The South Korean automobile industry was a powerful symbol of
ambitious South Korean industrialization in recent years, and labor
unions and other critics of the deal with Renault attacked it as a
sellout to foreign interests. But the South Korean government had
no alternative, given the absence of suitors other than Renault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
