<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-CHOREOGRAPHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE WORKSHOP OFFERS CASES OF THE JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Too bad ``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown''
is already the name of a movie. It would have been a fine title for
the Fresh Tracks program on Wednesday night at Dance Theater
Workshop. Jittery women filled all the offerings of this latest
event in a series featuring new choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the jitters held the attention: for instance, the
uncertain steps forward and backward that Monica Bill Barnes took
in ``She's Snapped, She Left,'' a solo in which she appeared to be
trying to survive in the rat race of daily life. And the
deliberately awkward way in which Ivy Baldwin had four women slip
and slide in ``One Flew Sideways'' made this piece a study of
desperate attempts to preserve physical and mental balance.
</P>
<P>
   Several dances emphasized eye-catching costumes or props.
Portraying a woman desperate for attention in ``If I Were a Beauty
Queen,'' Michel Yang posed and preened while trying on various
articles of clothing. Then, apparently realizing that glamour does
not necessarily guarantee peace of mind, she doused herself with
water.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes props were more interesting than movement. In her
``Secret History of Water,'' Tessa Nebrida bathed her feet in a
bowl as if performing a mysterious purification ritual. The women
with apples on their heads in Carmelita Naval's ``Tell'' could have
been William Tell's children, but they moved for no apparent
reason. And ``Coldblooded Was the Bird,'' choreographed by Despina
Stamos and Wen-Shuan Yang, was little more than a display of
objects like a drawing of a rooster, a toy cat on wheels, a serving
dish and a cardboard pitcher paired with a real glass. There were
also a few dance steps _ nervous ones, of course _ to help get the
props in and out.
</P>
<P>
   The program will be repeated on Wednesday night at Dance Theater
Workshop, 219 West 19th Street, Chelsea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOSLEY-DANCE-REVIEW-N     04-21 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSLEY-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOREOGRAPHER BRINGS INTELLIGENCE TO A BARE-BONES PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The production values were simple and the theater a
bare-bones affair. An air of youngsters' getting together to put on
a show hung over ``Lil' This, Lil' That,'' a program presented by
Earl Mosley's Diversity of Dance company on Thursday night at the
Chernuchin Theater. But out of those homemade materials came an
evening of crackling imagination, hilarity and terrific performing.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, a teacher at the Alvin Ailey school, makes dances that
are comfortably rooted in the jazz and modern-dance idioms, though
he has a fondness for the occasional extraneous-looking gesture or
move. He knows how to make his dancers look good. What stands out
most about his work, however, is its fresh intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   In two duets from the new ``Pass It On,'' Mosley suggests
complex relationships through movement alone. Brian Brooks and
Alenka Flanders are the elegantly taut first couple, circling and
passing each other, then fleetingly clinching in odd and unexpected
ways. Laura Rossini and Matthew Rushing are lovers whose moodiness
fills the air with sultry electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young Words,'' a new suite of five solos set to music by
Charlie Coleman, inhabits an entirely different universe. The
dances are preceded by short, vivid poems by five authors, read on
tape. The solos embody rather than illustrate the poems, again
through physical acting made even more vibrant here by Mosley's
sense of theater.
</P>
<P>
   Leonides D. Arpon is an agile, ground-hugging creature with a
flicking tongue in ``Lizard People.'' Djassi Johnson's clawing
bundle of energy picks up its bowl, tilts it back and drinks in
``Cat in the Can.'' Frightened and meditative in turn, Ilana
Shtayer seems impelled by the danger described in her poem in
``Restless.'' Flanders reaches out to a sun that she fears in
``Frozen Tears.'' And Brooks is a vain dancer who gives new meaning
to vamping in ``Red.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Archibald, one of three guest choreographers,
contributed ``Sweet Signs,'' a simple trio for three young women
finding themselves to music by Terrence Blanchard, danced
powerfully by Maya Stewart, Rayven Ramijo and Cari Lynn Orr. Kanji
Segawa was a sleek, earthly angel in Arpon's ``Near My God to
Thee.'' And five men wound through a mysterious ritual in Sharon
Wong's ``Uncommon Dialogue,'' danced to music by Abdullah Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   The program will be repeated through April 30 at the Chernuchin
(314 West 54th Street, Clinton).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
