<HEADLINE>
QUAKE III'S TIMEDEMO FEATURE ACCESSED IN COMMAND CONSOLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a couple of reviews of video cards and computers you've
written, you mention running something called timedemo in Quake III
Arena to test the speed of the card and the computer. How do you do
this? I don't see it in the manual.
</P>
<P>
   A: While id Software makes great games, it doesn't do a very
good job of documenting them. Fortunately, the game community on
the Web takes up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   And actually, this is true of many games. If you are interested
in tweaking any PC game's look and performance, you usually can do
so through a series of arcane commands.
</P>
<P>
   In the games that use id's various Quake engines, the commands
usually are entered by hitting the tilde key, which brings down a
command-line console. From here you can type in the commands. A
good place to find lists of these commands is at PlanetQuake,
www.planetquake.com.
</P>
<P>
   The timedemo feature removes a kind of software governor from
Quake III so that it runs at an unrestricted speed. The only things
slowing the game down are the limitations of your computer's
hardware. Because Quake III Arena requires a fairly powerful
computer and graphics card, it's a good test of a modern PC's
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Before you run it, set the graphics settings in the game. You
can choose any of several pre-set configurations in the setup area,
ranging from Fastest to High Quality. You also can mix and match
settings in a custom configuration.
</P>
<P>
   Next, bring down the console by hitting the tilde key and type
this: /set timedemo 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hit the tilde key again to raise the console. Go to the main
menu of the game and click on Demos, and click on either Demo001 or
Demo002 and click Play.
</P>
<P>
   The demo, which shows a recorded battle, will play very quickly.
When it's done, bring down the console again and you'll see the
average frames-per-second count. You can then tweak the graphics
settings for a good balance of speed and visuals. The more eye
candy you turn on in a game like this, the slower your frame rate
will be.
</P>
<P>
   The timedemo feature also will work in the shareware version of
the game, which you can download for Windows, Macintosh and Linux
computers at www.quake3arena.com/demo/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an older, ISA-based sound card in my computer. I'd
like to replace it with a better one that fits in a PCI slot. What
are the steps in uninstalling and installing sound cards?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's pretty simple, as these things go. Of course, when
adding and removing hardware, simple is relative.
</P>
<P>
   First, you'll uninstall the current drivers. Check in the
Add/Remove Programs module in the Control Panel to see if there is
a listing for the sound card drivers, and if so, use it to remove
them. If not, check for a folder for the card's software in the
Program groups and see if there is an uninstall module in there.
</P>
<P>
   If not, then right-click on My Computer, choose Properties, then
Device Manager. Click on Sound, Video &AMP; Game Controllers, find the
sound card in the list. Click on it and click the Remove button. If
you are asked to restart, say NO. Instead, manually shut down the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Open the case, remove the old card and install the new. Then,
follow the instructions for installing the new card's software.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
