<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THE FAITH
</HEADLINE>
  Exploring the bonds between love and spirituality 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BERNADETTE MURPHY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Books reviewed: ``The Ladies Auxiliary'' by Tova Mirvis &QL; 
(311 pages, Norton; $23.95) &QL; 
``Chosen by God: A Brother's Journey'' by Joshua Hammer &QL; 
(241 pages, Hyperion; $22.95) &QL; 
``Love Is Stronger Than Death: The Mystical Union of Two Souls''by
Cynthia Bourgeault &QL; 
(218 pages, Bell Tower; $21) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
How we view spirituality and religious tenets is a huge factor in
how we see the rest of life. Three newly released books _ a novel
and two works of non-fiction _ explore the shadings of these views,
from the rigid lines of Orthodox Judaism found in closed
communities to the more esoteric, touchy-feeling realm of mystical
Christianity explored via an erotic love story.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the books traverse the road between religion as
an expression of obedience and conformity, an allegiance to things
past _ through to a spiritual realm where faith is never static,
but still evolving and, often, quite vague.
</P>
<P>
   In a compelling first novel by Tova Mirvis, ``The Ladies
Auxiliary'' gives us the Jerusalem of the South: a closed Orthodox
Jewish community in Memphis set in the current day where ``Shalom,
y'all'' might be a typical greeting. The tightly woven group of
women who compose the auxiliary hope to raise their children in the
protected world they've painstakingly created.
</P>
<P>
   When a convert, Batsheva, the widow of a young man originally
from the neighborhood, and the couple's young daughter, Ayala, move
in and try to penetrate the established ranks, all that has been so
carefully constructed comes under fire. As difficulties of the
world-at-large impede on the community, a few wise characters
recognize that ``divorce, drugs, and the rest didn't stay at bay''
because they were religious. Maybe religion was a buffer, but
eventually these things found their way in.
</P>
<P>
   The women of the auxiliary refuse to believe this is the true
nature of things. Rather, they look for someone to blame. Batsheva,
whose unbridled joy in her adopted faith calls attention to itself,
whose creativity in celebrating the holidays makes the other women
look less than perfect, is the obvious scapegoat. Though these
devout women of Memphis have always prided themselves on being part
of the friendliest community possible, their faith in the whole
system of belief begins to crumble as the women close ranks in an
effort to protect their children.
</P>
<P>
   To Mirvis' credit, the book skates a fine and exquisite line,
never degenerating into a finger-pointing rant on either the pros
or cons of strict religious observance. Neither camp is demonized.
Rather, she paints a picture in which there's a little good and a
little bad in everyone.
</P>
<P>
   One can easily identify with the auxiliary women's desire to
protect their children from the outside problems, even as they act
in a spiteful manner. The outsider, Batsheva, though portrayed
initially as someone too good to be true, develops into a full
character with an ``improper'' past, a woman who is trying in her
own halting way to find a new home in an imperfect world.
</P>
<P>
   The truth portrayed in this novel is vast and timeless. Those
very things that are meant to bring people closer to each other _
religion, holidays and communal gatherings _ are often the times in
which we feel more alienated than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Woven into the story in a low-key manner is also the issue of
women's equality, especially when it comes to preparing for
holidays, issues that apply to almost every religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we thought about it, there was no reason why the men
shouldn't help get ready for Pesach; they too had been taken out of
Egypt,'' the women mutter as the chores for Passover pile up. As a
first novelist, Mirvis has a keen eye, a sharp intellect and a
kindness that is uncommon in books dealing with touchy subjects
like religion. In reading this novel, one never gets the sense that
Mirvis is being disrespectful or poking fun, nor that she is toeing
some hard-and-fast line. The heartfelt nature of her story comes
through in every sentence, every struggle, every character. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Taking on the issue of religion and how its practice can cause
separation rather than coherence is the bittersweet memoir ``Chosen
by God: A Brother's Journey'' by Newsweek writer Joshua Hammer. In
this keenly crafted work, Hammer examines his relationship with his
younger brother Tony, who is essentially lost to his family when,
in his early 20s, he enters a closed Hassidic community in upstate
New York. Hammer, like Tony, was raised nominally Jewish and views
his brothers ``embrace of fundamentalism'' as a ``total rejection
of who our family was: secular, liberal agnostics.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially Hammer waits for his brother _ who'd been known to
pick up and drop myriad interests _ to get over it. The years tick
by, and Hammer must finally acknowledge what he has feared. ``I
watch my brother, transfixed,'' he writes of observing his brother
in prayer after a five-year separation, ``repelled by his act of
self-surrender, and amazed at the depth of his emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyelids pressed together, lips pulled back, straining to
concentrate every part of his being on the Creator, the little
brother I grew up with has been transported to a distant place, and
I realize I will never get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of this memoir, in addition to its crisp writing, is
the raw honesty Hammer employs, narrating the conflicted emotions
he feels for his brother. When he decides to re-establish contact
with Tony, for example, Hammer finds he must do so as an objective
journalist in order to skirt ``the full-blooded visceral aversion''
he feels as a brother. ``It was only by approaching him though the
cold eyes of (an author) that I could find a way to repair a rift
and restore a semblance of completeness to my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammer spends a great deal of time with his brother and his
burgeoning family within their closed community in Monsey, follows
the strict tenets of his brother's faith during those visits, and
tries to understand what has become of the easygoing, goofy brother
he once knew. His journey, which never fully restores his brother
to his life, is filled with head-shaking moments. Asking his
brother why he considers certain leaders to be extraordinarily
holy, for instance, Hammer is baffled by his brother's answers.
Tony reveres one man who ``oversalted his food intentionally just
to spoil the taste,'' and another who had never had a haircut
because it required taking off his yarmulke. ``My brother, who once
idolized such people as Al Pacino and Teddy Kennedy, had developed
some odd new role models.'' When Tony makes a huge exception to
allow his children to go ice skating and enjoy a gypsy carnival,
Hammer's description is filled with the commingled joy and pain of
the children's sheltered life and what he sees as his brother's
limited one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed,'' Hammer writes of Tony ``like any father on an
outing with his children as he sent one ring after another spinning
toward the peg board ... It was the first time in 18 years that I
had seen my brother at play.'' Rather than being cold or
disparaging, the work glimmers with love and insight; it is a
reflection of the brother dance that has been enacted for
generations, regardless of religious differences.
</P>
<P>
   In his effort to understand his brother's choices, Hammer comes
to a kind of bruised acceptance, and in some ways, an appreciation
for what his brother has found. When he re-establishes fraternal
ties, Hammer joins Tony in his daily rituals and finds himself
wistfully hoping that he might gain a spark of what his brother
has. Ultimately, he knows that any relationship he builds with Tony
will have to be on Tony's limited terms and sees in the rituals
themselves ``a continual reminder to me of the abyss of perception
that would forever divide us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Something more than perception is the abyss that divides Cynthia
Bourgeault, author of the non-fiction book ``Love Is Stronger Than
Death: The Mystical Union of Two Souls,'' from her beloved, Rafe.
That something is death.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeault, an Episcopal priest, wrote this work to tell the
unconventional love story of her powerful bond with Brother Rafael
Robin, a Catholic monk, with whom she claims to have shared a
mystical, erotic love that has continued to grow and challenge them
both even after his death.
</P>
<P>
   This book takes whatever one believes about the nature of love,
death and static theology and stretches it to its outermost limits.
According to Bourgeault, the path she's sharing with Rafe _ an
active love that continues its dynamism through the opaque curtain
of death _ is largely unrecognized. She suspects that the
invitation to this kind of radical love is frequently declined
because of a ``cultural distrust of erotic love as the true path to
God,'' combined with a ``sloppy theology of death,'' and our
culture's insistence on having ``clear boundaries in
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Is Stronger Than Death'' is filled with great chunks of
theology and esoteric learning, but at its core is the story of how
the two came to recognize each other and why they had been drawn
together, if not as soul-mates (a term Bourgeault doesn't care
for), then as parts of an ``ablersoul,'' which she defines as ``a
relationship marked by a particularly intense conviction of
belonging to a whole that is greater than the sum of its parts. Far
more than a partnership, it is a kinship that is intuitively
recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the esoteric and theological arguments Bourgeault lays
down seem well-documented, it's the story of the relationship
between herself and Rafe when he was still alive that is most
compelling and the least described. As a person with limited
theological training, this reader wished for more love story and
less theology.
</P>
<P>
   That the line between skepticism and belief jumps frequently in
reading this work points to the hazy outlines Bourgeault is trying
to fill in, using theology and philosophy to make solid an
experience that is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Calling upon mystical Christian traditions to bolster her
arguments, she finds models of death-impervious love in the
relationships of Jesus and Mary Magdalene, St. Francis and St.
Clare, people ``whom our hearts instinctively recognize as couples
despite all efforts to spiritualize or explain away their
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the book doesn't move much beyond the conceptual. The
examples from her own life are helpful, but in the long run, too
meager to fully convince. ``Stronger Than Death'' treads the space
where black-and-white leaves off and the enigmatic shades of gray
begin, reminding us of the abstract, intuitive nature of faith and
its opposite, doubt. Prior to Rafe's death, when he was having
trouble understanding and accepting the nature of the relationship,
he told Bourgeault how he came to view their bond: ``I tried to
protect myself by giving it a shape,'' he told her, ``but it has no
shape. All I can do is open my heart more and more deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his devotion to her, the premise of this book seems
amorphous, requiring a type of faith and open-heartedness that,
even with esoteric assurances, is hard to come by. But then again,
if one could see how it all worked, faith wouldn't be
required.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
