<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE THREE MICE DEFINITELY NOT BLIND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As much as I hate to write this, I have come to believe it's
true: Microsoft has kicked the legs out from under the business of
designing and selling computer mice.
</P>
<P>
   This is not because the gang in Redmond, Wash., have bullied
competitors, acted in a monopolistic fashion or put horses' heads
in anyone's bed. It's simply because the company has made a better
mouse, instantly rendering almost all other designs obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, I reviewed Microsoft's IntelliMouse Explorer, a
breakthrough product that uses a tiny camera and a red LED to sense
movement instead of a ball. At the time, I was a die-hard Logitech
mouse user, and I figured I'd go back to the Logitech Cordless
MouseMan Wheel once the review was over.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen, much to my horror. I liked the Microsoft
mouse so much that I've stuck with it. Every now and then I'll take
my Cordless MouseMan out of its box, cradle it nostalgically, and
then put it away. I can't bring myself to go back.
</P>
<P>
   The IntelliMouse Explorer has three great advantages. You never
have to clean the ball and rollers, there are no moving parts to
wear out or break (except for the buttons and mouse wheel) and it
is very precise. It's excellent for both work and play. Its only
downsides are that it may be too large for some hands, is designed
only for right-handers and is a bit pricey.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of this revelation, I decided to check out three new
mice to see if my newfound belief could be challenged. One of them
is a different Microsoft mouse that uses the same optical
technology, but in a different package.
</P>
<P>
   _ Razer Boomslang 2000, $100, Karna: Among hardcore gamers, the
subject of mice is a passionate one. Gamers feel about their mice
the way guys in the 1950s felt about their cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Razer Boomslang debuted last year to mixed reviews. Some
loved its low, sleek design and oversized mouse buttons, while
others complained that it was awkward to use.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no argument that this was one of the most precise
mice around. This latest version is supposed to be five times as
sensitive as standard mice. The drivers even allow you to adjust
the sensitivity of the mouse on the fly, to give you an added boost
in the midst of a virtual firefight.
</P>
<P>
   The Razer Boomslang's design is certainly unique. If the back
end that fits into your palm is insect-like, then the front where
the mouse buttons are located looks like a bug that's been
squashed. The left and right buttons are huge hemispheres with a
wheel in the middle. There are two more buttons on the side of the
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a solid heft to it and is slightly textured. The
oversize mouse buttons are a big plus when playing quick-action
games. Overall, the mouse felt good in my hand _ at least
initially.
</P>
<P>
   But after using it for a few hours, I found that it was too low
and caused my hand to cramp a bit. I wanted the back to be higher
and fill my palm better. I also didn't like using it for work _ the
extra sensitivity that helps in games becomes irritating in
productivity applications. Fortunately, the sensitivity-on-the-fly
feature lets you adjust this at will.
</P>
<P>
   I also could not find a way to program the side mouse buttons to
page back and forth in a Web browser, a very useful feature of both
the newest Microsoft and Logitech mouse drivers.
</P>
<P>
   With a USB connection, it was nearly as precise the IntelliMouse
Explorer. The Boomslang driver also has a slick feature that lets
you update the driver painlessly _ just click Update and the new
components are downloaded and installed automatically.
</P>
<P>
   _ ScrollPoint Pro, $39, IBM: The folks at Big Blue had such a
hit on their ThinkPad notebooks with the TrackPoint pointing device
that they put it into a series of mice. But what worked well jammed
into the keyboard on a laptop doesn't necessarily translate when
plunked between the left and right buttons on a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   So IBM has tried again, this time with a variation that replaces
the familiar eraser-style tip with an ergonomic bar where most
mouse makers would place a wheel. It's a much better
implementation.
</P>
<P>
   With the original ScrollPoint mouse, I found my finger tired
when using the tiny TrackPoint head to scroll through Web pages.
Having a wider surface on which to push makes a big difference, and
the drivers that IBM provides also let you fine-tune the
sensitivity of the bar, but I still prefer a wheel for page
scrolling.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse has a blocky design, with a hard edge on the left
side. It looks like a block of clay that's been given a slight
twist, and it's very comfortable to use. Those who like a larger
mouse may love it; those with smaller hands may find it ungainly.
</P>
<P>
   Only three buttons are on this mouse _ the traditional left and
right buttons, along with a third button on the left side that's
meant to be used with a thumb. It, too, can't be programmed for use
in paging through a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   _ IntelliMouse Optical, $55, Microsoft: Here's Microsoft's
answer to complaints that lefties and those with small hands were
ignored in the design of the IntelliMouse Explorer. Unfortunately,
in making the changes, some flaws were added to the design.
</P>
<P>
   The IntelliMouse Optical is a simple curve that rises to fill
your palm. It goes straight back, lacking the twist that made the
Explorer comfortable only to right-handers. Long, curved, single
thumb buttons are located on each side.
</P>
<P>
   The Optical model is about 80 percent of the size of the
Explorer and is about $20 cheaper. Children and others with small
hands will like how it feels.
</P>
<P>
   But what I found frustrating was the placement of the thumb
buttons. On the larger Explorer, two thumb buttons are on the left
side _ one at least twice as large as the other. These are
programmed by default as back and forward buttons for Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   At times it was difficult to click the button on the right side
of the mouse using my fingertip. I found myself trying to place the
inside of my ring finger along the button to push it. At other
times, I would hit it without meaning to, which would cause me to
jump forward in my Web browser. It became annoying enough that I
eventually de-activated the extra button.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in using a mouse the employs Microsoft's
optical technology but don't want something as large as the
Explorer, another choice would be the IntelliMouse with IntelliEye,
which uses the original Microsoft Mouse soap-bar shape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
