<P>
   This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   CNS-ONLINE-BILLS (New York) _ The idea of paying bills online
has been around for while, but now there's a new wrinkle _ instead
of telling a bank when to pay the bills, consumers can sign up with
an online service. That, of course, raises other issues, like just
how safe is it? By Andrea McDaniels. (1250 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-LONDON-COFFEESHOPS (London) _ England, where a cup of tea is
supposed to solve everything, is under assault from, of all things,
coffee stores. In fact, there are more Starbucks stores in London
than in Seattle. And the British are drinking it up. By Rebecca
Webber. (750 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-FITNESS-CRAZES (New York) _ First came aerobics, then step,
then spinning, and now Pilates and kick-boxing. But every fitness
trend must start somewhere, and every gym must decide what to offer
and what to dump. It's a workout for the fitness directors who have
to decide. By Abby Tegnelia. (950 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-COMEDY-CLASSES (New York) _ When comedians step up to the
microphone, they reveal much about themselves. Would-be comics have
to learn not just timing, but how to plumb their inner souls for
material, and how to develop it into laughs. By William Siss. (1000
words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-NY-SMOKING-TAX (New York) _ When New York nearly doubled its
cigarette tax to $1.11 a pack, its intended purpose was twofold:
discourage people from smoking and take the extra revenue for
health insurance for those too poor to afford it. But critics say
those same people are the ones hit disproportionately by the tax,
and a few die-hard unemployed smokers say it will take more than a
tax to make them stop. By C.M. Lanzillotti. (1100 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-TRAPEZE-DANCERS (New York) _ They float through the air with
the greatest of ease, but these trapeze artists aren't in
performers in the circus. They're dancers, performing what amounts
to ballet high in the air. By Jocelyn Anderson. (950 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-JAIL-CENSUS (Undated) _ Minnesota wants to make sure that
everyone is counted in the census. So it's paying its prisoners $1
each to fill out the forms. That's making at least one lawmaker
very unhappy. By Kate Dawson. (725 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-MILLIONAIRE-PAUPERS (New York) _ These days, what with
Internet and stock market windfalls, being a millionaire doesn't
count for much. Even those who have a few million say they're not
really rich. They're comfortable, maybe, but they say it takes a
lot more than a few million dollars to allow one to feel special.
By Michael Goldman. (950 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-BLIND-GOALBALL (New York) _ The game is a lot like soccer,
with a heavier ball, played indoors, by people who can't see. But
goalball players say the game gives them an opportunity to be
athletes, not merely blind people. By Daisy Nguyen. (850 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-ADOPTING-MINEFIELD (Kusonje, Croatia) _ Not even the
graveyards and churchyards are havens from the legacy of wars.
Minefields are everywhere, in Bosnia, Afghanistan, Mozambique and
other places where the wars have ended but the danger has not. Now
there are efforts in the United States to raise money to pay
professionals to clear away the fear. By Nathan Hegedus. (925
words.)
</P>
