<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ONLINE-BILLS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS ONLINE BILL-PAYING THE ANSWER FOR BUSY PEOPLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Andrea McDaniels is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By ANDREA MCDANIELS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Daniel Isaacs was tired of seeing the stack of bills
looming over his desk every month. The 29-year-old advertising
agent hated having to keep up with what was due when, and paying
late fees for bills that had come in while he was often away from
his home in Austin, Texas. And, frankly, he had had enough of all
that ``licking and sticking.''
</P>
<P>
   So he signed up with Paytrust, one of the three companies online
that offer to organize clients' bill-paying. All his bills now go
directly to Paytrust, which alerts him via e-mail when a bill is
due. At the push of a button _ the company has all his bank-account
information _ he can have Paytrust cut a check or authorize a
credit-card payment. Isaacs doesn't have to keep track of a thing.
And he's reduced the time he spends paying bills from a couple of
hours a month to about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people have signed up for one of these online
services, and industry experts expect the field to grow to a
billion-dollar business within a few years. Web portals such as
America Online and Yahoo are expected to offer online bill-payment
under their brands and heavily promote it to their millions of
users.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the technology has to overcome a few hurdles _
people's reluctance to change old habits and their fears about
handing over so much personal information to a third party.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey O'Brien, a senior editor at Wired Magazine in San
Francisco, has been paying his bills online for years through his
bank, Wells Fargo. And yes, he has privacy concerns. ``Consumers
have to think about it. They have to realize the power and depth of
the information'' these companies have.
</P>
<P>
   Is abuse of the information likely? ``Clearly it could happen
somewhere down the road,'' O'Brien says. ``It could be a computer
glitch, an error, or unscrupulous, shady people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Isaacs says the convenience is worth the risk of someone
misusing his financial information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier for someone to get hold of my financial
information off my credit card at a gas station or by going through
my garbage than hacking into a secure server,'' he says. ``I'm not
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   International Data Group, a California-based technology research
firm, predicts that the electronic bill-paying business will grow
to $1 billion by 2004 with 25 million customers. The segment took
in $32 million in revenues last year, a number that includes online
billing services offered by banks and direct checking companies
such as Checkfree, which allow clients to write checks online.
</P>
<P>
   Online bill payment ``is still in its infancy,'' says research
manager Albert Pang. Part of it is a chicken-and-egg problem.
Companies stand to save big with electronic billing _ an electronic
bill costs 40 cents to send, versus $1.80 to $2.50 for a bill by
mail. But first companies want customers to show more interest in
paying online. On the other hand, customers want more billers to
issue electronic statements. That's on top of people's fear about
sending sensitive financial information online, Pang says.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he says, customers may all pay their own bills
online without needing third parties to receive and process paper
bills because everything will be delivered electronically. But he
says this future is still a ways away, since 60 percent of the
population doesn't do anything online. ``This will change as
electronic bill presentment and payment products become more
sophisticated with the inclusion of features such as secure e-mail
delivery,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Paytrust, the oldest of the online bill-paying
companies, has 10,000 customers paying $7.95 a month for the
service (the first three months are free). Paytrust chief executive
Ed McLaughlin says those most open to the idea of using the service
are Internet junkies, people already very comfortable with shopping
online. Also, those who travel a lot, such as military personnel
and business people, use the service because it allows them to keep
up with their bills when they're not there to physically receive
them, companies say. In fact, the founders of Paymybills.com got
the idea after a two-month-long trip to Guatemala that left them
stuck with late credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
   But for globe-trotters and homemakers alike, the appeal is
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no different from trading stocks online or online
shopping,'' says McLaughlin, who started the company with partner
Flint Lane in September 1998 with $200,000 of their own money. ``In
most households, paying bills is the task that sucks the most.
We're fundamentally compelling people to change their ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Online bill payment isn't a new idea. For years, major banks
allowed customers to check their bank balances, shift funds between
accounts, and issue checks online, and although most consumers
trusted these services, few signed up because they were poorly
promoted and cost money. Now these third-party companies _
Paytrust, Paymybills.com and Cyberbills Inc._ are hoping to
convince consumers that they're equally trustworthy with sensitive
financial information.
</P>
<P>
   Paytrust's guarantee is based on patent-pending technology that
doesn't need humans to operate. The processing center runs bills
through a high-speed scanner, lifts the information, puts it into
computerized form and sends out an e-mail notice to the customer
alerting him as to the arrival of the bill and the due date for
payment. Other companies have employees scan the bill ``blindly'' _
dividing up the task for security reasons so that no one employee
has access to all of the information at once. When the bill is
processed, the company sends an e-mail with a link to the company's
secure server where the customer can view the bill, download it and
make decisions about payment.
</P>
<P>
   Bill paying services can't afford to make a single mistake, says
O'Brien of Wired Magazine. At even ``the germ of impropriety,'' he
says, ``the company will be dismantled,'' possibly bringing down
the entire online bill-paying industry through word-of-mouth panic.
</P>
<P>
   Paymybills.com is the only company that sells insurance to its
clients against the possible misuse of their personal financial
information, offering up to $100,000 in damages. The company says
that's one of the reasons it has been cited by PC World and Forbes
magazine as being among the best on the Web. But to some consumers,
the sales offer itself raises a red flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be one thing if they gave you the insurance, because
that would mean they stand by their privacy policy,` says Jean Ann
Fox, director of consumer protection for the Consumer Federation of
America. ``But if they sell it to you, that looks like they don't
really believe in what they're doing.'' comments
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lazaroff, director of marketing for Paymybills.com, says the
company offers the policy because it's ``adamant about security.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, it may not be technological insecurity that's the
biggest challenge to the spread of bill paying services _ it's
overcoming the status quo, says Lazaroff, whose firm sprang up last
July and garnered $30 million in its most recent round of funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still have to get over the idea that writing checks and
licking stamps is the best way to pay bills,'' he says.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
