<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3793 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-LONDON-COFFEESHOP     04-21 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-LONDON-COFFEESHOPS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COFFEE TAKES ON A TEA TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Rebecca Webber is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By REBECCA WEBBER   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON  &UR; _ &LR;  To many Americans, a dainty saucer bearing a steaming
teacup, with sweet biscuits on the side, is the stereotypical
vision of British culture. So what does one make of the familiar
round green logo that has popped up on the twisting streets and
historic avenues of England's city on the Thames?
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks coffee, it seems, is posing a challenge to English
tea. The coffee maker from Seattle has installed 124 thriving
coffee shops in the United Kingdom. London alone boasts 67.
Seattle, by comparison, has 66.
</P>
<P>
   Few would have predicted the success of the American coffee
chain in the land where tea has reigned supreme for four centuries.
But from Glasgow to Bath, lattes and Frappuccinos, espressos and
mochaccinos are selling like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks has had a great reception in the UK and is excited
about its growth opportunities, according to Helen Benedict, the UK
director of marketing. The company plans to open 50 new stores this
year and establish at least 300 in the UK by 2003, said the chief
executive, Howard Schultz, during a recent visit.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain this success? Perhaps the British perceive the
coffee chain, like all things American, as a sort of adorable
grandchild descended from colonial forebears. Or, as some suggest,
it could be because they have never mastered a potable cup of brew,
relying on instant grounds since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coffee was always drunk, but it was always pretty bad
coffee,'' said London native Daniel Guthrie, explaining why he and
friends welcomed Starbucks with open wallets. ``Now, between 8:30
and 9 every morning, you see everyone clutching their little white
cup on their way between the tube and the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the fad aspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coffee is sort of a new thing, so it's trendy,'' said Jo
Walsh, a 25-year-old Londoner. She visits Starbucks to grab a
coffee and sweet ``to takeaway,'' or to meet up with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks is not the only coffee chain invading London's
streets. A British chain called Coffee Republic has 40 stores.
Costa Coffee, another local company, has 70 shops. And the
ubiquitous Pret a Manger snack shop sports a hip coffee bar,
serving up cappuccinos along with its packaged sandwiches at 78
London locations.
</P>
<P>
   But while the English have embraced the coffee chains with
enthusiasm, they sniff at some undesirable side effects. ``It's a
bit ugly having chains all over the place,'' said Walsh. Guthrie
says the British quietly wonder, ``Is it something that's here to
stay or will it go away?''
</P>
<P>
   The newfound success of coffee may also reveal a yawning
generation gap, according to Edward Bramah, founder and curator of
London's Tea and Coffee Museum. There was a time when tea-taking
was second nature to all subjects of the queen.
</P>
<P>
   But now, ``Fifty percent of university students wouldn't know
what to do with a teapot if you put it in front of them,'' he
lamented.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their enthusiasm for coffee, even university
students aren't ready to predict the demise of tea. ``All my
friends drink tea, not coffee,'' said Nathaniel Roberts, 23, of
Liverpool. For convenience, they may well go to the coffee shop to
do it, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just nip in and get one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee stores offer a selection of teas to placate the likes
of Roberts, but they still make their money off frothier _ and
costlier _ coffee drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do offer a large range of tea beverages but our tea sales
only make up around 5 percent of sales,'' said Graham Norton, a
Coffee Republic sales analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The big picture supports Norton's data. Tea consumption by the
British has gradually declined over the past two decades according
to the Tea Council of London. Still, the council's most recent
national survey, in 1997, revealed the English consumed an average
of 3.39 cups of tea each day, and only 1.65 cups of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tea industry should look forward to tea's continued
domination of the total drinks market,'' the Tea Council boasts,
perhaps somewhat hopefully, on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Britain continues to import more tea than coffee. And many
believe that the UK need only withstand the American invasion
today, because the pendulum will swing back tomorrow with world
domination by tea.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Seattle in 50 years,'' Bramah deadpanned, ``they'll be
drinking tea.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
