<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3794 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-FITNESS-CRAZES &LR;      04-21 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-FITNESS-CRAZES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE LATEST FITNESS CRAZE IS A REAL WORKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Abby Tegnelia is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By ABBY TEGNELIA   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK  &UR; _ &LR;  David Rosenbaum, a dancer and aerobics teacher in
Manhattan for more than 20 years, said he grew tired of coming home
from the gym with aching, tense muscles from high impact exercise.
Without intending to put together a class, he started to create
exercises to heal his body, starting with static stretching then
progressing to rib and hip isolations. Then he approached the
fitness director about adding his creation to the aerobics
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd figured something out,'' he said. ``And I wanted
to share this with my students.''
</P>
<P>
   The result: ``hot stretch,'' a flexibility and movement class
that combines modern dance, yoga and ballet to create a ``sensual,
erotic'' workout. Rosenbaum now teaches the class at all of the
Manhattan Equinox health clubs, and the concept has spread to other
gyms as well.
</P>
<P>
   Fitness crazes such as these come and go, and it's up to
aerobics directors to decide which ones to offer. National
conventions, home fitness videos and infomercials hawk the latest
fitness crazes, and pop culture contributes music and style
direction. Often, aerobics directors look to their clients, who
know what competing gyms are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each gym has its own personality,'' said Johnny Hunt, a
fitness instructor at Bulldog Gym of Hollywood, a Los Angeles gym
known for its nightly DJs who spin pumping techno and hip-hop
music. ``You have to choose workouts for your particular type of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said Bulldog changes the aerobics schedule about every six
weeks to allow new classes to be added. Classes, most of which have
30-50 students, are dropped from the schedule when attendance fails
to reach half the capacity. That happened with onetime crazes such
as double-step and slide classes.
</P>
<P>
   Most new workouts start in either Los Angeles or New York, and
every workout must be tailored to the specific gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher of the new workout has to convince the owner that
people are interested,'' said Hunt, who has blended kick boxing
with exercises from several other types of martial arts to create
his own workout at Bulldog. ``The facility has to be geared to it,
and there has to be that type of people in the gym.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Krauss, group fitness manager at Equinox &UR; ,  &LR; said there is
also a list of fitness criteria that must be met. She often
auditions new instructors one-on-one, or goes to another gym to
watch them teach. She sometimes offers a one-time class with the
instructor, to see if the people at Equinox like the workout style.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, it needs to be safe,'' she said. ``And it
needs to have an actual purpose. We're looking to find a special
gain,'' like cardiovascular enhancement, muscle strength, or
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really want to be entertained and need to feel they've
accomplished something,'' said Krauss, who oversaw the addition of
Pilates classes, a workout for flexibility and postural alignment.
``They want to look better and feel better, and the workout needs
to answer all those little prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   The prayers of the instructors, too. ``Instructors work hard to
develop something that's their own,'' said Krauss. . ``People like
to stand out.'' Many instructors seek to market their workouts on
home video, but first he or she must sell a concept to a gym and
develop a local following.
</P>
<P>
   Once a new workout is sold, Hunt said, teachers often pass out
flyers to advertise their class and create posters for the gym's
bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instructors have to sell themselves,'' Hunt said. ``It's like
they're running their own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum, the instructor at Equinox, often does TV and magazine
interviews, as well as fitness fashion shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to get the word out,'' he said. ``New instructors
often come up with a clever name for their class or trademark their
workout. Anything to create some hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Although instructors often come to the gyms to widen their
workout audience, fitness directors must actively seek out trends
to make sure they've got the latest craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our trends follow music and fashion,'' Krauss said. ``Latin is
huge right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Equinox is trying out a salsa class that will teach moves that
students can use at clubs that play music by Latin sensations Ricky
Martin and Enrique Inglesias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always reading magazines or watching TV to see what's
going on in the real world,'' said Donna Cyrus, national group
fitness director for Crunch, which has gyms in Manhattan, L.A. and
Miami. ``I watch to see where trends seem to be going.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyrus said she stays tuned to pop culture to cater to Crunch's
young, urban crowd. She has drag queens teach aerobics, for
example, and she recently added karaoke machines to some of the
spinning classes. She also attends national aerobics conventions,
which bring acclaimed aerobics instructors to teach the latest
fitness trends. Most conventions survey gym owners and aerobics
teachers, then offer seminars based on the most popular trends in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``People attend conventions to see what everyone else is
doing,'' said David Gilroy, director of communications for IDEA, a
membership fitness organization that will run a convention in
Anaheim in August. ``Then they take the exercises and adapt it to
their gyms. Then things start to catch on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We follow the beat of the city,'' Hunt said. ``That much
research doesn't need to be done. It's not like we're looking for a
new way to purify water.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
