<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3795 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-COMEDY-CLASSES &LR;      04-21 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-COMEDY-CLASSES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDY CLASSES PLACE STUDENTS IN SPOTLIGHT, ON COUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(William Siss is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By WILLIAM SISS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stepping up to the microphone stand, under the glare
of the spotlight, budding comic Buz Whalen opens up a vein.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first wife really put an exclamation point at the end of
our marriage,'' Whalen tells the small crowd. ``She stabbed me in
the back.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience pauses, wondering what to do. Then Whalen giggles
in a way that says, it's OK: you can laugh at this, too. He doesn't
tell them that it really happened.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen works out his new material in a virtual nightclub, a
cozy, dark rehearsal stage at Raw Space on 42nd Street in
Manhattan, where he's a student at the Comic Studio. The new series
of classes, taught by comic veteran Tommy Koenig, 46, allows
students from a variety of professions to develop and hone their
acts, and learn what it takes to succeed in the competitive world
of stand-up comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first wife really did stab me in the back,'' Whalen says
off stage. ``I went to the hospital and almost died. But it's not a
sensitive point with me anymore. I never brought it up in classes
before, so one night I just decided to use it. Now I think I'll be
using it quite a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Whalen did not press charges in the stabbing incident, and the
case was ruled an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Along with six others on a Thursday night, Whalen demonstrates,
quite literally, that what doesn't kill you makes you stronger. And
funnier. Whalen, a video store owner from New Jersey, started
developing his material at night classes as a psychology professor
at Rutgers and Kean universities. Dressed in black, with white hair
flowing to his shoulders, the round-faced Whalen looks like a
taller version of diminutive actor Mickey Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   At the Comics Studio, students dig deep to mine for material.
Kind of like psychoanalysis with punchlines. While some members of
the psychoanalytic community sense potential harm in this
technique, they also say its benefits can be enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand-up comedy is a form of therapy for comics to get up and
talk about themselves,'' says Koenig, a thin, curly-haired comedian
whose expressions shift from intensity to wide-eyed goofiness. ``I
have a joke in my act: `I'm going to tell you people because I
can't afford therapy.''' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Koenig, whose own stand-up career spans from opening for Jerry
Seinfeld in the early 1980s to packing houses at Caroline's comedy
club in New York, charges $349 for his six weekly workshop classes.
He breaks them up into three experience levels: from unpolished to
slick and ready to get paid. He launched the Comics Studio in March
after years of private coaching, and currently works with 35
students, some of whom will display their talent at clubs like
Stand-Up New York and the Comedy Cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I create a safe environment,'' Koenig says. ``This is a place
where you will be nurtured and loved and allowed to open up
yourself, and not get put down or criticized. And people take to it
in a therapy kind of way. I want them to express themselves. From
there, we can turn that into comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first few weeks, students share their life stories.
Some, like Whalen, delve into marriages gone sour. Others explore
the experience of coming out of the closet or difficulties in
meeting the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   When actress Karen Sklaire told her story, instead of funny, she
was fretful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started talking about how I wasn't going to make it, how I
need a job,'' recalls Sklaire, who now works at a gym. ``The next
thing I know I'm practically in tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Sklaire, who takes the class to help her television career, sees
the temptation of confusing professional training with therapy.
``You have to be careful and remember that it's still a
classroom,'' she says. ``I know this from years of acting class. A
lot of people will use a class to unload their problems. Tommy's
very responsible about that. He sort of takes the rope and pulls it
on in.''
</P>
<P>
   Koenig says he is careful with new comics who open up closed
chapters of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not abandon them,'' Koenig emphasizes. ``But I have to
learn how to establish boundaries, just as a psychiatrist would.
Except I don't give them a 45-minute hour. I actually give more.''
</P>
<P>
   While stand-up comedy is a nerve-wracking pursuit, creating
one's stage persona can be therapeutic, says Stephen Rosenfield,
director of the American Comedy Institute, which offers training to
comics in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know your life and experiences are part of your
comedy, it can be reassuring in a way,'' he says. ``You're able to
use your sense of humor in a really productive way, if you're
comfortable about talking about your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Sterling, a New York psychologist, shares Rosenfield's
belief, but warns that one can take a joke too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface it sounds like a very fine opportunity, and a
way to turn painful aspects of one's life into shared stories,''
Sterling says of stand-up comedy classes. ``But it's important for
the teacher to know when to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Manhattan-based Actors, Writers, and Performers
Psychotherapy Center, Dr. Eric Riss works with a number of stand-up
comedians. ``They come to us because they can only go so far,'' the
psychologist explains. ``They might talk about their life in their
comedy, but not actually deal with their problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Riss says that comics hold onto the myth that their anxiety
makes them better comics. ``They're mistaken,'' he says. ``They can
actually perform better when they overcome their anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   In using the truth in their acts, Koenig says, comics display
unique bravery.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we become comics is that we feel so
deeply,'' he says. ``They say that one of the reasons why people
sing is because their feelings are so deep, they couldn't possibly
be expressed in words. Some thoughts are so painful that the comic
has to turn everything into humor to make it easier to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
