<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3797 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-NY-SMOKING-TAX &LR;      04-21 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-NY-SMOKING-TAX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SMOKERS RILED BY NEW TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(C.M. Lanzillotti is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By C.M. LANZILLOTTI   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK  &UR; _ &LR;  When Sheilam Brooks, 46, an unemployed smoker who
lives on the Upper West Side of Manhattan, received her Social
Security check in early March, she went to the local grocery store
to indulge in a pack of cigarettes. Handing the clerk a $5 bill,
she waited for her cigarettes and her change. But this time she got
just the cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was ripping me off,'' she says, sitting on a
wooden bench in front of a donut shop where she begs for money.
``He explained to me that the price went up because of a new tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, New York State nearly doubled its sales tax _ adding
55 cents to each pack _ making its $1.11 tax the highest in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The tax is expected to raise about $400 million per year, $150
million more than in previous years, and allow financing of a
program to provide health insurance coverage to more than a million
uninsured state residents.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the tax is unfair, because with higher smoking
rates, the poor are getting hit the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeff Schaler, psychologist and professor of justice, law and
society at American University, and author of ``Addiction is a
Choice,'' says poor people smoke in higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is likely more stressful and smoking is an easier and
cheaper way to reduce their anxiety and depression, which is more
due to their environment and mindset than a physiological
addiction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wealthier people can afford better health insurance policies,
which cover either psychotherapy, anxiety-reducing drugs or
anti-depressive medications.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Hansen, a spokesman for state Senate Majority Leader
Joseph Bruno (R-Brunswick), who is a proponent of the plan, said
the tax itself lends toward smoking cessation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax is also intended to deter young people from taking up
smoking,'' he said, under the premise that teen-agers have less
money to splurge on cigarettes. ``Primarily, if we can convince the
young not to start smoking, then that'll be a big help,'' toward
reducing cancer rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the smoking rate among adults is almost half of what
it was in 1964, the rate for teen-agers has been growing steadily
since 1990, despite a national trend of higher taxes on cigarettes.
According to the commission for a Healthy New York, at least
one-third of teen-agers in the United States smoke.
</P>
<P>
   As for the charge that the tax is unfairly affecting low-income
residents who smoke, Hansen says, ``There are high incidents of
cancer among them as well,'' and that they'll ultimately benefit
from quitting.
</P>
<P>
   The tax increase was hailed by Gov. George Pataki as both a
social and public health initiative, discouraging residents from
smoking and providing some with health care. But others see the tax
as an opportunity for the government to make money at the expense
of the poor, while only marginally affecting smoking rates.
</P>
<P>
   The tariff is not intended to directly pay for treating
illnesses related to smoking. Instead, the new program is aimed at
helping the approximately one million state residents who are not
poor enough to qualify for Medicaid and those whose employers don't
offer benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Another $37 million will go toward tobacco prevention programs,
up from $8.2 million in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   New York State is already relying on tax dollars from
cigarettes, an amount built into the state budget, said Jeff Stier,
spokesman for the American Council on Science and Health, a public
health organization. The organization believes taxing cigarettes
misses the point of educating the public about the dangers of
smoking, and is largely ineffective toward reducing the purchase of
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that the money is not going toward educating
the public'' about the harm smoking can cause, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Of the money allocated toward tobacco prevention programs, more
than half will go toward community programs designed to encourage
adults to quit, and almost a half will go toward school programs to
discourage teen-agers from starting.
</P>
<P>
   He claims that politicians in the United States have spent $246
billion in the last year on public health initiatives, including
smoking cessation, but that this really masks their true intentions
of funding ``pet projects,'' like schools and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has become a beneficiary of the sale of cigarettes,
and the government has become just as addicted as the smokers.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the recent tax increase on cigarettes is a ``regressive
tax,'' that won't make poor people stop smoking, but instead make
their addiction more painful as they fork over more and more of
their small income to keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 survey of 695 randomly selected adults in central Harlem
found that 61 percent of people without working telephones smoke,
while the national average for adults is 25 percent, according to
the Commission for a Healthy New York, an anti-smoking group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicotine is a highly addictive drug,'' Stier says. ``If people
are addicted to it, they'll find a way to get their fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvillo Johnson, a 58-year-old homeless man, is doing just
that. He says he can buy cigarettes for as little as $2 a pack in a
booming black market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are doing it. They're driving out of state, and
selling 'em here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ryan, a spokesman for the cigarette manufacturer Philip
Morris, acknowledges that the sale of ``taxed'' cigarettes in New
York State has declined, but says there are many other transactions
that cannot be gauged. He cites low-tax cigarettes imported from
other states, and those sold on Indian reservations, where there is
no tax.
</P>
<P>
   Of the idea of using cigarette money to provide for health
insurance, he says, ``It's very risky to tax a small minority of
the population to pay for something as important as health care.''
</P>
<P>
   He also says the tax places an unfair burden on the poor. He
cites a 1996 study conducted by the Citizens for Tax Justice that
found that the poorest 20 percent of American families pay 16.7
times more of their income on ``pleasure'' taxes than the richest
one percent of families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax burden is equal and consequently accounts for a higher
percentage of a poorer family's income,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, the unemployed women, has cut back on her generosity.
Now, when a passing stranger sometimes asks her for a cigarette,
she pretends she doesn't have any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, I used to just hand them out to anyone,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
