<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0422-COX     04-21 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0422-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REMOVING ELIAN BY FORCE PRESENTS DAUNTING CHALLENGES TO
AUTHORITIES
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The house where Elian Gonzalez lives is on a two-lane
street in the middle of a modest neighborhood. There's no place
nearby to land a helicopter _ powerlines crisscross the area _ and
while there is an expressway about a mile away, getting to it might
prove a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Should Attorney General Janet Reno decide it's time to send
federal officers to take the 6-year-old Cuban rafter to be reunited
with his father, it won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of protesters may jam the neighborhood, with many
locking arms in front of the house or sitting down in the street,
waiting to be arrested and dragged away. Others may offer more
active resistance, although Cuban exile leaders have pleaded with
the crowds to remain nonviolent.
</P>
<P>
   A caravan of huge dump trucks may appear, drivers intent on
blocking access to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Television crews from around the world have cameras trained on
the front door, and news helicopters would likely appear within
seconds, hovering overhead and broadcasting everything on live
television.
</P>
<P>
   Reno spent Friday meeting with top Justice Department officials
_ and briefly with the boy's father _ saying she still hopes for a
peaceful resolution to the long-running standoff. A spokeswoman
said late Friday that Reno had been working with unnamed
intermediaries in Miami on a possible agreement to transfer custody
of the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
   But her deputies have been preparing plans for an enforcement
action, and the pressure has grown for Reno to move.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges she faces are daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Cuban exiles don't want the boy to go, and he's living
in the middle of their turf. It's a cramped, urban neighborhood
with narrow streets. Most houses are surrounded by fences. There's
no open space, no secret way in or out.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cuban activists have trained for years in the nearby
Everglades, waiting for the day when they might mount an invasion
to win back their island. While no one believes they would use arms
to keep Elian in Little Havana, some are bent on a determined
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   There are unconfirmed reports that sentinels for the protestors
are posted with hand-held radios on all the streets around the
house, relaying word of any moves by law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   And communications in Cuban Miami are instantaneous. The city's
ubiquitous Spanish-language radio stations crackle with every new
development. People in the crowd carry transistor radios, and
radios blare all day in Little Havana's shops, businesses and
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of attempts to take the boy during the past weeks have
prompted the crowds near the house to swell quickly. They have even
grown after unmarked helicopters hovered over the area. Twice,
lines of giant dump trucks have jammed the neighborhood, horns
blaring, drivers waving Cuban flags.
</P>
<P>
   Most people say they will put up no active resistance, but warn
they can't be sure about others.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be here around the clock,'' said Frankie Perez,
23, a salesman who took off work to be at the house Friday. ``I
really don't know what to expect if they come for Elian. I don't
think it will be as bad as the media says, but the Cuban people are
passionate. They get excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowds outside the house wax and wan, from a few dozen in
the middle of the night and early morning to hundreds in the
evenings after work. On weekends, hundreds come to the house to
sing, chant, pray or just mill around. Vendors sell cold drinks,
hot dogs and ice cream from carts stationed on street corners.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters include old men and women, sharply dressed
businessmen with cell phones, parents with toddlers and babies in
strollers and teenagers wearing earrings and rock-band T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, some in the crowd seemed resigned to losing the
boy, but a favorable court ruling and the Miami family's successful
defiance of a deadline set by Reno have spurred a new sense of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton and Reno have made people more determined,'' said
Michele Reyes, 24, who has come to the house for weeks. ``I think
they've miscalculated Cubans.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have erected barricades at either end of the block of
Northwest Second Street where Elian lives, with more barricades on
other nearby streets. The media are allowed in at one end of the
street, and they have erected a permanent camp under tents across
the street from the house.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters are allowed in at the other end of the street, and
gather at a barricade that cuts across the street about 50 feet
from the house. The barricade is attached to fences in yards on
either side of the street.
</P>
<P>
   Once previously protesters overturned the barricade and rushed
the house when a rumor surfaced that the boy was about to be taken,
but police have since reinforced the metal fence.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago when Reno issued a deadline for the Miami relatives
to turn Elian over, police expanded their perimeter. Officers
closed portions of two nearby arteries, Flagler St. and NW 22nd
Ave.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands of protesters still poured into the area on foot,
and presumably would again, alerted by Spanish language radio.
</P>
<P>
   The protests that day were peaceful, and tensions evaporated
after a surprise court ruling negated Reno's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But protests in January triggered by Reno's initial decision to
send Elian back to his father boiled over into scuffles with
police, with more than 100 people arrested. Demonstrators blocked
the entrance to Miami's bustling seaport and tied up traffic with
slow-moving caravans on several major roads.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, any plan to take Elian will be fraught with
imponderables.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have been understandably vague about
specifics, but reportedly would send plain-clothes immigration
officers and federal marshals to the house. They would rely on
local police to keep public order.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago questions arose about just how helpful local
police would be. Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas angrily vowed
police would do nothing to help take the boy out of the home. He
backtracked after critics said he came close to inviting a
disturbance, and has since called for calm.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Miami Police Lt. Bill Schwartz said police will
maintain order, but he hoped there would be no confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crowd is decent, law-abiding citizens,'' he said. ``They
are our brothers and sisters. My fear is that if the mob mentality
comes out, people could get hurt. There are people in the crowd who
might want to incite things. We'd rather have cooler heads
prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams can be e-mailed at: mikew(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
