<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TRAPEZE-DANCERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAPEZE DANCERS DO MORE THAN JUST HANG OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Jocelyn Anderson is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By JOCELYN ANDERSON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When dancers come to Julie Ludwick's class, the first
thing she does is instruct them to go to the playground and hang
upside down on the monkey bars. They should stay there for at least
30 minutes, she says.
</P>
<P>
   After a few visits, the dancers are ready for Ludwick's intense
two-hour classes _ in trapeze dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to hold on,'' said Ludwick, who teaches at
Soundance Studio in Manhattan and heads a trapeze dance company,
Fly-By-Night Dance Theater. ``You may be strong at lifting weights,
but maybe you can't hang upside down because you don't have the
grip.''
</P>
<P>
   Trapeze dance, a form of what is known as aerial dance, attracts
both professional dancers and everyday fitness buffs. But, despite
the image its name conjures, trapeze dance bears little resemblance
to circus performing.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent class, Ludwick led six students through a graceful
series of exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers experimented with twirling on trapezes that hung from
three to five feet above the ground. They swung sitting on the
bars, dangled by their arms, dropped to the ground in somersaults
and hooked their elbows around the ropes to spin. They pulled their
bodies over the bar and slid slowly down. They threw the bar to
dodge the trapeze as it swayed back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artistically, it's about finding the utmost control,'' Ludwick
said. ``But at times you have to allow the trapeze to take you.
It's your partner with its own momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who make the movements look smooth can put their talent to
work performing for audiences. Ludwick's dance theater troupe drew
packed crowds for six shows in March at a small theater on
Manhattan's Lower East Side. And other aerial dance companies are
springing up across the country as traditional dance companies
incorporate aerial elements into their programs.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, there were only about 12 professional aerial dance
companies, according to Nancy Smith of Frequent Flyer Productions
in Boulder, Colo. That number has more than doubled, with new
companies as far away as Europe, Australia and South America. Some
dancers have enlarged the genre by use of hanging strips of fabric
or swinging hoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the next step in dance,'' said Terry Sendgraff, of
Oakland, Calif., who is credited with inventing low-flying trapeze
dance in Colorado in &UR;  &LR; the early 1970s. ``I think it is the
avant-garde form. If you want to be a dancer these days, you had
better learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although trapeze dance was well accepted in Colorado, it has
taken years for the genre to gain wider acceptance as a legitimate
dance form. Sendgraff said that when she moved to California, she
had to persuade skeptics that it was not a circus act with
performers flinging their bodies 30 feet above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Critics said it wasn't dance, and someone else called it
therapy,'' said the 67-year-old Sendgraff.
</P>
<P>
   While circus trapezes are supported by two parallel ropes
attached to the ceiling, the dance trapezes have two ropes attached
to the ceiling in a triangular fashion. Trapeze dancers also keep
low to the ground and don't leap between swings like circus
performers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the appeal of trapeze dancing is the weightless
sensation, dancers say. There are also psychological benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you dance the salsa, you are not afraid for your life,''
said Smith. ``Here, you have to overcome fear of something terrible
happening. As you gain trust in your own body and other people, you
do something you didn't think you could do. It's a different kind
of thing than any other dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwick's students also talked about their enhanced strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I am challenging my arm muscles,'' said Cassandra
Marshall, who was a dance major in college. ``I feel ripped, and I
never felt that way before.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Ludwick's dance theater say their rock-hard legs and
muscularly defined arms were built by trapeze practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to do it you have to make it look easy,'' said
Despina Stamos, a member of Fly-By-Night. ``It's hard to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, dancers say this is an accessible art form that
anyone can pick up. Stamos started performing with Ludwick after
only six months of class. And strength should not be a barrier
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who are lovely on the trapeze who can't do a
pull-up,'' because trapeze requires different muscle use, said
Cathy Gauch, of Aircat Aerial Arts, which is now performing in
Gaum.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers who have been using the trapeze for years say they are
not surprised it has taken off in popularity. Pop star Ricky Martin
has an aerial dancer on stage during his concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping it's not a fad but something beautiful that catches
on,'' said Maria Carrillo, director of the Flying Trapeze
Association of Roseville, Calif. ``I want people to take hold of
this, not as a cheesy circus act, but as a beautiful art.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
