<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3800 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-JAIL-CENSUS &LR;      04-21 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-JAIL-CENSUS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS FORMS COUNT FOR A BUCK BEHIND BARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Minn.)  
 (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Kate Dawson is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By KATE DAWSON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To get prison inmates to fill out their census forms, Minnesota
corrections officials are paying them each a dollar, in what is the
first effort of its kind in any state prison system.
</P>
<P>
   One dollar may not seem like much, but Minnesota's 5,900 inmates
earn an average of a quarter an hour for chores. In hopes of
getting everyone to comply, officials plan to shut down the state's
eight prisons for one day in the middle of April. Prisoners will
remain in their cells while corrections officers help them
individually fill out the form.
</P>
<P>
   Though all adults living in the United States are supposed to
fill out census forms, including the 1.4 million men and women
behind bars, the law requiring them to do so is rarely enforced.
But Shari Burt, a spokeswoman for the Minnesota Department of
Corrections, said prisoners will not be forced to complete the
questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where officers can tell prisoners when to sleep, when
to get up and when to eat, it may seem curious that officers do not
fill out the forms themselves, as if they were heads of households.
</P>
<P>
   But Burt said that prisoners are more likely to cooperate and
provide accurate answers if they do not feel coerced.
</P>
<P>
   Though the corrections system has personal information on
inmates, she said, it is not always comprehensive. For example,
Burt said, ``the warden doesn't know which tribe an American Indian
came from. We just don't keep those kinds of records.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guarantee that they'll be any more honest than anyone
else,'' she said. ``But we don't believe in using force to fill out
a form and this is just a simple way to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the state's lawmakers, State Representative Phil
Krinkie, called the plan ``bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it our institution has to lead the way in bribing
inmates for their census forms?'' he said. ``These people are not
homeless _ those are the ones who could really use it. These people
are incarcerated.'' The money is coming from surcharges on phone
calls and items at the canteen.
</P>
<P>
   Krinkie said he understands why the Department of Corrections
would resort to paying inmates to fill out the forms. Census counts
help determine federal funding for everything from schools to parks
to prisons. And Minnesota, he said, always seems to pay out more
federal money than it gets it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are always the net loser when it comes to funding, of
course they'll do anything they can for more money,'' Krinkie said.
``But this is bribery. We have to be the only state to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. Texas, which has the second highest number of prisoners
in the country, simply gives its 149,500 inmates the census forms
to fill out. Department of Criminal Justice officials there said
that if a prisoner does not speak English or is illiterate, a
census official or an officer trained by the Census Bureau will
assist him.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at New York's Department of Corrections in Albany said
they use a similar system. With 71,730 prisoners, the state has the
second-highest inmate population nationwide _ too many inmates for
wardens to fill out their forms, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The story is similar in Florida, which has the country's
fourth-highest inmate population. Correction officials there said
the biggest incentive their 70,100 inmates receive for filling out
a form is a baseball cap with a census slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Census Bureau said that though they had never
heard of another state paying prisoners to fill out census forms,
Minnesota's effort did not surprise them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help the state tremendously with federal and special
funding,'' said Bill Wallin, a spokesman for the Census Bureau in
Minneapolis. ``We're interested in accuracy and as long as it's
legal and legitimate, we're all for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Krinkie said the payments simply make his state look stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if I don't fill out my form, some census guy comes over
to my house and asks me to do it, or I could get a fine,'' Krinkie
said. ``Give the inmates additional phone time if they're desperate
to get a big head count, but these guys don't deserve cash.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
