<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-MILLIONAIRE-PAUPE     04-21 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MILLIONAIRE-PAUPERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MODERN MILLIONAIRE: PAUPER OR PRINCE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Michael Goldman is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By MICHAEL GOLDMAN   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mohesh Kalita is a millionaire, a multimillionaire,
in fact. But this 57-year-old, who recently retired from his post
as a vice president at Citibank, doesn't consider himself rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``One million dollars is not a lot of money,'' he said. ``It's
enough so I don't have to worry about day-to-day things,'' said
Kalita, talking on the phone from his four-bedroom colonial in
Princeton, N.J.. ``But then again I can't afford to buy a townhouse
in Manhattan. Even a big apartment might be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to today's American economy.
</P>
<P>
   With Internet company IPOs creating wealth quicker than you can
say dot-com and the Dow soaring to dizzying new heights, affluence
has trickled down to more and more Americans. But with that wealth
has come a certain nonchalance about what in sparer times was
considered a lot of money. It appears as if having a net worth of
$1 million, the benchmark that once separated the truly rich from
those just doing very, very well, no longer has much cachet.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that a million doesn't command any respect at
all. The ABC game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' after
all, is the most-watched show on television. That said, the
short-lived Fox spinoff ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire''
suggested that a mere million isn't even enough to attract the kind
of woman willing to get hitched on air to a complete stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason $1 million isn't getting the respect it once
did is because in this booming economy, so many people are loaded.
In 1962, only 922,000 American households were worth $1 million or
more, just 2 percent of the total population, according to Edward
Wolff, an economics professor at New York University. Today, Wolff
said, that figure is 4.5 million, or 4.5 percent of the total
population. ``It's probably at an all-time high.''
</P>
<P>
   To get a better sense of the number of millionaires in America
today, think of Ireland, population 3.6 million. Now imagine every
single Irish citizen as a millionaire. Even if that were the case,
Ireland would still need an influx of about a million additional
millionaires to equal the number of millionaires in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   If the number of millionaires in the U.S. is at an all-time
high, then so, too, seems to be the ease with which one can become
one. There are, of course, charter members of the Microsoft team
and others similarly blessed by being in the right place at the
right time. But more conventional routes to a million exist.
Financial advisers say that if a 25-year-old earning $30,000
invests 10 percent of that salary a year and realizes a modest
annual return of 6 percent, that person can accumulate about $1.1
million by age 65.
</P>
<P>
   One million, is not, quite literally, what it used to be.
Because of inflation, to equal the buying power of someone with $1
million in 1960, a person today would need $5 million, according to
Wolff, the economics professor.
</P>
<P>
   If statistics don't drive the point home, consider the lifestyle
of the modern-day millionaire. Jennifer Barnum, a 25-year-old
student at Shasta College, a community college in Redding, Calif.,
inherited her money from the family newspaper business. She says
investments yield her a $2,500 pre-tax monthly income, enough to go
to school full time without working, but hardly enough to afford a
yacht or any of the other trappings of wealth commonly associated
with millionairedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drive a 1996 Subaru Legacy Outback Station Wagon that I paid
$21,500 for,'' she said, ``and a good half of my clothes are either
hand-me-downs from my sisters or left over from high school.''
Barnum added that although she considers herself fortunate, ``I
would like to have more money. There are lots of people with more
money than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnum's attitude is typical, according to David Krueger, a
Houston psychiatrist who is the author of numerous books on the
psychology of money. Krueger said that with news reports and
cocktail party discussions turning more and more to the subject of
money, it's easy even for the relatively affluent to feel insecure.
``Freud,'' Krueger said, ``said that money was the last taboo.
Well, money in our current society is much more open and talked
about. The last taboo has come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Barbanel, a psychotherapist in New York who has also
written about the psychology of money, agreed. But Barbanel said
the reason people aren't happy with $1 million isn't purely
psychological. Referring to New York, she said, ``In this city,
that's just not enough to take advantage of the shows, the
restaurants, the location where you live, the vacations, the
taxis.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is enough money to command the respect that $1 million
once did? Wolff, the economics professor, said $5 million would be
sufficient to ``make heads turn.'' After calculating that there are
currently many American households (670,000) worth that amount or
more, he adjusted the number upward. ``Probably to be rich today,
you need $10 million or more.'' he said. ``There are only 230,000
households worth that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kalita, the former Citibank vice president, said he's
content with the approximately $3.5 million he's acquired since
emigrating from India in 1971 with no more than an undergraduate
education and $400 in his pocket. ``I came from a poor country,''
said Kalita. ``What I have right now is good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
