<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-BLIND-GOALBALL &LR;      04-21 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BLIND-GOALBALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLIND ATHLETES FIND FUN AND CHALLENGE ON GOALBALL COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Daisy Nguyen is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By DAISY NGUYEN   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patty Ashbury, wearing a blindfold and pads on her
knees and hips, stands by a wall and waits for her husband, Andre,
to throw a two-pound rubber ball towards her. As the bell inside
the rolling ball signals its position, she lunges to the ground.
The ball hits her chest. Success! Patty has blocked the ball from
hitting the wall and prevented her opponent from making a score.
</P>
<P>
   The Ashburys are playing goalball, a soccer-like game specially
developed for blind or visually impaired people. The Ashburys,
considered legally blind, have been ardent players of goalball for
over 10 years. ``It's a bloody game but we're addicted to it,''
said Patty, 38, a special education teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Goalball is popular among blind athletes because it is the only
team sport available to them. ``It allows the blind to compete
without visual limitations,'' said Andre, 35, a student in computer
science.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Eason, 33, a member of the New York Association of Blind
Athletes' goalball team, said: ``It's physical, it's challenging,
you've got to have skills to play. I love it when I hear the ball
hit people's faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalball players compete year-round and meet for regional,
national and international competitions. Seven regional teams,
encompassing men's and women's divisions, belong to the United
States Association of Blind Athletes. Patty Ashbury and Eason are
part of the American women's team, which is ranked third out of 14
teams that competes in international tournaments. They will head to
Sydney, Australia, this October to compete in the international
Paralympic. ``We've got a good chance of winning the gold medal,''
Patty said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Ashburys regularly practice with eight other
athletes in a high school gym. The three-person teams play on
hardwood floors the size of a volleyball court, with string
defining the boundaries. Blindfolds on the eyes of every player
ensure that even those with limited vision cannot see. One person
has eight seconds to toss the ball, hoping to roll it past the
opposition to the goal. The opposition can block it and throw it
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine playing soccer with hands, completely in the dark,''
Andre explained.
</P>
<P>
   Since no one can see the ball, players must use their sense of
hearing and intuition. So the game requires silence for players to
``listen'' to the direction of the ball. As a result, the coach and
the spectators cannot speak or cheer during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange to play a game to a quiet crowd,'' Patty added.
``But it's incredibly rewarding when you score the final goal and
hear people holler from the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Brown, 19, was first introduced to the sport when he was
studying at the New York Institute for Special Education. ``It's a
stress releaser,'' he said. ``I like the competitive nature of the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dan Parisi, the team's coach, goalball teams
receives little public or private funding, though the New York
association gets some money from fundraising efforts and private
donations. The members of Local 1104 of the Communications Workers
of America, of which Parisi is vice president, donates some money.
``The donation is helpful, but they're not enough to cover all
expenses,'' said Parisi, 54, who volunteers his time to coach and
drive the team to tournaments. ``But the athletes make do with what
they have and they haven't missed a tournament yet.'' The team
members pay for their own uniforms and travel expenses when they
have to.
</P>
<P>
   Parisi, who has his sight but became involved after seeing a
goalball tournament in 1984, said that the lack of support,
particularly from large corporations, prevents many blind athletes
from competing. ``A lot of big companies would rather fund an
able-bodied athlete so that they could put that person in front of
a Wheaties box,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't stop people like Dawn Davids, who is 37. ``Goalball
is so fun that we pay to play,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the monetary hurdles, the athletes say they manage to
travel and play in every regional or national competition. ``We
work too hard to miss any games,'' said Eason.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they enjoy developing relationships with
teammates and opponents on the court, forming a national network of
goalball players. Patty and Andre met in a Paralympic event 12
years ago and have been married for the past six years. They are
close with the coterie of blind athletes all over the nation,
thanks to the year-round competitions. ``You see these people more
often than your family members in a year,'' Patty says with a
laugh. They also exchange correspondence through e-mail and meet in
Internet chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the court, everyone is the same,'' Davids said. ``Goalball
is predictable, you know what to do with the ball. In the real
world, there are barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   Parisi added: ``The sanctuary is within the court.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
