<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-ADOPTING-MINEFIEL     04-21 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ADOPTING-MINEFIELD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ADOPTING' A MINEFIELD HALF A WORLD AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Nathan Hegedus is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By NATHAN HEGEDUS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUSONJE, CROATIA _ A small tree grows from the shattered roof of
the Serbian Orthodox Church in this eerily tranquil village. Bombed
houses settle into the mud, and elderly caretakers tread cautiously
among the graves of a dilapidated cemetery. Neither the dead nor
anyone else finds peace in Kusonje where hidden land mines are a
constant menace.
</P>
<P>
   Some four miles down the road, another Orthodox cemetery, in
Pakrac, holds the same dangers, its centuries-old gravestones
standing sentry over a terror that makes homage to the deceased a
deadly risk.
</P>
<P>
   The two cemeteries laden with land mines are ominous reminders
of the four-year &UR;  &LR; war that virtually destroyed this rural area of
eastern Croatia and left villagers fearing for the lives of
children at play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is constant fear they will go to a minefield,'' said
Obrad Ivanovic, who heads a local nonprofit group providing
services to ethnic Serbs. ``We feel trapped as if we were captured
and put in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, a New York church group is determined to erase the
danger of those church sites. The Hudson Valley Presbytery,
consisting of 95 Presbyterian churches in seven New York counties,
this year raised $27,600 to remove the mines in Pakrac and Kusonje.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could deal with an overwhelming problem and feel like we
were actually doing something,'' said Jennifer Watts, the volunteer
who organized the Presbytery's fundraising. Thirty-four of the
Presbytery's 95 churches contributed money, working through the
``Adopt-a-Minefield'' program of the nonprofit United Nations
Association-USA. It matches donors with minefields in Croatia,
Bosnia, Afghanistan, Mozambique and Cambodia _ a few of the 70
countries worldwide where 26,000 people lose their lives to mines
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Since launching the program last March, UNA-USA has managed to
have 50 minefields ``adopted'' at costs ranging from $20,000 to
$40,000 each, according Oren Schlein, the New York-based director.
The United Nations Development Program coordinates the mine
clearance.
</P>
<P>
   At the Huguenot Memorial Church in Pelham Manor, N.Y., Sunday
school teachers showed a UNA-USA video of children whose legs were
blown off in a mine blast.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Virginia Lunt said she fled the room in horror when
the video showed mine-clearing equipment exploding the mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think where or who we help matters,'' she said. ``We
are all created by God and God's children should help each other.''
The Sunday school students raised $357 for the cause with a bake
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard one young father at the bake sale say, `We have to buy
something. This is important. This is significant,''' said Jean
Tischler, the church's director of Christian education. ``Another
parent told me that because of the video her children realized the
real impact violence has on families and individual lives.''
</P>
<P>
   At other churches, parishioners took up special collections or
donated money from parish funds. The youth group at the Hitchcock
Presbyterian Church in Scarsdale sought sponsors by cleaning a
local park.
</P>
<P>
   All of the funds are designated to pay professional companies to
``de-mine'' roughly 42,600 square feet in Pakrac and Kusonje, where
Croat and Serb forces battled between 1991 and 1995, according to
Per Kvarsnik, the regional adviser to the UN Mine Action Center in
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The professionals use metal detectors, explosive-sniffing dogs
and spades, knives and scissors. They poke the ground at one-inch
intervals with metal rods to detect mines that range in size from
that of a hockey puck to cylinders the size of car tires. Officials
said the Pakrac and Kusonje sites could be cleared within weeks
once the contractor was chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Outside those sites, an estimated 12,000 mines remain around
Pakrac, a fraction of the 400,000 mines laid in Croatia during the
war. Military maps of the mines around Kusonje have been lost so no
one really knows the extent of hidden danger there, said Kvarsnik.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing the Pakrac and Kusonje sites may encourage the return
of Serbian villagers, more than 80 percent of whom fled the war in
1995, said Schlein.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a little contribution to a larger effort in which
people return and reclaim their lives,'' he said, noting that many
returning Serbs have no place to live or work.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic, who worries still about land mines hidden beyond the
church sites being cleared, said he would like a chance to thank
the New York churches for helping.
</P>
<P>
   But few other local people seem to know about their American
benefactors. In Kusonje, four elderly returnees sit in the one
heated room of a brick house and drink thick Turkish coffee. They
don't care who clears the mines. They just want to live without
fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will never find a man brave enough to say he is not afraid
of mines,'' said Marinko Radojcic, 60, a sturdy, round ex-factory
worker wearing a thick sweater and a black Nike hat. ``But with no
church or graveyard, the culture of our nation would be lost. There
would be no history of our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Jacqui Buchanan at Huguenot Sunday school in New
York, sees it in terms a little less global. ``It doesn't matter
how big or small the place is _ just that there is one more safe
place and one less family in danger.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
