<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TESTBAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN SEEN TAKING UPPER HAND IN COMING TALKS WITH US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Suddenly, arms control is all the rage in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of Russia's parliament upstaged the United
States Friday when it overwhelmingly ratified a treaty banning
global nuclear testing. President Clinton was unable to persuade
the US Senate to approve the same treaty last October.
</P>
<P>
   The 298-74 vote approving the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty came
exactly one week after lawmakers here broke a seven-year deadlock,
ratifying the 1993 START II strategic arms control treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's rapid-fire ratification of the two pacts will allow
Russian President Vladimir V. Putin to claim the moral high ground
in upcoming arms control talks with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ratification gives Russia an excellent chance to seize the
initiative in nuclear arms talks,'' said Dmitry Rogozin, chairman
of the State Duma's committee on international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The test ban treaty has been signed by 154 countries. But only
52 of them, including Russia, have ratified it.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty will not go into effect unless all 44 countries with
known or suspected nuclear capability ratify it. Besides the United
States and China, other holdouts include Egypt, Pakistan, India,
and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow and Washington are at loggerheads over an array of arms
control issues. The most contentious is the Clinton
administration's desire to build a missile defense system to
protect the United States against potential attacks by what it
calls ``rogue states'' such as Iraq and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has unsuccessfully tried to persuade Moscow to
support amendments to the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty, which
prohibits missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has staunchly opposed the move, saying it would
damage Moscow's national security and upset the fragile nuclear
balance between Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's newfound interest in ratifying lingering arms accords,
analysts here said, is part of a strategy to pressure the United
States to abandon its plans to install a national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes on the eve of a series of high-profile
international arms control meetings.
</P>
<P>
   A United Nations conference on halting the spread of nuclear
weapons technology begins in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Clinton will travel to Moscow to hold his first summit
meeting with Putin, with arms control issues high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Yevgeny Volk, a defense analyst at the Heritage Foundation in
Moscow, said Russia's new approach to arms control ``is a
propaganda offensive designed to stop the American advance on
ABM.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is designed to put the Senate and the Clinton
administration in the limelight of international public opinion by
showing that Russia is interested in arms control while the US is
not,'' Volk said.
</P>
<P>
   When it ratified START II on April 14, Russia's parliament added
amendments linking it to Washington's adherence to the ABM treaty.
Legislators also approved a 1997 US-Russian protocol to START II
that pushes back from 2003 to 2007 the deadline for Moscow to scrap
its nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The US Senate, where a missile defense system has broad
bipartisan support, has yet to approve the amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans say the ABM treaty, a centerpiece of
US-Soviet strategic relations, is obsolete now that the Cold War is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said he would tear up START II and abandon any future arms
treaties with Washington if the United States breaks the
antiballistic missile treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the United States are also at loggerheads over how
deep to make the weapons cutbacks in next strategic arms treaty,
called START III.
</P>
<P>
   Under START II, the US and Russia must cut their arsenals from
6,000 warheads each to between 3,000 and 3,500.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations on START III, the Clinton administration has
called for cutting down to 2,000 to 2,500 warheads. But Russia,
which lacks the funds to maintain such an arsenal, is pushing for
deeper cuts, to 1,000 to 1,500 warheads for each side.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have suggested that Clinton and Putin could strike
a deal under which the Russians agree to a limited missile defense
system and the US accepts deeper cuts in strategic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Russia's security council approved a new military
doctrine that upgraded the role of nuclear weapons in the country's
national defense.
</P>
<P>
   The new doctrine says Russia will use nuclear weapons if
necessary to fight off a conventional attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
