<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOO OLD' HITS EARLY IN LAW ENFORCEMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ At age 37, Miklyn Provenzano is over the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she's a mother of two young daughters and walks with
a spring in her step, Provenzano is too old to get a job as a
federal law enforcement officer.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law enforcement agencies have a rule that new hires
cannot have reached their 37th birthday by the time they join. That
way, the reasoning goes, the law enforcement officers can retire at
the mandatory retirement age of 57 and receive a pension, which
requires at least 20 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law, which went into effect in 1974, covers the
gun-toting investigatory jobs in the federal government, including
those at the FBI, Postal Service, U.S. Customs Service, Drug
Enforcement Administration, U.S. Department of Agriculture, Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, U.S. Probation Department and the
U.S. Bureau of Prisons.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people try to apply who are older than 37, said U.S.
Postal Inspector William Scott. But the situation is actually
better than it was years ago when applicants had to be under 35.
That was the rule when Scott joined the postal inspectors squad.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't care about a pension and you just need a job
like Provenzano, it doesn't matter. She went through a divorce
recently and has to feed her two young children. You can't get
hired if you are older than 37.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think education will help. It doesn't matter that
Provenzano is finishing up her master's degree in criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DISCRIMINATION IRONIC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the federal government slams the door in the face of
``older'' job seekers, there is also a federal law that forbids
employers from discriminating against people who are 40 years of
age or older.
</P>
<P>
   The irony wasn't lost on Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas, who was
stunned when he heard there was an age cutoff for federal law
enforcement jobs. The government should live by the same rules as
private employers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates should be judged on whether they can physically
and mentally do the job, he said. There ought to be more important
criteria than using retirement qualifications as the basis for
hiring someone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green said he would direct his staff to look into the current
law and said that he plans to introduce legislation to open up the
jobs to all workers.
</P>
<P>
   The government says the reason for the age cutoff is to allow
the officers to retire with a pension, but Houston lawyer Joel
Androphy doesn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies, especially the FBI, want their agents young
because they want to be able to mold them to their liking, Androphy
said. They figure it's too difficult to reprogram an older person.
</P>
<P>
   Al Tribble, a special agent for the FBI in Houston, scoffed at
Androphy's suggestion. It's not easy to meet the physical
requirements to be an agent, which include running, sprinting,
push-ups, pull-ups and sit-ups.
</P>
<P>
   However, ironically, there are no mandatory physical fitness
tests for existing agents. They can eat all the donuts they want
and still stay on the force.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AGE-OLD RULES FRUSTRATING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The city of Houston also has a rule that police officers with
the Houston Police Department can't be older than 35 when they
join. However, in the city's case, it's not tied to a pension,
because there is no mandatory retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   The law dates back to the late 1940s, when the Texas Legislature
voted to allow cities with more than 10,000 residents to adopt a
maximum age for new police officers. The only exception is if the
applicant is under 45 and has five years as a peace officer or in
the military.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that if someone is 40 years old, his five to 10 to
15 years of law enforcement experience compensates for his
diminishing physical abilities, according to a lawyer for the city.
</P>
<P>
   It was all very frustrating for Provenzano as she sat in her
spacious northwest Houston home over a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a job,'' she said, her voice rising.
</P>
<P>
   While she earns some money as a substitute school teacher,
there's a job opening she's heard about that she'd like to pursue
at the federal probation office. While her 35- and 36-year-old
colleagues in her criminal justice program at the University of
Houston Clear Lake can go for it, it's beyond her reach.
</P>
<P>
   It's not fair, she said. Older people are physically fit, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
