<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BACTERIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERM-KILLER IN RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bacteria-fighting antibiotics are classic victims of their own
success. The more one antibiotic proves effective in killing off
one germ or another, the more it is used and the more quickly
mutant bacteria that are resistant to it proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   That is why US Food and Drug Administration officials want use
of the newest miracle drug, Zyvox, limited as much as possible to
hospitals and nursing homes. Because of the heavy use of
antibiotics in those settings, they are breeders of the most
dangerously resistant strains. Zyvox comes in both intravenous and
oral forms, so doctors can start patients on it at the hospital and
have them finish with it at home, but physicians would do well to
think twice before starting it on patients who are not in a
hospital or nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   In tests, Zyvox has been shown to be impressively _ but not
universally _ effective against both staph infections that resist
methicillin and enterococcus bacteria that can survive doses of
vancomycin, a long-time last-resort antibiotic. It also is
recommended for cases of hospital-acquired pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the effort of the FDA and the drug's makers,
Pharmacia and Upjohn, to stop overuse of Zyvox, its label will ask
doctors to ``carefully consider alternatives before initiating
treatment with Zyvox in the outpatient setting.'' Other antibiotics
have been used too indiscriminately both by doctors and by
livestock farmers, who often include antibiotics in their animals'
feed.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists who developed Zyvox are hopeful that bacteria
resistant to it will not spring up too quickly. The first truly new
antibiotic to be approved in 35 years, Zyvox strikes at the
bacteria life cycle at an earlier stage than other antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Developing new drugs is not the only approach medical science
has to the problem of Superbugs. Other researchers are working to
modify existing antibiotics, like tetracycline, and others seek to
reduce the need for antibiotics overall by developing preventive
vaccines against bacterial diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, it is incumbent on health officials and
practitioners to protect Zyvox from overuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
