<SLUG> BC-PROTESTER-AFTERSHOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PROTESTERS, HARD TO RETURN TO NORMAL LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Monday, Kate Purdy was saving the world from
globalization. But Tuesday was the hard part: Going back to
Hampshire College, to be a normal sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   So on Thursday, Purdy drove back to Washington. And by Friday,
four days after the anti-World Bank demonstrations ended, Purdy was
back in protest mode, joining some two dozen students and activists
from western Massachusetts who never left here at all.
</P>
<P>
   They called their mission ``solidarity,'' gathering outside the
District of Columbia jail in a vigil for the 150 or so activists
who had been held since the weekend until they were finally
released late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the students hanging around the lawn at the D.C. jail,
there seemed to be an after-shock quality to their efforts as well
_ what one student called a ``hangover,'' making it all but
impossible to return to the banality of daily life after taking on
the police, the World Bank, the economic structure of the entire
planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shifts your priorities,'' Purdy, 19, said. ``A lot of
people had a lot of trouble getting back into the academic spheres
of their minds. I think we all naively assumed things would go back
to being the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Information, none of which could be confirmed, trickled out of
the jail for days: That the prisoners were on a hunger strike. That
groups of women had taken off all their clothes to avoid being
moved by police. That scores of vegetarians were unable to eat at
all, given the nature of jail food.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the prisoners were there because they refused to give
their names, instead being labelled as Jane or John Doe. Under a
plea bargain reached late Friday, according to their lawyer, the
charges against the prisoners were reduced to jaywalking and they
were fined $5 each and released.
</P>
<P>
   Some had claimed they were mistreated in the jail but city
officials denied that.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, things have more or less returned to normal. The
last protest signs are being ripped down, and the last police
barricades outside the World Bank and International Monetary Fund
headquarters were hauled away earlier in the week. The debate is
now post-game: Did the police act too aggressively? Did the World
Bank deserve the criticism? Did the protesters know what they were
fighting for at all?
</P>
<P>
   For a handful from Massachusetts, however, as well as some
others from Washington and other cities nearby, the demonstration
never stopped. They have been at the mercy of strangers for more
than a week, sleeping first at a Jewish Community Center, and then,
more recently, on the floor of a Washington church. They have
skipped class and work. They have barely slept. Many of them have
gotten sick.
</P>
<P>
   But they seem less eager to go home than to continue bonding
with one another. And for many of the students, the atmosphere
outside the D.C. jail was not all that different from life on an
especially grungy college campus quad: Some people sat huddled
together under plastic tarps. Others sang and played the drums. A
small group did yoga. At one point, the group went on an impromptu
parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us were really prepared for what the whole arrest
experience was going to be like,'' said Sienna Baskin, 22, a
substitute teacher who graduated from Hampshire College earlier
this year. ``After I got out of jail (where she spent the night),
there was just no way I could leave until I knew everyone was
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment is what kept Kai Newkirk, 19, from going back to
his dog in western Massachusetts until early Friday. It has kept
Matthew Knoester, 25, a Roxbury public school teacher, here all
week. It is why Kazu Haga, 19, is missing work as a chef in
Amherst, and why Laura Anderson, 20, has missed history and writing
classes at Hampshire College, even though she knows doing so could
affect her grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in this kind of situation, when you have friends
in jail and hunger strikes, your perspective changes,'' Anderson
said Friday, as she crouched on a curb outside the D.C. jail under
gray skies. Nearby, beneath the painted protest signs stuck to the
make-shift tents on the jail lawn, lay giant plastic bags of bread,
cans of black beans and tins of coffee, at the ready in case a
group of prisoners was released. ``I'm not sure my professors will
be understanding. But that doesn't really matter as much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could quite explain the disproportionate number of people
from Massachusetts who hung on to the event, the first major
anti-globalization effort since last November, when thousands of
activists surprised the world by temporarily stopping the World
Trade Organization summit in Seattle. More than 1,000 Massachusetts
protesters were here over the weekend, organizers estimate.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the spirit of western Massachusetts _ long a bastion
of activism _ played a role. So did the sheer number of students,
whose schedules and idealism are at the foundation of many a noble
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just brought so many people down,'' said Haga, wearing a
black sweatshirt with Western Massachusetts emblazoned across it.
Against the bland brown backdrop of the D.C. jail, he spoke to
friends, chatted on a cell phone, and checked periodically to see
if any new information about the prisoners inside had been
released. ``We are very dedicated to staying until they get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, they were rewarded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
