<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3830 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-21 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME RANDOM THOUGHTS ON LEO, OPRAH AND OTHER WEIGHTY MATTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A week at the beach clears the mind with the vigorous efficiency
of a tropical storm, allowing one to focus on the important stuff,
such as ...
</P>
<P>
   The journalistic credentials of Leonardo DiCaprio. Some Web site
periodistas, particularly the ``media critic'' types, have treated
this dustup with the reverence accorded cleavage at the Oscars or _
gasp! _ Kathie Lee's successor. Upon learning that a mere
entertainer would get to interview the president of the United
States while card-carrying journalists stewed in their own bitter
juices _ today's special: boiled crank au jus _ some newsies were
said to be in high dudgeon, which I'm told is nothing like tall
cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the affront! An actor posing as a journalist! Why, that
would be like a ballplayer becoming a sportscaster, or an Army
general becoming a school superintendent. How silly. Where does an
actor get off thinking he can ask intelligent questions of POTUS?
Surely it is written that only well-coiffed journalists with
impressive egos, er, resumes can ask thoughtful, probing questions,
and that non-journalists are not only unworthy of an audience with
the first bubba but also incapable of pulling it off without
embarrassing themselves or the presidency. And on the off chance
that Mr. DiCaprio's interview, which was scheduled to air as part
of an ABC Earth Day special Saturday night, did include a dumb
question, what of it? It's not as if it would be the first time a
network infotainment figure had said something stupid on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that the public thinks journalists are a bunch
of smarmy, elitist microbes who have nothing better to do than
worry about their bruised feelings? That is, when they're not
contemplating ...
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of Planet Oprah. No, this isn't a snide reference
to weight fluctuations. I'm just uncomfortable when something or
someone gets big enough to qualify as a Dow Jones industrial.
Monoliths scare me, and when you've got your own TV show, a piece
of a cable channel, a book club, a production company and a
magazine with your picture on the cover every month, well, your
lith most definitely has mono. Like Disney. Microsoft. Martha
Stewart. And Hearst (which owns part of Oprah's magazine, not to
mention this newspaper).
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't the Justice Department be thinking about divvying up
Oprah into several miniliths right about now? If it doesn't, we all
know what'll be next: Oprah franchises. For only half a million
bucks and your solemn word that you won't tell anyone what Oprah is
really like, you'll be able to operate an Oprah drive-thru in your
neighborhood. Dispense Oprah's wisdom, pathos, book excerpts and
favorite recipes while interviewing your kid's Little League coach
about the importance of achieving a metaphysical oneness with the
infield fly rule. It's bound to happen, as long as Janet Reno is
busy starring in ...
</P>
<P>
   Elian, the Miniseries. When I was about 6 years old, I wanted to
live with my Uncle Joe because he drove a trailer truck every day,
which was too cool to imagine. Who knew that if I had pressed my
case in the U.S. Court of Appeals I might have forced my
station-wagon parents to relinquish me into the custody of a
relative with an 18-wheeler?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there was nothing like ``Elian, the Miniseries''
to show me the way. Back when I was 6, TV networks hadn't yet
discovered that they could create the impression of a news story
simply by reporting the same thing for weeks on end. Nowadays, the
networks and their local affiliates, in the spirit of public
service, subscribe to the no-news-is-still-news theory because it's
easier to camp out in one spot for a long time than waste expensive
gas traipsing all over the country looking for real news. This
helps explain the widely held penchant for ...
</P>
<P>
   Anniversary journalism. Born of the long-held belief that a
story should always have a news ``peg'' before it gets reported to
the masses, an anniversary is one of the flimsiest _ and most
popular _ excuses to manufacture coverage. If done well, it can
help us understand what we've learned since the original event. But
more often than not, be it the fifth anniversary of Oklahoma City
or the first anniversary of Columbine, it's little more than a
cheesy attempt to draw viewers with maudlin, manipulative
programming.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make one want to take a vacation. From
television. And, as it happens, Monday is the first day of TV
Turnoff Week, a national campaign to wean America away from the
tube. For more information, call TV-FreeAmerica at 202-887-0436,
write TV-FreeAmerica, 1611 Connecticut Ave. N.W., Suite 3A,
Washington, D.C. 20009, or visit the Web site: www.tvfa.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
