<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEALERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUCLEAR TRIGGER-LOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Jan. 25, 1995, a US weather rocket launched from Norway
caused the nuclear suitcases of Russian leaders to be activated.
Somehow Russian officers who had been informed of the scientific
rocket launch did not pass the message on. As a consequence,
Russian leaders and their nuclear advisers held an emergency
conference to decide whether they should authorize a nuclear
retaliation. It took eight fateful minutes to determine that the
rocket from Norway was not indicative of a surprise first strike
from American nuclear submarines.
</P>
<P>
   That frightful false alarm was significant for what it
demonstrated about the dangers of an unintended or accidental
nuclear war. Boris Yeltsin and his advisers came within four
minutes of the deadline for ordering a nuclear attack on the West,
according to Russia's procedures for a retaliatory
launch-on-warning.
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since that close call, the likelihood of a
nuclear catastrophe caused by a false alarm has only become
greater. The deteriorating computers and communications equipment
in Russia's nuclear command system malfunction more often. Russian
early-warning satellites and ground radar installations are more
likely than ever to produce nuclear false alarms. Underpaid,
unpaid, demoralized, and suicidal personnel in Russian nuclear
units add to the peril of an apocalyptic accident.
</P>
<P>
   The safest and most feasible method for reducing the risk of
accidental nuclear war produced by a false alarm is to de-alert the
nuclear weapons of all eight nuclear states. There are several
measures that could increase the time needed to respond to a false
alarm, but the most effective would be to remove warheads from
missiles and store them, under multinational verification, at
separate sites.
</P>
<P>
   The model for such de-alerting was the unilateral action of
George Bush in September 1991 in the aftermath of the coup attempt
in the Soviet Union. All bombs were then taken off US planes and
sequestered. When he returned to Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev
reciprocated. Those sage precautions taken by Bush and Gorbachev
should become models for the de-alerting of all nuclear missiles in
the world's current state of permanent peril.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
