<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BEOWULF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWER OF MYTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 23, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 1,000 years or more _ possibly 1,200 or 1,300 _
``Beowulf'' is a bestseller again.
</P>
<P>
   In a brilliant new translation from the Old English by Nobel
poet Seamus Heaney _ one that opens modern eyes to what Heaney
rightly calls ``a work of the greatest imaginative vitality'' _ the
Scandinavian hero strides with fresh boldness to rid the world of
the monster Grendel, ripping his arm off at the shoulder; then
Grendel's enraged mother; then, late in life, a fire-spewing
dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Many treasures of the poem are quickly apparent, from such
striking images as the reference to a stretch of ocean as ``the
gannet's bath'' to powerful passages on the dangers of power and
the loss of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us in the news business, frequently criticized for
dwelling on the violent and the sensational, may be excused for
noticing that Beowulf's three great battles dominate this story,
while his 50-year reign as king in peace and prosperity merits
three lines.
</P>
<P>
   But the more intriguing question is the reason for the book's
surprise success. Why is it jostling with the Harry Potter books
for rungs on the best-seller list?
</P>
<P>
   Why in this age of instantaneous futuristic techno-everything
are we suddenly captivated by myth, including monsters and
fire-breathing dragons?
</P>
<P>
   Possibly it has to do with the fact that our society is awash in
rationality, inundated with technology, infatuated with money and
speed.
</P>
<P>
   In such a soulless world, myth has obvious appeal. We want to
believe that something magical can still happen. That it's easy to
tell the white hats from the black. That heroes and goodness can
conquer evil. That in our most desperate hour there is still hope
that the wizard will come to save us.
</P>
<P>
   So these books are comforting now. But it has been said that
myth is embraced by all ages. Certainly, ``Beowulf'' and Harry
Potter are both read eagerly by small children at bedtime and also
by graying adults. No matter that one work is months old and the
other has crossed the millenia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
