<HEADLINE>
ATTN. EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On Sunday, April 30, the 25th anniversary of the fall
of Saigon, The Boston Globe will publish a 20-page special Vietnam
retrospective. Included in the package, to move in advance on
Thursday, April 27, with photos, a map and graphics, are:
</P>
<P>
   --A lead essay by Globe Editorial Page Editor H.D.S. Greenway,
and five additional ``postcards'' from Vietnam and Cambodia which
serve as the narrative spine of the section. Greenway covered
Vietnam regularly from 1967 to 1975 for both Time magazine and The
Washington Post. Since 1975, he has returned to the country six
times for the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   --An exclusive essay by Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist and
author David Halberstam, who writes about why Vietnam has been so
stubborn in lingering in the American psyche.
</P>
<P>
   --An exclusive commentary by Pulitzer Prize-winning author Neil
Sheehan, who argues that Vietnam actually helped America because it
made us less willing to become the world's policeman.
</P>
<P>
   --An overview by Globe Deputy Managing editor Ben Bradlee Jr.
describing Vietnam today.
</P>
<P>
   --Four retrospective essays by Americans who had a range of
experiences -- from fighting in the war to going to Canada to evade
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   --A feature on the war's impact on the arts, which led to its
own genre of books, movies and music that changed the American
culture.
</P>
<P>
   --A feature on Vietnam from the perspective of 20-somethings,
more of whom are taking an increasing number of college courses on
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   --A feature on the feelings of Vietnam veterans today.
</P>
<P>
   -- An editorial, and three op-ed pieces by Vietnamese with
different perspectives: a Hanoi poet, a former North Vietnamese
Army officer who accepted the surrender of Saigon but has since
defected, and a Vietnamese-American who argues it is time for those
in the exile community here to bury the hatchet with Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   For questions, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the Boston
Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS designator and
move under the  &UR; International (i)  &LR; category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 1954EDT &QL; 
