<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3838 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-21 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEFINING MOMENT AT FOXBORO STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As we sat there this week watching the video sweeping
us into new $325 million Foxboro Stadium on the wings of reality,
my mind shot back to the opening days of its predecessor, the
former Schaefer Stadium, a marvel of modern construction at a cost
of $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference 29 years can make. The next new stadium for
only $319 million more. But as fancy-schmancy as it's going to be,
it will never open with the same drama produced on Saturday, Aug.
28, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Super Flush. Perhaps the critical day in Patriots history.
</P>
<P>
   There we were, your humble servant and a handful of others,
suddenly called upon to save the franchise. It wasn't easy, even
though we still had our own teeth and hair in those days. Reaching
back with every ounce of strength and stamina to save the stadium
from disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember what happened?'' said Bob Marr, former Patriots
president, whose brother, Dan, was the stadium's prime mover. How
could I forget? I was one of the heroes of Super Flush, but I'll
continue to be humble and let Bob Marr tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had played the first game ever in the stadium two weeks
before against the New York Giants and we had a disaster,'' he
said. ``At half, when the people went to the restrooms, the urinals
and toilets wouldn't work. We didn't have enough water pressure in
the stadium to make them work properly. You can just imagine the
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, the Patriots were due to host the Los Angeles
Rams in another preseason game. The state board of health
threatened to call off the game unless it could be assured the
urinals and toilets would work. On Saturday noon, on a boiling hot
day, a couple of sportswriters, a few owners' sons, and one or two
Patriot locker room employees were suddenly caught up in Super
Flush.
</P>
<P>
   The two people from the board told the Patriots the game had to
be canceled unless the team could demonstrate that the pressure
would work under pressure. Then someone came up with an insane
idea: Let's try to simulate what would happen at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it might have sounded reasonable _ if we had a person for
each of the nearly 500 stalls. But there were only seven or eight
of us. Nevertheless, we pushed on.
</P>
<P>
   It was decided that Super Flush would work this way: All of us,
standing in front of the main office building, at the word from the
state, would rush to assigned bathrooms, then, waiting for another
signal, would rush up and down, flushing our little heads off as
fast as we could.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a dozen of us were supposed to do the work of hundreds
and then return to home base.
</P>
<P>
   Back we came, sweaty, gamey, but flushed with the glow of
success.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, said the state employees, telling us they weren't
quite sure of their readings.
</P>
<P>
   About that time the rest of us were sure we'd like to kill the
two of them. But they were professional state employees. They stood
in the shade and gave orders while the rest of us hauled butt and
flushed.
</P>
<P>
   Back we went up the hill again, racing to our destinations, and
running madly through the empty restrooms, hearts pumping (even if
the toilets weren't) and wrists aching.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all worth it. The state gave the OK. The game could
go on. Some 53,000 could be entertained, feeling assured that they
could relieve themselves at the appropriate moments. But the day
didn't turn out that great. The Rams whacked the Patriots, 31-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized then we had a big problem,'' said Marr. ``The
system in the stadium, as it was, wasn't going to work. So we had
to spend another $250,000 and build the big water tank down there
in a hurry. Once we did it, that solved the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. There were other problems. For example, when Roman
Gabriel, a lanky 6-foot-4-inch quarterback for the Rams, went to
use a urinal in the visiting locker room, he came back and offered
to his teammates, ``These guys must have one of the biggest teams
in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The urinals in the visiting locker rooms had been placed too
high by the construction workers and had to be redone.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 19 came the season opener and a stunning victory for
the Patriots over the powerful Oakland Raiders. The Patriots,
behind a rookie named Jim Plunkett, rolled to a 20-6 victory. As
the fallen Raiders lamented their loss, some pipes burst in their
locker rooms, dumping you know what on some of the players.
</P>
<P>
   It was later discovered somebody, allegedly unhappy that
nonunion workers had been employed during construction, threw
planks and boulders into the pipes before they were sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's a prediction: Things will not go as smoothly as we
think from here on in with the beautiful (and it is a great-looking
stadium) facility in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the off-site parking lot owners are threatening a
boycott this year. They say they may close their lots or not even
apply for licenses because they feel they are being taxed too much
by the state to help defray the $70 million the state is putting
into the project for infrastructure. I'm told there are 8,000
off-site parking spots and the owners are being charged $50 per
spot, per year, by the state, which they think is too much.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I'm told, that even though the ``squatters'' (no pun
intended) are selling their homes in the trailer park at the back
of the property, there are a handful that are holding out and who
might try to make a noisy last stand. Reportedly, several of them
have guns and can be heard practicing. Who knows? We may have
another standoff. Talk about fanfare. The stadium can open with a
shootout. It would beat a flyover, any day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of stadiums, the Red Sox say they will hand over their
financial plan to the city and state within two weeks. I'll believe
it when I see it. But when it comes, the fun will be to see which
politician runs for cover the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   If I were running the Red Sox, I'd be dealing with the City of
Revere already, trying to get a park built on Suffolk Downs
property on the East Boston line. If Boston doesn't think it's a
big deal, build it somewhere else and let the politicians explain
about how downtown Boston became a wasteland when the Sox pulled
out of town. Baltimore, Cleveland, and Detroit were all dying
downtown, and built stadiums to revitalize those cities. Bob Kraft
has to be on the hook for $325 million to build the stadium in
Foxborough. When the Red Sox' plan comes out, they will want to put
up $350 million to build a new Fenway Park, which is more than any
other team, in any other sport, has ever put up to build a stadium
_ and they're going to get a hard time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's my spin on Pat Burns. The Bruins realized how popular he
was with the media and fans, while at the same time weren't pleased
with the team's style of play. In the meetings with Burns, team
president Harry Sinden emphasized that if Burns was going to coach
the final year of his contract, then Burns would have to switch
from his defensive-minded approach to an aggressive, offensive
game. Obviously, Burns and Sinden thought they could coexist with
their agreement on how things are going to be done next season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The talent hunt for the Bruins and Celtics: The hockey team will
look for another defenseman, most likley in free agency. And
they'll probably draft a young defenseman with their first pick in
the draft, seventh overall. With Ray Bourque gone, the Bruins have
to find another defenseman who can step in and play right away.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics will be looking to draft a big guard who can be a
stopper on defense. Kenny Anderson and Paul Pierce, excellent
offensive players, can't get it done on the defensive end. However,
getting this type of guard in the draft is not going to be easy.
Celtics top scout Leo Papile thinks there'll be at least 11 good
players in the draft. So, depending on where the Celtics select
(and they'll draft no lower than No. 11), a good player should be
on the board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some NFL personnel types think that the Patriots' top pick,
Adrian Klemm, has a chance to be an excellent pass-blocking
offensive tackle, but question whether he will be a good run
blocker. Klemm played in a run-and-shoot offense at the University
of Hawaii last season. But the Patriots say the previous year, when
he played in a run-oriented offense, he showed he had the potential
to be a good run blocker. Others say their second pick, J.R.
Redmond of Arizona State, is a third-down back. But Colts general
manager Bill Polian doesn't agree. ``Redmond is a power runner,''
he said. ``He can run through people. He's an every-down back, as
far as I'm concerned, and a good one. I couldn't believe he stayed
on the board until the third round. So I think it's a heck of a
pick for New England.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
