u f BC-UBS-PIONEER-BOS &LR;      04-21 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UBS-PIONEER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGEST SWISS BANK SEEKING PIONEER FUNDS, SOURCES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Switzerland's biggest bank is a leader in the bidding
for Pioneer Funds, sources close to the situtation said, as the
Boston mutual fund group faces investor pressure to find a buyer by
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The sources say Union Bank of Switzerland has taken the lead in
a bidding process that began in February, when Pioneer hired two
investment bankers to shop the 72-year-old firm. Pioneer is
expected to announce a buyer before its May 16 annual shareholders'
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   UBS's U.S.-based asset management group is Brinson Partners Inc.
of Chicago, which oversees $359 billion for institutions and in
mutual funds. UBS Brinson has bought other small U.S. investment
managers and is often seen as a buyer of American fund groups.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer manages about $24.5 billion of assets and has a long
history as a ``value'' player, or a firm that buys beaten-up stocks
rather than the growth technology stocks that have been dominating
the market in recent years. Brinson manages both growth and value
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer declined to comment on the bidders. In a letter to
shareholders last week, the company said, ``. . .your board is very
encouraged by the expressions of interest received to date.''
</P>
<P>
   Lens Investment Management of Portland, Maine, an activist
investor group, has launched a proxy fight against Pioneer. It
suggests the fund group could fetch between $29 per share and $42
per share in a sale, or between $760 million and $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer shares closed last week at $23.3125, down 25 cents. The
shares have risen 48 percent since Jan. 1, fueled by the buyout
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have suggested that the upper end of the range Lens
suggests would be rich for a firm that has failed to grow
significantly while rivals have surged ahead in the bull market.
However, a source said Fleet Financial Group bid aggressively for
Pioneer and was edged out, as were other bidders, by UBS.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bennett, director of governance for Lens, said the
suggested sale numbers were reasonable based on deals done in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Lens, in addition to pushing for a sale of Pioneer, is looking
to replace half of the fund company's board with its own nominees.
Pioneer, in the letter to shareholders last week, urged investors
not to approve Lens's nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Other large investors are interested in seeing Pioneer sold.
Mario Gabelli's Gabelli Funds of Rye, N.Y., hold an 8.9 percent
stake in Pioneer, and he has said he's for a sale. Southeastern
Asset Management Inc. of Memphis owns 17.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer's chairman, John F. Cogan Jr., holds 13.6 percent of the
shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
