<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GOMEZ-HOMESEEKERS-BOS     04-21 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOMEZ-HOMESEEKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVADA WEB REALTY SERVICE DISPUTES GOMEZ RANKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Nevada-based Internet real estate service is picking a fight
with a popular Web site rating service run by Gomez Advisors Inc.
</P>
<P>
   On its own Web site, Gomez touts the ``rigorous methodology''
behind its surveys. But HomeSeekers.com Inc. of Reno says two Gomez
surveys of their site were riddled with factual errors that led to
a poor score.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent ranking, Gomez, based in Lincoln, Mass.,
rated HomeSeekers ninth out of 20 real estate Web sites it surved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of hate mail from investors'' after the first
negative report in March, said company spokeswoman Pamela Johnston.
And though she has no firm data on whether the report drove away
customers, Johnston feared the worst.
</P>
<P>
   HomeSeekers hoped to boost its score by finding out exactly what
qualities Gomez looks for in a Web site. So HomeSeekers paid Gomez
$35,000 in order to gain access to the company's research tools and
data. But HomeSeekers chief engineer John Hensley says that Gomez
still refuses to reveal all of its rating criteria, making it
difficult for him to know what features of his site ought to be
improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was unreasonable they won't show the criteria
they judge everybody on,'' said HomeSeekers' chief engineer, John
Hensley. ``Even to a paying customer they won't show it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez spokeswoman Julie Ward dismissed the HomeSeekers complaint
as sour grapes from a disgruntled customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ranting,'' Ward said. She refused to comment further,
saying that because Gomez filed for a initial public stock offering
on Thursday, federal securities regulations forbid a detailed
discussion of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Web-site rankings are a notoriously subjective business, but
Gomez asserts that it bases its measurements on a set of
``consistent, objective, and replicable'' standards called Gomez
Scorecards. The company uses between 150 and 250 criteria for
judging a site's performance.
</P>
<P>
   But Hensley said that even after paying a subscription fee to
the company, Gomez would reveal only 35 of the criteria it uses. As
a result, he said, it was impossible for HomeSeekers to figure out
what it needed to do to get a better ranking.
</P>
<P>
   And as for the 35 criteria HomeSeekers was allowed to see,
Hensley claims some of them contained incorrect data about the
company. For example, Gomez said that the HomeSeekers site did not
include a mortgage payment calculator. In fact, the site does have
this feature. Hensley claims there are several other errors, each
of them tending to depress HomeSeekers' final score.
</P>
<P>
   For now, HomeSeekers is fighting back by publicly denouncing
Gomez' alleged inaccuracies. The company hopes the media attention
will make up for any bad publicity from the Gomez ranking. Asked
whether the company might take legal action against Gomez, Johnston
replied: ``At this time, we don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
