<HEADLINE>
GORE HOLDS FIRST NEWS CONFERENCE IN TWO MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., skedded earlier as GORE-TRUCKS)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROMULUS, Mich. _ After two months of keeping his distance from
the journalists who travel with him, Vice President Al Gore held
his first news conference since Feb. 19 on Friday in this auto city
30 miles from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he held a news conference at all, speaking for 23
minutes, seemed more noteworthy than what he said.
</P>
<P>
   He maintained his position on Elian Gonzalez, saying the boy's
family should be encouraged to get together and resolve the
dispute, declining to say whether he believed the Justice
Department should retrieve the boy from the home of his Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   To those who have faulted him for not lobbying aggressively for
permanent trade relations for China, he said he had called ``a
bunch'' of members of Congress, but would not say how many or whom.
``And I've made some progress in my calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore credited the minority leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, for handling his disagreement with the administration's
view on the trade bill ``in a very classy way.''
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside political questions, saying, ``I am not a very
good political analyst.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not taken questions on the record from his traveling
press corps since Feb. 19 in Springfield, Mass. Chris Lehane, his
press secretary, said of the end of the drought Friday, ``We had
time on the schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   So much time that during lunch aides rushed out to print up
buttons that said: ``I was at Al Gore's first general election
press conference,'' dated April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, Gore's Republican rival, holds
news conferences with his traveling press corps nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane insisted that Gore had not been avoiding reporters. ``We
make ourselves extremely accessible,'' Lehane said. ``We've given
hundreds of interviews during the course of this campaign and in
the last six weeks of this campaign to virtually every news
organization.'' Gore has held open meetings where he has taken
questions from voters.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore confidant, pointing to the lack of news conferences
during the primaries, said: ``We were in a very strong position and
it didn't make much sense to try to change the formula.'' But some
Gore aides have worried about tension building up with the press
courps, and campaign officials now assert that news conferences
will be held more regularly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
