<SLUG> BC-MA-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER JOBLESS, MORE JOBS IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts job creation continued at a brisk pace
last month, as the state's unemployment rate fell to 2.4 percent,
the fifth-lowest of any state.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Department of Employment and Training reported
Friday that a surge in hiring by construction and service
companies, a broad category that also includes software development
and consulting, more than offset job losses in the manufacturing
and trade industries.
</P>
<P>
   An increase in total employment of 1,200, on a seasonally
adjusted basis, pushed the jobless rate down from 3.1 percent in
February _ a steep 0.7 percentage-point drop.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' rate of joblessness ranks behind Iowa, New
Hampshire, South Dakota, and Connecticut. Nebraska and Vermont tied
Massachusetts, with 2.4 percent rates.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Winer, the state's chief economist, said such a large
decline for a single month is due in part to a statistical fluke.
Nevertheless, he said the state experienced its tenth consecutive
months of rising employment levels in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to add jobs at a strong pace,'' Winer said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' jobless rate is far below the national rate of
4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the state has increased employment by nearly 2
percent in a growing economy that has stretched its labor force to
its limits. Construction firms, due to a strong housing market and
work on the Central Artery/Tunnel project, hired 1,500 workers last
month. That resulted in a strong 7.7 percent rate of job growth
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Service companies last month gained 3,400 jobs, giving the
sector an annual growth rate of 3.2 percent. Driving that
performance was a 6.6 percent annual rate of job creation in the
high-tech, non-manufacturing industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
