<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBJECTIONS VOICED TO DEPICTION OF JEWS IN FAMOUS PASSION PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Western Christians, Saturday is the midpoint of a three-day
period freighted with enormous spiritual power. Friday was Good
Friday, which commemorated the crucifixion of Jesus, and Sunday
will be Easter, when believers proclaim his resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   The story can be experienced anew each year, providing many with
a sense of spiritual renewal and a hope for society's
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, amid an increasing awareness of religious
pluralism, some may wonder how to declare faith in a theological
triumph, yet avoid sounding triumphalistic, at the expense of
others who do not share their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   That question would seem pertinent, given the coming debut of an
internationally famous cultural event, the passion play at
Oberammergau, a German village whose residents have regularly
staged a version of the biblical events surrounding the
crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   The play, performed about once a decade since the 1600s, will
open in May and run through summer, attracting thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Among invited guests will be Rabbi Leon Klenicki, director of
interreligious affairs at the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith. He has long taken an interest in the event and, along with
others, has urged its organizers to remove anti-Jewish elements
from the script.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Klenicki said, the play ``reflected a sort of a
medieval view'' that blamed the Jewish people for the death of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The play's organizers began revisions in the 1980s, he said, and
important changes have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a report released by the league, Klenicki said that
while the organizers are to be congratulated on the revisions,
concerns remained, such as how the script depicts the Jews of
Jesus' time.
</P>
<P>
   Critical comments, Klenicki added, did not mean opposition to
staged portrayals of the trial and crucifixion of Jesus. Instead,
he said, ``We are against a negative interpretation of Jews and
Judaism based on the passion of Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, so too, he noted, was the Second Vatican Council of
the Roman Catholic Church. From an interfaith standpoint, the most
important of the council's reforms was its Declaration on the
Relationship of the Church to Non-Christian Religions, adopted in
1965. The statement deplored anti-Semitism and rejected the idea
that the Jews could be blamed for the death of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Orbis Books reissued a landmark history of the
council, ``Vatican Council II,'' by the Rev. Francis X. Murphy, who
reported on that event under the pseudonym Xavier Rynne. His
description of the debate over the declaration is a reminder of how
controversial the document was at the time, many years before the
Vatican would recognize Israel as a country.
</P>
<P>
   As for the play, it will be the subject of a book,
``Oberammergau: The Troubling Story of the World's Most Famous
Passion Play,'' by a Columbia University professor, James Shapiro,
to be published in May by Pantheon Books.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing the Death Penalty
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic peace organization, Pax Christi USA, used the
occasion of Good Friday to call for the end of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the organization said that its ``unconditional
opposition'' to capital punishment was based on ``the gospel of
Jesus Christ and in the consistent ethic of life, which teaches
that all life is sacred from the moment it begins until its natural
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholics who share that view have received encouragement from
church leaders. The American bishops published a statement against
capital punishment last year. More dramatic was the successful
effort by Pope John Paul II, while visiting the United States in
January 1999, to persuade Gov. Mel Carnahan of Missouri to commute
a convicted murderer's death sentence to life in prison without
parole.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the Resurrection
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America, with 1.5 million
members, hoped to remind people that not all Christians celebrate
Easter this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That day will be Palm Sunday for 250 million Eastern Orthodox
Christians, who follow a different liturgical calendar than their
Western counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   To mark Orthodox Holy Week, Archbishop Demetrios, the
archdiocese's leader, released an encyclical on the theological
meaning of Christ's resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on the 15th chapter of the Apostle Paul's First Letter
to the Corinthians, the archbishop wrote: ``The flesh he assumed in
the incarnation, although sinless, was like our own, susceptible to
death; the flesh that he raised in his three-day resurrection is
splendid and powerful, for he graced the perishable with
imperishability and the corruptible with incorruption.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
