<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ORGANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TRANSPLANT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, April 24, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the great advances in medicine in recent decades has been
doctors' ability to transplant organs into patients who would die
without them. Unfortunately, there are never enough organs for
those who need them, and last year 4,800 patients died before a
transplant could save them.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors and health officials have long believed that fewer
patients would die on waiting lists if there were a better way to
distribute organs as they become available. The Clinton
administration took this to heart and last month invoked
regulations that make medical urgency more important than
geographic location in distributing organs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system that had been in place, the country was divided
into 62 areas and 11 regions, and an organ was offered first to
patients within the donor's area and then region. This often meant
sicker patients elsewhere didn't have a chance at the organ, and
waiting times varied greatly from state to state. The
administration's more national distribution system makes better
sense and is overdue.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a motherhood and apple pie position, but it's
not. The old system tended to ensure a steady supply of organs for
the smaller transplant centers around the country. (There are 278
centers altogether.) A system based on medical urgency will steer
more organs toward the major centers, including Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Congressmen from districts with smaller centers helped pass a
House bill recently to block the new administration regulations. In
the Senate, the health committee last week passed a bill written by
Senators Edward Kennedy and Bill Frist, a Republican from Tennessee
who was a transplant surgeon before his election. Their measure
would let the Clinton administration regulations stand and would
set up a carefully crafted system for resolving organ-policy
disputes between the secretary of health and human services and the
Organ Procurement and Transplantation Network board.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy-Frist bill merits support as a way to make sure that
patients get the greatest possible benefit from the skills of
transplant surgeons and the generosity of donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
