<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OUTLETS BARRED FROM WHITE HOUSE TRAVEL BECAUSE OF DEBTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has been hopscotching the nation
and the world in the final year of his presidency, following a
frenetic schedule that shows no signs of letting up. But dozens of
news organizations have been barred from traveling along because of
outstanding debts, and the list may be growing.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Travel Office has restricted organizations
ranging from the Weekly Standard to the national television network
of Chile from participating in official White House trips. The
debts, according to the White House, range from $4.31 owed by
Esquire magazine to $10,131.71 past due from a group named
I'talio-Americano.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to recover the money, the White House Travel
Office recently began to bill the news organizations that travel
regularly with the president for the nearly $74,000 in bad debt of
other media outlets. The plan was endorsed by the White House
Correspondents Association, a group of news organizations that
cover the White House, but some media outlets, including The
Washington Post and The New York Times, are balking at paying
others' bills.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times has refused to pay $5,777.52, which the White
House says is its share of the other organizations' bad debt. The
White House has said that failure to pay the March 13 bill within
90 days may result in a newspaper being barred from future travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not our debts, and no one has explained to me why
we're responsible for the debts of other people,'' said Joseph
Lelyveld, the executive editor of The Times. He called the threat
to cut off The Times from presidential travel ``crude and almost
childish.''
</P>
<P>
   Other major outlets, including The Los Angeles Times and USA
Today, have opted to pay the debts. Susan Page of USA Today, the
outgoing president of the correspondents association, defended the
plan in a letter to news organizations last month. ``We believe
that this reallocation method represents an accurate and fair tool
to balance our books,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The news media pays its own way while trailing Clinton. A small
pool of reporters travels along on Air Force One while the rest of
the press corps flies on a separate press plane. The Travel Office,
which works with White House staff as well as the press, arranges
charter flights, hotel accommodations and other logistics.
</P>
<P>
   Some organizations on the bad debt list contend that Travel
Office billed them improperly. White House officials said they
would not discuss the billing.
</P>
<P>
   William Kristol, publisher of the Weekly Standard, said his
magazine had been challenging a White House charge of $504.97 since
1996, when a reporter traveled with the president to Jerusalem for
the funeral of Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Kristol said the reporter, David Brooks, told the White House he
merely wanted to fly to and from Jerusalem on the press plane but
did not require any space in the press center the White House
typically sets up at presidential events, or any food or ground
transportation. But Brooks did hop on the press bus at the airport,
Kristol said, prompting the White House to bill him for all the
ground services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kristol said he had no idea his organization had been
barred from White House travel and was also unaware that the debts
were being passed along to other organizations. ``I'm totally
stunned,'' he said. ``I have heard nothing from the White House for
years about this.''
</P>
<P>
   To prevent future bad debts, the Travel Office has instituted a
new policy that requires organizations that have never traveled
before to pay up front on costly foreign trips. Most of the
organizations that owe money are foreign media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Paying up front is the way White House travel was handled in
previous presidencies. But early in the Clinton administration,
presidential aides fired the seven-member Travel Office staff,
accusing them of financial mismanagement in their handling of press
trips and ordering a FBI investigation. The new office began
billing media organizations, which has proven to be a cumbersome
process.
</P>
<P>
   No fired workers were ever found guilty of any violations, and
the way the White House handled the matter was eventually
investigated by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. Starr's
replacement, Robert Ray, is expected to issue a report on the
matter in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel investigation also has affected the
current situation with billing. The White House has said that Starr
subpoenaed Travel Office records and held them so long that some
bills were not paid. Among them is a $300,000 AT&AMP;T bill from early
in the president's first term that the telephone company has
subsequently reduced to about $100,000. Because of the long delay,
officials have said they are uncertain for which trips the phone
bill applies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
