<HEADER>
A3858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-BLOCK-NYT &LR;      04-21 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMUEL BLOCK, 60, CIVIL RIGHTS HERO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Calif., Vt.)   By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samuel Block, who was repeatedly beaten and imprisoned as he
fought for voting rights for blacks in his native Mississippi Delta
during the 1960s, died April 13 in his Los Angeles apartment, his
sister Margaret said. He was 60.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Block said the cause of death remained undetermined, though
her brother was a diabetic and suffered from a number of maladies.
The family is arranging an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Block was a field secretary for the Student
Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, which helped blacks register to
vote in the face of stiff opposition from whites. He brought raw
physical courage, limitless energy and a fine singing voice to the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   He became the point man for the registration effort in a key
battleground: Greenwood, Miss. Greenwood was a cotton trading
center where the racist White Citizens Councils maintained their
regional headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Medgar Evers, leader of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People who was killed in 1963, had revoked
the charter of the local NAACP chapter because of its tepid
response to the infamous lynching of Emmett Till in Greenwood in
1955.
</P>
<P>
   In Block's first six months in Greenwood, Look magazine reported
in 1963, he managed to sign up only five black voters.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, after one of Block's arrests, a judge offered to
suspend his sentence if he would agree to stop working for the
SNCC, give up the voter registration project and leave town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge,'' Block replied. ``I ain't gonna do none of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Moses, an organizer for the SNCC who campaigned at
Block's side, sometimes in the face of gunshots, said the civil
rights workers faced a stark challenge in Greenwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when you go into a place like that,'' he said,
``you become a flash point for the authorities' and local people's
anger and frustration. You're basically seen as responsible for
starting all this.''
</P>
<P>
   James Travis, who was shot in the head and neck as he drove a
car with several SNCC colleagues in Greenwood in 1963, called Block
``very smart'' and ``fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He went through a lot,'' Travis said. ``He was beaten and
jailed on many occasions. He was dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Theodore Block was born in July 1939 in Cleveland, Miss.
His father was a construction worker and his mother was a maid.
</P>
<P>
   Block's feisty nature was apparent in the ninth grade, when he
refused to take an IQ test at the segregated school he attended.
``He said it didn't have anything to do with our culture and the
way we lived,'' his sister Margaret said. As a result, despite a
brilliant academic record, he was forced to repeat the ninth grade
Ms. Block said her brother is still known as one of the best
drummers in the town. In high school he played with other students
in a group called the East Side Jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, he enlisted in the Air Force,
but asthma led to a medical discharge the next year. He studied
political science for two years at Marlboro College in Marlboro,
Vt., then transferred to Mississippi Valley State College in Itta
Bena, Miss., a traditionally black college. He was expelled for his
civil rights activities, Margaret Block said.
</P>
<P>
   His difficulty in these activities, even at a black college,
reflected the precipice on which civil rights campaigners were
forced to balance. Often, other blacks were reluctant to associate
with them for fear of reprisal. For another example, when Block
first arrived in Greenwood, he was forced to sleep in cars for four
months because no one would give him a bed, Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   His own family, however, supported the movement and let the
Freedom Riders fighting for equal access to transportation stay in
their house. The young Block became involved in the movement
through his friendship with Amzie Moore, owner of a Cleveland gas
station, who became a leading civil rights activist in the Delta.
</P>
<P>
   As described by Taylor Branch in his 1988 book, ``Parting the
Waters: America in the King Years'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), Block
became a pivotal figure in Greenwood as the town's importance in
the civil rights struggle grew. Branch wrote: ``As the one SNCC
student who lived continuously in Greenwood during the nine months
of the registration project, Block had acquired a local reputation
as a stubborn, lonely figure among the strange new breed of devout
daredevils.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch continued: ``His seventh arrest in Greenwood was a
compelling topic of conversation while he stayed in jail over the
weekend. Some people had been won over by his sheer persistence,
others by his performances in the tiny mass meetings, where he led
call-and-response spirituals in a distinctively jaunty tenor,
marked by a hint of calypso syncopation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Travis was shot by someone in a Buick with no
license plates. The SNCC and other civil rights groups made
Greenwood their national focal point, and reporters from across the
country streamed into town. Dogs were unleashed to attack
demonstrators as scores of blacks flocked to the courthouse to try
to register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Seeger brought a young Bob Dylan to sing in Greenwood,
while Dick Gregory led marches. ``We will march through your
dogs!'' Gregory cried. ``And if you get some elephants, we'll march
through them. And bring on your tigers, and we'll march through
them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of his life, Block continued to support civil
rights causes, and was planning to attend an SNCC reunion when he
died. He became active in business, manufacturing a sealant to fix
flat tires, nutritional supplements and other products. From 1984
to 1988, he was in federal prison after conviction on wire fraud
charges; he never disclosed their exact nature to family or
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Moses said Block's ultimate importance was in ``opening up''
Greenwood, one of the toughest struggles in the civil rights
movement. ``In the early years, the question was whether we could
get a beachhead,'' he said. ``That was the importance of the work
Sam did.''
</P>
<P>
   But that left another, deeper question. ``Once you got a
beachhead,'' Moses said, ``could you actually survive?''
</P>
<P>
   Block is survived by his brother, Oliver, of Dobbins, Calif.;
his sisters Margaret Block of Cleveland, Miss., Minnie Jane
Bankhead of New York City and Olivia Block of Puyallup, Wash.; a
daughter from a marriage that ended in divorce, Veronica Block of
Los Angeles, and one granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2017EDT &QL; 
