<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA PLAYOFFS ARE REALLY THE TV PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA playoffs start today. We might have a new president
before the first round is over.
</P>
<P>
   With nothing _ nothing! _ but television considerations in mind,
the league has submitted schedules that are, in some cases, so
preposterous as to be laughable. The only problem is they're very
real, and people will be forced to play them.
</P>
<P>
   Exaggeration? You decide. Let's take Indiana-Milwaukee. Game 1
is Sunday. Game 2 is Thursday. Los Angeles-Sacramento. The same.
Utah-Seattle. Game 2 is Monday. Game 3 is Saturday. New
York-Toronto. They've schdeuled 13 days for a five-game series,
with Game 3 on a Saturday and Game 4 (if) on the following Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about ratings. Forget the combatants. Forget the paying
customers. In the NBA's world view, it is far better that a guy in
Fargo, N.D., have a TNT or TBS doubleheader or an NBC tripleheader
just about each and every day or night than to do something that
might stimulate competition or serve the needs of the people who
actually have a direct rooting interest.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the prickly matter of game times. All potential
Games 4 and 5 in the first round are listed as TBA. As far as the
local fans are concerned, the T and B might as well stand for
``Tough Bananas.'' And I've likewise got an idea what the A stands
for, if you get my drift.
</P>
<P>
   This is pure panic on everyone's part. Yes, the NBA is a damaged
product. It is not delivering the goods for its national television
broadcast partners. But God forbid that anyone accept that in the
world of sport, life can be cyclical.
</P>
<P>
   In saner, simpler times, people were reconciled to the concept
of booms and busts. Attendance didn't go up (itals)every(unitals)
year. General interest fluctuated, mostly according to Ws and Ls.
But no matter what was going wrong, management always tried to act
in the best interests of the local paying customers, who were
perceived to represent the so-called bread and butter of the
operation, and you messed with them at your peril. If you had to
submit a somewhat convoluted playoff schedule it was for one reason
only: you had an arena conflict of some sort. You would do the best
you could and you'd make sure to apologize for any inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   But the league has already abadoned the traditional fan,
blasting him or her out of the building with raucous rock music
while steadily bombarding everyone with flying T-shirts and inane
games of all description. The NBA no longer trusts its product,
and, of course, the game really isn't as good as it once was, for a
reason no one wishes to acknowledge. (Hint: It begins with an ``E''
and it results in there being too many people in the league who
don't belong there.)
</P>
<P>
   Now it just so happens that there is a slight sliver of blue up
there in the NBA's clouds. There are some appealing young stars,
but none of them are Michael, Magic, or Larry, so it will take time
for them to catch on with the public. People will find them at
their own pace.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA wants to catch up to where it was when it had the 76ers,
Celtics, Lakers, Bad Boys, and Michael, but it doesn't have the
patience to allow nature to take its course. That's what happens
when you sell your soul to television. People have got to believe
there is a viable product, and the post-Michael/Magic/Larry NBA has
not yet earned their complete trust. All these scheduling
machinations won't have any effect, anyway. As Yogi Berra would
say, ``If people don't want to watch, you can't stop 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   But we know how these TV fools think. If the ratings for the
first round go up by so much as half a point, the assumption will
be that all their clever scheduling was the reason. This will, of
course, be nonsense, since no one really knows the whys of viewing
habits, any more than anyone really knows how many really are
watching anything, anyway, ratings being the single greatest myth
in the history of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   What (itals)will(unitals) matter are entertaining games and
spirited series. But how can Indiana-Milwaukee be a passionate
series when Game 1 is on a Sunday and Game 2 is on a Thursday; and
when Game 4 (if) is on a Monday and Game 5 (if) is on a Thursday?
Way to stoke those fires, guys.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm not mistaken, we used to have playoff series around here.
And, as I recall, the most emotional series were always bang-bang
affairs. Nothing kept the pot stirred better than those
back-to-backs, or those Friday night-Sunday afternoon turnarounds.
You were really (itals)into(unitals) it, and I'm talking about
fans, media, team executives, ushers, ballboys, and even the
referees, not to mention the players. You will find none of that in
the NBA of 2000. You'll have people walking around town after town
saying, ``Who are we playing, anyhow? It's been so long since we've
had a game. Geez, maybe it's over, and I missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   How smart do you have to be to understand that the product
should always come first, not the packaging? They can stretch the
first-round series out for a month and put on one game a night, and
they can offer to pay everyone who watches it, oh, I dunno, $5, and
it still won't matter in the long run if the game reeks. If I were
the NBA, I'm not sure I'd want (itals)anyone(unitals) to watch
Miami-Detroit. I'd consider handing out blindfolds to the people in
attendance. I'd schedule doubleheaders at 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Attention, David Stern: Your league was a little more
entertaining this season, but it is still in an artistic recession,
OK? Accept it. Deal with it. Use your influence to make sure teams
hire coaches who will recognize that the stated object of the game
is to put the ball in the basket, not merely prevent the other team
from doing it. Basketball isn't different than any other sport.
Offense sells tickets. Tinker with the rules as much as necessary
in order to promote offense. But have a little patience. Trust your
game. It can come back. It (itals)will(unitals) come back. But The
Supremes told us you can't hurry love, and I'm here to tell you
that you can't hurry up the fans, either. Give them a little time.
</P>
<P>
   But just who am I talking to? The David Stern I used to know
would never have to be told what was right and what was wrong. This
David Stern, I fear, is a total captive of television. How sad. How
destructive. How foolish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
