<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PEDRO-PAN-LOOKBACK-AR     04-21 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEDRO-PAN-LOOKBACK-ART-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBANS RECALL SEPARATION FROM PARENTS IN 1960S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was 1961, in the nascent days of the Castro
revolution, and 10-year-old Michael Musa stood in the Havana
airport, waiting to board an airplane for the United States, not
knowing if he would ever see his parents again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just before I got on the plane, I saw my father walk away to
hide, so I couldn't see him,'' said Musa, now a 49-year-old
business executive in Indianapolis. ``But I did see him. He was
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1960 and 1962, some 14,000 Cuban children were spirited
out of the communist nation in what was known as Operation Pedro
Pan. Administered by Catholic Charities, with aid from the U.S.
government, it was said to be the largest exodus of unaccompanied
children from any nation.
</P>
<P>
   Now the case of Elian Gonzalez has loosed a flood of memories
and emotions for the alumni of Pedro Pan, people who long ago
blended into the fabric of everyday American life.
</P>
<P>
   They are people like Musa, who was eventually reunited with his
family, and Rafael Pavelo, a 52-year-old social worker in Chicago
whose parents were never able to emigrate to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Cuban parents believed they were sending their
children to America for only a few months, to keep them out of
harm's way until Fidel Castro fell from power and life returned to
normal in the island nation.
</P>
<P>
   The children were housed temporarily in camps in Miami, and then
sent to foster families around the United States. Most were
teen-agers, but some were as young as 3 or 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a man in Miami drawing a sketch on paper of the
United States, and showing me Indiana,'' said Musa, whose voice
still breaks with emotion as he revisits the memories. ``I had
never heard of Indiana. But he pointed at it and told me, `That's
where you're going.'''
</P>
<P>
   The boy and his sister, Maria, who was 6, were placed in
Indianapolis with a family who did not speak Spanish. Six months
later, the Musa parents made their way to Indiana, where they
started a new life. But about half the young Cubans who were
evacuated to the United States never again lived with their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   That was the fate of Pavelo, who was 13 when he was sent to
Miami. Soon after, he was sent to a seminary in Costa Rica, where
it became clear to him that the promised reunion might never take
place.
</P>
<P>
   For Musa, the president of a division of Ameritech, ties to Cuba
have been eclipsed by his identity as a suburban family man in the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me what I am, I will tell you that most of all I am
a Hoosier,'' Musa said, referring to the old nickname for residents
of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   As he watches the highly publicized custody battle over
6-year-old Elian _ with the boy's father and other relatives
fighting over whether the boy returns to Cuba or stays in the
United States _ Musa said he shakes his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy should be with his father,'' Musa said. ``It's a
no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a view shared by others who came to the United States in
the Pedro Pan operation, a stance vehemently opposed by many
Cuban-Americans in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miami Cubans, they either came to the United States with
their families or were reunited with them very quickly,'' Pavelo
said. ``They don't understand. It's a very different situation when
you're talking about taking a boy away from his parent.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boy in the seminary, he recalled, he received a letter from
his mother. The stationery was stained with tears. And the envelope
held a lock of her hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember holding her hair in my hand and crying,'' said
Pavelo, who fought vainly to hold back tears as he recounted the
experience. ``I missed my family so much.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the months after he was sent to the United States, Pavelo
said, his parents began to blame each other for the decision to
send the boy away. Within two years, they divorced.
</P>
<P>
   The fears of Cuban parents at the time were largely driven by
rumors that the Castro government would take all children away from
their families, enroll them in camps and indoctrinate them with a
philosophy that the state was more important than the family. In
fact, the Cuban government had taken many children out of urban
schools and sent them to the countryside in a literacy campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Pedro Pan operation unfolded around Christmas 1960, when a
homeless Cuban refugee child appeared in the office of the Rev.
Bryan Walsh, who was the director of Catholic Charities in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   A Cuban-American man had taken the boy to Walsh and asked if he
could help find a home for him and also help a handful of other
children who had been sent from Cuba. Walsh agreed to help, and
soon word got back to parents in Cuba about the priest in Miami who
would look after young refugees.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of children arriving in Miami grew, Walsh sought
help from the administration of President Dwight D. Eisenhower.
Walsh, who was born in Ireland, said the U.S. government agreed to
waive the visa requirement for the children, as long as an agency
outside government, like Catholic Charities, administered the
program in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The aid was expanded after President John F. Kennedy took
office. Father Walsh said the flights were often financed by U.S.
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest share of refugees came from Catholic schools in
Cuba. But Walsh said at least 500 of the children were Protestant
or Jewish. The Protestant children were taken by United Way, and
the Jewish children were turned over to the Hebrew Emigrant Aid
Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all word of mouth,'' said the priest, now 72, a
monsignor who has retired from charity work. ``When the children
arrived, they were very often frightened and confused.''
</P>
<P>
   He said about 60 percent of the refugees were teen-age boys. All
of the children were supposed to have been at least 6 years old but
some were considerably younger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on the resettlement, Musa said he was amazed at how
quickly he and his sister had assimilated, even before their
parents arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty good life,'' he said. ``There were no other
Latin-Americans in the neighborhood, but most things _ playing,
going to school, listening to the nuns _ were really not that
different than they had been in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he bore a heavy weight in the first six months, worrying
about his parents in Cuba, in a way that his younger sister did
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a world of difference between the way I looked at
things as a 10-year-old, and the way my sister looked at things as
a 6-year-old,'' he said, noting that Elian is also 6. ``For my
sister, it was all kind of an adventure. For me, I quite clearly
understood what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the time that he waited for his parents to arrive in the
United States, he said, he never fully unpacked his suitcase. His
mother had folded his clothes, and he did not want to disturb any
lasting touch of her hands on the fabric.
</P>
<P>
   He also kept all the letters sent from Cuba by his parents. But
he cannot bring himself to open the envelopes and read them again.
Reading those letters, he said, would put him back in the shoes of
a little boy in a strange country, terrified that he might never
again see his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll read them,'' he said, ``one of these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearing 50, he is not ready quite yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
