<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AUCTION-SUIT-LAWYERS-     04-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-SUIT-LAWYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER AUCTION IN AN AUCTION TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For two months the federal judge presiding over
mountains of litigation against the auction giants Sotheby's and
Christie's knew that he faced a thorny problem: how to select the
lawyers from at least 25 firms across the country to lead the
growing class-action suit charging the two houses with
price-fixing.
</P>
<P>
   Friday he came up with an answer. Hold an auction.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lewis A. Kaplan of U.S. District Court in Manhattan issued
a court order Friday in which he invited all the lawyers
representing the approximately 40 plaintiffs so far to submit
secret bids by May 12 to determine who will manage the plaintiff's
case, a prize that could be worth millions. The judge appointed an
interim team of six lead lawyers on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The bids are to list a maximum amount of recovered money that
the lawyers would be willing to see go entirely to the plaintiffs.
For any recovery beyond that, the lawyers are to list a fee that
they would take in full. If the recovery exceeds the sum of both of
these, the lawyers would get one-quarter of the additional amount
with the rest going to their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, experts said, the lawyers have an incentive to offer a
maximum financial recovery to their clients at a minimal legal fee.
If the recovery is exceptionally large, the lawyers would make much
more.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's innovation, experts said, was the formula that
increases legal fees as the recovery increases.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the plan relied on the kind of free-market
competition that Sotheby's and Christie's are accused of subverting
by colluding on fees and commissions charged to buyers and sellers
since 1993. The houses are also being investigated by federal
antitrust prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The judge did not promise to select the low bidder but ``which
bidder is likely best to serve the interests of any class that may
be certified, taking into account the economic terms of bids as
well as qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Such bargaining to limit lawyers fees in class-action suits has
occurred in several previous cases, but Kaplan wrote that his
bidding process ``never has been used as far as the court is
aware.''
</P>
<P>
   He invited comments from the interim lead lawyers, who are
likely to argue against changing lawyers now, and even from
outsiders, and he said that if the plan drew significant opposition
he might scrap it.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew K. Niebler, a Washington lawyer whom the judge cited
as an expert on lead counsel auctions, applauded the new formula.
``This is really an important advance for better aligning the
interests of the class members and plaintiffs' class counsel,'' he
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The formula also won high marks from at least one plaintiff's
lawyer who had been prepared to drop out of the case, feeling, as
he said, that ``other guys carved it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked late Friday if he had heard of the order, that lawyer,
Stephen Susman of Houston, said, ``No, but I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way judges ought to do it,'' he said. ``Pick the
lawyers who offer the most reasonable deal to the class.'' Now, he
said, ``we'll definitely be back in.''
</P>
<P>
   The six interim lead lawyers have not responded to calls. They
are Frederick P. Furth, Stanley M. Grossman, Michael D. Hausfeld,
Robert N. Kaplan, Christopher Lovell and Robert A. Skirnick.
</P>
<P>
   In another decision Friday, the judge rejected Christie's
contention that there was no basis for the lawsuit and commented,
``Certainly the interim lead counsel and their clients are capable
of pursuing the litigation in an appropriate manner.''
</P>
<P>
   One effect of the formula, the experts said, is to reduce the
attractiveness to the plaintiffs' lawyers of a quick settlement,
for which they might ordinarily do little work but get a big fee.
</P>
<P>
   There are no set fees in class-action cases. Judges commonly
award lawyers 10 to 30 percent, but the lawyers do not know the
amount going in, creating uncertainties for lawyers and clients
alike.
</P>
<P>
   In class-action suits, where many plaintiffs sue collectively,
lawyers often designate the lead members themselves and the judge
approves them. Lead counsels shoulder the bulk of the work and also
commonly reap the largest fees.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan assured the lawyers that if he decided not to go ahead
with his bidding formula, he would not reveal the bids. He also
ordered them not to discuss their positions among themselves or try
to rig their bids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
