<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-SKINNER-NY     04-21 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-SKINNER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKINNER EXPLAINS ANOTHER DISAPPOINTING FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Skinner had to talk about it. Again. Explain how he lost
another race he could have won.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner is getting used to the could-haves, would-haves and
should-haves that seem to dot his racing career and his
second-place finish Sunday at the Talladega's DieHard 500 has
joined the list.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as bad as Atlanta, a race Skinner dominated before
blowing an engine. That was a race he should have won. This was a
race he could have. Even Jeff Gordon, the winner at Talladega,
admitted that.
</P>
<P>
   During the final laps, Skinner was so tight on Gordon's bumper
it was almost like they were one car. A little tap in the right
place, Gordon goes for a spin and Skinner has his first win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had two or three good runs at me,'' Gordon said, ``but
either he lost momentum, went down on the grass or bumped me. I
guess he did all three. He bumped me a few times because he had
momentum and he didn't want to go on the grass.''
</P>
<P>
   But Skinner never hit Gordon hard enough to knock him out of
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Irwin could really get on us down in the corner and
through the corner but he just couldn't get a big enough push to
get me by Jeff,'' Skinner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I was going to beat him was if I hit him and spun
him and took a chance of hurting somebody, and I don't want to win
my first race because I knocked somebody out who had raced me clean
all day,'' Skinner said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gordon wouldn't have been where he was without
Skinner's help. With 18 laps to go, he was ninth, but he got behind
Skinner with about 10 left and the two of them went to the front.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gordon darted around Skinner, past Mark Martin, into the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dale Earnhardt was behind Skinner, and maybe Gordon
was fortunate Earnhardt was running third and not second, because
Earnhardt has been known to push the envelope, so to speak, when
the race is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, the only way I was going to get by Gordon was if
I ran in there real hard and just hit him, and I wasn't going to do
that,'' Skinner said. ``I didn't want to win the race that way. I
think we've got a strong race team, and I think we can win them
without doing that to a guy who races us as clean as he did all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
