<HEADER>
A3869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EARTH-DAY-BOS &LR;      04-21 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-DAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTH DAY, THE TECHNOLOGY ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Environmentalism is one of America's most successful social
movements since World War II, responsible for making the air, land,
and water cleaner, especially in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But now activists are confronting the price of success: a whole
raft of new issues that are steeped in cutting-edge science that
even activists scarcely understand.
</P>
<P>
   Life used to be so much simpler.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1970, when 20 million Americans marched on the first
Earth Day, air pollution over Los Angeles was as thick as fog,
while raw sewage floated in Boston Harbor and toxic chemicals drove
the bald eagle, America's national symbol, to the brink of
extinction. Ugly as it was, the environmental mess was such a clear
and present danger that it galvanized a movement.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as millions more prepare to celebrate Earth Day's 30th
anniversary, the issues have become far more complex, abstract, and
harder to sell.
</P>
<P>
   An invisible gas people exhale is warming the planet. Radiation
is pouring through an ozone hole six miles up in the sky.
Protesters rally against something called the International
Monetary Fund, complaining that it is plundering faraway nations.
And environmentalists once-reliable targets, from car makers to
forest clearcutters are claiming to be green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easier back then because the threats were so obvious,''
said Denis Hayes, cofounder of Earth Day and current chairman and
chief executive of Earth Day Network. The group is coordinating
events in 185 nations today, from a festival in London to a car
boycott in Indonesia, from a parachuting demonstration in Croatia
to a free concert on the Charles River Esplanade.
</P>
<P>
   While Hayes is not nostalgic for the hideous black smoke or
lead-poisoned children of yesteryear, he says he found those issues
easier to deal with than issues like global warming, where the
threat is invisible and almost everyone in the United States is
part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Hayes admitted, global warming, an important theme of
this year's celebration, ``is, candidly, a little bit boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of the difficulty of the new issues, the
environment has slipped in the public's consciousness. The public
is still deeply concerned _ 52 percent of people surveyed by
Newsweek magazine feel the United States has made only minor
environmental progress since 1970 _ but the protest over
genetically engineered corn doesn't draw the visceral reaction of
the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new complexities are due to the wealth of scientific
information amassed over the years, yielding far more detailed
understanding of some ecological problems while identifying new
problems that had been obscured by the old.
</P>
<P>
   Some on Capitol Hill still complain that ``sound science'' is
lacking on issues from dioxin to desertification. But others say
there is no shortage of science, thanks to environmentalists who
have pushed for more and more research.
</P>
<P>
   Yet science is only part of the story. Environmental concern is
now woven into American life, from street protests to clothing
catalogs, from hybrid cars to Hollywood films. Americans support
the environmental movement so deeply that they have virtually
silenced or converted its critics. Few speak ill of nature these
days.
</P>
<P>
   But, if everyone from E.O. Wilson to Leonardo DiCaprio is now an
environmentalist, leading environmentalists are concerned over how
to keep the movement focused in the coming years, especially as it
takes on issues such as climate change that do not lend themselves
to clear direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent, this is a generational challenge that affects
all movements,'' Hayes said, citing ``the feminist movement, civil
rights movement, labor movement, where people forge bonds and
values in a series of battles that proceed from assumptions not
always inherited by the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's particularly true of the environment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That nature is better off now than it was in 1970, at least in
the United States, is hard to dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the 1960s and the first Earth Day, in 1970, we have made
some remarkable gains,'' writes Vice President Al Gore in his new
forward to ``Earth in the Balance,'' his 1992 book reissued today.
``Especially in the last seven years, we have laid the foundations
to make the first decade of the twenty-first century the
Environment Decade, for America and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House report released nine days ago concluded that since
the start of the Clinton Administration in 1993, 44 million more
Americans are breathing clean air and 34 million more are drinking
clean water. Superfund hazardous waste sites are being cleaned up
three times as quickly, environmental exports have more than
doubled, and spending on environmental priorities has
''dramatically risen.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as clear is that many of the ecological threats known
in 1970 persist, although in some cases not as severely, while new
ones are cropping up about as quickly as endangered species are
vanishing. The Worldwatch Institute's ``State of the World 2000''
report painted a gloomy picture of disappearing species, rising
temperatures, and collapsing fisheries, all while the global
population has doubled since 1970 to 6 billion people. It will hit
9 billion by 2050.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scale and urgency of the challenges are unprecedented,''
said Worldwatch president Lester Brown. In this country alone,
environmentalists say, sprawl is encroaching on open lands,
drinking water is beset by pollutants, the summertime air in many
cities is sending asthmatics to hospitals, exotic plants are
wreaking havoc with ecosystems, and national parks are being
overrun by tourists.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely that sense of crisis that attracts many young
people to the environment as a cause, jamming environmental studies
programs and launching Internet campaigns against multinational
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmental issues seem so threatening, so imminent,'' said
Suzanne Slezak, 18, a Wellesley College freshman. She joined other
area students last Tuesday in calling on their peers nationwide to
pledge, via a web site, not to work for, invest in, or buy from BP
Amoco and six other companies, contending that the firms pollute.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hollywood is turning out films such as ``A Civil
Action'' and ``Erin Brockovich,'' both of which rely on old-style
contamination issues to create a sense of good versus evil.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the emerging environmental issues don't fit the neat
profile of corporations illegally dumping chemicals on innocent
victims. Important issues such as sustainable development in
developing nations are awash in tough science, obscure treaties,
and a pervasive sense that everyone is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Even many of the young people who were the foot soldiers in
recent protests in Boston, Seattle, and Washington, D.C., against
global trade and biotechnology are part of the problem, according
to Hayes, if only because their lives reqire so many natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Young people ``are incredible consumers,'' he said, quite
different from ascetically minded elders such as Raph Nader who
have dominated the environmental movement for decades. Today's
teenagers are completely wired to the Internet, which makes them
easier to organize, but all the electronic gadgetry consumes vast
amounts of energy and contributes to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   But Hayes is far from downcast about environmentalism, because
he is convinced that, in the main, people want to do the right
thing, a commitment that leaders can tap into.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmentalism emanates from a set of values that includes
diversity,'' he said. ``Those values will be summoned up with force
and dynamism around key issues, be they individuals like Newt
Gingrich trying back in 1995 to roll back 25 years of environmental
progress or events like the Exxon Valdez and Chernobyl. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side of it is that we have a far more educated
populace now when it comes to the environment,'' Hayes said. ``In
1970, if you asked people whether they were environmentalists, my
guess is 90 percent of them would have asked you what that is.
That's not true now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
