</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONSERVATIVES-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH NOT ALIENATING CONSERVATIVES AS HE REACHES OUT TO MODERATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a retreat from recent Republican tenets, Gov.
George W. Bush in the past several days has advocated an expansion
of the federal role on programs ranging from education to
low-income housing to health care. And he has made overtures to
constituencies, such as gays and gun control proponents, that have
never been mainstays of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what is most striking about Bush's repositioning in the nine
weeks since the South Carolina primary, when he presented himself
as an unflinching conservative, is that prominent fiscal and social
conservatives _ many of whom have been outspoken about past
nominees _ have been silent. Not one leading conservative
organization has aggressively spoken out against Bush. Some have
even embraced his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews over several days, prominent conservatives on
Capitol Hill and around the country said they were intent on
rallying behind the presumptive Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why they were essentially giving Bush a pass, many
conservatives offered the same explanations again and again _ often
using the identical word: After eight years, they were ``hungry''
to win back the White House, even if that might mean sacrificing
some bedrock Republican positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some risk to the strategy of the Republican Party
asking, `Where does he stand overall on basic Republican
principles?''' said Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas. ``But Republicans
are hungry to win the presidency, and that makes people more
willing to be understanding when proposals like these come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such forgiving attitudes, some leading conservatives
said Bush's positions might make them all the more insistent that
he not pick a running mate who favors abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I describe it as the great accommodation,'' said Marshall H.
Wittmann, director of congressional relations for the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative group, said: ``But this can only go so
far. I do believe Bush would run into a major problem if he put a
pro-choice running mate on the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, conservatives are showing no signs of defection.
Like many of his peers, Stephen Moore, director of fiscal studies
at the Cato Institute, which has long condemned new federal
spending, offered a rationale for the measures Bush has taken that
he finds distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bit of a Clintonesque quality to these policy
proposals,'' he said. ``I'm not trying to defend the guy. The
housing program he came up with was really absurd. But, when you're
talking about a $2 trillion budget, the price tag on that program
was maybe a few billion. I don't like the programs, but it's not
like they'll bust the bank.'' Such proposals, Moore said, may be
``what it takes to wrest the White House from Clinton and Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush did name a running mate who backs abortion rights,
many social conservatives went as far as to say they would stand
behind him _ albeit less enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Schlafly, president of the Eagle Forum and a leading
abortion foe, did not seem particularly unsettled by recent
comments of Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania who called for loosening
the party's anti-abortion plank. He is considered a prospect to be
Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd lose if he did that,'' she said of the possibility of a
running mate like Ridge. ``There's enough of a pro-life
constituency who would feel so betrayed that they would not vote
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Schlafly vowed to remain loyal even if Bush picked a running
mate who backed abortion rights. ``I'll probably stick with the
ticket,'' she said. ``There really isn't any option. Bush isn't
Gore _ and that's a big plus.'' Asked if she would defect to Pat
Buchanan, who is steadfastly against abortion and is seeking the
Reform Party nomination, she said, ``Well, I'm a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's courtship of moderates also underscores changing dynamics
in the country and in his own party: With huge federal surpluses,
even Republicans now can afford to espouse bountiful spending. And
many Republicans who were riding high after the Republicans'
takeover of the House in 1994 said they have been humbled by their
losses in 1996 and 1998 _ and that now an unabashed conservative
agenda may not be politically sensible. Some conservatives said
they would not object to the governor's proposals because they were
more a symbolic nod to Democrats and not a repudiation of
Republican philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is able to continue to reach to the center without
alienating his party's base of conservative voters, that could make
him a far more formidable candidate than if he were distracted by
the intraparty sniping that plagued Bob Dole's campaign in 1996 and
President George Bush's re-election drive four years before that.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's success thus far belies the predictions of many
Republican strategists, and many backers of Vice President Al Gore,
who said the Texas governor would trigger an outcry if he returned
to the more moderate path he had scrupulously followed throughout
1999 before his sharp detour to the right _ symbolized by his
appearance at Bob Jones University _ in late February.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's refreshing that in large part our policies have not only
appealed to nontraditional Republican groups but have not
engendered any backlash,'' said Stephen Goldsmith, a former mayor
of Indianapolis who is Bush's chief domestic policy adviser. Asked
whether conservatives were backing the governor's proposals for
pragmatic reasons, Goldsmith said: ``Sure. Absolutely. It's nice to
have people wanting to win but also be happy about our policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans are warning that Bush's strategy could lead
some conservatives to refuse to vote in November. ``He's going to
the left of Al Gore,'' said L. Brent Bozell, president of the
Conservative Victory Committee, which contributes to Republican
candidates. ``When Republicans take their base for granted, that
base stays home _ and Bush would not stand a prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   But an important reason why Bush is free to reach beyond hard
core Republicans is that polls show that Republicans voters have
rapidly consolidated behind him. A poll of registered Republicans
that was conducted April 13-14 and published by Newsweek found that
85 percent said they would support Bush. Candidates usually are not
able to muster such impressive levels of support until after they
rally the faithful at their national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said whenever any conservative
raises questions about Bush's bonafides on abortion or question his
proposals for more spending, he has a ready answer: ``They'd better
concentrate on the fact that the next president of the United
States is going to nominate three or four people to the Supreme
Court. Do they want Bush doing that? Or do they want Gore doing
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mueller, who was a strategist for the Steve Forbes
campaign, said, ``Nobody wants to be held responsible for hurting
the nominee of the party who's at least talking about some
conservative issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Many political strategists say that Bush's aggressive efforts to
reach out has given him the upper hand over Gore in recent weeks.
They likened his approach to Bill Clinton's successful shift from
the liberal wing of his party when he ran for president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is trying to emulate what we did,'' said Al From, who
heads the Democratic Leadership Council, a centrist group that was
a foundation for Clinton's bid for the White House. ``And he's had
no pressure from the Democrats or the right wing. Maybe the
Republican right will roll over dead and he'll have a free ride.
Then it will be up to Gore to show who's the imposter.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some staunch supporters of the vice president warn that he
should not allow Bush to appropriate issues from the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me squirm a little bit when he endorsed what we did on
Medicare,'' Sen. John Breaux, D-La., who has pressed his own party
to steer a moderate course, said of Bush. ``He's done it on
education, he's done it on health care. He's actually been
aggressive in those areas. Now Gore also has to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore campaign officials said any advantage Bush may enjoy
will be short-lived. In coming days, they said, the vice president
will intensify his attacks, asserting that Bush cannot both call
for a tax cut of $483 billion over five years as he is proposing
more government spending. They also said Gore will begin to poke
holes in the Bush proposals themselves as mere window dressing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``What we call the Bob Jones Redemption Tour is flawed in a lot
of different ways,'' said Carter Eskew, a leading architect of the
Gore strategy. ``The more he talks about education and health care,
the more he exposes the fundamental flaw of his campaign: the tax
cut, which is a deal he had to make with the devil to secure his
nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's move to the center ``might look like a politically
clever move,'' Eskew said, it will damage him in the end. ``If you
start to raise expectations that Bush is going to address those
problems, voters are going to put a spotlight on him. And we get
into a comparison. Guess what? That's our turf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
