u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-COURT-835(2     04-21 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-COURT-835(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN CASE PUTS FOCUS ON A CHILD'S RIGHT TO CHOOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Ga., N.Y., Calif., Ill.)  (Eds.: With CUBAN-BOY) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal appeals court ruling Wednesday in the Elian Gonzalez
case has startled experts on family law because it suggested that
immigration officials should ask 6-year-old Elian whether he wanted
to return to Cuba or remain with his Miami relatives, regardless of
the wishes of his father.
</P>
<P>
   But just how much control should a 6-year-old have over his
future? Beyond the international political fight, and the chanting
of the crowds outside a small Miami house, should Elian be able to
choose his country?
</P>
<P>
   At least until Elian's case, the answer under American law
seemed to be that a 6-year-old had no such right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule is that parents decide for children,'' said Martin
Guggenheim, an expert on children's rights at New York University
Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the language of the preliminary ruling from the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta, and the reaction of legal
experts this week, has suddenly placed unusual attention on a
little-examined corner of American law. In fact, very young
children, those under 12, are seldom asked to decide questions as
important as whether they will live with their parents, legal
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers and judges pointed out that the appeals judges'
suggestion that Elian should be interviewed by immigration
officials did not mean that his preferences would carry any
significant weight. Immigration officials may still conclude that
he is too immature to make meaningful decisions about seeking
political asylum in this country.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the experts said they were troubled by the fact that
the judges seemed actually to suggest that the boy had already made
meaningful decisions about seeking asylum. The court said not only
that Elian might be able to apply for asylum but ``it appears he
did so.'' The appeals judges noted that the 6-year-old had signed
an application filed with the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a nearly meaningless question to ask a 6-year-old
whether he prefers one economic system to another economic system,
one culture to another culture,'' said Lee E. Teitelbaum, an expert
on juvenile law who is the dean of Cornell University Law School.
``These questions are hard enough for adults to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In American courts dealing with more routine disputes like
custody battles, older children are sometimes asked their views,
but courts do not necessarily feel bound to abide by them.
</P>
<P>
   That legal approach to children is based on a view that very
young children, do not have the maturity to make decisions about
their future and that to ask them to try may be psychologically
harmful.
</P>
<P>
   But the legal question is complicated in the Elian Gonzalez case
partly because there is no absolute rule in American law setting
forth how old children should be before their opinions are
considered in court. ``We tend not to draw the line,'' said Carol
Sanger, an expert on children's legal rights at Columbia Law
School.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanger said the courts have not expanded their flexible
approach to credit the wishes of a 6-year-old on an issue as
important as where he should live when a living parent has
expressed a strong desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use a maturity standard,'' Sanger said. ``But the judicial
system thinks a 6-year-old is inherently immature. We think they
discuss what they want now: chocolate milk, an electric car.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts said the suggestion by the appeals court that
officials should ask a 6-year-old to decide whether to seek asylum
violated principles that have been widely accepted in the legal
system. ``American courts think certain things have to be decided
by adults and the adults who decide them ought to be the parents,''
said Michael S. Wald, a specialist in children's legal issues at
Stanford University law school.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some expansion of children's rights in recent
years, with children treated less and less like the property of
their parents. In the 1970s, Hillary Rodham Clinton was one of the
proponents of that movement, writing law review articles proposing
the expansion of children's rights in some circumstances. (She has
said Elian should be reunited with his father.)
</P>
<P>
   But even taking into account this more modern view of children,
some experts say it would be difficult for the courts to use this
case to expand children's rights to the point of giving a
6-year-old veto power over his father's decision that no asylum
application should be filed for his son.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the varying treatment of children in the
American legal system depends on the context. For example, the
``age of majority'' at which children are deemed to be able to make
all decisions independently varies from 17 to 21. Under federal
law, 18-year-olds are eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, children 7 and younger are typically deemed
so immature in their thought processes that they cannot form the
conscious intent to commit crimes. As a result, even when they
commit violent acts they are often immune from prosecution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But when children are called upon to testify as witnesses,
judges apply a different test. They evaluate whether a potential
child witness understands the nature of the oath to tell the truth
by asking, for example, whether the child knows what it means to
lie.
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim of New York University said that under that test,
very few 6- or 7-year-olds qualify to present sworn testimony. But
he said many courts across the country did hear sworn testimony in
civil and criminal trial from children 8 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Sanger of Columbia said the courts had different standards in
evaluating children's participation in court proceedings. As
witnesses of events involving other people, like observing a crime,
one test is whether a child would be a reliable witness. Many
courts have concluded that children can correctly report events
they have observed.
</P>
<P>
   But she and other experts said a different issue arose when a
child was being asked to explain in court what he or she wanted in
the future, for example, when parents were battling over custody.
In the cases of very young children, she said, courts have
overwhelmingly shied away from asking children to make choices
between parents.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because judges typically conclude that children
can be manipulated and that they can suffer psychologically when
they later consider the choices they made as children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been concluded by the courts that for the majority of
children,'' Wald of Stanford said, ``it will be harmful for them to
have their voices heard because it puts them in loyalty conflicts
and it encourages disputes that get drawn out for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts have suggested that Elian's Miami relatives
may be focusing on the issue of Elian's ostensible desire to seek
asylum here as a legal strategy to draw out the case.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier case that was similar in some ways, a 12-year-old
Ukrainian immigrant, Walter Polovchak, decided in 1980 with his
17-year-old sister that he did not wish to return to the Soviet
Union when his parents left the United States to return to their
country.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, an Illinois trial court first found that two
children were ``persons in need of supervision,'' which limited
their parents' rights. The court then declared the children wards
of the state. In the meantime, the Ukrainian boy had applied for
asylum. The asylum application was later granted.
</P>
<P>
   When the case was appealed, however, the Illinois appeals courts
overruled the trial court, saying the court had no grounds to limit
the parents' rights. Eventually, the Illinois Supreme Court ruled
that ``Walter should have been returned to his parents.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time all of the court battles were over, Walter
Polovchak had turned 18 and had decided to remain in the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
