<SLUG> BC-BBO-COMMENT-JEFFERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGGIE JEFFERSON IN THE SWING IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The last time I saw Reggie Jefferson, he was smiling.
</P>
<P>
   He wants people to know that he has a job with a professional
baseball team in Japan that needs his services. He said he's sorry
he missed Opening Day at Fenway Park. His friends will understand.
The rest don't matter.
</P>
<P>
   He voiced these sentiments in sort of a goodwill gesture to the
Red Sox, who kept him off the playoff roster and then released him
in the offseason. After turning down three major league offers,
none of which came with a guarantee of playing time, the Seibu
Lions of the Pacific League came along and upped the ante by $1
million. Jefferson, 31, quickly accepted _ although he had never
visited Japan before spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson had very little choice. In 1999, he had managed only
206 at-bats and a .277 batting average while playing in just 83
games. These were clearly not good numbers for a designated
hitter/first baseman who earned $3.25 million in his final season
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When he signed as a free agent in '95, Red Sox general manager
Dan Duquette referred to him as a ``professional hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Although injuries plagued him during stops in Cincinnati,
Cleveland, and Seattle, the Red Sox took a chance after Jefferson
hit .347 in 122 games in '96 and gave him a three-year contract. It
seemed to be the right move the next year when Jefferson hit .317
and appeared in 136 games.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all downhill the next two seasons. In '98, Jefferson
played in just 62 games (and none after July 15) because of a lower
back strain. Last year, his absence from the lineup had more to do
with the manager's choice than injuries. The return of Mike Stanley
and the emergence of rookie Brian Daubach cut into Jefferson's
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   He knew the ax was near. But he didn't know when.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew all along that they weren't going to put me on the
(playoff) roster,'' said Jefferson. ``They could have released me,
or something like that, during the season. The situation was dead.
A couple of teams did call the Red Sox. But with my salary, nobody
was going to make a deal with the Red Sox unless the club agreed to
pay some of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told Mark Portugal in September that he could go home.
That's when I asked, `Why are you going to keep me around? You know
you're not going to use me.' Last year, I was hurt 90 days, and
even when I was there, I'm sure a lot of people felt like I was
done. You don't want to have three straight years in the big
leagues in which you don't play. I'm just glad that it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson has no illusions about his immediate future. He signed
a one-year contract with the Lions, who are based in suburban
Tokyo. Barring injuries, he will try for another major league job
next year. In signing with Seibu, which has won 13 Pacific League
championships since '82, he will be with a winner playing in a
domed stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he can withstand the rigors of a Japan League season,
and the lifestyle that goes with it, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one Cecil Fielder,'' he said, referring to the
most famous Japanese crossover player. ``So obviously, this will be
a big adjustment. Ideally, this is for a guy who never got to play
in the major leagues, a guy who has been in Triple A for a while
and didn't get his shot. This is a chance for a guy like Lou
Merloni to make some money.
</P>
<P>
   ``But maybe if I come here and play every day, people know I'm
healthy. My idea is to play for a year. If nothing else, it will be
a good cultural experience. The worst I can do is come back in good
shape and get an offer to play in somebody's game. Also, there will
be several more dollars in the bank. It's not like I had that great
offer sitting on the table. So play here and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson said it's hard to describe what it's like to play in
Japan after nine seasons in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to forget all the things you learn in the major
leagues in order to have success over here,'' said Jefferson. ``You
have to put everything out of your mind. And once you're here,
focus on what you have to do. Pitching, the umpires, the way they
play the game itself, you can't compare it. If you try to compare
it to the major leagues, you just make it hard on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson said he is just glad the market has changed enough in
the last three years to allow veterans to make their own deals in
Japan. Until recently, younger players were sought for the slots
reserved for foreign players and the Japanese clubs received a
large chunk of the money. Jefferson still has power and Seibu
hasn't won a Japan Series championship since '92. Bigger
marketplace, more jobs, more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take it for what it is: Japanese baseball,'' said
Jefferson. ``I will just try to have a good year. That's how I look
at it. If I don't have a good year, that's fine, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've saved a little money for a rainy day. Mostly, I want it
to be a good experience. If I hit .200 and they send me home, I'd
still like for it to be a good experience. I've had a few cultural
experiences already that I won't forget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
