<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS &LR;      04-21 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY'S RELATIVES, US SEEKING WAY TO PLACE HIM IN FATHER'S CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD AND BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ ``Outside parties'' in Miami are drafting a plan that
would transfer Elian Gonzalez from his Miami relatives to his
father's care, Justice Department officials confirmed Friday night.
The officials said they ``would welcome a real agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   A department official would not disclose who the third parties
were, except to say they were people from the Miami community and
that they were working with the Miami relatives and were in contact
with Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties are still working out the details of such a
plan,'' the official said, adding that ``significant gaps''
remained in the negotiations and that an immediate transfer to the
father must be included. The plan had not been presented to Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, Elian's father, who came to the United States from
Cuba 17 days ago to reunite with his 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   After a tense day of swirling reports that Reno was ready to
send law-enforcement officials into Little Havana to retrieve the
boy, the unexpected news of a plan for a peaceful, negotiated
settlement raised hopes inside the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is the appearance of viability here, and as
long as that possibility exists, it has to be explored,'' a Justice
Department spokeswoman said. She said she expected the deal to be
brokered or die within hours. ``Whoever these outside parties are,
they have a vested interest in having this ended peacefully. They
saw the writing on the wall, and they are trying to have families
agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno met with Juan Miguel Gonzalez Friday afternoon and told him
she could ``not commit to a particular course of action or
timetable'' to reunite him with his son. It is not clear what the
status of the mediation in Miami was, or whether Reno discussed it
with Elian's father.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, inside the Justice Department, plans were still going
forward to remove the Cuban boy from his Miami relatives as early
as Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not ruled out this weekend,'' a Justice Department
spokeswoman said, adding that law-enforcement officials were still
weighing such factors in Little Havana as crowd size, the weather,
and the public reaction to taking Elian from his great-uncle's
house over Easter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to minimize civilian injury, not to mention
casualties, and trauma to the child, and we want to utilize the
option with the highest probability of officer safety,'' the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Elian's temporary home in Little Havana, Cuban-American
protesters reacted angrily to reports of plans to seize the boy.
Even as community leaders continued to advocate peaceful
resistance, a small number of ardent Cuban exiles warned that an
attempt by federal authorities to forcibly remove the young refugee
could be a recipe for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not giving him back,'' said Jose Clemente, a
construction worker who was born in Cuba, arrived in Miami as a
child, and later served in the US Army. ``We don't want violence,
but if they break the law and try to take that kid by force, we're
going to have another Waco, I guarantee you.''
</P>
<P>
   Waving a large replica of the flag that flew over Cuba before
Castro's revolution, Clemente said, ``They're going to have to kill
a couple of people here, and we're ready for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno refused to confirm reports that she had decided to send
agents to break the human chain in Little Havana. ``If I were going
to do something like that, I certainly wouldn't tell you,'' she
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to work it out,'' Reno said before her
15-minute meeting Friday with Juan Miguel Gonzalez and his lawyer,
Gregory B. Craig. ``I'm exploring every possibility I can to see
this resolved peacefully, promptly, and properly.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement released later, Reno said she assured
Gonzalez that she would continue working to reunite him with his
child. ``I was deeply moved by Mr. Gonzalez's evident love for his
son,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department reported receiving more than 7,000 calls
Friday in the wake of a public plea Thursday that Americans back
his cause. Joe Lockhart, President Clinton's spokesman, said the
White House had gotten ``a good volume of calls'' that
overwhelmingly supported the father's request.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Clinton Friday also heard from Florida Gov. Jeb Bush,
who wrote them that ``the forcible separation of Elian and his
current caregivers is unwise and unwarranted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mediation, not confrontation, is what is in young Elian's best
interest at this critical point in time,'' said Bush, who urged the
federal officials to accept an offer by the 11th Circuit Court in
Atlanta to provide mediation services to resolve the custody
dispute between Elian's father and his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a meeting, free of governmental pressure and away from
the glare of media attention, would present the best chance for a
family-inspired solution to this controversy,'' said Bush, a
Republican and the brother of GOP presidential candidate George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court, which on Wednesday ordered Elian to remain in
the United States until it decides whether he should get an asylum
hearing, suggested the custody case be mediated, but it did not
order it.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department says it does not object to family talks
as long as the Miami relatives, who have cared for Elian since he
was rescued from a shipwreck on Thanksgiving day, are prepared to
turn the boy over to his father. In a meeting with federal
officials in Miami Friday, Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great uncle,
reportedly again refused to accept that condition.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, at the White House, repeated what the president said
Thursday, when he weighed in with his most substantive comments on
the case. ``The time for (the Miami relatives) to come forward and
effect a transfer to the father is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said he was not aware of any new overtures from the
Miami relatives, and he questioned how serious they had been in the
past about reuniting father and son. The steps they had taken so
far, he said, proved to be ``false starts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite clear that if that's what they'd like, they should
come forward in good faith and do that,'' Lockhart said.``You know,
this is not about playing games, it's not about public relations,
it's not about trying to influence the coverage of this. It should
be about coming forward and doing what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   No official suggested the government is playing games with a
threat to use force in Miami, but it may be waving its trump card
as it tries to get the Miami relatives to relent and give up the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain amount of brinksmanship that comes into
play,'' a Justice Department official said. ``If you have the whole
federal government staring into your face, saying we are coming
tomorrow with all these law-enforcement officers to support us,
there is a possibility, albeit slim, that the family will talk
turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials understand the dangers involved, both physical
and in public opinion. To minimize crowds and the risk of violence,
the Justice Department is relying on local police to push back
barricades and block additional streets around the Gonzalez home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can minimize the numbers of protesters, but people may try
to jump the barricades, and get arrested, and maybe there will be
bloodshed,'' a Justice Department spokeswoman said. ``This stuff is
not going to look pretty or nice, unfortunately.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House is obviously concerned about that. Chief of
staff John Podesta was getting periodic updates from the Justice
Department on the situation, and Lockhart said the president would
be briefed before the attorney general ordered a law-enforcement
action.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart denied reports that the White House is dissatisfied
with Reno and her agency's handling of the case. ``The president
has been very supportive of the work they've done,'' Lockhart said.
``He has done his best to make sure that he does nothing to inject
politics further into this.''
</P>
<P>
   As Easter weekend began, Elian was seen increasingly in the
heavily Catholic exile community as a symbol of hope that Cuba one
day will triumph over Castro's regime. Several demonstrators
marched through Little Havana with crosses on their shoulders,
advocating keeping Elian with his relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a spiritual war, and I don't know how they can battle
that,'' Connie Crespo, a Cuban-American exile, said of the Clinton
administration. ``They're going by the laws made by men, which has
nothing to do with what God has in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Leonard reported from Washington and Hohler from Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2055EDT &QL; 
