<HEADER>
A3895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALAMIN-HEARING22-COX     04-21 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMIN-HEARING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin flown back to Georgia
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin is back in Georgia,
after unexpectedly abandoning his extradition fight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Marshals flew Al-Amin in a helicopter from Alabama to
Atlanta soon after the extradition hearing ended, said Arnold
Perkins, spokesman for the U.S. Marshal's office in Atlanta. He was
then driven to the Cobb County jail.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin is accused of killing one Fulton County deputy and
seriously injuring another.
</P>
<P>
   A decoy vehicle with an armed escort also drove to Atlanta from
Alabama, followed by television news crews.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said the heavy security and decoy was ``just for
security purposes. We didn't know what to expect ...'' Nancy
Bodiford, spokeswoman for the Cobb Sheriff's Department, said
Al-Amin is being held without bond in the jail on the original
warrant for his arrest for failure to appear in court on relatively
minor charges _ theft by receiving a stolen car, impersonating an
officer and no proof of insurance. Fulton Deputies Ricky Kinchen
and Aldranon English were shot trying to serve that warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Bodiford said Cobb will eventually release Al-Amin to
authorities in Fulton County to answer the more serious charges
against him there.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County officials would not discuss Al-Amin's whereabouts
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's decision to waive extradition came at the end of a
hearing at which flamboyant attorney J.L. Chestnut argued that
documents authorizing his client's return from Alabama were
improper because they were signed by Gov. Don Siegelman's legal
advisor and not the governor. Chestnut didn't repeat allegations
raised in earlier petitions that there was a government conspiracy
against his client and that Al-Amin's life would be in danger if
brought back to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Charles Price ordered a 90 minute recess to consider the
legal argument. When he re-convened the hearing, Chestnut stepped
forward and withdrew his petition to keep Al-Amin in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, who had promised a long battle to keep Al-Amin from
being brought back, said the decision to waive extradition was a
joint one between him and Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been dealing with things in Georgia and here and when
some things were put in place in Georgia we were prepared to go
back. But we were not prepared to do anything in the midst of the
hysteria that I saw in two states,'' Chestnut said later.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut wouldn't say what has changed to make it safe for
Al-Amin's return. But he said there has been a cooling off period
and that has eased tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of hysteria did not surround Timothy McVeigh, who
blew up a federal building in Oklahoma and killed 168 people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's court proceedings lasted less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The packed courtroom, which was filled with Al-Amin supporters,
security and reporters, grew tense as Al-Amin rose to make a
statement. His only previous public utterance has been, ``It's a
government conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of accusing his accusers, Al-Amin read a brief,
prayerful statement inviting people to be Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nations are raised by their righteousness,'' he said, ``and
they fall by their corruption of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his statement, Al-Amin thanked the court saying,
``I appreciate your patience and your tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Erik Friedly, spokesman for Fulton County District Attorney Paul
Howard, said that if routine is followed, Al-Amin's first
appearance would be at his plea and arraignment sometime within the
next two weeks. At that hearing, the state would have to announce
if it plans to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Martin, one of Al-Amin's Atlanta attorneys, attended the
hearing Friday and met with Chestnut and Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad he's back in Atlanta,'' Martin said Friday
afternoon. ``He wants to fight these charges. He wants to prove his
innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said it's too early in the process to predict when
Al-Amin could be brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all just learning the facts in this case. We're
investigating those facts, carefully and calmly. It behooves us all
to reserve judgment,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin couldn't predict when Al-Amin would stand trial in
Georgia. That depends on whether the prosecution seeks the death
penalty and other factors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first order of business,'' Martin said, ``is to find out
what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Joshua B. Good, David
Pendered and Jack Warner contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
