<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AFRICA-ZIMBABWE-NYT &LR;      04-21 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-ZIMBABWE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN ASKED TO BACK ZIMBABWE LAND REFORM WITH MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Skedded in some digests as AFRICA-CONGO) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA FALLS, Zimbabwe _ Rallying behind Zimbabwe's president,
Robert Mugabe, the leaders of three of this country's closest
neighbors called on Britain Friday night to follow through with
financial pledges to support land reform here in its former colony.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after several hours of talks in Victoria Falls,
Zimbabwe's premier resort city, the presidents of Mozambique,
Namibia and South Africa said they were satisfied that Mugabe was
taking the steps necessary to halt the ongoing occupation of
white-owned farms by blacks and end the violence that has flared in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the regional leaders insisted that only action by Britain
would ultimately resolve the question of how to redistribute land
to the vast majority of the population that has no land. When
blacks won majority rule from a white-led government 20 years ago,
the agreement with the former colonial ruler governing the
transition period committed Britain to helping pay to redistribute
land from white owners to black peasants.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement reached in 1998 was supposed to have accelerated
the acquisition and redistribution of that land. But nations
helping pay for the plan objected to the way the limited land
reforms had been carried out, and they held off on financing
Zimbabwe's efforts. This in turn touched off a standoff between
Britain and Zimbabwe that persists today.
</P>
<P>
   The backing Friday by the three presidents was a victory for
Mugabe, who has faced mounting international pressure to act
against the thousands of squatters occupying white-owned farms
around the country. Led by President Thabo Mbeki of South Africa,
the three leaders refused to criticize publicly the 76-year-old
president, who was one of the leaders of the fight against white
minority rule more than two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki and Presidents Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique and Sam
Nujoma of Namibia said Friday that they had been asked by the
British government to reach out to Mugabe and begin the work of
rebuilding the bridge between Zimbabwe and Britain. The two
countries have been locked in a war of words in recent months, with
the tone escalating as the crisis here has deepened.
</P>
<P>
   But the tension appears to be easing after Mugabe's efforts this
week to mediate the dispute between white farmers who own much of
the country's fertile land and protesters who are leading the fight
to be given that land. Britain had already invited a Zimbabwean
delegation to London for talks on British financial support for
land reform. The ministers from Zimbabwe are expected to arrive
there on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the presidents' meeting, Britain reaffirmed Friday
night that money was available for land reform. Peter Hain, the
Foreign Office minister, said Britain would dicuss a fair land
reform program and fair elections ``within the rule of law'' with
the Zimbabwean delegation in London next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been on the table since 1998,'' Hain said. ``We have
been waiting since then for President Mugabe to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe, who has publicly condoned the farm invasions, has been
accused of exploiting the land issue as a way to hold on to
political support for his party, the Zimbabwe African National
Union _ Patriotic Front, which faces parliamentary elections next
month. With the economy a shambles and a new opposition party
drawing considerable support, the governing party is facing its
most serious electoral threat since it came to power 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the government is using the farm invasions as one
instrument in a campaign of intimidation against supporters of the
new party, the Movement for Democratic Change. Two white farmers
who back the new party and two black members of the party have been
killed in the last week in confrontations with the farm squatters
and governing party supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Mugabe's counterparts said their meeting with the embattled
leader had convinced them that Mugabe wants to see an end to the
occupation and the violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
