<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-CAPITALIST-$     04-21 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CAPITALIST-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE CAPITAL IS OPENING DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See INTERNET-ENTREPRENEUR FOR alternate viewpoint)  
(For release Sun., April 23) 
 By TIMOTHY DRAPER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ To say that entrepreneurs and venture
capitalists are wasting money in these exuberant times is
provincial at best, and anti-markets, anti-risk-taking and
downright un-American at worst. It is true that in many instances,
young entrepreneurs are spending like drunken soldiers on leave
(hopefully, none are in our portfolio), but they are the exception,
not the rule, and market forces quickly dispose of inefficient
market behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The typical start-up aspires to be the leader in its space,
often requiring a big marketing budget to grab market share before
the competition does. Creative marketing doesn't have to be
expensive, but I know that when a company has a breakthrough and
customers are anxious to buy, it is time to pour in the rocket
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is the greatest revolution in the history of the
world. And for all the capital we have plowed into Internet
businesses, we are probably undercapitalizing the industry as a
whole. When adequately capitalized, these revolutionary companies
can improve our quality of life that much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   I say this with confidence because, through our investment
activities and those of our affiliates, I have been privy to a
glimpse of the future.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, we backed one of the first Internet companies, Internet
Software, which has since been acquired. Internet Software showed
us that commerce could be done on the Web. About two years later,
we financed Hotmail, which used ``viral'' marketing to spread to
more than 11 million users in its first 18 months and serves about
100 million today. Sabeer Bhatia, the founder, sent one e-mail
message to a friend in India, and three weeks later Hotmail had
100,000 registered users there.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it was clear that the Internet was global _ it
could reach and connect us all. Put this information together with
the fact that commerce could be done on the Web, and you have a
phenomenon that can break through the bad governance of India, and
presumably China, Pakistan, Africa and even the United States,
allowing everyone in the world to participate actively in the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of selling widgets to the usual 500 million suspects,
a company could reach all six billion of us! That could conceivably
power a 12-fold increase in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers suggest that all Internet profit margins will
collapse and cite a few examples from electronic retailing. The
margin shrinkage that they envision happens in all commodity
businesses. But how do America Online, Yahoo, Microsoft, GoTo.com,
NetZero, Kana, Tumbleweed, Digital Impact and so on all have
expanding margins? Clearly, they are not commodity businesses; they
are changing the way the world works.
</P>
<P>
   The margins I see collapsing are not commercial, but
governmental. The Internet allows a new kind of competition that
could drive down government's share of the nation's economic output
to 15 or 20 percent, from 40 percent today. Sure, the military and
the police may still have to be location-based monopolies. But why
couldn't I choose my Social Security program, my education program,
my welfare program and my medical program from a host of choices in
cyberspace? Competitive efficiency in government would be
refreshing, and very good for long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   I do not hope to predict exactly what will happen, or how. But
the market shaped by these changes will be a venture capitalist's
dream. Our $10 trillion economy could grow by an order of
magnitude, to more than $100 trillion. Where will the value be
created? In Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Consider ones like GoTo.com, with its auction system for Web
marketing, or Tumbleweed, with its efficient, secure digital
delivery of customer information, or Aveo, which gives computer
users support even before they know they need it, or EdgeMail,
which helps companies base all their operations on the Web without
needing Windows. These and others like them are real companies
generating real margins that nonetheless need cash to continue
their growth.
</P>
<P>
   I would say that the $60 billion or so that the venture capital
industry has invested around the globe is well justified and even a
little light, given the immensity of the market we are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is creating this value in every sector of the world
economy, not just in technology fields. Every industry will be
recreated, from sporting goods (think of FogDog, say) to mail order
(Digital Impact). The number of new companies doing the recreating
will grow exponentially, and so will their size.
</P>
<P>
   Stock investors will be believers one day, Doubting Serges the
next _ but the revolution will rage on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2103EDT &QL; 
