<HEADLINE>
CAMBY EXPECTS THE RAPTORS TO GET PHYSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ When practice ended at SUNY-Purchase Friday,
Marcus Camby walked off the court by himself and unfolded his long
body against the wall under a basket. He had made it through his
first workout since reinjuring his right knee last Saturday and was
certain he would be ready for the start of the playoffs against the
Toronto Raptors on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Before he took the floor, Camby was surrounded by tape recorders
and cameras, drawing more attention than he wanted. He could handle
the questions about his right knee, which had a large ice pack
wrapped around it. But Camby found himself the center of attention
for other reasons. He has become a potential target of his former
team. It was an odd situation for a player built more for stealth
than for banging.
</P>
<P>
   After he was quoted as saying that Coach Butch Carter of the
Raptors had lied to him before Toronto traded him to the Knicks,
some of the Raptors players responded by saying that if Camby
insulted the coach, he had insulted them, too. The Raptors have a
front line of Charles Oakley, Antonio Davis and Kevin Willis, so
Camby was aware, but unafraid, of the ramifications of his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just all about playing now,'' Camby said. ``I've just got
to play. Winning is the cure-all, so we just have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, any doubt surrounding Camby's abilities to function
in the postseason spotlight came from within the Knicks'
organization. But after soaring over and around the Miami Heat and
the Indiana Pacers, the belief in him in New York is firmly
established. Now, the questions arise from his role as a vital cog
on the Knicks, as well as how he will respond to being targeted by
the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot because of the way they handled us during the
season,'' Camby said. ``But by that being my former team and the
animosity going on, it's just that they beat us three times
handily. It's an obstacle we have to overcome, beating them and
trying to move on. I'm not going to try to make it an individual
thing between me and them. We just want to go out and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm more relaxed,'' he added. ``I'm not as nervous as
last year, that being my first time in the playoffs. Last year I
didn't really know what to expect. People were saying they didn't
know how I would react in the playoffs, but I managed to put all
that stuff aside and go out there and just try to play hard. That's
all I'm going to try to do in this playoff series.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Davis was a part of the Pacers team that Camby
played so well against last year in the playoffs, Camby admitted
that his forays to the basket were not as easy this season, because
teams had seen what he was capable of doing and were determined to
stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just a physical ball club,'' he said. ``I have to play
my game. It's not as easy as it was last year. I think I snuck up
on a lot of people last year. Now, as I've seen during the course
of the season, I'm not sneaking up on anybody anymore. Guys are
putting two or three guys on me, trying to bang me from getting to
the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change my game because a team is a physical
ball club. I'm just going to go out there and try to be me. There's
no special trick Knicks coming in for me, no special assignments.
I'm just going to play my game.''
</P>
<P>
   But after spraining a knee on Feb. 6 and undergoing arthroscopic
surgery, which caused him to miss 17 games, he is still feeling the
effects. He reinjured the knee last Saturday after taking a charge
against the Cleveland Cavaliers' Andre Miller and sat out the final
two games of the regular season. Although he said he would play
Sunday against the Raptors at Madison Square Garden, it will not be
without some ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt all right for the most part today,'' Camby said.
``I'll be ready to go come Sunday. It's a whole lot better than
when I came back before. I've still got a little lingering from the
surgery that I had before. I've still got some swelling in it, but
it's going to be like that the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really worry about it. Ever since I came back from my
knee, I've been trying to do the things I've been doing, taking
charges, diving on the floor, just trying to do the things I was
doing before I got hurt. I'll be myself. I'll be out there trying
to bring that energy. I don't expect anything to change. I went the
whole practice, did everything that everybody did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
