<HEADER>
A3940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HURRICANES22-COX     04-21 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voluntary evacuees a hurricane problem for Florida last year
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ ``Shadow evacuees'' _ people who didn't have to
leave but did anyway _ caused the biggest problem in the
unprecedented and chaotic evacuation of the East Coast during
Hurricane Floyd last year, according to a Florida State University
study.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 7,000 people in coastal Florida, Georgia and the
Carolinas showed many weren't in mandatory evacuation zones _
usually right at the coastline or in low-lying areas _ but left
anyway, said FSU geography Professor Jay Baker, a 25-year veteran
of hurricanes and how people react to them.
</P>
<P>
   Baker presented the figures Thursday at the National Hurricane
Conference, a gathering of weather forecasters and researchers,
emergency managers and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers surveyed 600 people in each of 11 clusters, one of
them composed of Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie, Indian River,
Okeechobee and Hendry counties. In that region:
</P>
<P>
   _ Twenty-three percent of those living in flood-prone areas but
not in mandatory evacuation zones left their homes. In addition, 22
percent of those living in nonflooding areas of coastal counties
fled and 20 percent in inland counties fled. Many inland residents
did have to evacuate because they lived in mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 60 percent of those ordered to leave went to a friend's
home, 30 percent to hotels, and only 1 percent to public shelters.
But more than half of those who left their homes left their county.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you worry about in terms of road congestion,''
Baker said. ``It's these people who ... try to go to Orlando or
Jacksonville or Atlanta.'' _ Of those who evacuated, 18 percent
said they would stay in their homes next time.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, which was just shy of a Category 5 hurricane as it bore
down on the Eastern Seaboard, sparked the largest peacetime
evacuation in American history, with some 3.5 million people
leaving their homes either voluntarily or under orders, from
Miami-Dade County to North Carolina's Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   While no one died in the evacuation, it was still chaotic and
could be improved, said Joe Myers, director of the Florida Division
of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do a better job of communicating,'' Myers said.
Ideas include an Internet page on which residents can enter their
ZIP code and see whether they are supposed to leave, he said. The
Web page, www.floridadisaster.org, is already up and offers other
features, but officials hope to have the ZIP code information ready
by the start of hurricane season, which runs June 1 through Nov.
30, Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, governments need to continue to preach to residents to
build the safest house they can and stay in it rather than risk
being trapped in traffic when the storm arrives, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the conference are known to play a parlor game
of predicting which of their colleagues will be the ``star'' of the
following conference, the one representing the area struck by that
season's big storm. In 1999, it was virtually everyone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, just about the only part of the Southeast that didn't
face a monster storm last summer was the city hosting this
convention. That's small consolation; when the Big One hits the
low-lying Big Easy, the potential for catastrophe here is greater
than anywhere in the hurricane target zone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
