<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: Resending to add TELEVISION-NEWS.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, April 22, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Dennis Liff at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION-NEWS (Los Angeles) _ A new nationwide survey has
found that endless, annoying promotions and sensationalized stories
have so turned off local television news viewers that they are
flipping off the tube now more than ever before. The study of 402
adults found that 10 percent of television viewers now refuse to
watch any TV news shows _ double the figure from 10 years ago _
while in some markets the figure was as high as 33 percent. By
Harrison Sheppard. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, April 22, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Dennis Liff at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-VERDICT (Los Angeles) _ The Walt Disney Co. coerced an
executive dying from AIDS into signing away millions of dollars in
benefits, a federal jury ruled. In an 8-0 vote, jurors rejected
Disney's argument that Robert Jahn chose to give up his benefits
after he was discovered taking kickbacks. ``It's a moral victory.
This is the appropriate verdict. And I hope this corporation gets
the message. It shouldn't conduct business like this,'' said Larry
Sackey, an attorney for Jahn's estate. Disney's lawyer had no
comment. A judge will decide how much to award Jahn's estate. By
Greg Gittrich. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MAHONY-FREEWAYS (Los Angeles) _ Can religious believers find
peace, or at least become patient motorists, on Los Angeles'
clogged freeways? That's one of the points Cardinal Roger Mahony
is, ahem, driving at in his Easter message. The Roman Catholic
archbishop of Los Angeles _ head of the nation's largest
archdiocese, located in the fatherland of America's freeways _
issued an Easter message highlighting several areas where believers
can remove ``obstacles in our lives,'' including, he said,
overcoming frayed nerves that cause loss of temper and hostility
toward other motorists. He also tailored his remarks to other
aspects of life in L.A., including the area's ethnic diversity. It
should be noted he is building a new cathedral above the Hollywood
Freeway. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
