<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      04-21 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AIDES CRITICIZE GOP'S MEDICARE PRESCRIPTION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House has sharply criticized the House
Republican proposal for Medicare coverage of prescription drugs,
saying it seemed ``like a Swiss cheese plan with more holes than
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's economic policy adviser, Gene Sperling, and
his health policy coordinator, Chris Jennings, said on Thursday
that they were frustrated by the lack of specifics in the
Republican plan and disliked the details that they did know.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials insisted that they wanted to work with
Republicans in Congress to add prescription drug benefits to
Medicare, the health insurance program for 39 million people who
are elderly or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican plan, outlined last week, would use private
insurance subsidized by the government to help pay prescription
drug costs for people treated outside hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's proposal, in contrast, drug coverage would
become a standard part of the Medicare benefits package, available
to anyone willing to pay an extra premium, and the government would
bear most of the financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   At a White House briefing Thursday and in interviews Friday,
White House officials appeared to be sending two messages.
</P>
<P>
   First, they said, the House Republican plan is flawed. Second,
they still want to work out a compromise on the issue, which will
figure prominently in the presidential campaign and in many
congressional races this year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe their strategy in passing the
legislation, Sperling and Jennings said they pinned their hopes on
the Senate Finance Committee, where members of the two parties have
a history of working together. The committee has held several
hearings on Clinton's plan and on drug benefits in general.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican plan, Jennings said, there is no guarantee
that private insurers will offer affordable drug coverage in all
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what provision of the proposal assures that all,
most or even any Medicare beneficiaries will have access to the new
drug benefit,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans are fleshing out their proposal, drafting
legislation based on cost estimates they had received from the
Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   John P. Feehery, a spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
said: ``White House officials are shooting in the dark. They want
to turn this into a political issue. If they would try to work with
us instead of just shooting at us, we might be able to get
something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human services, said,
``The silver lining of the Republicans' prescription drug plan is
that they finally came up with one, though it's two pages.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, Sperling said, ``What we have now from the
Republicans is a two-page document which has more questions than
answers, and to us, it still seems like a Swiss cheese plan with
more holes than substance.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration also said the financial outlook for Medicare
was brighter than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare's hospital insurance trust fund will be solvent until
2025, two years later than previously projected, Shalala said. A
report issued on March 30 by trustees of the Medicare program said
the trust fund would be exhausted in 2023.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year difference can be explained by a computer
programming error, officials said. Because of the error, the
government underestimated the interest that would be earned for the
trust fund. The assets of the trust fund, beyond the amounts needed
to pay benefits and other expenses, are invested in special
government securities.
</P>
<P>
   Richard S. Foster, chief actuary of the Medicare program, said
the amount of the underestimate, $2.1 billion this year, would
increase gradually to $20 billion a year by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Many liberal Democrats have questioned the sincerity of House
Republicans, suggesting that they are drafting a prescription drug
plan to provide political cover in this fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Sperling said he would not challenge the Republicans'
motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing for us right now is not to try to read their
minds, or read their motivations,'' Sperling said, ``but, for the
good of the country, to take seriously any suggestion someone makes
that they are sincere and trying to work together with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to respond to the Republicans, he said, is ``by
giving them the benefit of the doubt and taking them at their word
that they want to work together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
