<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STODA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In a familiar battle, Heat without its strongest soldier
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was difficult to watch.
</P>
<P>
   There was Tim Hardaway, not so long ago the Heat's most
important player, on the sideline at LaSalle High School while his
teammates went through a final practice Friday afternoon in
preparation for today's NBA playoff opener against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   There was Hardaway struggling through exercises on knees and
legs and feet so sore he is unwilling or unable to describe the
pain that burns too often and lingers too long. He would dip, and
labor to return to a standing position. He would balance on one
leg, and strain _ especially on his left side _ to stabilize for
more than a few seconds. He would step up and down, on and off a
bench in movements too deliberate to hide the exertion necessary to
complete the task.
</P>
<P>
   He is 33 years old, and closer to the end of a very good career
than he cares or allows himself to admit.
</P>
<P>
   He is 33 years old, and still tormented by last spring's
disappointment when New York's belligerent Knicks bumped the Heat
from the first round of the playoffs. That episode only compounded
the disappointment of the previous spring when the Knicks also took
out the Heat in a first-round confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, perhaps more than anyone on Miami's roster, craved a
return playoff test. April and its so-called second season couldn't
get here quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Now, here it is.
</P>
<P>
   And the harsh reality of it all as the Heat come lugging their
baggage of playoff failures past into playoffs present is that
whatever they do _ beginning against Detroit _ they'll probably do
without Hardaway assuming any kind of a leading role.
</P>
<P>
   SWIMMING AGAINST A STRONG TIDE
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway isn't a great player anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In his current state of physical disrepair, arguments have grown
from whispers that Hardaway isn't much better than average. His
feet hurt. His ankles hurt. His knees hurt. And his feet, ankles
and knees hurt beyond the normal range of pain many NBA players
endure at this stage of a long season.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that the most recent of Hardaway's injuries _ an
inflamed plantar fascia tendon in his left foot _ is a mask for
recurring problems stemming from his knee injuries anger him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my foot,'' Hardaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Heat head coach Pat Riley, too, says it's Hardaway's foot. And
then he says more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the deal,'' Riley said. ``There's nothing under the
rug. Even when he was healthy and playing, Tim was hurting. He has
had knee problems. That's nothing new. The foot? The ankle sprains?
It's like a bathtub you turn on and forget about ... it overflows.
That's what Tim is fighting now.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Hardaway would strap himself into a harness
and walk against water resistance in a pool at AmericanAirlines
Arena. The force of the spray can rush out at an impact of 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway won't drown.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, without him, might.
</P>
<P>
   HARDAWAY CAN ONLY GIVE SO MUCH
</P>
<P>
   The Heat played almost half the regular season (30 games)
without Hardaway, and Riley insists he is comfortable with rookie
Anthony Carter, who was a Yakima Sun King in the CBA last season,
at the point. That's what he says. Whether he means it or not is
another question. Riley, though, is absolutely uncomfortable about
the 10 or 15 minutes every game the Heat play without Hardaway when
Jamal Mashburn goes to the point in relief of Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A position we don't like to be in,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where Hardaway, if available, might fit.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said it's ``doubtful'' Hardaway will play at all in the
opener against the Pistons, but that's coachspeak gobbledygook
meaning little. More revealing is Riley's admission _ hope, is what
it was _ that the Heat might milk those same ``10 or 15 minutes'' a
game out of Hardaway at some juncture in the Detroit series.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who remains more capable of producing the heroic
moment than anyone else on the team simply because he remains more
willing to take the heroic risk than any of his teammates, can't do
what he wants to do these days. So it is that Riley will get from
Hardaway what he can.
</P>
<P>
   Because he must.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
