<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-MISSILES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATORS TELL CLINTON THEY OPPOSE HIS ANTI-MISSILE GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By ELIZABETH BECKER and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior Republican senators told President Clinton
this week that they opposed his efforts to renegotiate an arms
control treaty with Russia and to build only a limited anti-missile
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The senators _ including Majority Leader Trent Lott and Foreign
Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms _ favor a full, robust
defense system against missiles, and many of them prefer to scrap
the treaty altogether. They worry that Clinton will be too willing
to compromise in order to conclude a strategic arms agreement with
Russia before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   The president has promised a decision this summer on whether he
will proceed to build a anti &UR; - &LR; missile defense system, which would
violate the treaty unless it is amended.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Clinton, 25 senators complained that his proposal
would tie the hands of a future administration by letting Russia
dictate changes in the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty of 1972. That
accord prohibits any national anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without significant changes to your approach, we do not
believe an agreement submitted to the Senate for consideration
should be ratified,'' the Republicans said in a letter sent to the
White House on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have embraced missile defense as their issue and
hope to use it against Democrats in the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed Republican
presidential nominee, said he would deploy an anti-ballistic
missile system ``at the earliest possible date.'' He also said he
would be willing to withdraw from the treaty if Russia refuses to
make the changes he proposes.
</P>
<P>
   But Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee,
supports Clinton's approach and wants the president to decide
during the campaign on deployment. That would allow Gore to fend
off Republican charges that the Democrats have been soft on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Fuerth, Gore's national security adviser, said recently
that Clinton ``has time, and there is every reason why he should
make this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In its search for a compromise, the administration has come up
with an approach that pleases neither the Russians _ who believe
the Americans want to build too large a missile defense _ nor the
Republicans. They say they will block the proposal because it is
not big enough.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is attempting to lock the United States into a
system that cannot defend the American people against even the
limited threats we face today,'' Helms, a North Carolina
Republican, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed amending the treaty to allow the United
States to begin building 100 missile interceptors at a site in
Alaska; it would be the center of a system guided by ground and
space-based radars. The shield is intended to protect the country
against a limited missile attack from potential threats like North
Korea and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, the U.S. and Russian officials have been engaged
in informal talks, which a senior administration described as very
tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are not anywhere near accepting what the
administration has offered,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The senators said the president's actions would make it
difficult to field a much larger anti-missile defense system later,
or to take advantage of other promising technologies, like
space-based lasers and anti &UR; - &LR; missile defenses aboard ships.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A senior Senate Republican aide said the timing of the letter
was meant to blunt Clinton's enthusiasm for negotiating a deal with
Vladimir Putin, the newly elected Russian president, when they meet
in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to try to get word to the White House of the views
of most Senate Republicans,'' said the aide, who said there were 10
to 15 other Republicans who support the aims of the letter. ``The
president wants a strategic arms accord for his legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   While most Republicans in Congress have pushed the
administration to deploy a missile system, some, like Sen. Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska, are not in a rush, arguing that it would be
better to wait for the next administration to make such an
important decision.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are wary of building a missile shield if it undermines
the agreements to prevent the spread of nuclear weapons, a position
supported by many European allies.
</P>
<P>
   This week at the behest of Putin, the Russian Parliament passed
two arms control treaties, including Start II, which nearly halves
the nuclear arsenals of both countries. But Parliament conditioned
those agreements on American adherence to the ABM treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Start II treaty can take affect, the Senate would
have to agree to several protocols, including extending the treaty
to 2007 and accepting that Russia is one of the four successor
states to the accord. It takes a two-thirds Senate vote to approve
a treaty or the protocols.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's strategy is to demonstrate to the world that it is
Washington and not Moscow that is jeopardizing the ABM agreement
and all subsequent treaties to curb the spread of nuclear and other
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators from around the world convene in New York on Monday
to begin reviewing the nonproliferation treaty, under which nations
without nuclear weapons vow not to acquire them, in exchange for
help with civilian nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans who signed the letter this week could block any
treaty changes submitted to the Senate for approval. While it takes
34 votes to reject a treaty if it comes to the Senate floor, in
practice either Helms or Lott could block one by himself. Helms
could keep any pact bottled up in his committee, or Lott could
refuse to call it up for floor action, even if it had come out of
committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
