<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-U.S.-GYPSY-PROFILE-     04-21 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-U.S.-GYPSY-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYPSIES AS OUTSIDERS   OSTRACIZE THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT33 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There he sits, Jimmy Marks, two rows of diamonds on
the bridge of his glasses, diamond cuff links, gold and diamond
rings. He won't give up his fight, this Don Quixote, this deposed
prince of the Gypsies of Spokane, Wash. Most of Spokane's Gypsies
would just like Marks to shut up. He has brought too much exposure
to their secretive world, they say, and he plays into Gypsy
stereotypes. Now he is ``marime'' _ ``unclean'' in Romany, the
Gypsy language _ an outcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They refuse to invite me to a funeral, or a wedding,'' he
said. Recently, he went to a Gypsy gathering, and he was
ostracized. ``They didn't offer me food,'' he said. ``Do you
understand? They didn't give me coffee or cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Marks was sitting in a Greek coffee shop in the Chelsea section
of Manhattan, in town to promote ``American Gypsy,'' a documentary
film by Jasmine Dellal that tells the story of how Marks came to be
an outcast.
</P>
<P>
   The film describes the police raid in 1986 on the houses of
Marks and his father, Grover, a ``baro,'' ``big man,'' a patriarch
of Spokane Gypsies. The Markses were fortunetellers and used-car
dealers in Spokane. The police said they were searching for stolen
goods. They tore gold-plated false fingernails from the women,
snatched earrings from a girl, searched a baby's diapers. They
found $1.6 million in cash, some sewn into quilts, and $160,000 in
jewelry. There were items from 35 different burglaries, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later a Superior Court judge ruled the search
illegal because it had taken place before a warrant was issued. The
Gypsies, who do not trust banks, often keep money at home.
Eventually, four charges were dropped; the cash and jewelry were
ordered returned. Marks and his mother, Lippie, pleaded guilty to
misdemeanors, saying they had unwittingly bought a few items from
an informer for the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Marks family then sued the city of Spokane in federal court
for $40 million, claiming their civil rights had been violated.
Marks was now considered unclean because his home had been
``polluted'': the careful boundaries of Gypsy custom between men
and women, between the upper and lower body, had been violated by
the police in their search. He had also committed another crime in
the Gypsy world: he had brought unwelcome attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   During the 11 years the legal dispute lasted, ``I entertained
myself with the city and county of Spokane,'' Marks said. He
presented a set of deer horns to Spokane's late mayor, Jack
Geraghty. ``I told them, `I gave you horns because you're all
devils.''' He left hundreds of telephone messages for city
officials and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1997 the case was settled, and the city and county
awarded $1.4 million to the Markses, without admitting wrongdoing.
Marks took only a dollar. His brothers split the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Dellal, who produced the film, is from a Jewish-English
background. She said she began making ``American Gypsy'' because of
the almost casual prejudice against Gypsies in the United States
and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Her film opens a door onto a culture long hidden from
``gadje''(non-Gypsies in Romany). (Gypsies usually prefer to be
called ``Rom,'' or ``Roma.'') The exact number of Gypsies worldwide
is unknown because they distrust outsiders and often do not
identify themselves. ``If I were asked where I was from,'' Marks
said, ``I'd say I was Greek because this is a Greek coffee shop.''
</P>
<P>
   There are estimated to be about 12 million Gypsies worldwide, 1
million in the United States. They have always been nomadic _ and
persecuted. Between 500,000 and 1.5 million Gypsies were
slaughtered during the Holocaust, which is known in Romany as the
``Porrajmos'' or ``the devouring.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions for Gypsies in Eastern Europe continue to be
precarious, according to journalists and Gypsy organizations. They
were targeted during and after the war in Kosovo, with 100,000
reportedly driven from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The film addresses some of the myths about Gypsies. It was once
thought that they originated in Egypt, hence the word ``Gypsy.''
But, ``evidence points to their having been a multi-ethnic military
body assembled to fight off the spread of Islam,'' said Ian
Hancock, a professor of Romany Studies at the University of Texas
in Austin, who appears in the film. Hancock is a Romanichal Gypsy,
descended from British Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   The Romany term ``gadjo,'' ``outsider,'' is related to the
Sanskrit ``gajjha,'' or ``civilian,'' Hancock said. The Rom began
migrating from India in the 11th century; until 1864 they were
slaves in the area that eventually became Romania. Today, Romanian
Gypsies, or ``Vlax,'' the group to which the Marks family belongs,
form the largest population of Gypsies in the United States and are
the least assimilated. Rom are divided into groups and subgroups by
country of origin and profession. Among the Vlax are the Kalderash
and Machwaya. The Kalderash, once coppersmiths, often work in auto
body shops; Machwaya women are usually fortunetellers. Marks comes
from both groups.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, who believes he is about 52, was born in a tent near
Boise, Idaho. His parents were migrant laborers. ``They washed my
diapers in cold winter in the river,'' he said. ``I decided to do
my birthday Feb. 14,'' Valentine's Day, he said, to make it easier
to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Dellal's film describes the powerful sanctions against
``pollution'' that govern Gypsy life. The lower part of a woman's
body is considered unclean because of menstruation and is
traditionally covered by a long skirt. Separate towels are used by
both sexes for the upper and lower bodies. Scholars think the
taboos arose because the Rom were forbidden by the local people to
use their public wells, and the customs helped maintain hygiene. A
woman can deliberately ``pollute'' a man by flicking him with the
end of her skirt, causing him to be ostracized. Gypsy marriages are
arranged; a married woman wears a head scarf in public. Among the
Vlax, violations of taboos are judged by a ``kris,'' a court. And
the ultimate punishment, like that imposed on Marks, is
``marimos.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gypsies have long been identified with petty crime. But their
advocates argue that they have been driven to crime because of
discrimination and their inability to get jobs. Still, there are
Gypsy physicians and lawyers. Gypsies are reluctant to send their
children to school, partly because it could provoke interference by
outsiders, and because, they say, they are afraid their children
will learn about ``outside'' ways like drugs and sex. Thus many
Gypsies are illiterate or semiliterate, like Marks, who had only a
second-grade education.
</P>
<P>
   Though Marks technically won his case against the city of
Spokane, he is still crying for justice. He said that his fellow
Gypsies continue to ostracize him ``because I'm still talking to
the media and to city hall, opening our culture to the world,'' he
said. ``The settlement was just money. I know I'm a victim of a
vicious rape.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said that his family is still being harassed by the
police. Over the Labor Day weekend last year, family members,
including his son, David, were arrested at the grave of his father,
where they said they were following the Gypsy custom of ``sharing''
food and alcohol with the dead. ``They want us to leave our dead,''
Marks said. But the Spokane police have denied harassing the
Gypsies. Sheriff Mark Sterk defended the actions of the deputy who
arrested the Markses. ``He asked them to do certain things to
comply with the law and was violently assaulted instead,'' Sterk
told The Spokesman-Review.
</P>
<P>
   Dellal, sitting in the coffee shop with Marks, said that he had
become obsessed. ``That's what's allowed him to triumph,'' she
said. ``But it's also his downfall. He's a loudmouth. It
perpetuates the way he's ostracized.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marks sees himself as a hero, ``your Daniel Boone.'' Marks
asked, ``why didn't he keep his mouth shut?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
