   &UR; REVIEW (All stories to move Saturday) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-MEMORIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Serving in Vietnam, we
bonded, we changed. And we returned home to the other Vietnam, the
domestic battlefield of hard-hats and peaceniks, the Vietnam that
one side proclaimed the frontline against godless communism, and
the other a symbol of all the greed and immorality of a perfidious
establishment. The protests waned, but we still avoided talking
about the war. Many people viewed veterans of the war with
condescension. But the image of Vietnam and the veterans that
developed in the 1980s was far different from any grunt, or any
Vietnam I knew. By Serge Schmemann. (Moving in the `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SNOBS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In these digital days, not knowing
the difference between memory and hard disk space can be grounds
for social ostracism. Cell phones are required for professionals
from a certain class background, and it helps to flaunt a personal
digital assistant _ preferably one with data-beaming capabilities.
``Early adopters'' have always been a bit obnoxious. From the first
proud few to replace slide rules with calculators to CB radio
hobbyists to the audiophiles who paid thousands of dollars for the
first CD players, gadget freaks have often seemed to exist in a
jargon-filled matrix of their own, oblivious to the mundanities of
civil society. By Amy Harmon. (Moving in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-PERKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Americans have new
expectations from their health care system. They want the latest in
medical technology, just as they hunger for the latest sports
utility vehicles and other jazzy consumer goods. But they also seek
balms for psyches often embattled by illness, and ways of dealing
with pain and discomfort that do not come in pill form. They are
also want medicine to improve their looks, often in an environment
where a checkup, a cancer screening and a facial can all be done
under one roof. And the health care industry is responding to
consumer demand. It is offering more aesthetic procedures and
complementary services. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Elian Gonzalez case illustrates
that courts run on adult time while children suffer the
consequences. For many American children, their destinies remain
uncertain, sometimes for months and years, as their custody and
child welfare cases wind through the courts. Experts see tension
between two competing notions of time: the deliberate, adult pace
of the law, in which a day, or a week or a month may be seen as not
significant, and the the highly compressed time of child
development, in which bonds can be made, or poisoned, in the same
space of time. By Somni Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-HISTORY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Both sides in the gun control
debate assume that America's earliest experiences with guns shaped
the modern American character. Where they differ is on whether
Americans should embrace their frontier heritage and reliance on
guns, or resist it. But in a new book due this fall, a historian
challenges what he calls a modern myth and argues that gun
ownership in the frontier era was far from universal. By Anthony
Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   PIPEDREAM.COM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In this time of dizzying
volatility on Wall Street, no company's fortunes have seesawed
quite so dramatically as those of PipeDream.com, whose initial
public offering in January zoomed from an initial price of $2 a
share to 468 5/8 in its first week of trading, making its founder
and chief executive officer, Ethan Proctor, 17, the youngest
dot-com billionaire on record. During the recent sell-off in
technology stocks, however, PipeDream plummeted to 2 1/4. An
interview with Proctor.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE-SECRECY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Nations were once able to
hide their armaments, misdeeds and fortresses from the eyes of nosy
civilians, while militaries could pry into most corners of the
globe from spy satellites, secure in the knowledge that they could
control who got to take a peek. No more. Taking pictures from space
is undergoing a revolution, and it is making some governments feel
naked. Private companies are launching increasingly sophisticated
reconnaissance satellites, and governments are finding it harder to
restrict what snapshots they distribute to anyone willing to pay
the price. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-PHOTO-REVIEW (Undated) _ It became the most remembered
photograph of the fall of Saigon, and most people believed that it
showed desperate Americans crowding on to the roof of the U.S.
embassy to board a helicopter. That is what the picture caption
usually says. But as with much about the Vietnam war, the caption
is wrong. The building is a nearby apartment complex. The people
fleeing are Vietnamese. The last flight out of Saigon was hours
away. In its way, the photograph is a metaphor for all the
misunderstanding that plagued the Vietnam War. By Fox BUtterfield.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Washington) _ Iran is in the midst of a brutal,
open-ended political war being waged on several fronts - the
courts, the press, television, the Parliament, the pulpit, the
bazaar, the streets. The current round of fighting heated up after
reformists candidates swept to victory in the first round of
Parliamentary elections in February. And the stakes are high -
nothing less than the nature of the Islamic Republic itself. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-THIRDWORLD-REVIEW (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ The changes
created by the Internet in rich industrialized nations are well
known, affecting everything from the way people date to the way
they work. But less is known about impact on communities with
limited contact with the rest of the world. As examples of such
experiments multiply, at least one outcome seems certain: the way
people in these communities relate to each other and with the
outside world is likely to be altered forever. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-CONTRASTS-REVIEW (London) A correspondent describes the
contrasts he observed after leaving the World Economic Forum in
Switzerland, and then heading to Africa: rubbing shoulders with
dot-com billionaires, oil industry barons and sleek investment
bankers, in an Alpine village set among among the pristine snow
fields, and then, on the Angola-Zambia border, mingling with the
poorest of the poor, where the meaning of the word economy had been
distilled to the barefoot essentials of survival. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
