<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY DIDN'T BUCKLE, AND THE DEVILS CREDIT ROBINSON 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it was over on Thursday night, when the Devils had swept
the Florida Panthers out of the playoffs with four straight
victories, it was time for a few admissions. Yes, the Devils said,
there was real relief that they had avoided the humiliating
first-round exits of the previous two seasons. And yes, the calm
guidance of Coach Larry Robinson had made a real difference for a
team that in recent years had found a way to underachieve at the
worst possible moments.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took Friday off and will practice Saturday in New
Jersey. The second round of the playoffs will not start until
Thursday _ and the Devils are not sure yet whom they will be
playing _ but for now they can take some encouragement from the
fact that the way they took care of the Panthers this week was
reminiscent of the way they captured the Stanley Cup in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in the 1995 postseason, the Devils used brilliant
goaltending from Martin Brodeur. Scott Stevens, the Devils'
captain, neutralized Florida's best player, Pavel Bure, in the same
way he defused Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr, Philadelphia's Eric
Lindros and Detroit's Sergei Fedorov in the 1995 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So now it is 1995 that the New Jersey players will probably be
asked about as they get ready for the second round next week, and
not 1998 and 1999, when the Devils were upset by Ottawa and then
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we were scared that it could happen again,'' a relieved
Randy McKay said Thursday night of the Devils' concern of being
ousted in the first round again. ``There was a lot of that
around,'' he said of the fear, ``but we have a lot of character
players on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he added tellingly, ``we have a good coach.''
</P>
<P>
   In the happy Devils locker room, Bobby Holik raved about the
influence of Robinson, who was named head coach with eight games
left in the regular season and the team in a serious slump. He said
Robinson's emphasis on being positive _ on even looking ahead
beyond the first round _ had bolstered the team's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry said, `Let's not be satisfied with one round,' and we
started to believe,'' Holik said. ``I don't know how many times he
calmed us down on the bench and said the right things in the
dressing room.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Robinson's speeches in the dressing room took place
during the first intermission of Thursday's game. The Devils had
played a poor first period and they could have been down by more
than Bure's only goal in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say whether he was angry or composed,'' Holik
said, ``but I can tell you he got his point across. It was because
of Marty that we were down by just a goal. We could have been down
by four or five.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson spoke, the Devils listened. They came out with
enthusiasm for the second period and took the lead on goals by
Patrik Elias and Scott Niedermayer before the period was over. They
then protected their 2-1 lead until the final four minutes of the
game, when Sergei Nemchinov scored twice to wrap up the series.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Devils will try to stay sharp while waiting for their
next opponent to emerge. If Pittsburgh can pull off its threatened
upset of Washington, then the Penguins will play the Philadelphia
Flyers in Round 2, while the Devils play the winner of the
Toronto-Ottawa series, which is tied at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger issue for the Devils at the moment has to do with
their long layoff between the first and second rounds. The Devils
say it is good for them because they have players who need time to
heal their injuries and because they have two 36-year-old
defensemen, Stevens and Ken Daneyko, who can use the rest. Still,
after a week off, the Devils will not have quite the same momentum
they do right now.
</P>
<P>
   They will practice lightly on Saturday at their South Mountain
Arena training facility in West Orange, N.J. On Sunday they will
get the day off. And then the pace picks up as the Devils try to
write a sequel to 1995.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
