<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRASER, VANNEY TURNING INTO DYNAMIC DUO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ The dangerous strike tandem of Ariel Graziani and
Jason Kreis was nearly shut out last week by Galaxy central backs
Robin Fraser and Greg Vanney, both U.S. National team regulars.
</P>
<P>
   Kreis, Major League Soccer's reigning MVP, was shut down and
Graziani scored on a broken play in the 82nd minute, providing some
exciting final minutes before the Galaxy escaped with a 2-1 victory
over the Dallas Burn at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from that mishap and a couple others that figure to
happen along the way as the two work side-by-side for the first
time, Fraser and Vanney are developing into a dominating backline
duo.
</P>
<P>
   And, again, they will have their work cut out for them tonight
when the Galaxy play the Miami Fusion at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is led by strikers Eric Wynalda, coming back from an
anterior cruciate ligament injury that forced him to miss most of
the 1999 season, and Roy Lassiter, who had a successful season with
D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wynalda and Lassiter have been among the league's finest,
but they've struggled this season.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Wynalda, from Westlake Village, and Lassiter has
been erratic, which might explain Miami's early offensive troubles.
The Fusion has scored only four times, but remains 1-1-3 since it
has allowed a league-low three goals.
</P>
<P>
   However, when Wynalda, Lassiter and former Galaxy striker Welton
get on track, the Fusion will be tough to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin and I take pride shutting down the other team's forwards
and I thought we did a good job against Graziani and Kreis until
that silly goal,'' said Vanney. ``With Roy, you've got to stay with
him in the box because he finds ways to get on the end of crosses
to put away goals, but he's usually not going to create many
chances for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric can create things for himself, but he gets frustrated a
lot. You just have to stay on him and make sure you don't give him
those chances and at some point he'll get frustrated and probably
start to get on his teammates and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanney, a midfielder converted to left back and now central
back, has been a teammate of Fraser's since the inaugural season,
but the two had never occupied the same central space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin and I have good communication,'' said Vanney. ``We
understand each other and know our roles, so it's worked out all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has matched its MLS-record scoring pace in 1998,
scoring a league-high 12 goals, but Los Angeles also has given up
six goals in five games, a reason the team is 3-0-2 instead of 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Four of those goals against the Galaxy came in Graziani fashion,
either on a broken play or a set play, which Vanney said he and
Fraser recognize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't given away that many good goals; most of them are
from bad clearances,'' said Vanney. ``There has also been too many
balls bouncing around the box that we're a second late getting to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we eliminate those kinds of silly goals, we'll be tough
to score against because our offense is doing a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid thinks Miami coach Ivo Wortman may
change his lineup with the Fusion struggling for goals. Miami has
been shut out three straight games and has gone without a goal for
315 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're an improved team but I'm sure they're frustrated
because they haven't scored goals in a while,'' said Schmid. ``I
wouldn't be surprised if Welton starts, or if they start (Henry)
Gutierrez instead of (Andy) Williams. We have to be prepared for
the Miami team that has been playing or the new one that might show
up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
