<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TECHNOLOGY-STOCKS-$AD     04-21 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOLOGY-STOCKS-$ADV23-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING SOLID GROUND AMID FALLEN BODIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to remove graphic note; no other changes.)   By ALEX BERENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE CHIPS? OR WOODEN NICKELS?
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the leading technology stocks might be wondering
how to appraise them after the plunge of early April left the
technology sector as skinny as a football lineman on an
all-broccoli diet.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell an ugly tale. Cisco Systems stood at $80 on
March 27. By April 14, it traded at $57. Sun Microsystems slid from
$105 to $76.50 over the same span.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisco and Sun have held up well, compared with the Internet
stocks, which have been in a bear market since January. The
bellwether there, Yahoo, was down more that 50 percent, to $114.375
on April 14, from $237.50 on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Those are enormous declines, considering that companies like
Cisco and Yahoo are supposed to be the new-economy leaders, with
solid products, superior management and real sales and profits.
Buying them was supposed to be the safe way to invest in technology
_ at least when compared with the hordes of dot-coms that have
proliferated since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And it is true that the blue-chip technology companies have held
up a bit better and recovered a bit faster than their more
speculative kin during the Nasdaq's rocky ride this month. But
losing 30 or 40 percent of an investment in two weeks never feels
great, even if someone else's stock is down 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So where do these companies stand? Is the recent sell-off
nothing more than a short-term dip and the latest buying
opportunity? Or is it a warning to investors that there is no such
thing as a technology blue chip, that even the best technology
companies are overpriced and due for a fall?
</P>
<P>
   To answer those questions, Money &AMP; Business reviewed the
prospects of six technology leaders in six key markets with Wall
Street analysts and institutional investors. The common thread to
the experts' views: in a market filled with uncertainty, investors
will have to pay up for the quality they seek.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL: NO LONGER A CYCLICAL?
</P>
<P>
   Intel, the world's largest maker of microchips, is a powerhouse
whose lofty earnings, according to Wall Street's consensus
estimate, will rise 23 percent a year, on average, over the next
five years. Yet the ratio of the company's current stock price to
estimated earnings for this year is below 40, a bit under the
average for technology companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index. And that multiple is well below those of other leading
information technology suppliers like Sun Microsystems (92.1) or
Cisco ( 126.5).
</P>
<P>
   So is Intel a bargain? The fact that it fell just 8.1 percent
during the technology sell-off suggests that a lot of people think
so. And it certainly deserves to be an anchor holding for any
investor in information technology, according to L. Roy Papp, whose
firm has 12 percent of its $1.25 billion under management invested
in Intel.
</P>
<P>
   His firm, L. Roy Papp &AMP; Associates of Phoenix, invests in what
its researchers determine are the growth stocks with the strongest
outlooks over the next three to five years. His investment case for
Intel, his largest holding, is built on the conviction that it is a
stellar company with outstanding management.
</P>
<P>
   It is also predicated on the belief that the semiconductor
industry that Intel dominates has changed. As the productivity
payoff from information technology has become increasingly
apparent, Papp said, companies have come to regard computing as
both fast-changing and essential. Accordingly, their spending
patterns will hold steady, because they have recognized that
technology is a continuing cost of doing business. Intel should be
a prime beneficiary of that trend. ``This is no longer the cyclical
swing business that everybody has always said it was,'' he said.
That line of reasoning would explain why Intel easily warrants its
current P/E multiple of 38.1.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the company faces daunting challenges as computing's center
of gravity moves beyond the PC industry _ Intel's stronghold _ and
toward the Internet. If the highest growth comes from Internet
appliances like hand-held computers and ``smart'' cell phones,
Intel could be hurt. It has a promising entry for that niche, the
StrongArm chip, but it has a host of competitors including
start-ups like Transmeta.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is moving forcefully to make chips for powerful server
computers that are the hubs of computer networks. Its
microprocessors for servers are very profitable, selling for $1,000
to $3,000 apiece, compared with as little as $65 for the Celeron
chips that power low-cost PC's.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts say server chips account for only a tiny
percentage of Intel's chip volume and could not soon offset real
slippage in its basic PC business. ``Potentially, these are huge
problems for Intel,'' said Keith Diefendorff, editor in chief of
Microprocessor Report, a newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   And a revived Advanced Micro Devices is giving Intel competition
for the high-performance, high-profit chips that run more costly
PC's.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Intel is coping pretty well with its challenges. Its
share of the PC processor market is 82 percent, up from 76 percent
at the end of 1998, when it was slow to respond as rivals began
making low-cost PC chips, according to Mercury Research in
Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Internet challenge, Intel appears to be moving
quickly to adjust. Once before it made a tough but successful
transition in its business _ when it abandoned memory chips in the
mid-1980s and bet its future on microprocessors. ``Intel is a
company that reinvents itself,'' said Dean McCarron, a Mercury
Research principal.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVE LOHR
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO: AN EARNINGS ENGINE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Yahoo may have fallen from a high of 240 on Dec. 31 to
barely half that level last week, but the company's fans are as
confident as ever in its future.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that even at its current levels, Yahoo, the leading
Internet portal, has a market valuation of more than $70 billion
and a price-to-earnings ratio of 279.2. Never mind that even if
Yahoo's earnings rise 50 percent a year for the next five years and
its stock stays flat, Yahoo will still have a P/E ratio of near 40
in 2005. Yahoo may be expensive, but investors get what they pay
for, analysts and money managers say.
</P>
<P>
   That Tiffany-style reasoning may infuriate value investors. But
anyone who is even considering buying Yahoo is no value investor.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the bulls' case:
</P>
<P>
   At a time when most dot-coms are losing money, Yahoo makes a lot
of it. In the first quarter this year, Yahoo reported sales of $228
million and net income of $63 million. That is a net after-tax
profit margin of 28 percent, far higher than that of most
old-economy companies.
</P>
<P>
   The high margins are no accident, according to Lise Buyer, an
Internet analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``Like America
Online, Yahoo is benefiting from scale,'' Buyer said. Once the
company's servers are running and its technical support staff is in
place, the cost of each additional Web page it delivers to a viewer
is close to zero. But it is likely to earn additional advertising
revenue on each of those pages. That spells high margins once the
company passes its break-even point.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's huge audience, meanwhile, makes it more desirable to
advertisers and content providers, analysts say. That enables it to
offer better content to visitors, who are then more likely to
return, a virtuous circle that reinforces the company's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really fail to understand the strength of their
business model,'' said Minyoung Sohn, research analyst at Janus
Capital, which owned more than 5.5 million Yahoo shares at the end
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Janus sold Yahoo shares last year as the company's price rose
steadily, but Sohn said Janus was again buying. Yahoo should easily
surpass Wall Street earnings estimates of 54 cents a share next
year and 70 cents in 2002, because overall spending on Internet
advertising is likely to soar, Sohn said. He noted that the
Internet now accounts for 10 to 15 percent of media use, but only
about 2 percent of advertising spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately,'' he said, ``dollars will follow eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's international revenues are also likely to soar over the
next several years, said Susan Walker White, an Internet analyst at
J.P. Morgan. She noted that 40 percent of the company's users were
already outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo is one of the blue-chip Internet companies,'' White
said. ``It's one of the stocks that investors need to own.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the company's sky-high P/E ratio and market
capitalization, White is not worried. ``It's hard to use
traditional valuation metrics to measure these stocks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX BERENSON
</P>
<P>
   CISCO: NEW KING OF THE HILL
</P>
<P>
   No event better underscored the changing of the guard in the
Internet economy than when the market capitalization of Cisco
Systems surpassed that of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly peaking at a half-trillion dollars before slipping over
the last month, Cisco has been the exemplary Silicon Valley growth
machine of the last five years: Its annual earnings growth over
that period has averaged almost 43 percent; revenue growth has been
above 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Microsoft marked the shift from centralized
computers to the desktop PC. Cisco's dominance is evidence of the
new hegemony of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For many industry executives in Silicon Valley, Cisco's
ascendancy underscores two growing beliefs: that Microsoft has
peaked, and that the financial success stories of the Internet age
will be driven by the world's insatiable appetite for additional
communications capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is the leading manufacturer of the Internet's plumbing _
powerful computers that route and switch the data packets among Web
servers and Internet surfers. As such, it stands to be the largest
beneficiary of the growing push toward multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   Under John Chambers, its chief executive, the company has
pursued a strategy of growth by acquisition that has been so
successful that in the valley the company is known as the Borg _
after the ``Star Trek'' character that incorporated its enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Its growth-by-acquisition model has allowed Chambers to scan the
horizon for the next important Internet niche and then to buy the
companies whose technologies will ensure that Cisco maintains a No.
1 or No. 2 position in markets where it chooses to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest issue in the future is how many balls can John
Chambers juggle?'' said David Bunnell, author of ``Making the Cisco
Connection: The Story Behind the Real Internet Superpower'' (John
Wiley &AMP; Sons, 2000). Of course, growth also depends on the stock
market's continued enthusiasm for Cisco, he noted; the company now
uses its explosive stock value to provide ``Cisco dollars'' to fuel
its acquisitions, of which there have been dozens.
</P>
<P>
   But with a P/E of well over 100, it is fair to question the
inflated value of that currency. ``The valuation is extreme,'' said
Andrew S. Cupps, portfolio manager of the $850 million Strong
Enterprise fund, who adds that Cisco's current multiple assumes
that it will be able to maintain its dominance of networking and
continue to execute its strategy flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   That is a tall order. ``I don't think they are going to just
roll over into the next paradigm,'' Cupps said. Indeed, while the
growth of Cisco's router and switch business seems assured, the
company has begun zeroing in on markets that are certain to lead to
titanic industry battles: Internet telephony and Internet
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers has said that he is anxious to remove the traditional
analog telephone from his desk and replace it with one that routes
voice conversations over the Internet. That will ensure that Cisco
collides head-on with two of the companies that are already its
biggest competitors, Lucent Technologies and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, that battle may pale in light of Cisco's growing
interest in the market for Internet appliances _ consumer devices
designed to permit Internet surfing from the kitchen or the den.
Thought to be the next great area of Internet growth, the struggle
over the appliance market will inevitably set Cisco on a collision
course with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   _By JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON.COM: E-TAILERS ON SALE
</P>
<P>
   No new-economy sector has taken a worse smack on the chin than
Internet retailers. Stock prices of merchants like eToys and
Bluefly started plunging well in advance of the Nasdaq downswing.
As a group, the stocks remained depressed well after technology
stocks started to rebound last week. Are such shares
bargain-basement buys or damaged goods?
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com remains the 800-pound gorilla of Internet retailers,
with a market capitalization of more than $18 billion. And in many
ways, Amazon exhibits the attractions _ and vulnerabilities _ of
the group. Sell-side analysts remain as bullish on the company as
they were a year ago, even though the stock has fallen 50 percent,
to $52.375, from a 52-week high of $113 on Dec. 9. Of the 28
analysts who follow the stock, 11 rate it a strong buy and 10 rate
it a buy, according to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks
company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Here is why they have faith: Customer demand for online shopping
is more robust than ever. In a study released last week, Shop.org
and the Boston Consulting Group predicted that online sales would
soar 85 percent in 2000, to more than $61 billion. And as a market
leader, Amazon stands a better chance of reaping the benefits;
indeed, its sales continue to skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   Tumbling stock prices could play to Amazon's favor, if weeding
out the competition leaves more spoils for the top players.
``Tightening of capital markets is good news for all the folks
trying to build lasting companies, as opposed to the subset that
are trying to build flash-in-the-pan stocks,'' said Jeffrey Bezos,
Amazon's endlessly optimistic chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But this last-man-standing theory ignores that Amazon, like many
of its virtual competitors, relies on complex marketing
arrangements with other dot-com companies to produce revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has deals in which it takes stakes in companies that it
finds promising _ Living.com and Audible.com, for example; those
companies agree to pay Amazon substantial annual sums for the
patronage. Amazon is counting on these deals to bring in a revenue
stream of nearly $100 million a year over the next five years _
something that is not likely to happen if the overall market for
dot-coms collapses.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of cost controls. As every quarter
passes, Amazon's losses deepen. Bezos is promising that this will
change as of the fourth quarter this year. ``We are looking to
drive our loss as a percentage of sales to single digits by the end
of this year,'' he said. That means losses won't end, but will
finally start to grow less rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but investors have heard that before. As of last week,
First Call predicted a loss of $1.22 a share for 2000, and a loss
of 58 cents a share for 2001. It was just a year ago that the
guidance Amazon gave analysts led them to forecast losses for 2000
of 14 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LESLIE KAUFMAN
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The Inktomi Corp. crossed an all-too rare milestone last week:
for the first time, it reported a net profit. And for the eighth
consecutive quarter, the company had revenue growth of over 200
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you are new to Inktomi's story, you are not alone. Founded in
1996, Inktomi makes products that are largely invisible _ much like
the Intel microprocessor inside a personal computer or the Cisco
Systems router shuttling bits on the computer network. That is
because Inktomi specializes in Internet infrastructure. Its first
``product'' was actually a service, a Web search engine for Yahoo,
Hotbot, Lycos and other big portals. The company also sells Web
shopping and directory services.
</P>
<P>
   But the big revenue driver has turned out to be a software
product, Traffic Server, which Inktomi sells the old-fashioned way,
in a shrink-wrapped box. Traffic Server, which runs on Unix or NT
servers, is an Internet cache that functions like the bit of cache
memory on a microprocessor to speed delivery of Web pages. Used by
big Internet service providers like America Online and
Excite(at)Home, Traffic Server monitors network traffic and stores
information nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dravis, an analyst at BancAmerica Securities, rates Inktomi
a ``strong buy'' and a core holding among Internet software stocks.
``They are very uniquely positioned, one to have their business
model driven by people doing searches and shopping on the Web, and
second by the focus on content distribution because they have a set
of technologies to sell to network providers to enhance
performance,'' he said. ``In a world where everybody is trying to
pick between the haves and the have-nots, they're definitely among
the haves.''
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi has been surprising in its ability to deliver on that
assessment. For the quarter ended March 31, Inktomi reported
earnings of $1 million, or a penny a share; analysts had expected a
loss of 2 cents a share, according to First Call. Revenue rose to
$47.3 million, compared with $15.2 million in the period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   With growth like that, it is no surprise that some investors
think that Inktomi is a buy, especially given the fact that at
$129.125, it is trading at just over half its value of a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Inktomi faces ample competition, from established
companies like Cisco Systems, which offers a line of cache servers,
and Novell, which sells caching software to server manufacturers.
It also is up against newcomers like CacheFlow, which sells caching
appliances _ simple servers preloaded with a proprietary operating
system and caching software. Oracle has talked about giving away
caching with future releases of its database. And Akamai
Technologies, the other big name in speeding up the Internet,
offers caching as part of its suite of content delivery services on
a pay-as-you-go basis.
</P>
<P>
   But Inktomi executives say the company was never just about
caching, and they point out that by publishing the application
programming interfaces to Traffic Server, they are in fact
establishing a new platform. That means that independent software
developers could write programs that run on Traffic Server much as
they write programs to run on Microsoft's Windows or Oracle's
database.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only group that has third-party developers for
Internet infrastructure software; that's by design,'' said Eric
Brewer, Inktomi's chief scientist and a co-founder. ``If you're
just doing caching, you don't need any of this. But our view has
always been that we're rebuilding the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE M. FISHER
</P>
<P>
   SUN MICROSYSTEMS: SUN, IN BLAZING COLOR
</P>
<P>
   Ask Steven A. Ballmer, Microsoft's chief executive, about Sun
Microsystems and he sees red.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just that Ballmer views Scott McNealy, Sun's
co-founder and chief executive, as a ringleader of a Silicon Valley
cabal that persuaded the Justice Department to pursue its antitrust
investigation of Microsoft. Sun has also been in Microsoft's cross
hairs ever since Microsoft began trying to move up the computer
industry food chain in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Yet last quarter, the one in which Microsoft began to ship its
long-overdue ``Sun Killer'' Windows 2000 operating system, Sun's
revenue grew by a striking 35 percent, to $4 billion, and earnings
rose 49 percent, to $436.2 billion. That means that Sun's revenue
growth is almost certain to accelerate this year above the 25
percent it averaged in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The financial numbers are all the more remarkable because of the
threats that Sun faces from all sides. It is apparently managing _
at least for now _ to disprove what its archrival Microsoft would
like to establish as industry wisdom: that Microsoft's Windows
2000, offered in conjunction with low-cost hardware based on Intel
microprocessors _ would be Sun's undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's success in recent years is an exceptional gauge of the
growth and impact of the Internet. These days, the computer maker
is usually the first company that a new commercial Web site comes
to when it wants to create an Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rivalry in the service space is intense. Indeed,
Microsoft ranks second among the Internet software threats faced by
Sun. The free Linux operating system and its Apache Web server is
actually the leading Internet server software.
</P>
<P>
   McNealy has also been the primary target of both Louis V.
Gerstner Jr. of IBM and Carly S. Fiorina of Hewlett-Packard. Both
chief executives have scrambled in recent years to catch up with
something that Sun understood first: that the market for powerful
and reliable server computers is the backbone of e-commerce growth.
</P>
<P>
   But neither of them appears to be gaining ground, at least not
yet. Analysts said Sun's numbers indicated that it was actually
gaining market share against its rivals in the hot market for
dot-com e-commerce servers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sun's 239.2 percent rise leading up to the Nasdaq peak,
its shares retreated only 18.8 percent from March 10 through April
14, far less than Nasdaq's decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun's decline was exceptionally moderate and underscores the
company's strength,'' said Roger McNamee, a fund manager at
Integral Partners in Menlo Park, Calif. ``If you are in a period
like we are in today _ when you don't know where we are in the
cycle and there is a flight to safety _ then Sun is a huge
beneficiary of that.'' Sun shares closed on Thursday at $87.75.
</P>
<P>
   While some investors are taking a ``show me'' attitude toward
Sun as they wait to see what inroads Windows 2000 will make in its
server business, McNamee minimizes that threat: ``I think the
market is expanding faster than Microsoft can serve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McNealy has no shortage of challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry executives expect the portable and mobile
Internet appliance world to be the dominant growth area of the
future. It may be the most significant part of Sun's business to
watch _ and the measure of whether McNealy will continue to keep
Ballmer huffing and puffing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
