<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: MINISTER IS ASKED TO FORM CABINET
</P>
<P>
   President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi asked Treasury Minister Giuliano
Amato to try to form a government, following the resignation of
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema. Amato, a socialist who was briefly
prime minister in 1992, said he would present a cabinet soon after
Easter. Parliament, where the center-left has a thin majority, will
then hold a vote of confidence. The center-right opposition,
emboldened by its success in regional elections, wants to block
Amato and force early elections.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PAVAROTTI FACES TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Bologna have asked an investigating magistrate to
rule that Luciano Pavarotti be tried on tax fraud charges for
claiming that his primary residence is in Monte Carlo. The
prosecutors, who say the opera star's residence is in Modena,
accuse him of owing the government nearly $5 million. Last week
Pavarotti lost an appeal against an order that he pay another $5
million in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: RED LIGHT GUIDE
</P>
<P>
   The Amsterdam police, recognizing that some foreign tourists are
attracted to the Dutch capital partly or wholly for the
availability of its sex and drugs, will publish an English-language
guide to the city's temptations. ``Police Red Light Guide'' will
include tips on how to avoid tricksters when buying soft drugs or
visiting a prostitute, activities not strictly forbidden by law.
The leaflet, to be published soon, is written buy a veteran officer
who has spent 12 years on the red-light district beat.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: JOINS CHEMICAL BAN
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has become the 134th nation _ and the last in Europe
_ to agree to adhere to the convention banning chemical weapons,
the group monitoring the treaty said. This requires Yugoslavia to
renounce production, stockpiling or use of chemical weapons and
report those chemicals that can be used for military as well as
peaceful goals, said the Organization for the Prohibition of
Chemical Weapons.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: OPPOSITION MEETS
</P>
<P>
   Ninety members of Serbia's opposition and Crown Prince
Aleksandar Karadjordjevic of Yugoslavia appealed to the Yugoslav
army to join their drive to topple the Belgrade government. The
opposition leaders, led by Zoran Djindjic of the Serbian Democratic
Party, made the appeal at the start of a two-day conference in in
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: BRIBERY INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   A long-running investigation of improprieties in the real estate
market has revealed that a lobbyist paid $135,000 to 15 politicians
on Dublin's county council under the guise of election campaign
contributions. Frank Dunlop is said to have made the bribes in 1991
to win votes for the rezoning of a shopping center. While the
recipients have yet to be named, six Dublin county council members
then in office now hold seats in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: RULING UPSETS ANWAR
</P>
<P>
   After months of indecision, a judge denied a request by the
defense to call Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad to testify in the
sexual misconduct case against his former deputy, Anwar Ibrahim.
Ibrahim argues that the charges amount to a political vendetta
against him by the prime minister. A lawyer said Anwar was so
frustrated by the ruling that he was considering abandoning his
defense altogether.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA: KHMER ROUGE TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The government says it is considering a letter from
Secretary-General Kofi Annan of the United Nations that tries to
end a stalemate over how to set up an international tribunal to try
former leaders of the Khmer Rouge. Annan recently met with Prime
Minister Hun Sen to discuss possible arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: DRIVE AGAINST `HONOR KILLING'
</P>
<P>
   The military ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, told a
government-sponsored human rights conference that he would ensure
that so-called ``honor killings'' are aggressively prosecuted as
murder. The practice of male family members killing female
relatives who have demanded a divorce or are suspected of sexual
indiscretions usually goes unpunished. The general offered no
timetable for a return to democracy or an end to the ban on
political rallies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: PREMIER OPTIMISTIC
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi said the country's economy will
still grow at a rapid rate this year despite the devastating floods
of February and March. Flood damage to infrastructure and
agriculture will inevitably slow growth, but the economy is still
expected to grow between 6 percent and 8 percent this year, he
said. In 1999, the country's gross domestic product grew by 9
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
