<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEXT PHASE OF THE CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 22:
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau announced with relief this week that 65
percent of households had already mailed in their census forms,
about the same as in 1990. That may not seem like a grand
achievement. But the response rate has been dropping steadily for
decades, and the bureau was predicting a further decline this year.
Now it moves to the more difficult and expensive task of
door-to-door canvassing of families that did not respond by mail.
This phase will be especially critical for New York City, whose
mail response rate fell to 52 percent this year from 53 percent in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Accuracy is important because census counts serve as the basis
for apportioning seats in the House of Representatives and state
legislatures as well as distributing about $200 billion for
education, health and other federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   This year's response rate may have been dampened when some
Republican leaders complained that the long form _ sent to one in
six households _ contained intrusive questions about the number of
bathrooms and residents' mental condition, and asserted that it
need not be completed in full. Indeed, the response rate for
families receiving the long form has fallen six percentage points
below the 1990 level. That is unfortunate, because the long form
seeks information pertinent for everything from enforcing civil
rights legislation to designing the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau must now persuade households that have not
returned their forms to open their doors when census takers knock.
The workers never ask to enter anyone's home, but they need an
opportunity to pose their questions. To address the problem, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani said Friday that New York City would buy photo
identification cards for census takers, so residents need not fear
the arrival of strangers at their door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
