<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO CHASE THE MOMENT IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vince Carter arrives at Madison Square Garden Sunday,
carrying a nation and a television network. Tim Duncan trudges into
a San Antonio training room, a franchise's hope tied to his injured
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the 67-victory machine powered by Shaquille
O'Neal, who recently made his postseason intentions clear: ``I know
what I want as a player now,'' the Lakers' supernova center said.
``I want the bling-bling.''
</P>
<P>
   Bling-bling? ``Yeah,'' O'Neal said. ``That's the look of a
trophy when it's all nice and shiny, sitting in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's title aspirations aside, almost as many of the league's
stars are hovering above the rim as are hurting Saturday and Sunday
when the National Basketball Association postseason begins with
eight first-round games.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan has torn cartilage in his left knee. His availability for
the Spurs' series against Phoenix, who lost Jason Kidd to injury
last month, is as uncertain as San Antonio's chances of defending
its title.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-Detroit series may also be affected by health
concerns. The Heat's Tim Hardaway has a foot injury that may keep
him from playing in the first round, and the Pistons' Grant Hill
has a bone bruise in his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs begin Saturday at 12:30 p.m. with Game 1 of the
Detroit-Miami series at American Airlines Arena in Miami.
Phoenix-San Antonio, Seattle-Utah and Philadelphia-Charlotte will
follow.
</P>
<P>
   The other four series _ Toronto vs. the Knicks,
Minnesota-Portland, Sacramento vs. the Lakers and Indiana-Milwaukee
_ begin Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A long and drawn-out first-round schedule, created to
accommodate the league's broadcast partners, has also caused a
commotion. In a move designed to improve the league's
cable-television ratings, the first-round matchups are spread over
two weeks. Rather than having the usual four games per night, TNT
and TBS _ the Turner networks _ will not compete against each other
for viewers on weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme examples of time off between games include a
Sunday-Wednesday-Sunday format for the first three games of the
Knicks-Raptors series. The Lakers and Kings have four days off
between Games 1 and 2 of their series.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing opening series features Carter making his
playoff debut in New York on Easter Sunday, leading the Raptors in
Game 1 against the Knicks _ a team he singed for 33 points and a
few breathtaking dunks per game during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Kobe Bryant face off against Jason Williams and Chris
Webber in a Western Conference shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along, we felt we matched up well with them,'' said
Webber, whose Kings lost their three games to the Lakers by a
combined 11 points. ``Now we'll find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley will coach his 243rd playoff game Saturday, 74 more
games than Red Auerbach coached and 90 more than Lakers Coach Phil
Jackson. But two first-round exits against the Knicks the past two
seasons has jangled his reputation as the game's premier motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fashionable notion about the Miami Heat,'' Riley said.
``Everybody in the league talks about it. All the teams in the
Eastern Conference want to play us. We'll be there, and we'll be
there with very strong character.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill wants to propel the Pistons out of the first round, a feat
Detroit has not accomplished since it drafted the All-Star forward
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hungry,'' Riley said, ``but no hungrier than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   With plummeting television ratings and a general perception that
the league's popularity is still suffering the aftereffects of
Michael Jordan's retirement two seasons ago and a labor fight that
shut down part of last season, the NBA is banking on the flair and
flash of its young stars to boost interest in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But it may have to wait for at least another season. Like Kevin
Garnett's Timberwolves, Webber's Kings and Allen Iverson's 76ers,
Carter's Raptors are underdogs to advance to the conference
semifinals. Small-market graybeards like Karl Malone in Utah and
Reggie Miller in Indiana may still be around much longer than their
younger counterparts, unless a few first-round upsets occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when people start watching and they start following
some of these great stars,'' said Doug Collins, the former coach
and NBC analyst. ``If we can get some of these guys with some great
rivalries, that's when stars are really born. You go back and look
at Michael Jordan and Isiah Thomas and Larry Bird and Magic
Johnson. That's when they really made their mark.''
</P>
<P>
   After all the off-day hyperbole between first-round games, it
may come down to O'Neal and Bryant carrying a heavy load in June.
They may not only be playing for the Lakers' first post-Magic title
but also for a league in need of genuine star power.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we win it, you guys are going to give me a week to
celebrate and then you're going to say, `Magic won back to back,
can you?''' O'Neal said, smiling. ``And after we win two in a row,
they'll say `When Pat Riley was there, they were talking about a
three-peat. Can you do it?'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK. First, we have to get one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-EARTH-DAY-NYT &LR;      04-21 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EARTH-DAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE EARTH DAY CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 22,
Earth Day:
</P>
<P>
   On the 30th anniversary of the first Earth Day, there is much to
celebrate and much to remind us of the unfinished business of
protecting the planet.
</P>
<P>
   While the job of cleaning the water, air and land continues, the
world must begin tackling the less visible threat of global
warming, an issue largely unknown 30 years ago. This new threat is
less immediate and less easily solved, and therefore will require
an even stronger commitment in the years ahead. This is essentially
the message of the organizers of Earth Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, some American rivers were so polluted with chemicals
that they were fire hazards. Big cities were choked in smog, toxic
wastes leached freely into the land, and bird and fish species were
disappearing. In a generation's time, with the creation of the
National Environmental Policy Act, the Clean Air Act, the Clean
Water Act, the Endangered Species Act and the Environmental
Protection Agency, a great deal has been achieved to reverse
decades of environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
   This shift was propelled by citizen activists and a handful of
political leaders who first gave voice to a broadening ethic that
made protecting the environment a political as well as moral
obligation.
</P>
<P>
   The same public passion and political will must now be summoned
to confront the global greenhouse effect. Congress has given little
attention to this issue. For that reason, the Earth Day organizers
have done a public service by making global warming a focus of this
year's program.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike polluted air and contaminated water, global warming is
not a local problem that can be seen or felt. But its impact on
every region on earth could be devastating. Most scientists agree
that the earth's climate is warming, due at least partly to the
accumulation of greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide that trap
the sun's energy. Although the effect may be gradual, the
consequences could be catastrophic, with increased floods and
droughts, rising sea levels and destruction of ecosystems caused by
climate change.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 more than 150 nations, including the United States,
signed the Kyoto Protocol to limit the amount of greenhouse gases
released into the atmosphere through the burning of fossil fuels.
The agreement calls for industrialized nations to cut their
emissions by 2010. But few nations have moved to carry out the
agreement. The United States is the largest greenhouse gas emitter,
but the Senate is opposed to ratification of the Kyoto agreement
and the policies needed to carry it out.
</P>
<P>
   Curbing these gases requires intensive energy conservation and
the promotion of cleaner energy sources such as solar and wind
power. The political and economic hurdles are substantial, both in
this country and abroad. They can be overcome if the public is
educated about the importance of this issue. The 30-year history of
the Earth Day movement shows that when people are awakened to an
environmental crisis, they will ultimately demand change in the way
we live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2203EDT &QL; 
