<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORE ADMITS ERROR
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong. Vice President Al Gore said Friday that he had
erred when he wrote in his 1992 environmental credo, ``Earth in the
Balance,'' that the internal combustion engine could be eliminated
in 25 years. ``I now see we can do it in less than 25 years while
preserving and creating new jobs,'' he told an audience in Romulus,
Mich., where he was joined by the Teamsters president James P.
Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that his critics had ridiculed that suggestion but,
he added, ``I expected that criticism then and I wear it as a badge
of honor today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa and Gore later lunched together. No word from Gore on
trade, and no word from Hoffa on if or when he would endorse Gore.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH LEADS IN 2 STATES
</P>
<P>
   Polls in two Midwestern states show Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
leading Vice President Al Gore in tight races. In Illinois, Bush
was leading Gore 44 percent to 42 percent, with Pat Buchanan
getting 3 percent, and 11 percent undecided, a Mason-Dixon poll
found. In Ohio, Bush was leading Gore 46 percent to 39 percent,
with 9 percent undecided, in a poll by Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS MONEY MISMATCH
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is such a devoutly Democratic state that
Republican candidates often tend to be outmatched in fund raising,
but not usually this outmatched. In campaign finance reports filed
this week, Sen/ Edward M. Kennedy, a Democrat, said he had $3.7
million on hand. His Republican rival, Jack E. Robinson III,
reported having $631. Of course, Robinson has not started raising
money in earnest. A wealthy entrepreneur, he has also said that he
will spend a lot of his own money. Still, Robinson's cash supply
looked even more underwhelming compared with the Libertarian
candidate, who had $30,867 on hand, and the Constitution Party
candidate, who had $9,714.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA CLUB ON ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club is running radio advertisements criticizing the
environmental record of Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who is up for
re-election. ``Instead of protecting Washington's water and salmon,
Sen. Slade Gorton has been carrying the water for the mining, oil
and gas and development industries,'' asserts one advertisement on
Seattle radio stations. Though Gorton has a hefty campaign war
chest, state Democratic leaders say he is vulnerable because he is
more conservative than most voters. A Gorton aide dismissed the
Sierra Club commercial as ``a bunch of phony, unsubstantiated
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   EMBATTLED IN CALIFORNIA
</P>
<P>
   The California insurance commissioner, Charles Quackenbush, one
of only two Republicans still holding a statewide office, is
embattled on several fronts these days, facing inquiries into his
handling of cash settlements paid by insurance companies after
disputes about their handling of claims from the Northridge
earthquake in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Miller, a Democrat and a former state secretary of state
who supports campaign finance limits, has also filed a complaint
with the state's Fair Political Practices Commission that accuses
Quackenbush of receiving campaign contributions from insurers who
failed to disclose that they had issues pending before the
commissioner. Quackenbush has denied any impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH No events &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
