<HEADLINE>
THESE CLIPPERS NEVER HAD A CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first incision for Clipper Autopsy 2000 was
based on seniority.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Eric Piatkowski, who now has worn the colors for six
seasons in a row, wielded the scalpel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a terrible year,'' said Piatkowski of the 15-67
nightmare, qualifying as the second-worst season for what Sports
Illustrated so shrewdly declared the worst franchise sports in
history. ``What's disturbing is that there's so much talent here. I
don't know if anybody realizes how much we underachieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to take responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone should.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no excavation to locate a definitive turning
point; this team could have been pronounced dead at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Clippers gathered for two-a-days at L.A. Southwest
College, the optimism roared. Rookie messiah candidate Lamar Odom
had blindsided his historic accountability gap and was on board ...
on time. Sure, Maurice Taylor had gone from franchise bedrock to
free-agent mercenary _ a role also occupied by newly acquired
sniper Derek Anderson _ but it was hoped the anticipated contract
audition would become motivation to accelerate the team's victory
curve.
</P>
<P>
   The voodoo had been removed from Michael Olowokandi's trick knee
and Brian Skinner had evolved through tireless offseason workouts.
Tyrone Nesby had been re-signed, snatched from the clutches of the
San Antonio Spurs. Rodney Rogers' tummy and Lamond Murray's
shooting percentage were gone. Sherman Douglas, Pooh Richardson and
Darrick Martin were out; Eric Murdock was in.
</P>
<P>
   And Chris Ford, who grimaced through a post-lockout catastrophe
of 9-41, was back for round two.
</P>
<P>
   His second Clippers team _ the NBA's youngest _ would play to
its strengths, he said. It would mitigate its inexperience with
speedy, opportunistic offense and relentless pressing defense, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a month of rehearsals, the finer points of such tactics
were rarely, if ever, taught. There was no workshop on defending
the pick-and-roll. No lab for refining outlet passes and defining
fast-break lanes.
</P>
<P>
   And no apparent worries when the exhibition season yielded 5
victories in 8 games.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 30 points in his debut, Odom was unable to muster a
victory in the Staples Center launch vs. the Seattle SuperSonics,
refugees from the previous NBA draft lottery. Odom didn't match or
eclipse that number until producing 33 points in Wednesday's closer
at Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The first month ended with four wins in 14 games; month two
produced five in 15. Then things turned chilly. Ford, whose style
seemed better-suited to self-policing veterans, realized his team
had turned to another channel.
</P>
<P>
   Downright chummy off the floor, the Clippers were strangers on
it. They didn't share the ball on offense or embrace the notion of
team defense. Taylor took a verbal swing at Olowokandi after an
ugly defeat at Denver, and practices became little more than
slow-motion waltzes.
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor, the Clips' vice president of basketball
operations, started attending these workouts, quietly seething over
what her perceived as a lack of attention to detail by Ford, a
coach he wasn't wild about hiring in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   No, credit for that maneuver, and the $8 million in salary-cap
overflow Baylor could have been used to hire a savvy veteran or
two, should be presented to owner Donald T. Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing every year,'' Taylor said, ``and it all
goes back to Sterling. There are things that easily could have
nipped in the bud, but never were.''
</P>
<P>
   Nesby, who celebrated last season's hunger to escape the CBA by
showing up at camp 30 pounds heavier, thought he was obliged by his
new contract to shoot more often. He openly groused about his
career being ruined by the very team that provided an opportunity
to create it.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, who supplied several portents of future greatness,
retreated into a funk when confronted by what he presumed were
officiating conspiracies and scoreboard truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to get in the weight room and I need to work on the
pull-up jumper, the greatest shot in the game,'' Odom said early in
the campaign. Odom seemingly was waiting for the season to end
before beginning any such regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner _ the inside defensive presence _ rolled his left ankle.
Murdock _ the sage floor leader _ did the same. They would miss 49
and 42 games, respectively. Olowokandi may never invalidate critics
of his selection with the first pick in the 1998 draft, but did
provide a few head-scratching moments of sunshine (he scored 17
points and had 20 rebounds against Dikembe Mutombo in Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   However, most of his sophomore season was spent in the same
predicament that muddled his rookie season _ foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor did slightly improve in most statistical categories, but
was far from the $70 million property now offered by his new agent,
David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a variety of things,'' Taylor said. ``That includes my
situation ... that didn't help. But there was chemistry,
uncertainty among players as to who would be here and who wouldn't
next year, a coaching change ...''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, the Suns annihilated the Clippers 114-68 in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was a goner the next day. He was replaced by loyal
assistant Jim Todd, who was given the job on an interim basis.
Todd's first move was to request the hiring of former Celtics great
Dennis Johnson as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Abdul-Jabbar joined the party two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   With Todd going from good cop to bad cop, the Clippers won 4 of
37 games.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sterling must decide to either trust Baylor's instincts in
the hiring of a full-time coach or make some other bizarre
provision. Since the damning SI cover story, executive vice
president Andy Roeser has gone on record declaring the entire
organization will be evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Todd has made a public pitch to be retained, but that seems
wildly farfetched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grass is always greener unless you've been in this
situation,'' said Todd of those aspiring coaches who think they
would be a franchise salvation. ``But it's not so much Xs and Os.
You (head coach) have to be in a position of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the returning players have endorsed Johnson as their
next head coach, but the expected tidal wave of NBA vacancies also
means additional candidates will be available. Abdul-Jabbar, while
respected and liked by the players, doesn't seem to fit their
unofficial profile. But he could fit Sterling's.
</P>
<P>
   There also will the traditional lottery pick, possibly the
selection No. 1. Throw in the 17th and 30th picks. Don't forget cap
room galore for free agents who probably won't be signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be here when everything is fixed,'' said Johnson,
who doesn't dodge the question when asked about his desire to
become head coach, but has made a point of not overstepping Todd's
authority. ``I know it's going to happen one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all things are repairable.''
</P>
<P>
   But that assumes things were whole in the first place. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
