<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SEEKS TO CLAIM THE CENTER AND SHOW HIS WARMTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.C., Ohio, Texas, Tenn., Iowa, N.H.)   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROMULUS, Mich. _ George W. Bush may be portraying himself as an
unconventional Republican, but Al Gore plans to portray him as
really unconventional.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Bush tries to move to the political center, the vice
president is trying to define him as extreme. It is all part of a
newly emerging strategy for Gore as he moves into what his advisers
call the ``compare and contrast'' phase of the presidential
campaign: compare his proposals with Bush's and then ``contrast''
them.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Gore rips his rival's proposals to shreds and
presents his own as reasonable alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Gore has his own careful balancing
act to perform. While hammering Bush on policy matters, he is still
struggling to overcome a problem that has dogged him since early in
the campaign: how to demonstrate that he has a warm and human side,
a passion for the presidency and firm ideals that are not tossed by
political winds.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to warm up his image is guiding much of the Gore
campaign's planning in this stretched-out period until the party
conventions this summer. Indeed, that effort is why he will be
spending full days in schools, staying overnight with families and
visiting them in their workplaces (yes, in earth-tone casual
attire). The idea is to show him to be just an ordinary person who
is both engaged and engaging.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the issues, and the vice president's effort to depict
Bush's positions as extreme, will be by any means ignored. The
other day, addressing gun control, Gore said the governor's signing
legislation allowing Texans to carry firearms into churches
demonstrated how beholden he was to the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at a news conference here in Michigan, the issue was the
environment. Gore said that ``Governor Bush seems to have the smug
assumption that he can get away with calling himself an
environmentalist,'' when Texas is ``the worst-polluted state in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore plans additional speeches in the next couple of weeks
focusing on other differences with Bush, starting with the
governor's proposal for a big tax cut, what the vice president
calls the ``risky tax scheme.'' That theme will be hammered
relentlessly by the Gore campaign until November.
</P>
<P>
   ``People haven't noticed it yet,'' said Bob Shrum, a top Gore
adviser, ``but I assure you, they will: that George W. Bush doesn't
have any money to pay for his tax cut or the programs he's
proposing. By giving into the right wing on the tax cut and
proposing a tax giveaway for rich people, he has disabled
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, while it may seem that Bush is the one dominating the
news lately with one fresh proposal after another, Gore aides
express confidence that with major policy positions already laid
out by the vice president, he is now well positioned to counter any
public infatuation with his rival, much as he did in the primary
campaign against former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   One central issue that should benefit the vice president is the
economy. While he has distanced himself from President Clinton in
several areas, he has of course fully embraced the robust
Clinton-era economy. The Clinton economic record has been so
successful that the voters, who once favored Republicans as
stewards of the economy, now say they more trust the Democrats in
that role.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Gorlin, a Democratic consultant not affiliated with the
Gore campaign, said this amounted to a sea change that should work
to the vice president's advantage. ``You could never convince
voters that a Republican is more fiscally irresponsible than a
Democrat,'' she said. ``That's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   But while crediting Gore for positioning himself to benefit on
issues, Gorlin, like others, said he had still not made voters
comfortable with him as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He acts like he's someone who's too scared of losing,'' she
said. ``He thinks the answer lies in a rational process.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a quarter-century in public office and nearly a
year formally on the presidential campaign trail, Gore remains a
remote and distant figure, according to independent polls and his
own advisers. Changing that perception of him, his aides say, is
his most important mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``His biggest asset is that he came out of the nominating
process strengthened rather than weakened, and we still have a good
economy and we can say we're better positioned to keep things
going,'' one top adviser said. ``His weakness is his ability to
connect. George Bush is a likable guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problem is virtually the opposite of Bush's. The governor
is bulking up on policy statements with a Democratic tilt to
compensate for the perception that, though likable, he is a policy
lightweight who veered too far right during the primaries. Gore has
to convince voters of his human side, of his understanding how
ordinary people feel, and also that he has lasting principles that
make him more than a mere political tactician.
</P>
<P>
   ``His biggest problem is that he needs to find himself,'' said
another Democratic strategist not affiliated with the campaign.
``The biggest thing that voters perceive is that he doesn't have a
North Star.''
</P>
<P>
   That perception has been evident to Gore advisers, and to the
candidate himself, since the fall, when they began a concerted
effort to strip him of the trappings of the vice presidency and
place him in settings where he could appear unscripted and have a
chance to interact with people. The goal, then as now, was to
cultivate a sense of humanity that still eludes him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, he doesn't project that warmth, that
strength of his personality,'' said one supporter, Elizabeth
Bagley, former ambassador to Portugal. ``When people see him on a
one-on-one level in a personal, intimate setting, then they realize
he's a warm, caring person. He's become very good at town meetings.
He likes them and gets positive feedback from them. What he started
doing on the campaign, once Bradley became a threat, has really
helped him.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a continuation of the town meetings that Gore held as a
congressman from Tennessee and renewed in the primaries, his
campaign is putting him in settings that scream ordinary American
life: schools, homes and workplaces. The idea is that once people
see him on a human scale, they will perceive him as, well, more
human.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stalwart vice president in a blue suit standing behind the
podium _ that is still the view that prevails in most states,'' a
Gore insider said. ``We have to put him in settings where that's
not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   His advisers think those settings show his assets: not just the
breadth and depth of his command of policy but personal assets too,
like a willingness to open himself up to spontaneous situations and
his hunger for the job of president.
</P>
<P>
   This is essentially a national retail strategy, in which Gore is
trying to win voters over one by one. ``The lessons of Iowa and New
Hampshire are clear: the more people see him, the more they like
him,'' said Chris Lehane, his press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   This means not only campaigning exhaustively but also pushing
the Gore story, and the anti-Bush message, through advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both campaigns will be able to run Iowa- and New
Hampshire-like campaigns, with real advertising budgets,'' a senior
adviser said. ``We will be able to really introduce the candidate
and tell a story that has a beginning, a middle and an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore plans to visit a school at least once every two weeks. He
spent two full days in schools last week, one in Ohio, one in North
Carolina, staying with families overnight. The visits generated
positive local news coverage while showing the vice president
involved with real people on education, a topic of major concern to
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is also preparing for a more concerted
challenge from Bush than it received from Bradley. One theme that
Bradley arrived at belatedly and expressed only sporadically is one
that Bush has already begun to exploit: that Gore changes his
positions with the political winds and so cannot be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   As if it were a company logo, Bush press releases are stamped
with perhaps the single most damaging sentence that Bradley spoke
to Gore during the primaries: ``Why should we believe that you will
tell the truth as president if you don't tell the truth as a
candidate?'' The real question, Bradley said, was one of
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley posed that question during a New Hampshire debate, after
Gore, who early in his career opposed federal financing of
abortion, maintained that he had always been consistent in
supporting abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign clearly perceives credibility to be a matter
on which it is vulnerable and, taking a page from the Clinton
playbook, is trying to turn the issue against Bush. In a virtual
echo of Bradley's question, the vice president recently told a
gathering of newspaper editors: ``How can we believe what he says
he would do nationally when we see what he actually has done as
governor? This is about something more than public policy. It is
about credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   That tack is only a slight detour from the larger message that
the campaign has been delivering: that Gore has the experience to
be president, while Bush would be too much of a risk. It will be
countered by an equally simple message from Austin: that Gore
cannot be trusted, while Bush would restore honor and integrity to
the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
