<HEADER>
A3979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-JOURNALS-REVIVE-ART-N     04-21 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALS-REVIVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY HELPS REVIVE AN OLD IDEA: THE LITERARY JOURNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT34 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Small magazines that publish short fiction come and
go, but Barbara Probst Solomon longs for the glory days of the
``little magazines,'' those literary journals that made a dent on
the public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, 70, a writer who teaches about the history of the
little magazines in a course on modernism at Sarah Lawrence
College, hopes to recapture those days with her own new quarterly,
The Reading Room. She is publishing it with a print-on-demand
technology that promises to help make such journals financially
viable again.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue of The Reading Room, a 331-page paperback, has
work from well-known writers like Madison Smartt Bell, James Purdy,
Stanley Crouch, Daphne Merkin and Kenneth Koch. Among the new
writers are a few of Solomon's top students in graduate writing
programs at City College and Sarah Lawrence. (She said she felt
dreadful that they had no place to submit their work.)
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's advisory board includes Saul Bellow, the Nobel
Prize-winning novelist, and the next issue will feature work by
another Nobel Prize winner, Jose Saramago of Portugal, and the
Spanish writer Juan Goytisolo.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon came of age in New York, Paris and Spain, in the 1950s
when small fiction magazines were still flourishing. The little
magazines like New World Writing, New American Review, Discovery
and the original Story created outlets in which budding writers
could gain a reputation before publishing a novel or finding an
audience in a mass-market magazine like The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Even though fine magazines that publish fiction remain, Solomon
said, they do not play the role that certain magazines once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of my generation owe our reputation to the little
magazines,'' said Solomon, an author of six books whose early
writing appeared in New Campus Writing, Partisan Review and
Peninsula, a literary journal in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now young writers, on the whole, are expected with their first
novel to make it big with a kind of mass audience. And if they
don't, they risk not existing. It's like a movie opening. In my
generation, reputations were made more slowly. It's a much harder
trip for writers today.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon wanted to start a literary quarterly in the late 1980s
but gave up because of the cost. ``It would have been like trying
to put on an Off Broadway play that had the budget of a Broadway
musical,'' said Solomon, who is also the New York cultural
correspondent for El Pais, the Spanish newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Literary journals suffer from the same difficulties that make
book production so worrisome. To justify high printing costs at a
standard press, publications must be printed in large quantities.
Then there is the costly risk of overprinting copies that might not
sell.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon believes she has found a way around the problems with a
new digital printing technology that is more commonly viewed as a
way to rescue out-of-print books.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ingram Book Group, a leading book distributor,
made the system available through its subsidiary, Lightning Print.
The process electronically stores the publication in a digital
library for $100 to $150. A copy can be printed within seconds
after a bookseller places an order and shipped within 48 hours. The
process lets publishers print one or two copies _ or hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Solomon has spent less than $5,000 to start The Reading
Room. It is the only major literary magazine to be started with the
print-on-demand technology, said Ed Marino, the president and chief
executive of Lightning Print.
</P>
<P>
   The other night in Park Slope, Brooklyn, an audience of mostly
young people jammed into Barnes &AMP; Noble to hear young and old
writers read from their work in The Reading Room.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy, an elderly man with intense blue eyes, read in a soft,
gentle cadence from his story, ``Easy Street.'' The crowd seemed
mesmerized. No one left, and no one coughed.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon says she hopes that established writers like Purdy can
help push along the reputations of young unknown writers whose work
will make up more than a third of her quarterly, which she
described as eclectic and international. ``It's literary,'' she
said, ``but not so abstruse that no one knows what you're talking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Watson, 47, a City College student, said he was grateful
that Solomon published his short story, ``Backward the Drowned Went
Dreaming.'' He had a novel published in France two years ago, but
has had little luck here. He has worked in the kitchen of a
restaurant in Williamsburg, Brooklyn, to support himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publishing business here is very commercial,'' he said,
``so if you're not known, they are pretty timid about taking on new
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Obaso, 32, a former student in Solomon's creative writing
workshop at City College, has also been frustrated by many
rejection letters. Her story in the magazine _ her first published
work _ is about a woman in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is to not only get noticed,'' Obaso said,
``but that people see the work, appreciate the work and understand
what I am trying to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
