<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CORPSE-FLOWER-ART-     04-21 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CORPSE-FLOWER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONX TO SHED A SYMBOL WITH AN ODOR OF DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bronx has long had its share of image problems,
what with a high crime rate and burned-out neighborhoods. In recent
years, though, Bronx leaders have become optimistic that the
borough may be finally shedding its old reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But for Borough President Fernando Ferrer, one of the last
pieces of the image still needs to be changed: the county's
official flower.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1939, the Bronx's official bloom has been the
Amorphophallus titanum, more often called the corpse flower, or the
devil's tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, native to the rain forests of Sumatra, is one of the
world's largest. It blooms only once every 30 years or so, and when
it does, its odor has been described as eerily similar to that of
rotting flesh.
</P>
<P>
   So, in anticipation of Bronx Week, the third week of May, Ferrer
said he would officially remove the designation of the corpse
flower as the Bronx bloom in favor of the day lily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day lily is infinitely more fragrant, blooms more
frequently and can be seen in the front yards of countless Bronx
homes,'' Ferrer said this week.
</P>
<P>
   The day lily also seemed an apt choice, Ferrer said, because the
pioneering hybridization of the plant was accomplished at the New
York Botanical Garden in the 1920s and '30s by Arlow B. Stout, a
Bronx native.
</P>
<P>
   The choice appears to have wide support among other borough
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to think of the corpse flower as the Bronx flower,
because people would think the Bronx and think, `The Bronx
stinks,''' said Michael Ruggiero, the senior curator for
horticulture at the New York Botanical Garden. ``The Bronx is a
people place, and the corpse flower is not a people plant. The day
lily is, and therefore is a good fit for the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   The corpse flower was designated the borough's official flower
on July 6, 1939, by Borough President James J. Lyons, when one of
the exotic plants bloomed at the botanical garden. Two years
earlier, another corpse plant at the garden produced the first
recorded bloom in the United States, an event attended by
considerable sensation and throngs of spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The 1939 event also attracted hundreds of visitors, and
newspaper accounts described Lyons as so taken by the flowering
that he proclaimed it the Bronx's own on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The plant was, to Lyons' mind, an apt representative of the
Bronx as he saw it then. ``Its tremendous size shall be symbolic of
the fastest-growing borough in the City of New York,'' he said of
the giant plant, which grows as much as four inches a day when it
is in bloom. When fully grown, its leaves can reach a diameter of
15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying smell, however, was less admired. News crews
were posted around the clock to record the plant's blooming in the
sweltering confines of the garden's greenhouse, and they were said
to have nearly fainted from the smell.
</P>
<P>
   (The official flowers for the other boroughs are much less
exotic. Brooklyn has the forsythia, Staten Island the pinkster
azalea and Queens the tulip and the rose. Manhattan has not
selected a flower.)
</P>
<P>
   For all the fanfare of 1939, the corpse flower's status as the
Bronx's official bloom could hardly be called common knowledge
today.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with nearly two dozen people on Fordham Road, just a
few blocks from the botanical garden, found not one resident aware
of the plant's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they were thinking of the South Bronx about 20 years ago
when they named it,'' said Juan Colon, a resident of the area, when
informed of the plant's name and status.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Ferrer and borough historians said, Lyons was simply
looking for some publicity for his borough. ``This is a man who was
known to plant our flag in other boroughs,'' Ferrer said.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the corpse flower has remained the county bloom, and
borough officials said they were looking forward to the designation
of the new flower, scheduled for May 15 at the botanical garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea,'' said Lloyd Ultan, the borough
historian. ``The Bronx has had some image problems in the past as
it is, and while the day lily may not be as unique, it certainly is
more fitting. The Bronx is flowering too, after all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
