<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, APRIL 22
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ZIMBABWE-LAND-DISPUTE-NYT (moved on Sunday, April 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, April 16,
about the dispute over land in Zimbabwe misstated the title of
Nomore Sibanda, who described an attack that killed two political
opponents of President Robert Mugabe. Sibanda is the information
officer for the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions, not spokesman
for the opponents' party.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ZIMBABWE-FARMS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, April 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, April
19, misstated the country's previous status. Two decades ago,
blacks won their struggle for independence against a white minority
government, not against Britain.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COLUMBINE-ANNIVERSARY-NYT (moved on Thursday, April 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, April
20, about the first anniversary of the shootings at Columbine High
School in Colorado misstated the relationship of Michael Shoels,
who is suing the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department, to Isaiah
Shoels, a victim. Michael Shoels is Isaiah Shoels' father, not his
stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BUSH-NEPHEW-NYT (moved on Monday, April 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 17,
about the role of George P. Bush in the presidential campaign of
his uncle George W. Bush misstated the name and station of a
television talk show on which the nephew recently appeared. The
show was ``Cafe California,'' not ``Cafi California''; it is on
KWHY-TV in Los Angeles, not Telemundo.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT (moved on Thursday, April 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, April
20, about the documentary ``George Wallace: Settin' the Woods on
Fire,'' to be shown tomorrow and Monday on PBS, misidentified the
opponent in Wallace's televised confrontation with the United
States government in 1963 over desegregating the University of
Alabama. He was Deputy Attorney General Nicholas deB. Katzenbach,
not Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CAMBODIA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Tuesday, April 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, April 18,
about two first-person accounts of life under the Khmer Rouge in
Cambodia misstated the estimated death toll under that regime. A
widely accepted figure, from Yale University's genocide project,
under the auspices of the State Department, is more than one
million, not two million.
</P>
</TEXT>
