<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-RUSSIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SEIZES JAPANESE BOAT IN INTERNATIONAL WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Changes ``Russian president-elect'' to ``new Russian
president'' in 3rd graf. Adds to end of 4th graf.) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Russian coast guard fired on and seized a Japanese
fishing boat Friday in waters near Japan's northernmost main
island, according to Japanese and Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The incident threatens to revive tensions between the countries,
which have had disputes about maritime boundaries and possession of
a number of small islands in the area since the end of World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, is scheduled to visit
the new Russian president, Vladimir Putin, in Moscow on April 29.
Japan has been pressing Russia to negotiate a formal peace treaty,
which it says should include the return of northern islands seized
by Moscow in the closing days of the war.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russian officials who briefed journalists in
Moscow, the Japanese fishing vessel disobeyed orders from a Russian
patrol boat to stop for inspection in international waters between
the countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intruder was shelled by the Russian border guards when it
attempted to escape from the Russian economic zone into neutral
waters,'' the Russian ITAR-Tass news agency said. None of the 20
crew members was injured, Japanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian authorities said the Japanese ship, the No. 7
Daitoku-Maru, was operating with its name and identification
numbers concealed and had tried to escape after being summoned.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese authorities gave an entirely different account, saying
that the fishing vessel was operating in Japanese waters near what
Japan calls its Northern Territories.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese coast guard sent three aircraft and four patrol
boats to the scene, 60 miles south of the cape of Ochiishi off the
island of Hokkaido. But officials said the Japanese coast guard
withdrew after the fishing vessel was brought, under escort, into
Russian waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that two Russian soldiers are standing on the
bridge of the Japanese ship,'' said a Japanese official quoted by
Reuters. ``If this continues, we will consider the ship seized.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
