<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- April 21, 2000 -- JOURNALS-REVIVE --
Literary journals suffer from the same difficulties that make book
production so worrisome. In order to justify high printing costs at
a standard press, publications must be printed in large quantities.
Then, there is the costly risk of overprinting copies that might
not sell. Barbara Probst Solomon, 70, believes she has found a way
around the problems with a new digital printing technology that is
more commonly viewed as a way to rescue out-of-print books.
Solomon, a writer and college teacher, surrounded by some of her
students, is publishing a new literary journal entitled ``The
Reading Room.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- April 21, 2000 -- U.S.-GYPSY-PROFILE --
Jasmine Dellal, made ``American Gypsy,'' with Jimmy Marks, the
deposed prince of the Gypsies of Spokane, Wash. ``American Gypsy,''
a documentary film tells the story of how Marks came to be an
outcast, in part due to the fact that he and his mother, Lippie,
brought unwelcome attention to the Gypsy world by suing the city of
Spokane in federal court for $40 million, claiming their civil
rights had been violated in a 1986 police raid on their house.
Dellal's film opens a door onto a culture long hidden from
non-Gypsies. (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MONTICELLO, N.Y. -- April 21, 2000 -- NY-CASINO -- The
St. Regis Mohawks, who are the verge of winning approval to build a
casino in the Catskills, have signed a deal that would turn over
all their rights to build, develop and manage casinos in New York
State to Park Place Entertainment, the largest gambling company in
the world. The Catskills Development Group, which had planned to
donate 30 acres to the tribe for a casino in Monticello, learned
only Friday about the deal. Robert A. Berman, one of the principals
in Catskill Development, L.L.C., at Monticello Raceway. (Joyce
Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- April 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 23 --
INTERNET-STOCK-BUBBLE-4 -- Even in a momentum-driven environment,
some financiers like venture capitalists certainly play their part
in the making of fads. When James Tousignant, left, and Isaak
Karaev founded Multex Systems seven years ago, they wanted to help
brokerage firms send electronic research to institutional clients.
``Then the Internet happened,'' says Karaev, the company's chief
executive. ``And all our investors said, 'This is an Internet
play.' We took the opportunity to change ourselves.'' Now as
Multex.com, ``Our strategy hasn't changed,'' says Karaev. ``The
challenge is which component to highlight.'' (Marty Katz/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- April 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 23 --
INTERNET-STOCK-BUBBLE-3 -- Steve Smith, a founder of OneMain.com,
an Internet service provider, which went public on March 25, 1999.
OneMain.com's stock hit a high of $39.5625 the day it began
trading, an 80 percent increase over the offering price. ``I found
people were only interested in the story,'' he says. ``They hadn't
read anything at all.'' OneMain.com's shares have since drifted
downward, falling 87 percent since their peak to close at $6.25 on
April 20, even though Smith says the company has met the earnings
and revenue targets it set for itself. (Marty Katz/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- April 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 23 --
INTERNET-STOCK-BUBBLE-2 -- ``IVillage Becomes a Metropolis on First
