<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HACKER-ARREST-1STLD-W     04-21 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-ARREST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKER IS SAID TO LIVE IN A MONTREAL SUBURB 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS coding)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ILE BIZARD, Quebec _ It is the picture of North American
suburban normalcy: a new four-bedroom house on the edge of a golf
course, an orange basketball left outside in the rain by the
15-year-old son, a soggy cigar butt left outside on a plastic chair
by dad.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the Canadian and American police, the
15-year-old basketball player is Mafiaboy, for the moment charged
as North America's latest computer criminal. From this house, the
Canadian police have carted away computers that they say the
ninth-grader used to sabotage CNN.com on Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing OK,'' a young man who answered the door said Friday
of his younger brother, the 15-year-old. The older brother cut
short questions, noting that his father and brother were out and
that his girlfriend was visiting Friday, a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Innocent suburban normalcy was also the image painted Friday by
Yan Romanowski, the Montreal lawyer hired to defend the 15-year-old
against two charges of criminal mischief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is your everyday teen-ager, not the kind of guy who
isolates himself in a basement,'' said the lawyer, adding that he
had known the family for years. He ``attends high school, has many
friends, enjoys sports, wears baggy clothes, Nike sneakers'' and
his cap turned backward, Romanowski continued. ``He has never
committed nor been accused of any criminal offense, nor has he been
involved with police authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post, citing classmates and law enforcement
officials, reported Friday that the boy had been suspended
repeatedly from two high schools over the last two years. In
response, Romanowski said: ``I have absolutely no knowledge of the
veracity or falseness of that, or of his grades. I am more
concentrated on preparing the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the cul-de-sac in this upper-middle-class, largely
English-speaking development in Montreal's western suburbs, Denis,
a computer consultant who declined to give his last name, said he
had talked to the boy's father, John Calce, on Wednesday night,
hours after the authorities disclosed the charges. ``He said he
didn't know anything about the computer stuff,'' the neighbor said
of Calce, a heavy-set, 45-year-old bus company executive who
routinely goes out on the front porch to smoke a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN site was hit in a wave of strikes in early February that
blocked or hindered access to some of the biggest Web sites for
hours at a time. In the attacks, remote computing centers were
taken over and used to relay streams of meaningless data at the
target site, overwhelming it with traffic. A spokeswoman for
CNN.com, which is owned by Time Warner, said the site was
``seriously affected'' for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, some computer experts have surmised that more
than one person was involved because of certain differences in
technique, and that copycats may have gotten into the act. If so,
Mafiaboy was not most skilled among them, the authorities said on
Wednesday _ or in any case, not the most careful. ``He was not what
we would call a genius in that field,'' said Inspector Yves Roussel
of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   Among the evidence that led to the Montreal boy, authorities
said, were records from a California campus computing center used
as a relay point and online conversations by someone using the
Mafiaboy screen name. But in the end, the police say, it was Calce
who precipitated his son's arrest, and his own.
</P>
<P>
   About two months ago, investigators from the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police questioned Calce's 15-year-old son about the
attacks. Without enough information to make an arrest, they placed
wiretaps on the family's telephones.
</P>
<P>
   In listening to family conversations, the police say, they
overheard Calce conspire with a friend to have a business associate
assaulted. In a raid before dawn last Saturday, police officers
arrested father and son. Calce and his friend were charged with
conspiracy to commit aggravated assault. Both men pleaded not
guilty and were released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Calce, who lives here with his second wife and two sons from his
previous marriage, put his house up for sale last summer, asking
the equivalent of about $320,000, high for a Montreal suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Calce's 15-year-old son, whose name the Canadian authorities
have not used because he is a minor, pleaded not guilty and was
freed on conditions that forbid him from going on the Internet,
from entering a business with computers, or from going into a
computer store. Also, he is not to talk with his three closest
friends, a restriction requested by prosecutors who hope to use
them as witnesses against him. In online chats, Mafiaboy had
bragged of temporarily disabling a host of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can say my client is Mafiaboy,'' said Romanowski, the
defense lawyer. ``But according to what I have read, many other
people around the world have bragged about being Mafiaboy.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities are considering whether to file any charges
against Calce's son or any others involved in the attacks, Steven
Berry, an FBI spokesman, said Friday from Washington. The Royal
Canadian Mounted Police, who are handling the investigation, have
said they may bring additional charges against the boy once they
have finished studying the seized computers.
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski predicted that a trial would expose the vulnerability
of the Internet, with sabotage ``recipes'' posted for easy
retrieval and ``security experts who don't take the necessary
measures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The best-known hackers have offered their support and help,''
he said, adding that his defense work would be bolstered by ``a
team of computer systems specialists and computer security
specialists.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the lawyer said he hoped the interest of news
organizations would fade so that his 15-year-old client could get
back to his weekend basketball and final exams at Riverdale High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that he will be back in school on Tuesday,''
Romanowski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
