<HEADER>
A3995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES042     04-21 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES0422-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mulholland completes performance
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One game might have been a welcome sight. Two is a
roll for Terry Mulholland. And the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The man who started this five-game winning streak with a
dynamite outing in Milwaukee, brought it full circle Friday night
with the Braves' first complete game of the season in a 6-2 victory
over the Pirates in the first of a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland (2-2) allowed eight hits, two walks and struck out
three in his first complete game since June 18, 1997. He has 46
career complete games.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves did their best to recreate the scene of Mulholland's
Milwaukee turnaround with an assist from Mother Nature. Playing in
chilly conditions, the Braves got him another 2-1 lead and braced
themselves for a close finish.
</P>
<P>
   That only worked for an out before Mulholland gave up a
game-tying homer to Aramis Ramirez, going against what Mulholland
had tried to do for his last two starts and leaving a stray pitch
inside for Ramirez to turn on for his first homer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Ramirez's second hit in his past 23 at-bats and
ended a streak of 13 innings without allowing a homer for
Mulholland. He'd allowed six homers in his first two starts, both
losses.
</P>
<P>
   But Mulholland regrouped, and the Braves backed him up with two
runs in the bottom of the inning on an RBI single by Andres
Galarraga and a Javy Lopez sacrifice fly. Quilvio Veras set the
offensive pace for the night, going 3-for-his-first-3 with a pair
of RBI singles.
</P>
<P>
   His only blemish was getting thrown out at home plate for the
third out of the fifth inning on an Andruw Jones double to left.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Pirates, ragged from their 3:12 a.m. arrival into
Atlanta on Friday, sent recently recalled right-hander Jose Parra
to the mound for his first major-league start since 1996. And by
the end, that was the best thing they had going for them. Parra had
held the Braves to two runs, leaving after five innings with five
hits and seven strikeouts and the game tied at 2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves chipped away at the vulnerable Pirates bullpen
for four runs over the sixth and seventh innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland pitched well outside of two lapses with the pitcher
Parra at the plate. Mulholland walked him twice on nine pitches,
the first of which cost him a run. That's because it came with two
outs, allowed Chad Hermanson to move into scoring position and set
up Jason Kendall for a run-scoring single to center.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall has hit in eight consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   That broke a streak of 14 scoreless innings for the Pirates,
going back to the first inning of their extra-inning game against
the Marlins on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
