<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYLOR-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WARRIOR TO ANOTHER: KEEP THE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don Baylor sat in the Chicago Cubs' nearly deserted
clubhouse Friday afternoon. The Cubs' game with the Mets had been
postponed because of rain. Baylor had finished his audience with
members of the press, had said his piece about Mets manager Bobby
Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   Now he was headed with his wife for dinner in Manhattan, where
the most likely topic of conversation would be the Knicks. The
Knicks begin a best-of-5 series against the young and talented
Toronto Raptors Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The focal point has been Patrick Ewing. Will this be the year?
Or will this be another spring of futility in his pursuit of an
elusive NB A championship?
</P>
<P>
   I was curious to hear what Baylor thought about Ewing, about
championships pursued and won late in life. They are involved in
different sports and are really part of different generations.
Baylor is 51, Ewing 37. But they share a perspective on the sense
of urgency an athlete assumes as a career ends.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, like Ewing, was known as a gallant warrior in a major
league career that began in Baltimore in 1970 and ended in Oakland
in 1988. Like Ewing, his career had always been linked with the
absence of a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was 38 years old when he finally won a World Series
championship. Ewing will be 38 in August. What thoughts did Baylor
think were going through Ewing's mind on the eve of a playoff
series with a tough, young opponent? ``Patrick's got to be
thinking: `I'm 37. How many more shots will I have?''' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's chase is a lot like Baylor's. Although Baylor played
with five different teams, while Ewing has played for one, each had
heartbreaking near misses. Ewing's disappointments are known: no
playoffs in 1985-86, then a string of first- and second-round
eliminations, a pair of Eastern Conference championship losses, an
NBA championship loss to Houston, and then, in what must be the
most frustrating moment of his career, a defeat to San Antonio in
last year's NBA finals while he sat out with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor leaned back and recalled his litany of frustration. He
broke in with Baltimore at the end of the 1970 season. The Orioles
won the World Series that year. While Baylor wasn't on the roster,
he figured his time was near. Then the run of near misses began.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1973 we won our division, but we ran into the A's,'' he
said. ``In 1974 we got beat by the A's.'' In 1979, Baylor was with
the Angels, who lost to the Orioles in the American League
Championship Series. Three years later, the Angels faced the
Brewers in the ALCS. ``The Angels had to win one game _ we won the
first two and lost the next three to Milwaukee,'' Baylor said. ``To
me, that was the heartbreak to all the others before 1986 with the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '85 Yankees were the best team I ever played on _ player
for player _ and we finished second. Sometimes playing on a good
team isn't enough. It comes down to something else totally out of
your control.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 Baylor went to Boston. In the World Series, the Red Sox
had a three-games-to-two lead on the Mets _ in the very stadium
where Baylor was sitting yesterday. Boston was an out away from
winning the World Series. But the Red Sox wound up losing the game
and the series.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the middle of the 1987 season, Baylor was traded to
Minnesota, a team treading water. Minnesota won the World Series,
and Baylor finally had his ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't believe those guys who talk about their individual
stats; they'll tell you how they were the most valuable player or
the leading scorer or had the most runs batted in,'' Baylor said.
``But the point is: how many rings do you have? You can have all
the money, and all of the stats, but they don't have a championship
trophy. Rod Carew, before he went into the Hall of Fame, said: `Now
I can say my career is complete. I'm in the Hall of Fame. But I
still don't have a World Series that I participated in.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an MVP sitting at home. I have a Roberto Clemente
trophy at home. I also have the World Series championship sitting
at home. In our business, what you're measured on is
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Who does Baylor like between the veteran Knicks and the young
Raptors?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Knicks; I like the toughness of the Knicks,'' he
said. ``You have young guys coming in all the time. But then you
have some of those old warriors like Patrick Ewing that say, `This
is my one shot; I have to rise to the occasion.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor likes Ewing, one warrior to another, who knows what it's
like to chase the dawn. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
