<HEADER>
A4010 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-RENTS-OAKLAND-SFCHRON     04-21 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENTS-OAKLAND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND BENEFITS FROM SCARCITY OF COMMERCIAL SPACE IN
SAN  FRANCISCO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID SCHOLZ 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ted Elliott laughs out loud when he races across
the Bay Bridge during his morning commute from San Francisco and
sees the hordes of commuters waiting in traffic at the toll plaza
to go the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Oakland, Calif., was seemingly a speed bump for
companies of all sizes that over the years had looked at the East
Bay, the last two years have been a different story.
</P>
<P>
   The city now is on the radar screen of businesses that are
increasingly unable to find _ let alone afford _ commercial space
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first quarter of this year, vacancy rates in
downtown Oakland have sunk to an unheard of 3 percent from 12
percent two years ago, while annual rents have risen to more than
$42 per square foot from $20 since early 1998, according to Cushman
&AMP; Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, president and chief executive officer of Jobscience
Inc., an Internet health care resource center for nursing
professionals, is among the vanguard of a growing number of
dot-coms and other businesses that have found relief from the
space-crunch heartache in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to what San Francisco landlords were demanding from
him, including warrants in his company, first and last month rents,
security deposit and jokingly, ``his left arm and first-born,''
Elliott was pleasantly surprised by the reception he received from
property owners in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want you,'' Elliott said was the reception he
received from Oakland's landlords.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case in San Francisco. For seven months, his
operations were crammed in the top floor of a home in Pacific
Heights. By contrast, he can spread out his operations in a
two-story building on Webster Street in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   His new accommodations are large enough to house as many as 120
workers for an employee roster that now numbers 30.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott was surprised by the flexible attitude in the lease
negotiations. The landlord, he said, was willing to pay for all the
tenant improvements, settle for a minor security deposit and
establish a graduated scale of lease payments.
</P>
<P>
   His lease averages out to $20 annually per square foot, compared
with the $60 annual rates sought in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's commercial real estate market started to change with
the slow, steady transformation of the city's downtown area. Most
notable was the development of the City Center project and Jack
London Square office and retail complex, as well as the addition of
two large government buildings and the University of California
headquarters building.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the turn in Oakland's commercial real estate
market, the Shorenstein Co. is developing a $100 million, 20-story
office building adjacent to the City Center complex. Oakland
planning officials have put the proposal on a fast track, with
final approval expected soon and groundbreaking as early as summer.
</P>
<P>
   The project comes as the market, particularly for Class A (or
new) office space, the most desirable property, has become
virtually nonexistent due to the heightened demand for space by
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with today's booming economy in the Bay Area, tight
commercial real estate markets in other parts of the region and
Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown's push to spur business growth, Oakland
's commercial real estate market looks inviting to space-starved
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the battle now brewing in San Francisco over
whether city officials should squelch desires of dot-coms to
establish operations in neighborhoods could spur increased interest
in Oakland and surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's popularity among companies that are either moving
there or expanding their presence in the region is bolstered by the
proximity to BART.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland is the best transit center in the Bay Area because you
are on the right side of the Nimitz freeway and it's easy to get to
where you need to go,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   CAS Systems Inc., another former San Francisco firm that
provides telecommunications services to high-tech companies, also
fell victim to San Francisco's rising rents as it pondered signing
a new lease for space in the Financial District. It looked toward
Oakland, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later, it has turned out to be the best thing that
happened to the company. Not only was the new rent affordable for
CEO Barry Hanson, but the company's new home is centrally located,
making it easy to draw from the East Bay's labor pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to our business growing is finding and attracting
people who want to enter the high-technology field but don't have
any technology expertise,'' he said. ``We have found a wonderful
location for people who cannot cross the bridge that is located
right on the BART (Bay Area Rapid Transit rail) line at 12th Street
and City Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Emeryville, Calif.'s pro-business environment also has snared
its share of firms that looked east for space to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, North Point Communications, a broadband provider of
digital subscriber products and services, took occupancy of a
100,000-square-foot facility that now houses nearly 500 workers. At
the same time the 3-year-old company was committing to that space,
its management had an option to take an additional 100,000 square
feet, which would have accommodated the company's future growth.
</P>
<P>
   Emeryville houses North Point's network operations center and a
lot of customer support. The company's operations on both sides of
the bay work well together, North Point spokeswoman Susan Doerr
said.
</P>
<P>
   The central location, by either car or public transit, also made
the Emeryville space attractive. ``It's part of our company's
culture to make it easy to get to work, and that has made it easy
to hire new employees,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With the cheaper space and better commute, Elliott's eyes also
have been opened to the quality of life that others have come to
recognize on the east side of the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sunny, warmer and the people want you,'' he said. ``It's
kind of nice to be in a place where people want you. It's nothing
like San Francisco, where it has become like Manhattan, where there
are too many busy people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
