<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TORONTO-NYT     04-21 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TORONTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS SNAP YANKEES' WINNING STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Fastballs thrown with intent to bruise are often
senseless coded messages, but the mild exchange of hit batsmen
Friday will allow the New York Yankees to remember their 8-3 loss
to the Toronto Blue Jays for something other than how badly they
played.
</P>
<P>
   While dressing after Friday's game, some Yankees debated quietly
about whether the Blue Jays' Chris Carpenter had drilled Tino
Martinez purposefully, and whether the Yankees' Todd Erdos had
retaliated by bouncing a ball off Carlos Delgado's hip. There was
no point, after all, for the Yankees to review their many mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   So they will just move on, with their winning streak over after
eight games. ``As long as we cram it into one game _ as long as we
don't space out the garbage, and do it all at once,'' was manager
Joe Torre's way of getting beyond this off day, as he expounded on
a series of Yankee gaffes detailed by reporters. ``Just get it all,
line it up, and I'll initial it.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, a scorecard from Friday's game would be covered
with giant JT's, in almost every inning. In the bottom of the
first, the Yankee starter, Ramiro Mendoza, threw wildly after
fielding a ball hit in front of the mound, and Homer Bush was safe
at first, credited with a single.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi, the Blue Jays' hard-swinging right fielder, was
next. Third baseman Clay Bellinger felt unsure how he should defend
against Mondesi, for Mendoza throws sinkers and mostly induces
ground balls. On the artificial surface at the Skydome, the ball
moves much faster than on grass, and when a grounder hits the seam
between the dirt and the artificial surface, it tends to skid.
</P>
<P>
   So Bellinger was not entirely comfortable when Mondesi ripped a
grounder down the line, and he failed to backhand the ball _ a play
that Torre said later that he thought should have been made.
Mondesi's bounder rolled into the corner, where Ricky Ledee rushed
for it too quickly and was fooled by the carom.
</P>
<P>
   Bush scored, and Mondesi ended up on third base with what was
initially ruled a double-error, on Bellinger and Ledee. Several
minutes later, the official scorer changed that call, but not
Bellinger's sentiment that he ``probably should've made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays assumed a 2-0 advantage, but Mendoza's sinking
fastball stopped sinking after the first inning and Delgado slammed
a home run in the fourth. Mendoza subsequently lost command of his
fastball and hit a couple of batters, and when Ledee overthrew a
cutoff man, it allowed Toronto to score four runs in the inning,
rather than three.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes just kept coming. Mondesi led off the fifth with a
grounder that skipped toward the shortstop hole, and Bellinger
flashed over in pursuit of the ball. Shortstop Derek Jeter stopped,
Bellinger never reached the ball and Jeter wound up catching the
ball flat-footed, disgusted that he had not just kept moving. The
team ``kind of seemed dead,'' Jeter said later.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees finally mounted a rally in the sixth against
Carpenter, scoring twice, even after Shane Spencer failed to tag up
and take third base on a fly to center. Martinez strolled to the
plate with two out and two on, a home run away from cutting the
lead to two runs against a Blue Jays team whose pitching had been
getting pounded and whose bullpen was exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   But incredibly, Bernie Williams, the runner on first base, was
thrown out trying to steal second, ending the inning. ``Not very
smart,'' Torre said. ``A bad choice.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a forgettable performance in between an exchange of
purpose pitches. With his control suffering, Mendoza hit Brad
Fullmer and Marty Cordova in the fourth inning, and none of the
Blue Jays seemed to think he did this intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting batters repeatedly _ even accidentally _ is often
considered grounds for retaliation. In the top of the fifth,
Carpenter pitched far inside to Williams, who grounded out, then
bounced a fastball off Martinez's left buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez flipped his bat away and trotted to first. He said
later that he did not know whether Carpenter hit him on purpose,
but it seemed that Carpenter did so; within the code of beanball
ethics, if you are going to hit a batter, hit him on the lower
body.
</P>
<P>
   That might have been the end of it. But in the bottom of the
fifth, the Yankee reliever Todd Erdos bounced a fastball off
Delgado, who glared at Erdos as he slowly moved to first. Mondesi,
who had been at first, walked slowly to second, watching Erdos and
Delgado, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Erdos insisted he did not aim a fastball at Delgado. ``I was
just trying to come inside,'' he said. ``I had a guy on first base
at the time, and I didn't want to put another guy on.''
</P>
<P>
   After that half-inning, Delgado stopped at the mound and chatted
briefly with Carpenter, and four batters into the top of the sixth,
Carpenter grazed Jeter with a fastball. Jeter smirked as he walked
toward first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did me a favor,'' said Jeter, meaning that he was trying to
get on base.
</P>
<P>
   The beanball conflict, limited as it was, ended there. The
competition _ as in who would win the game _ concluded long before
that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
