<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPAN'S NIKKEI INDEX POSTS A DECREASE OF 3.7 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Japanese stocks fell as sweeping changes in the makeup of the
benchmark Nikkei index on Monday forced investors who track it to
raise money to buy the new components. The Nikkei index of 225
issues declined 706.64 points, or 3.7 percent, to 18,252.68. For
the week, the Nikkei fell 11 percent, its biggest one-week loss
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, Korea's Kospi rose 0.8 percent, led by Korea
Telecom and other companies that were expected to post strong
first-quarter earnings. Taiwan's TWSE index rose 0.1 percent as
investors bet that Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing would profit
after the government ordered a rival to stop construction of a
plant. Malaysia's composite index rose 0.2 percent. Markets around
the world, including in Australia, Hong Kong, India, Indonesia,
Europe, Latin America, Singapore and the United States, were closed
in observance of Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   AMERITRADE OFFERS FREE TRADING
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade, the electronic brokerage firm, has introduced a
trading service that does not charge any commissions on orders to
buy or sell stocks at market prices. The bare-bones operation,
called freetrade.com, expects to make money from interest on loans
to investors, from payments it receives from other companies for
sending trades their way and from selling ad space on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN TRIBE IN NEW GAMBLING DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the St. Regis Mohawk tribe, who were on the verge
of gaining approval to build a $500 million casino in the
Catskills, have turned their back on that plan. Instead they signed
an agreement to give exclusive rights to build, develop and manage
any Mohawk casinos in New York state to Park Place Entertainment,
the owner of three casinos in Atlantic City, N.J. Those rights
could be worth billions of dollars, experts said. In return, the
Mohawks would receive a $3 million loan and a large percentage of
the profits from any casino, if and when one is built.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS MAY HAVE TO BID FOR A JOB
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge presiding over the class-action lawsuits
charging auction houses Sotheby's and Christie's with price-fixing
has decided to hold an auction. He invited all the lawyers
representing the 40 plaintiffs so far to submit secret bids by May
12 to determine who will manage the plaintiff's case, a prize that
could be worth millions.
</P>
<P>
   BUYERS LOOKING AT ORANGE PLC
</P>
<P>
   Telephone companies around the world have begun to jockey for
position in what is expected to be a fierce round of bidding for
Orange PLC, the British mobile-telephone operator. Orange is
expected to be sold or spun off by Vodafone as a condition of its
merger with Mannesmann, the German telecommunications and
engineering conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   AN AMBITIOUS COMPUTER LAB CLOSES
</P>
<P>
   Interval Research, a computer laboratory founded eight years ago
with a $100 million investment from Paul Allen, a co-founder of
Microsoft and a computer scientist, has closed. The research
concern was established to design technologies that would shape the
industry far into the future. Some 30 of the company's 50 employees
will be offered positions at a smaller advanced broadband
development group that will be established by Vulcan Ventures,
Allen's investment group.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKKEEPING PROBLEMS AT BANK ONE
</P>
<P>
   Bank One said it had bookkeeping problems in 1999 as it
integrated the computer systems of its capital markets operations
with those of First Chicago when the two banks merged. Bank One
said the problems would have a small impact on its financial
results.
</P>
<P>
   DANONE MAY TAKE A LOOK AT NABISCO
</P>
<P>
   Franck Riboud, the chairman of Danone Group, said his company
might consider buying Nabisco Group Holdings, a U.S. rival, or its
80.6 percent stake in Nabisco Holdings, the maker of Ritz crackers
and Oreo cookies.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL MARKETS REOPEN MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   Stock, bond and commodity markets in the United States and many
other countries were closed in observance of Good Friday. Markets
in the United States will reopen on Monday, but most European
markets will be closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
