<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-RESPONSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE COMPANY WITH NO DRIVER IS CRITICIZED FOR IGNORING ALARM 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN FLYNN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fire officials Friday chastised an engine company
that did not respond to a fire Wednesday afternoon, saying the
company should have answered the call even though none of the
firefighters on duty had been trained to drive a fire truck.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Engine Co. 303 in Jamaica, Queens, appeared to have
violated any regulations, Chief Peter Ganci said, but they broke an
unwritten code saying firefighters should do whatever is necessary
to protect lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disappointing thing for me,'' he said at a news
conference, ``is that we have five members of the New York City
Fire Department who had a fire to respond to and, for whatever
reason, contractually or otherwise, they thought it was not
necessary for them to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the four firefighters and a supervising
lieutenant were just following department rules that permit only
those with special training to drive fire trucks.
</P>
<P>
   A neighboring fire company responded to the house fire at 107-33
159th Street, in which a young boy suffered minor burns. It arrived
a minute and a half faster than the average response time. But the
incident underscored the tension between the department's
self-image as a place of derring-do and the perception by some that
it can be a nitpicking bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a fire officer had let a firefighter drive,'' said Capt.
Peter Gorman, president of the Uniformed Fire Officers Association,
``and he was not qualified and there was an accident and someone
was hurt, the same fire officials who are complaining would hold
the officer accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver for Engine Co. 303 hurt his back sliding down the
firehouse pole as he began an earlier emergency run about 3 p.m.
Wednesday, officials said. After that job, the driver left work,
and the company notified superior officers that the company would
be unable to respond while it waited for a replacement driver to
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, a 911 call reported a serious fire. The
company did not go, Gorman said, because the lieutenant in charge
determined that no one else in the company was capable of driving
the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Ganci said the commonsense approach for the firefighters would
have been to ignore the rule, get in the truck and go. Many
firefighters, he said, are capable of driving engines, even though
they have not gone through the department's chauffeur training
course. Certainly, he said, no one would have punished them for
trying.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman said the incident shows that the department needs more
training programs so more firefighters are qualified to drive
engines. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
