A4119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BUSINESS-ATTIRE-NY     04-21 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUSINESS-ATTIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRMS GOING CASUAL HELP DISADVANTAGED JOB SEEKERS SUIT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT WORTH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As this city's major law firms, banks and consulting
firms shift to a casual dress code, the question arises: what are
they doing with all those suits?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that they are giving them to job seekers, some of
whom may soon be better dressed than the city's power elite.
Cadwalader, Wickersham &AMP; Taft, which recently became the first
major Wall Street law firm to go casual full time, asked all its
lawyers and staff members to donate a suit or other business attire
and collected more than 500 clothing items, including scores of
costly suits.
</P>
<P>
   Other major companies have organized suit drives recently,
including American Express, Goldman, Sachs, PaineWebber, McKinsey
and McGraw-Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the managing partner of Cadwalader, Robert O. Link
Jr., helped carry the firm's donated suits out to a delivery truck.
Link, who donated two dark pinstripes, a Hugo Boss and a Burberry,
said he was happy to see them go. ``It's more comfortable,'' he
said of the muted green shirt, chinos and blazer he was wearing.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later, Claudio Young, a 24-year-old
unemployed man from upper Manhattan's Washington Heights, was
trying on a dark Paul Stuart pinstripe suit that had been donated
by a Cadwalader employee, along with a Brooks Brothers shirt, a
yellow silk tie and black wingtips. ``I'm not a suit guy; I'm a
hip-hop guy,'' he said. In fact, he said he had never worn a suit
or a tie before. His usual outfit consists of baggy jeans _ Mecca
and Sean John are his favorite brands _ Timberland boots, a
basketball jersey and a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Young received his suit in a midtown warehouse belonging to
Career Gear, a nonprofit organization that works with low-income
men to give them the clothes they need for interviews and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Career Gear clients, Young has had his share of
troubles. After dropping out of school, he developed a drug habit,
and was arrested in August 1997 for selling cocaine to an
undercover agent. But he completed a treatment program, earned his
general equivalency diploma, and after three months of job
training, wound up at Career Gear.
</P>
<P>
   And like most of the men who show up at Career Gear's basement
warehouse near Madison Square Garden, Young was uneasy about his
new clothes at first. Few of the men who come here know how to tie
a necktie, and some find the suits uncomfortable. ``I had one guy
with a scar from ear to ear, a former gang guy,'' said Connie von
Tobel, a volunteer at Career Gear. ``He didn't want anything tight
around the neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Young will soon have his first job interview. ``I want to pay
taxes, you know, real taxes,'' he said. He hopes to find a position
as a photocopy machine technician.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that he will feel a little overdressed for his
interview? Gary Field, Career Gear's founder, said: ``I don't think
so. What's more important is the way it makes them feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Pryor, a former hotel worker, put on a Brooks Brothers
suit after going through addiction and job-training programs, and
now has a job with the New York Center for Addiction Treatment
Services. ``It boosts your confidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Field, a social worker who has had his own struggles with
unemployment and addiction, founded Career Gear last year. He had
worked briefly at a law firm where female lawyers donated business
clothing to Dress for Success, which works only with women and has
been in business for three and a half years. ``The male attorneys
kept asking why they couldn't donate suits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Field and Arlene Wallace of Dress for Success said the
shift to casual dress among New York companies had been a
tremendous windfall for them. Career Gear has received about 2,000
suits over the last year. Dress for Success' New York affiliate has
received 8,000 to 10,000 pieces of business clothing in the last
three weeks, most of them suits, said Wallace, the organization's
associate director. Both groups have also received hefty donations
from designers, including Brooks Brothers, Polo and Ferragamo.
</P>
<P>
   Field added, however, that the shift to casual wear posed
complications. For one thing, his clients will have to keep up.
``We're working with retailers, so they can get dress-casual stuff
when they come back for the alumni programs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As businessmen dress down and job-seekers dress up, will the
suit's status suffer? Probably not. Even at Cadwalader, lawyers
dress up when they meet with clients. And the suit has survived
similar challenges in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a flexible scheme of clothing,'' said Anne Hollander, an
art historian and the author of ``Sex and Suits: The Evolution of
Modern Dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been around for 200 years, if not more,'' she said. ``So
it has a likelihood of lasting much longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
