<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4121 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-21 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT TO SHAQ: GO FOR IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille, my man. Wilt here. This columnist
channeled my spirit Friday while you were doing yoga with the rest
of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   I was one happy cat to have the open line. I've been trying to
get your attention all year (haven't you sensed my aura?), so I
could deliver my ``Win one for the Big Dipper'' pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   You've had a monster season, my man. To lead the league in
scoring again is cool and don't think I didn't notice your 299
assists. Those 63 double-doubles you have to show for all your toil
and trouble were sweet, but they won't mean a thing if you don't
win a ring.
</P>
<P>
   Those positive vibes you're feeling from the public can turn
into chills in the time it takes a series to slip from your grasp.
Trust me, I know the score even if no one else does.
</P>
<P>
   You're the most visible Laker on a squad everybody sees as
unstoppable. Wasn't it just the other day Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy was quoted as saying his players are intimidated by your
team?
</P>
<P>
   Right, baby. Now you cats know what it feels like to be Tiger
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions you yourself will face in these playoffs, only I
know. It's not easy being 7-feet-1 when that final playoff game
isn't won.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, baby, I know. I was the league MVP as a rookie in
Philadelphia. My third season in the NBA, I averaged 50.4 points.
Two years later, I led San Francisco into the Finals. We lost in
five games to Boston, after which a San Francisco fan grumbled to a
local paper, ``Wilt Chamberlain? I can't love a 7-feet-1 loser.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's not easy being so very tall. Win and it's a team
effort. Lose and the failure is yours alone to bear.
</P>
<P>
   Your size makes you an easy target. Your teams have been swept
out of the playoffs the past two seasons, so you know what I'm
saying. It's tough, but you're stronger for having been double- and
triple-teamed by adversity.
</P>
<P>
   I'm proud of you, my man. I really am. This season, you've
proved you can share the ball, you've demonstrated you can play
defense, you've shown you can take a lick and keep kicking butt.
</P>
<P>
   I especially enjoyed that elbow you delivered to David
Robinson's midsection in the game at San Antonio the other day.
That was one small blow for big men right there. When will people
appreciate the pounding we 7-footers have to absorb night in and
night out?
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you, I got so tired of it, the second game of the
divisional playoffs against Boston during my rookie season, I took
a wild swing at Tom Heinsohn, missed him, hit my teammate Tom Gola
flush on his arm and hurt my hand.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to be smarter than I was in 1960. My hand wasn't
right the rest of the way, and it ended up costing us the series.
</P>
<P>
   I applaud the way you've kept your composure. You've been one
cool cat.
</P>
<P>
   It is essential that you maintain your emotional equilibrium
during the playoffs. Remember: The sweetest retaliation of all is
winning.
</P>
<P>
   That's how you must approach your critics, too. The problem is,
my man, you've raised the expectations so high with your sublime
play during the regular season, you've set yourself up for a crash
landing.
</P>
<P>
   I know you want the world to wrap you in a bear hug, no matter
how much you feign indifference. I know, because I was the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, the public's love is harder to win than that of a
good woman.
</P>
<P>
   The more you give the public, the more it wants. No matter what
you do, it might never be enough. You've built a Frankenstein, and
it's not going to be easy to run away from it.
</P>
<P>
   So my advice to you, my man, is play for your teammates, not
your town.
</P>
<P>
   Those cats know the score. I heard Glen Rice say Friday he
doesn't know what else people possibly can ask of you. He said he
hopes the Lakers can win the title this year to remove that burden
from your back.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds to me like a guy who has your back.
</P>
<P>
   I heard you say you're going to try to raise the level of your
game to new heights in the playoffs, starting with the Lakers'
best-of-five series against Sacramento. That's cool if you want to
try to block more shots, get more rebounds, set more screens.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep this in mind, my man: When I won my first NBA title in
1967, I averaged a mere 17.7 points in the championship series
against San Francisco. Rick Barry had 55 points in one game and 43
in another for the losing team.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 6, I didn't take a shot in the second half, but I pulled
down eight of my 23 rebounds and blocked a half-dozen shots in that
span. And I was the one in Barry's face when he heaved his final
errant shot that allowed my Philadelphia team to escape with a
125-122 series-icing win.
</P>
<P>
   I remember telling a reporter afterward that sometimes it's
easier to play against a team that has one man doing most of the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it was a hard-earned lesson. I hope you'll keep it in
mind and continue kicking the ball out to Kobe Bryant or Glen when
your shot's not there, same as you've done all season.
</P>
<P>
   And don't fret your free throws, my man. As one of my coaches,
Frank McGuire, once told me, ``If you hit all your free throws we'd
never lose. It would be too easy and that wouldn't be any fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't surprise me that your coach, Phil Jackson, came out
and said he is at peace with the prospect of your being put on the
foul line in the fourth quarter with the game hanging in the
balance.
</P>
<P>
   The Zen Master has a clear line to the metaphysical world. He
sees that you're in your eighth year in the league, same as I was
when I won my first NBA championship. I'm pretty sure he recognizes
my aura is with you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
