<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CABDRIVERS-SAFETY-     04-21 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CABDRIVERS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARFUL CABDRIVERS WELCOME SAFETY STOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The yellow taxi bore medallion 6Y70, but it was not a
yellow taxi.
</P>
<P>
   It was a police cruiser, a radio car in disguise, and it was
occupied by members of the Brooklyn North Street Crime Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before midnight on Wednesday, with its engine revving
and a portable red light flashing from its dashboard, the car
lurched through its gears and bore down on a livery cab in East New
York. When the livery cab pulled to the curb, three officers
stepped out of the fake taxi and encountered a shift in the local
law-enforcement climate.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the livery cab, Juan Sampson, 23, watched the officers
converge. He had not been speeding. His papers were valid and
up-to-date. Sampson might have been expected to be irritated, even
angry, about the inconvenience of having a fake taxi laden with
police officers force him to the curb. Instead, he rolled down his
window and grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for checking on me,'' he said. ``Thank you very
much. I appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when critics have accused the Police Department of
stopping too many people with too little reason, and of using the
discretion granted police officers to institutionalize harassment,
New York's livery-cab drivers have adopted the opposite stance.
</P>
<P>
   And for the department's Street Crime Units, vilified for their
aggressive tactics since the fatal police shooting of Amadou Diallo
last year, stopping livery cabs offers more than a new high-profile
assignment. It offers a chance at public redemption. ``That's how
I'm encouraging the guys to look at this,'' said Capt. Barry
Galfano, commanding officer of the Brooklyn North Street Crime
Unit. ``Here's a chance to make friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven livery drivers have been killed this year, a pace not
matched since 1994, and most of the drivers have been killed during
the commission of robberies.
</P>
<P>
   At the taxi industry's urging, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police
Commissioner Howard Safir have created a livery task force of more
than 300 officers, and have issued rules that make it easier for
officers to stop livery cabs and initiate a search. The authorities
and the drivers say they hope that frequent traffic stops will show
robbers that livery cabs are no longer easy marks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the traffic stop program, the department is
setting up five or six safety zones in each borough, where drivers
with suspicious passengers can go to find officers, and tripling
the number of decoy cabs on patrol, although the authorities have
declined to say how many will be deployed in all.
</P>
<P>
   But at the forefront of the driver protection effort are the
eight Street Crime Units, consisting of roughly 240 officers whose
previous assignment had been to patrol high-crime areas in unmarked
cars by night, primarily in plain clothes, trying to surprise
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   It was four Street Crime Unit officers who fired 41 times at
Diallo, who was unarmed, in February of last year. And after more
than a year of demonstrations and denunciations, the unit's very
name remains shorthand in some circles for high-risk, in-your-face
policing. Safir said Friday that the livery driver protection
mission might erase some of the unit's post-Diallo stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what Street Crime was designed to do: to focus
on spikes in crime, particularly violent crime, and to deal with
it,'' Safir said. ``We are now dealing with a segment of the
population that is saying, `We want you to be more involved with
us, not less.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
