<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-LAPTOP-STATE-DEPT-NYT     04-21 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPTOP-STATE-DEPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY FACES REVIEW AFTER A LAPTOP VANISHES
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department is considering a
reorganization of its security system after a laptop computer
vanished from an intelligence office with highly sensitive files
about weapons proliferation, a senior administration official said
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators have not yet determined that the laptop
was stolen, its theft would represent the highest possible breach
of classified material, officials said. The computer contained
files designated `code-level', a status beyond top secret.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright may recommend stripping
the Department's Bureau of Intelligence and Research of its ability
to manage its own security and place it under the aegis of the
Bureau of Diplomatic Security, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary of state is furious about this incident,'' said
the official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``I've rarely
seen her as angry about anything as this case.'
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is leading an investigation into the disappearance of
the laptop, which was reported two months ago by the Office of
Intelligence and Research. The office, which is under the direction
of Assistant Secretary of State J. Stapleton Roy, a former
ambassador to China, is the department's main source of
intelligence data and analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The incident stirred an outcry among some Republican lawmakers.
Rep. Benjamin Gilman, the chairman of the House International
Relations Committee, said it was the latest in ``a long string of
security failures'' at the State Department, including the recent
discovery of a eavesdropping device in a conference room that was
believed to be placed by Russian spies.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to elaborate on the contents of the missing
material, except to confirm that it involved sources and methods
relating to weapons proliferation, including data gathered by
satellites and human and electronic sources. New details of what
may have been contained in the laptop were reported by The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Intelligence and Research has been under fire for
lax security for several years, including those under the direction
of Roy's predecessors. Department officials had recently considered
and rejected a proposal to transfer the bureau's security to the
Bureau of Diplomatic Security, which protects diplomats and foreign
dignitaries and fights terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department internal audit in December found that the
department had allowed contractors and maintenance staff members to
wander around the building without escorts.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, who plans to hold hearings into the recent breaches,
said the department lacked a ``professional environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign policy analysts attributed the security problems to
a culture that is somewhat resistant to onerous security measures
and to sweeping cutbacks in the department's overall budget.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when there are ever greater demands on the department
_ and need for more diplomatic missions in the wake of the breakup
of the Soviet bloc _ Congress has steered resources away from
diplomacy and into law enforcement and counterterrorism operations,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Albright has ordered an internal review of the Department's
security procedures. David Carpenter, the assistant secretary for
diplomatic security, is leading a team of security specialists from
various federal agencies in that study. The results are expected
soon.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Albright said she was ``continuing to study the
possible need for structural changes to ensure that the mandate for
the best security is everywhere understood and everywhere
applied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
