<SLUG> BC-NY-OPERA-EDUC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELEMENTARY SCHOOL WEAVES OPERA INTO CLASSWORK 
</HEADLINE>
 - 980(2TAKES)-NYT  (ko) 
 By NINA SIEGAL     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four fifth-grade girls from Public School 314 escaped
class one recent afternoon in Sunset Park, Brooklyn, not to buy
sweets at the corner bodega, or to swap secrets over blush in the
bathroom, but to slip into a music room to work on their opera, a
three-act (six-page) work involving a popular girl, a class clown
and a meteorite blazing toward Earth.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the four girls, who have been learning about ``Tosca''
and ``Aida'' since kindergarten and attending performances at the
Metropolitan Opera since the third grade, can bat around opera
terms like aficionados. So as a group of second-graders sang
slightly discordant scales in the back of the music room _ which
housed computers nicknamed Verdi, Rossini and Puccini, 10-year-old
Kristina Maisonet buoyantly described her original work, using an
obscure term unfamiliar to even many opera lovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really an opera seria, not an opera,'' Kristina said,
explaining that an opera seria is chock-full of arias and short on
recitative, or sung dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kristina nor many of her classmates come from homes
where parents and grandparents listen to opera as daily background
music. More than three-quarters of the 1,918 students at P.S. 314,
the Luis Munoz Marin Elementary School, are Latin American and
Caribbean, and the second largest ethnic group in the school is
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1992, Vincent Grippo, the superintendent of Community
School District 20, started weaving opera into the fabric of the
school, inspired by a teacher who wanted to shape her classes
around an opera motif. And he says it has set off a remarkable
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the state education commissioner included P.S. 314 on a
list of the 43 most academically troubled public schools in the
state. While it is still not a high-ranking school, P.S. 314
finished 408th out of the city's 677 public elementary schools in
reading achievement for 1999 and has escaped the list of failing
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my expressions is, `If it's good enough for the rich,
why don't we try it on the poor?' '' Grippo said. ``It's art for
art's sake, but beyond that, it creates self-esteem and a full
human being. One of the reasons it works is because we're taking
poor immigrant children and exposing them to a whole world of
creativity and beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, a group of kindergartners might be practicing
screechy Suzuki violin; second graders might be rehearsing
``Mikey's Dream,'' a 25-minute opera that they wrote and produced;
a group of fourth graders might be working on an interactive CD-ROM
about ``The Queen of Spades,'' responding to a performance they had
just seen at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Opera Guild says the school employs the only
full-time opera teacher in the New York City school system. The
teacher, Mary Jo Lassen, tells students about the history of the
form, helps them read and study Italian and French librettos with
the help of translations, and has them memorize and sing translated
arias. In the fifth grade, students can join an opera club to
attend early rehearsals at the Met with Lassen.
</P>
<P>
   They meet stars like Placido Domingo, write their own works in
English and sometimes translate them and perform them in other
languages. (Boys seem just as interested as girls, said Lassen,
noting that last year most students in the opera club were boys.)
Earlier this year, mezzo-soprano Frederica von Stade visited the
school.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. 314 still has its troubles. Measured against other public
elementary schools in New York with students who have similar
economic and social backgrounds, P.S. 314 performs about average on
English tests, according to the most recent assessment by the New
York City Board of Education. Last year, 41.2 percent of the
students were reading at or above grade level. Still, Grippo said,
children studying the performing arts benefit in ways that cannot
be measured on standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   The school's program is financed through the Annenberg
Foundation and a city arts fund, Project Arts. Elements of the
program have been copied in about 20 of the district's 30 schools,
although few have the same kind of financial support. Teachers at
P.S. 314 say its program improves their students' academic drive
and helps them learn a wide range of basic skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each child in the class got a script, each child got to read
with the other children, and along with their lines, they learned
plot and structure,'' said Regina M. Gangi, a teacher whose second
graders recently wrote and performed a 25-minute opera. ``The other
kids came along with math by building the sets, doing the
electrical work, and that all has to do a lot with figuring out
equations. It's a different way of having the children open up
their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   By writing their own works in the music room (after school,
during lunch break, and occasionally during class), the students
seem to have gained insights into opera's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make it very juicy,'' Kristina said.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Lauren, added, ``You have to have a big climax, not
something that happens every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls giddily narrated the plot of their work, ``Friends to
the End,'' to a visitor, their eyes beaming, voices overlapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a popular girl and a boy who's like the class clown,
and he becomes more popular than she is and so she gets jealous,''
Kristina said.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Colon, 11, continued. ``So she shoves pills in his mouth
and _ she doesn't want to kill him; she just wants to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren broke in, ``There's a meteorite coming and the world is
going to end, but then it's just a little rock.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tiffany Cortes, 10, with a coy smile, insisted that the
ending was still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren conceded, ``It's supposed to be a comedy, but we might
make the world end anyway.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000421.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-OPERA-EDUC &LR; - &UR; 2NDTA     04-21 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OPERA-EDUC </SLUG>
 - 2NDTAKE-NYT  
 UNDATED: end anyway.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Her eyes darted for confirmation toward Lassen, the force behind
P.S. 314's devotion to opera. Twenty-two years ago, when she was a
fifth-grade teacher and the school's music program was faltering
because of budget cuts, she took a teacher training class from the
Metropolitan Opera Guild. Later, she tried to introduce her class
to ``Rigoletto.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one libretto and an audio tape of an opera
performance,'' she recalled. ``I read it out loud to the students.
How boring!''
</P>
<P>
   Lassen decided to give her students a more active role in their
opera lessons, and eight years ago she requested permission to
devote her attention to teaching opera to students in all grades.
</P>
<P>
   Christina C. Cortes, the interim vice principal of P.S. 314,
said that when she first saw Lassen's students sewing period
costumes for a show, she was instantly intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very focused on the elements of story, on narrative,
setting, time, problem solving, solutions,'' Cortes said. ``So it
was a direct carry-over to their developmental learning in
reading.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, second-grade students were asked to write and produce
their own opera, which eventually became ``Mikey's Dream.'' Last
fall, two second-grade teachers, Gangi and Laura Garzaniti,
attended half a dozen daylong workshops arranged by the opera
guild. Their students auditioned for various roles and
responsibilities for ``Mikey's Dream,'' from acting and writing to
set design and public relations work.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of March, members of the newly formed Star Opera
Company, a group of about three dozen 7- and 8-year olds, performed
``Mikey's Dream'' four times, once for their parents and three
times for a rapt audience of peers, many of whom sang along from
their seats.
</P>
<P>
   The work is about a little boy who cannot go out to play because
his room is a mess and he has not finished his homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had a servant,'' laments the protagonist, Mikey,
played by Juan Carlos Martinez, 7. ``I have one dollar. Maybe I can
buy a servant.''
</P>
<P>
   He falls asleep and has a nightmare in which all his friends are
fighting; but when he awakes, they are in his room, offering to
help him clean up.
</P>
<P>
   In his final aria, Mikey sings, ``I am so lucky I have good
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   During the third performance, one of five large set pieces
started to crack, and the students, alone backstage between scenes,
had to figure out what to do. One boy from Gangi's class decided to
stand behind the piece and hold it up throughout the scene, saving
the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really weird to think of a second grader figuring out
that if he stood there behind it no one would see him,'' Gangi
said. The boy had been very unmotivated, she said. ``He never used
to have his homework done. But since this, he's been coming in and
doing his work.''
</P>
<P>
   During a post-production discussion, some students even showed
precocious signs of the kind of self-possession that sets the opera
greats apart. Reflecting on her achievement, Melinda Lopez, 8, who
played the leading female role, Ashley, dabbed her brashly colored
eyelids like a true diva.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is when you grow up, you can remember about
this,'' she said. ``And you can be a singer and you won't be shy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-00 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
